<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STALKING A DANGEROUS NEWS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Bernard Adelmo Ortiz sat before a bouquet of TV
microphones that had been placed at the table spe cially for him.
He smiled. This was his moment, his dream come true.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the woman Ortiz has stalked for years and is ac cused of
stalking again _ singer Linda Ronstadt _ it must have been a
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Ortiz was sentenced to three years' pro bation
after he pleaded guilty to attempted stalking of Ron stadt. Within
weeks, he vio lated the deal and was sentenced to 10 months in
prison. At the time, he wrote a letter to the judge saying, ``Linda
Ronstadt has touched my heart, soothes my soul and occupied part of
my mind for 20-and-some years.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, May 7, he was in a Maricopa County jail, staring at
the unblinking TV cameras as if they were the eyes of Linda
herself. Channel 10 was there. And Channel 15. And Channel 3.
Earlier, he'd spo ken to Channel 5.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer wore the white tuxedo he'd been ar rested in
outside the Sun dome. He no longer carried the blood red rose he'd
hoped to give to Ronstadt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was content.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, May 6, the singer was making a guest appear ance on
Garrison Keillor's A Prairie Home Companion ra dio show being taped
in Sun City. Sheriff's deputies spot ted Ortiz in a 1978 white
Cadillac that he'd filled with boxes and flowers and copies of
letters to Ronstadt.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz admits to his obses sion. He says he wants noth ing more
than to reach Ronstadt. And here were Phoenix's major television
outlets, helping him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand where your coming from,'' Channel 3's news
director, Phil Alvidrez, told me Monday. ``Should we be putting
such people on TV? It's certainly a point worth debating.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   The answer should be obvi ous, particularly for people who work
in television.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a stalker was sentenced to prison for harassing
local newscaster Deborah Pyburn Brewer. Her attorney was Larry
Debus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a station in Phoenix that has a newscast that has
not had one of their woman harassed in some way,'' Debus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who's been through this knows all the stalker wants is
the attention of the person they're stalking. They want to be seen.
They have these demented delu sions. By putting them on TV they
play right into their hands. It's bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is a slow news day. Stories brushed off during the week
can lead a weekend newscast. The Republic con sidered covering
Ortiz's news conference but decided against it. So did Channel 12,
the only local TV news opera tion with the sense to ignore the sad,
nauseating show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any news value in it,'' News Director Mark Casey
said. ``And I felt bad for Linda Ronstadt.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel 3's Alvidrez, who said he wasn't involved in airing
Ortiz's interview, said, ``Gauged against the Suns having lost
earlier in the afternoon and the other events that happened over
the weekend, that was proba bly one of the more interest ing things
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same conclusion reached by most other TV news directors
in town. By people who've never been on camera. By people who've
never had someone like Ber nard Adelmo Ortiz try to bring them a
blood red rose. &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &QL; 
 &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
