<HEADLINE>
STALKING A DANGEROUS NEWS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Bernard Adelmo Ortiz sat before a bouquet of TV
microphones that had been placed at the table spe cially for him.
He smiled. This was his moment, his dream come true.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the woman Ortiz has stalked for years and is ac cused of
stalking again _ singer Linda Ronstadt _ it must have been a
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Ortiz was sentenced to three years' pro bation
after he pleaded guilty to attempted stalking of Ron stadt. Within
weeks, he vio lated the deal and was sentenced to 10 months in
prison. At the time, he wrote a letter to the judge saying, ``Linda
Ronstadt has touched my heart, soothes my soul and occupied part of
my mind for 20-and-some years.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, May 7, he was in a Maricopa County jail, staring at
the unblinking TV cameras as if they were the eyes of Linda
herself. Channel 10 was there. And Channel 15. And Channel 3.
Earlier, he'd spo ken to Channel 5.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer wore the white tuxedo he'd been ar rested in
outside the Sun dome. He no longer carried the blood red rose he'd
hoped to give to Ronstadt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was content.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, May 6, the singer was making a guest appear ance on
Garrison Keillor's A Prairie Home Companion ra dio show being taped
in Sun City. Sheriff's deputies spot ted Ortiz in a 1978 white
Cadillac that he'd filled with boxes and flowers and copies of
