</P>
<P>
   Ortiz admits to his obses sion. He says he wants noth ing more
than to reach Ronstadt. And here were Phoenix's major television
outlets, helping him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand where your coming from,'' Channel 3's news
director, Phil Alvidrez, told me Monday. ``Should we be putting
such people on TV? It's certainly a point worth debating.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   The answer should be obvi ous, particularly for people who work
in television.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a stalker was sentenced to prison for harassing
local newscaster Deborah Pyburn Brewer. Her attorney was Larry
Debus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a station in Phoenix that has a newscast that has
not had one of their woman harassed in some way,'' Debus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who's been through this knows all the stalker wants is
the attention of the person they're stalking. They want to be seen.
They have these demented delu sions. By putting them on TV they
play right into their hands. It's bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is a slow news day. Stories brushed off during the week
can lead a weekend newscast. The Republic con sidered covering
Ortiz's news conference but decided against it. So did Channel 12,
the only local TV news opera tion with the sense to ignore the sad,
nauseating show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any news value in it,'' News Director Mark Casey
