<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-95MAGIC-HNS &LR;      05-09 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-95MAGIC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ In some alternate universe, another reality, there
exists an NBA where the Orlando Magic is in the process of
defending another in a dynastic string of championships.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In that world, Shaquille O'Neal and Penny Hardaway are the next
generation's Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Magic Johnson, the duo who led
the Los Angeles Lakers to league supremacy during the salad days of
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs? They were dismantled long ago, just after David
Robinson signed a free-agent deal with the Lakers in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets? They won their title in 1994, but they were rolled
by Orlando the next season, with the Magic winning the championship
in five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls? Michael Jordan returned to Chicago, but in 1996, his
first full season back, the Bulls were beaten by the Magic in the
Eastern Conference finals, and Jordan called it quits for the last
time.
</P>
<P>
   A dynasty had been born in Orlando, and it would carry the NBA
into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the way it could have been. Or the way it was
supposed to be. In this reality, though, the Orlando Magic is now a
collection of discards _ the discount bin in the NBA's bargain
basement.
</P>
<P>
   But back in the early '90s, no one could ever have imagined such
a fate for the organization that was considered the model for all
expansion franchises to follow _ one that made the NBA Finals in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   But it was there, at what was supposed to be the height of
glory, that the doomsday clock began ticking on the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a mere five years later, the pieces of the league's ``next
dynasty'' have been flung to the far corners of the NBA world.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd twist, O'Neal, the biggest free-agent prize of the
decade who signed with the Lakers in 1996, and Hardaway, who exited
the Magic kingdom last season for Phoenix, are now meeting in the
Western Conference semifinals. With O'Neal scoring 37 points and
pulling down 14 rebounds, the Lakers crushed the Suns 105-77 in
Game 1 to take a 1-0 lead in the best-of-seven series that
continues here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And every time he sees O'Neal throw down one of his
Richter-scale dunks, Hardaway has flashes of what could have been
for the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see him (O'Neal) play now, and I remember all the good
times we had together, it's unbelievable,'' Hardaway said. ``I took
everything for granted back then, and now I wish I had it all back.
We just knew if we stayed together we'd be back in the Finals
another eight or 10 times before we retired. And then he left, and
that's when everything went downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Many think NBA history would have changed had Nick Anderson made
just one of the four free throws he had in the closing seconds of
Game 1 of the 1995 Finals. Instead, Anderson clanked all four, and
Kenny Smith hit a last-gasp 3-pointer to send the game into
overtime. The Rockets won 120-118 on Hakeem Olajuwon's tip-in at
the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The demoralized Magic lost the next game at home 117-106 and
then trudged to Houston, where they lost the next two, giving the
Rockets a sweep and their second straight championship.
</P>
<P>
   One year later O'Neal was gne, seeking championships with Los
Angeles, where many of the great centers _ George Mikan, Wilt
Chamberlain and Abdul-Jabbar _ played and won.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I had regrets, but I was young enough at that point,
I said to myself, `I can start all over,''' said O'Neal of his
departure. ``If I had been 29 or 30, I probably wouldn't have made
that move. That was an excellent team. The only bad thing about
professional basketball is the business side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all mini-conglomerates. And (Lakers vice president)
Jerry West gave me a better deal than the other people did. I took
advantage of that deal because I'll probably never get another deal
like that again in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway's downfall in Orlando began soon after O'Neal left
following the 1995-96 season. With O'Neal alongside him, he looked
like one of the best guards in the league. Without O'Neal, he
struggled under the pressure of trying to keep the team near the
top.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just too much pressure on me after that,'' Hardaway
said. ``It wore me down. (Coach Chuck) Daly didn't like me. The
fans were fed up with me because I wasn't scoring 25 points a
night. I felt like I was in a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a departure from how things started.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando seemed blessed, getting O'Neal with the top pick in the
1992 draft and then landing the No. 1 pick the next year as well.
Orlando took Chris Webber but dealt his rights to Golden State for
the rights to Hardaway, whom the Warriors had taken with the third
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a situation that seemed to be made in heaven,'' said
Lakers coach Phil Jackson, then with the Bulls. ``It seemed like
Orlando got all the breaks in the draft there for a couple of years
and put some pieces together. It was wonderful for them. It's
surprising how fast things can fall apart, but it was obviously a
situation where they didn't win a championship series that was
sitting there for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built our (Chicago) team around the fact that Orlando was
the team that was going to be dominant for a while, especially
after they raided Horace Grant from our team (prior to the 1994-95
season). It's funny how things changed so quickly, but it happened
to them, and it was kind of a forewarning of what was going to come
in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, more to the point, what was going to go _ which was almost
everyone on that Magic roster.
</P>
<P>
   Grant is now in Seattle. Anderson, the Magic's first draft pick
in 1989, was dealt to Sacramento in 1999. Dennis Scott, who earned
the nickname ``3-D'' because of his 3-point shooting, became a
vagabond, going to Dallas, Phoenix, Minnesota and New York before
ending up in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   To the Lakers' Brian Shaw, another member of that 1995 Orlando
team, the erosion of the Magic is a reminder of how fragile things
can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a delicate balance,'' Shaw said. ``You can't
take anything for granted. We thought that even though we didn't
win it that year with the team that we had, we'd get back again and
again and again, but it never happened. Look at them now. Darrell
Armstrong is the only player left from that team.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what could have been, O'Neal just smiled. But the
smile soon faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a nice team,'' he said. ``We could have been something,
maybe. It happens. Called life.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
