A9704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PUTIN-NYT &LR;      05-09 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PUTIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRESIDENT VLADIMIR PUTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 9:
</P>
<P>
   Presidential authority in Russia passed from Boris Yeltsin to
Vladimir Putin last New Year's Eve when Yeltsin resigned, but the
symbolism of Putin's inauguration on Sunday was still lustrous. It
completed the first transfer of power from one freely elected
leader to another in more than 1,000 years of Russian history.
After the ceremony, the energetic new president and his aging
predecessor stepped into the bright sunshine of Cathedral Square,
the very place where generations of czars appeared after being
crowned in the Cathedral of the Assumption. Little more than a
decade ago, the idea of a democratically chosen president occupying
that ground would have seemed unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   As Russians wait for Putin to make his intentions clear, they
should rejoice in the freedoms that have developed since Mikhail
Gorbachev first loosened the straitjacket of Communism and Yeltsin
set Russia on a course toward democracy and free markets. For all
the severe economic and political dislocations of the last 15
years, Russians today enjoy liberties, including open presidential
elections and a largely free press, that their ancestors never
attained. Any accounting of the period since the end of the Cold
War must begin with the recognition of this singular transformation
_ something that Americans should bear in mind in a campaign year
when there is likely to be a boisterous debate about how to handle
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Putin now has the chance to consolidate democracy in his
country. Working with the moderate Parliament that Russians elected
in December, he has an opportunity to stabilize the economy, to
reform a dysfunctional tax code, to crack down on crime and to
build a steady relationship with the United States and other
Western nations. After the stifling decades of Communism and the
erratic years of Yeltsin's rule, Russians yearn for a period of
sustained tranquillity and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who spent most of his career working for the KGB and its
successor security organization, may be tempted to exercise the
near-dictatorial powers that come with the Russian presidency.
Russia needs constant, effective leadership, not a modern variation
of authoritarian command. Putin's promise to rebuild a strong
central government should not become an excuse for drawing all
power back into the hands of the state.
</P>
<P>
   His initial moves reveal little about his governing strategy.
Putin's choice for prime minister, Mikhail Kasyanov, suggests a
desire to press ahead with economic reform and to reduce the
corruption that distorts Russian commerce. Kasyanov, 42, is a
financial expert with reformist instincts, but most of his work has
involved dealing with the West to reschedule Moscow's debts, not
wrestling with the deformities of the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's regard for police and military power is troubling. His
leap from political obscurity to the presidency was accomplished
primarily by directing a brutish military offensive against Chechen
guerrillas and civilians. If he applies the same approach to other
restless nationalities or uses excessive force in combating crime,
he will undermine democracy.
</P>
<P>
   As for foreign policy, Putin seems to want a wary friendship
with Washington and its allies, in part to attract Western loans
and investment. He has encouraged a new round of arms reductions
talks with the United States and reactivated Moscow's relations
with NATO, which were curtailed during the war in Kosovo. But Putin
has made clear he will plot an independent course designed to
maintain Russia's role as a great power. The Kremlin is now his to
command. What he does will help determine whether Russia is able to
escape its grim history. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
