u a BC-CHROMOSOME-MAPPING-1S     05-09 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHROMOSOME-MAPPING-1STLEDE-WRITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKTHROUGH ON CHROMOSOME 21, LINKED TO DOWN SYNDROME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: fixes number of chromosomes in 4th graph) 
 
By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) In the latest advance in the Human Genome Project,
scientists have unlocked the genetic code of chromosome 21, the
chromosome associated with Down syndrome and other serious
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough, which involved predicting the identity and
location of the chromosome's genes, is expected to eventually lead
to treatment for Down syndrome, in which affected children are born
with three copies of the chromosome instead of the usual two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us the necessary information from which to sort out
what's going on in biological diseases involving chromosome 21,''
said Katheleen Gardiner, a researcher at the Eleanor Roosevelt
Institute in Denver. ``Once we know what the genes do in their
normal function, we should be able to develop drugs to ameliorate
problems in people with Down's or other disorders.''
</P>
<P>
   Chromosome 21 is the second fully deciphered chromosome _ 22 was
mapped last fall _ in the government-sponsored, international
effort to decode all 46 chromosomes, which constitute the blueprint
of human life. The effort is expected to one day lead to cures for
inherited diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the international consortium behind the project,
which includes Baylor College of Medicine in Houston, said Monday
they're 85 percent finished and on schedule to complete a rough
draft in June. They said the last remaining DNA will flow into
public databases in the next six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gardiner, one of two Americans who joined with German and
Japanese scientists on the Chromosome 21 sequencing assignment,
said if researchers get lucky in understanding how the genes
operate, treatment for Down syndrome could be developed within
years; if not, it is more likely to be at least a decade. She said
Down syndrome currently is too complex a disorder to think in terms
of a cure.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Down syndrome, diseases linked to chromosome 21 include
Alzheimer's, epilepsy, Lou Gehrig's disease (amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis), manic depression and a certain kind of leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Chromosome 21 is the smallest of the 23 pairs of human
chromosomes. In a paper that will appear in Thursday's edition of
the journal Nature, the team researchers estimated that it has 225
genes, far less than the 545 on chromosome 22 and that up to a
third of it contains no genes.
</P>
<P>
   But the 225 genes are located in a complex tangle that will make
unraveling their functions challenging, Gardiner said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the key will be how quickly researchers find and learn
the function of the most important genes. It is unclear, for
example, whether a handful of genes underlies the disorders or
whether the general imbalance from the genes in the extra
chromosome causes the problem. But the decoding of chromosome 21 at
least establishes a catalog of the relevant genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us a toolbox where we have what we need to explore
gene function,'' said Gardiner. ``Once we have that knowledge, we
should be able to modulate gene activity, to adjust it to the
correct level.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardiner also said that the chromosome mapping may shed light on
why people with Down syndrome have a very low rate of breast, lung
and gastrointestinal cancers. She said scientists suspect that an
extra copy of chromosome 21 has tumor-suppressing qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Down syndrome, the most common form of genetically caused mental
retardation, occurs in about one in 700 live births. It can also
cause congenital heart disease and Alzheimer's by age 40.
</P>
<P>
   Because scientists had originally expected chromosomes 21 and 22
to have more genes, the small number they found has led them to
lower the estimated total number of human genes to 40,000 from the
70,000 to 100,000 figure that has historically been believed.
Scientists said that may mean humans are not that different from
the fruit fly, which was fully deciphered in March. It was
estimated to have 13,600 genes.
</P>
<P>
   But a California bioinformatics company called DoubleTwist said
Monday it has downloaded the Human Genome Project's existing data
and, with its own software, already identified about 105,000
probable human genes.
</P>
<P>
   Team researchers said the map of chromosome 21 is 99.7 percent
complete. Technical limitations prevented a complete mapping.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium is in a race with a private rival, Celera Corp.
of Rockville, Md., which is rumored to be about to announce that
it's decoded all the chromosomes. The directors of the consortium's
leading centers said Monday they've decoded 16 million units of DNA
and are now moving into the final phase _ filling in the remaining
gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've finished most of the hard part,'' said Richard Gibbs,
director of Baylor's Human Genome Sequencing Center. ``What we've
done is not perfect, but we're like a steaming juggernaut now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
