r n BC-GAS-PRICES-SFCHRON &LR;      05-09 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LOCKYER SEES NO END TO HIGH GAS PRICES IN CALIFORNIA  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Californians will continue to see price spikes and
consistently high gasoline prices unless the Legislature or
governor act, Attorney General Bill Lockyer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a 70-page report that wrapped up his yearlong investigation
into the state's soaring gasoline prices, Lockyer concluded that
while there are many factors causing the spike, there are few
immediate solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year when he created the task force, Lockyer promised to
take legal action if evidence of price gouging came to light, but
Monday he said that there is still no hard evidence to support
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to tilt at windmills unless it looks like there's
a serious chance to prevail,'' Lockyer said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, California gas prices spiked to nearly 50 cents a
gallon over the national average, and have remained about 20 cents
a gallon or more over the rest of the nation for more than a year,
the task force found.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer said lack of competition is the primary contributor to
the high prices, and that the situation will continue to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 10 years, we will be consuming 2 billion more gallons of
gasoline a year than we currently consume,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we figure out a smart way to both increase the supply
of gas and enhance competition, then the overpricing and the price
spikes that outraged consumers are going to be a regular market
phenomenon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer also blasted oil companies for continuing to increase
their profits during times of short supply. Profit margins rose
from an average of 25 cents to 66 cents in March, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of the oil industry dispute the notion that
high profit margins are what cause high gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``California refiners make no higher a profit than other
others,'' said Anita Mangels, a spokeswoman for the Western States
Petroleum Association, a group that represents oil companies.
``Right now, the global economy is having a heavy impact
nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, oil company profits have soared during the past year
as oil prices climbed to more than $34 a barrel, the highest level
since 1990. Oil prices rose as OPEC nations curbed the amount of
crude they put on the market.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, profits at Exxon Mobil Corp., the world's largest
publicly traded oil company, doubled during the first three months
of this year when compared with the same quarter a year ago. No. 2
Chevron's earnings rose fourfold.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the increase in oil company profits, however, came from
selling crude oil that the companies pumped out of the ground.
Profits from the sale of gasoline have generally not risen as
quickly because oil companies have not had time to fully pass on
the higher oil costs to their gasoline customers.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer is sponsoring several bills with solutions he believes
will help increase the supply of gasoline in California _ and
thereby reduce prices _ but the legislation is facing tough
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   One bill, which would create a strategic oil reserve, has been
held up in the Assembly Utilities and Commerce Committee for the
past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the committee, Assemblyman Rob Wright, D-Los
Angeles, said he does not see that there is a major problem with
gas prices _ and that the emphasis should be just as much on
decreasing demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's too high?'' he said Monday. ``There is no evidence that
the oil companies are price gouging. California has the highest per
capita usage of fuel anywhere in world. There's not that much the
state can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Other pending legislation would study the feasibility of
creating a pipeline to bring gasoline into the state and require
state purchasers to go outside the state to acquire gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has been noticeably silent on the issue, but his
spokesman said he has talked to oil companies and officials in
Washington, D.C., about some of the international causes of rises
in gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a variety of factors that cause the prices,'' said
Davis' spokesman Michael Bustamante. ``The governor has been in
office a little over a year, and in resonably short order has had
those conversations. They should have the opportunity to do the
right thing. Otherwise we may have to take a look at options.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said Davis has not taken a position on the bills
Lockyer is sponsoring. Last year, the governor vetoed $1 million
requested by Lockyer to more thoroughly investigate the gas prices
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the solutions are legislative, Lockyer did say he
is still considering pursuing a civil action accusing oil companies
of excessive profit taking.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that while he personally believes the oil companies
have been ripping off consumers, he is not sure there is enough
evidence to convince a jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take it on unless there is a serious chance
that we will prevail,'' said Lockyer, adding that without a budget
supplement some other program would have to be cut to pursue the
case.
</P>
<P>
   If a jury did find oil companies guilty of taking excessive
profit, they would probably order a disgorgement of the money
through refunds or dramatically reduced prices, Lockyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But oil companies argue that a wide variety of factors
contribute to California's spiking prices, including high taxes and
a special formula of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is essentially an island of petroleum,'' industry
spokeswoman Mangels said. ``We have the cleanest gasoline in the
world, and it costs more.''  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
