u k BC-EDIT-AIR-NYT &LR;      05-09 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S MESSAGE ON CLEAN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 9:
</P>
<P>
   Both houses of the New York state Legislature have approved an
innovative measure aimed at reducing the amount of sulfur dioxide,
the chief cause of acid rain, that drifts into New York from
coal-burning power plants in Midwestern and Southern states. By
itself, the measure may not do much to reduce windblown sulfur
emissions and the acid rain they cause. But New York's effort to
stem this pollution assault from other states sends a timely
message to the White House and to Congress that the federal acid
rain program is not doing the job it was intended to do, and badly
needs strengthening.
</P>
<P>
   One source of New York's troubles is a generally sound piece of
federal legislation, the 1990 Clean Air Act amendments, which
sought to harness market forces to reduce air pollution through a
trading system for pollution allowances. Companies that reduce
their sulfur dioxide emissions below federal requirements can sell
their unused pollution allowances to companies that find it cheaper
to buy such credits than to modernize their facilities. Over all,
the system has been a success, resulting in cleaner air nationwide
while reducing the cost of compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, on a regional basis, there have been serious
glitches. For example, New York utilities, which are relatively
clean because of strict state anti-pollution laws enacted in the
1980's, have done a brisk business selling credits to dirty
Midwestern plants, enabling them to avoid cleaning up.
Unfortunately for the lakes and streams in the Adirondacks, as well
as other ecologically sensitive areas of the state, these
Midwestern plants have returned the favor by sending their
pollution back east on the prevailing winds.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, which Gov. George Pataki is almost certain to
sign, any New York state utility that sells its pollution rights to
dirty, coal-fired power plants in 10 designated Midwestern and
Southern states _ plus the neighboring states of New Jersey,
Maryland, Pennsylvania and Delaware _ would be subject to penalties
that would negate any profit from the sales. Unfortunately,
polluters in the South and Midwest will still be able to buy
credits elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the bill sends an important message. If Congress wishes
to maintain the integrity of the trading system, it will have to
make it work all across the country. The best way to do that is to
tighten the national cap on emissions, which in turn would force
individual plants to lower their emissions. At some point, the
market price for allowances would reach a level where companies
would choose to spend money on actual controls rather than the
credits that give them the right to keep polluting.
</P>
<P>
   There is legislation in Congress that would do just that. A bill
sponsored in the Senate by Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Charles
Schumer, both of New York, and in the House by New York
representatives Sherwood Boehlert and John Sweeney, would require a
nationwide 70 percent cut in sulfur emissions from 1990 levels, as
opposed to the 50 percent cut required by the Clean Air Act. This
week's action in Albany is important symbolically and may yield
modest practical benefits. But the only sure way to get the kind of
reduction needed to protect the Adirondacks is to impose a far
stricter nationwide cap on sulfur emissions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 0055EDT &QL; 
