<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BURST OF EXTERMINATION IDEAS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ After much scientific study, which consisted of
reading some e-mails from readers who vaguely remember reading
scientific magazine articles, I can state conclusively that when
rats and cockroaches eat baking soda, they tend to explode
internally.
<P>
   It all started with a story about how the Conservatory of
Flowers is overrun by cockroaches, and how the staff there let
loose a horde of cockroach-eating gecko lizards.
</P>
<P>
   But one reader said the geckoes would attract rats. Another
reader said you can kill rats by putting out pans of baking soda,
which causes gas, and since rats can't burp, they explode.
</P>
<P>
   Other readers pointed out that cockroaches also react to
ingested baking soda by exploding.
</P>
<P>
   Can cars run on tanks filled with baking-soda-stuffed
cockroaches? The internal-belch engine. If you don't have
cockroaches, this almost makes you want to run out and get some,
doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   But if baking soda is so effective, why bother with the geckos?
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF rats and cockroaches, I can't wait for a resumption
of testimony in Clint Reilly's stop-the-presses lawsuit to halt the
sale of The Chronicle to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   I hear rumors that Hollywood wants to put the trial on TV, call
it ``Newspaper Publishers Say the Darnedest Things.''
</P>
<P>
   How about a bumper sticker: ``Honk if you're a Hearst exec who
didn't bother to read that Tim White e-mail outlining his offer to
sell the Examiner's soul for a warm Willie Brown smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Hearst execs must be like Woody Allen's dad (yes, another
Woody Allen reference!). Woody said he was kidnapped as a child,
the kidnappers sent his father a ransom note, but his father has
bad reading habits. He took the note to bed, read half of it and
fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   WONDER IF the big local movie star _ I'll call her Jane Dough,
even though she looks to be fit as a fiddle in movies and in person
_ knows that Spa Radiance in Pacific Heights is using her name
prominently in its promotional literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jane Dough) can't live without her endermologie treatments
and power peels ...'' crows the Spa Radiance press release.
</P>
<P>
   What is endermologie? The study of cockroach explosions? No.
Says the spa brochure, ``Even the slimmest of the slim can harbor a
secret under her pantyhose _ cellulite! Our Endermologie
Therapeutic Message reduces the appearance of Pillsbury Dough
thighs ... turn that cottage cheese into cheesecake.''
</P>
<P>
   And who doesn't dream of having cheesecake thighs?
</P>
<P>
   As for the power peel: ``Sometimes your skin needs a bit of
cosmetic sand-blasting to remove exhausted skin cells,
discolorations and minor impurities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow, superstar as fixer-upper.
</P>
<P>
   THE NRA HAS kicked in a million bucks to start a firearms-safety
education program for youth.
</P>
<P>
   That's the answer. If kids learn to handle guns safely, it will
cut way down on tragic assault-weapon mishaps among gangbangers on
their way to stickups, robberies and drive-bys.
</P>
<P>
   I DON'T LOVE you, so don't be afraid to download this column.
</P>
<P>
   I do like you a lot, though, and feelings can grow.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Cannata wonders, with the outbreak of the ILOVEYOU virus,
if anyone checked Bill Gates' activities last week. ``He is known
to be the petulant sort and the latest news from the legal front
could have pushed him over the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ultan O Broin was in a Seattle bar just after the Microsoft
breakup judgment and overheard two Microsoft execs discussing the
possibility of half the company moving out of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Exec A: ``San Francisco, South of Market, would be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Exec B: ``Way too expensive for Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Bill: This is San Francisco, amigo! Step into our back
room, we'll cut you a sweet deal.
</P>
<P>
   SAW ``GLADIATOR'' and now I'm afraid to shave or run through the
house carrying a pair of scissors.
</P>
<P>
   So many severed heads and human shish kebabs! What combat!
Picture NHL hockey without pucks, goals, officials or surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as violent as exploding cockroaches, but still messy.
It was as gruesome as Frank Gifford's self-flogging on that TV
interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   The scene where bad guys roar into the arena on speeding
chariots and slaughter innocent gladiators may have been inspired
by the red-light runners at Fifth and Mission.
</P>
<P>
   I was sorry to see that they cut the scene where Al Davis, owner
of the Gladiators, sues the city of Rome for a trillion drachma
because there are four empty seats in the arena.
</P>
<P>
   The major combat takes place in the Roman Colosseum, which I saw
in person a few years ago. It's so different in the movie. I love
what they've done with the place.
</P>
<P>
   We forget how primitive civilization was back then. A stadium
packed with 50,000 people and not one billboard, advertisement or
giant pop bottle. In the crowd scenes, I didn't see any of those
foam ``We're No. 1'' fingers. And the gladiators didn't wear Nike
sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Sport was pure back then. If you had gladiator combat now, even
dead guys would qualify for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously: Good movie. I give it two severed thumbs up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
