<HEADLINE>
DISARCINA RETURNS TO LINEUP, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Shortstop Gary DiSarcina returned to the
Angels lineup Monday for the first time in six days after resting a
sore throwing shoulder. The question is for how long?
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina is suffering from the same type of shoulder stiffness
that bothered him during the final two months of last season.
</P>
<P>
   If he's once again comfortable, he didn't look like it Monday,
twice lollipopping throws in the third inning that landed 10 to 15
feet short of first baseman Mo Vaughn. DiSarcina made two similar
throws in Baltimore last Tuesday, which led to him taking the rest
of the week off.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia said before Monday night's game
that the Angels' medical staff, including Dr. Lewis Yocum, had
examined DiSarcina and that he had ``confidence they've targeted
what the problem is. Obviously we'll watch it very closely.
(DiSarcina's previous problems) raises the level of concern a
little, but with proper treatment and maintenance, he should be
able to play through (any discomfort).''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels record is roughly the same with DiSarcina in the
lineup (6-6) as it is without him (10-11), but they clearly aren't
the same team. He's their most reliable infielder defensively and
he entered Monday's game batting .361.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina doubled to drive in two runs in his first at-bat
Monday and his perfectly placed, two-out, hit-and-run single in the
fourth led to another run.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we might monitor it a little bit,'' Scioscia
said of his shortstop's workload. ``But this guy is such a vital
part of the ballclub, we want him out there as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   INJURIES ELSEWHERE: Tim Belcher's recovery from offseason elbow
surgery took another turn for the worse Monday when an MRI revealed
that right-handed pitcher has inflammation in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were hopeful that Belcher, who underwent elbow
surgery in November, would be ready to join the team at the
beginning of this month. But Belcher experienced soreness after his
last minor-league rehabilitation start April 25 and has twice been
scratched from scheduled rehab appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials, in making the announcement Monday night, said
the inflammation is not related to the surgery and that Belcher
won't throw again until it subsides.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Dickson, another pitcher on the mend, threw in the bullpen
before Monday night's game. He is due to come off the 15-day
disabled list Saturday after straining a right hip flexor muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Mercker, who threw five scoreless innings Saturday against
Seattle, will again take Dickson's place in the rotation and pitch
Thursday against Texas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
