<HEADER>
A9716 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-EBAY-PAINTING-SFCHRON     05-09 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-PAINTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE AUCTION OF POTENTIAL DIEBENKORN HAS ART WORLD ABUZZ
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JESSE HAMLIN and CHUCK SQUATRIGLIA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  A ``wild abstract painting,'' initially offered for 25 cents on
a popular online auction site, has for days had art lovers around
the world betting fantastic sums in hopes that it's a lost
masterpiece worth millions.
<P>
   The top bid was placed late Monday by a Dutch art aficionado
willing to shell out $135,805, sight unseen, for a painting that
may _ or may not _ be a 1952 abstraction by the late Bay Area
artist Richard Diebenkorn.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, which looks something like a landscape, was offered
for sale on eBay by a California man known only as ``golfpoorly''
who also unloaded a ball of twine, an uninflated basketball, a
voodoo mask and other junk for $43.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got this big abstract art painting at a garage sale in
Berkeley (Calif.) ... back in my bachelor days,'' golfpoorly wrote
in his description of the piece. ``Then I got married, and my wife
has never let me keep it in the house. She says it looks like it
was done by a nutcase.''
</P>
<P>
   That nutcase may be Diebenkorn, the late master who blossomed in
the Bay Area Figurative school of the 1950s. Nowhere in his
description did golfpoorly, who reportedly lives in Sacramento and
could not be reached for comment, call the work a Diebenkorn, but
art experts said the piece bears many of the artist's hallmarks.
</P>
<P>
   The painting's mysterious heritage wasn't enough to dissuade Rob
Keereweer of the Netherlands from ponying up the top bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need time to explain to my wife why I am bidding so much
money on a painting that I have not seen in the flesh,'' Keereweer
wrote in an email to the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Keereweer thought he was bidding on a
Diebenkorn. But if the picture is the work of the late master, it
could be worth millions, according art dealers. A 1959 Diebenkorn
painting called ``Horizon: Ocean Park'' sold at Sotheby's for $3.9
million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Art experts said Golfpoorly's piece contains elements of the
abstract expressionist mode Diebenkorn was working in 1952 as a
graduate student at the University of New Mexico in Albequrque. And
the untitled work is signed RD, the way Diebenkorn, who died in
1993 in Berkeley at 71, typically signed his paintings. But whether
it's the real deal is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't say whether it's by him or not,'' said Diebenkorn's
daughter, Gretchen Grant of Berkeley. ``It's a picture (the family)
has never seen before. Nobody has seen it in the flesh; it's only a
photograph on the Internet. It's impossible to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Diebenkorn's family doesn't recall the painting, he
``was a very private painter,'' who created some works they never
saw, Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things surfaced during his lifetime that he had forgotten
about - and maybe in a couple of cases wasn't thrilled about -but
he had to say they were his,'' Grant said. ``One just doesn't know
without him here. I won't even venture a guess. It could be made
out of the wrong kind of materials. There's not enough
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Diebenkorn painted a series of abstract works during the early
1950s in successive locations for which the pieces are named _
Albuquerque, N.M., Urbana, Ill., and Berkeley. The Berkeley series
began around 1953, and art experts said an unknown 1952 work is
possible. They also said the colors in golfpoorly's painting _
predominantly orange, red and green _ match those Diebenkorn used
in the Berkeley series.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the Berkeley series have fetched as much as $1.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   The painting ``has some elements of landscape that fit what he
was doing in 1952,'' said San Francsico art dealer Kim
Eagles-Smith, who has sold several Diebenkorns. ``But based on
looking at it over the Internet, I have serious doubts whether it's
a Diebenkorn. You can't get any sense of the subtlety of the color,
which is really important. There's very little information.
</P>
<P>
   The painting is, according to golfpoorly's description, 2 feet
11 inches by 3 feet 11 inches. It has a small hole, the result of
an run-in with a child's Big Wheel tricycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be easy to fix with duct tape,'' golfpoorly wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that a Diebenkorn was being sold for a song brought
95 bids from people looking for a bargain. The top bid is among the
highest offered in an online art auction, though it is short of the
$168,000 paid for a 1959 watercolor by Lucio Fontana sold on
artnet.com last year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, golfpoorly's painting could just as easily be a
paint-by-numbers job by someone with the same initials as
Diebenkorn. Online auctions are strictly ``buyer beware''
operations, and eBay _ which has seen people auction body organs,
newborn babies and Elian Gonzales' raft _ doesn't vouch for the
authenticity of items listed for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either a Diebenkorn or somebody has gone to a great deal
of trouble to make it look like one,'' Eagles-Smith said. ``It's
like rolling the dice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
