r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-     05-09 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE OUT FOR A MONTH, AT LEAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Devon White was able to lift his left arm above his
head for the first time since he partially tore the rotator cuff in
his shoulder. But even if all goes well with his rehabilitation, a
return remains a month away.
</P>
<P>
   White still has inflammation in the shoulder, and he's yet to
begin exercises designed to build the muscle strength around the
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it'll be that long,'' Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone said. ``I figured three weeks to a month just because
he had surgery on the shoulder in the offseason. We're going to be
very cautious with it. We're going to err on the side of caution.
We'll take that approach.''
</P>
<P>
   There remains uncertainty as to whether White will need surgery.
The Dodgers are waiting for the rehab to be completed before making
a decision.
</P>
<P>
   White, on the 15-day disabled list, said he knows the process of
recovery is going to be slow, and he admitted a month away from
playing is realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my limitations of how far I can push it,'' White said.
``When I get to the point to hitting off a tee, that's big
progress. Why have surgery when you know you can strengthen the
muscles around (the shoulder)? If it's not the throwing shoulder,
then you're not going to damage it more.''
</P>
<P>
   With White out, Todd Hollandsworth will get the majority of the
starts in center field. But for the first time in five games since
White hurt the shoulder trying to make a diving catch,
Hollandsworth wasn't in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, F.P. Santangelo made his third start of the season
Monday against Arizona left-hander Omar Daal, and Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said he plans to get the versatile Santangelo more
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need F.P. to start feeling good offensively,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo was expected to be a major contributor, but he's been
relegated to fifth outfielder and used mostly as a late-inning
substitute. He had one hit in 20 at-bats entering the game.
</P>
<P>
   MILLS MALAISE: If the Dodgers make a trade, they're going to
want to attach right-handed reliever Alan Mills to the deal because
he is owed $5.25 million through the 2001 season, baseball sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mills' market value is extremely limited because he's
performing so poorly. He's been relegated to a mop-up role in the
bullpen, and working his way out of the funk could take some time.
</P>
<P>
   Mills is 0-1 with a 5.93 ERA, and opponents are hitting .345
against him. Pitching coach Claude Osteen said he's thinking about
setting up a program in which Mills throws five minutes every day,
or every other day, before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really trying to whip this syndrome he's in,'' Osteen
said. ``Either the hitters are picking up the ball ... they don't
swing at any of his (nasty) sliders. They let him bury himself in
the count. It's got to have something to do with the way they're
seeing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows what role he's in right now, and it's not a pleasant
role.''
</P>
<P>
   FUNDING IN FLORIDA: A bill that would provide $7 million to the
city of Vero Beach and Indian River County in their efforts to keep
the Dodgers in Dodgertown for the long haul is now on Gov. Jeb
Bush's desk. It passed through the Senate on Friday, and Bush has
30 days to decide what to do with it. Lawmakers in Florida believe
he will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's enticing to Florida, but we owe it to Las Vegas and we
owe it to ourselves to look at every option,'' Dodgers senior vice
president of communications Derrick Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Coming off a rehab appearance in Single-A San
Bernardino on Friday, right-hander Gregg Olson experienced
tightness in his right biceps and his time for a return has been
pushed back again. Instead of making another rehab appearance,
Olson is with the team and will throw bullpen sessions until he's
pain-free. He's been on the disabled list with a pinched nerve in
his right forearm since the first week of the season. ...
Right-hander Mike Fetters' inflamed right elbow is progressing, but
he's still not healthy enough to pitch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
