<HEADER>
A9720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-L.A.-POLICE-NYT &LR;      05-09 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES TO WORK WITH U.S. ON POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Adding new drama to a growing police corruption
scandal here, police and city officials agreed on Monday with the
nation's top civil rights enforcement officer to begin negotiations
about long-sought changes in police training and procedures in an
effort to avert a federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lann Lee, the acting assistant attorney general for civil
rights, briefed local officials on the results of the Justice
Department's four-year investigation into allegations of abusive
behavior and racial discrimination by Los Angeles officers.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said the inquiry found there was enough evidence of civil
rights violations to file a ``pattern and practice discrimination''
suit contending systemic failings. Such a suit could give the
federal government final say over major policies of the Los Angeles
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour meeting, Lee issued a statement saying the
Justice Department was ``willing to defer filing suit to allow the
city the opportunity to work toward a voluntary settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the city had accepted that offer to begin discussing a
resolution of the matter and had agreed to schedule a meeting next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Such a lawsuit would be a huge political and legal black eye for
the leadership of the nation's second largest city, which is
already reeling from charges of brutality, corruption and evidence
fabrication that have led to the dismissal or suspension of some 30
officers and the overturning of more than 80 convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The case became public after a former police officer confessed
to handcuffing and shooting an unarmed gang member, then planting a
gun near his paralyzed body.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and local officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Lee had arrived in Los Angeles with a letter outlining the
department's findings. One possible outcome, the officials said,
would be for Los Angeles to promise a series of changes, in the
form of a consent decree similar to those the Justice Department
has already reached with police departments in Pittsburgh and
Steubenville, Ohio, and with the New Jersey State Police, where the
aim was to bar racial profiling in traffic stops by troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles would be the biggest city to come under such direct
federal scrutiny, though the U.S. Attorney's office in Brooklyn has
amassed what officials call evidence of systemwide problems in the
New York Police Department's handling of brutality complaints, and
is pressing New York for changes with the threat of a similar suit.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said that Lee told them of the meeting only on
Friday, and that it had been arranged with such apparent haste that
Mayor Richard J. Riordan, a Republican, was not even in town. The
city attorney, chief of police, the president of the civilian
police commission and representatives of Riordan did attend the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has conducted its inquiry since 1996,
centering on excessive use of force by officers, under a 1994
federal law that authorized federal prosecutors to go to court to
seek changes in the operations of local departments.
</P>
<P>
   It was inspired by a tumultuous period here that saw the beating
of a black motorist, Rodney King, the subsequent acquittal of
police officers charged in the case and the resulting riots that
tore the city apart in 1992. In the wake of the King case, a
blue-ribbon commission recommended a host of changes in department
policy, including a new system for tracking ``problem'' officers
who amassed large numbers of misconduct complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department allocated money to help finance the
system, but in recent months it has become clear that efforts to
establish it fell victim to bureaucratic errors, infuriating
Justice officials.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, last fall, the police and local district attorney
made public their own sweeping investigations into contentions of
evidence-tampering, false testimony and brutality among officers in
the gritty Rampart division on the western edge of downtown, in the
city's worst corruption case in half a century. As that inquiry has
grown, it has led to bitter infighting between Police Chief Bernard
Parks and District Attorney Gil Garcetti, with Riordan at one point
reduced to accusing them of behaving like children.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's investigation had failed to uncover the
Rampart case, which local officials here said left the federal
government feeling pressure to step up its inquiry. In March, Lee
told local officials that the department was ratcheting up its
civil rights investigation. But according to one city official, Lee
said then that the federal government had ``no interest in running
the department,'' though the Justice Department had a ``role to
play'' in helping introduce reforms that had worked in other police
departments around the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKIES-ASTROS-HN     05-09 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
There was a paper trail of evidence to suggest Monday's Enron Field
meeting of the Astros and Colorado Rockies would produce the
offensive fireworks we have become accustomed to seeing on the
other side of the tracks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What else should you expect when two of the worst pitching
staffs in baseball convene at one of the most hitter-friendly yards
in the league? Certainly not what transpired Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Astacio won a battle of the arms with Chris Holt, pitching
the Rockies to a 3-1 victory before the smallest crowd to watch a
game at Enron Field. The paid crowd of 33,195 watched Astacio drive
the Astros silly with a three-hitter that offered further proof
Enron Field is not immune to well-pitched games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro and Chris both pitched good games,'' Astros first
baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``If that can bring some confidence to
our pitching staff, then maybe something positive can come out of
this loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The four total runs made for the lowest-scoring game at the
Astros' new ballpark. It also broke a string of four consecutive
games when the winning team at Enron Field scored at least 10 runs.
The Rockies' winning score was the lowest at Enron since the
Phillies beat the Astros 3-2 on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three runs usually won't hold up in this ballpark,'' Holt
said. ``You have to tip your hat to Astacio.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker tweaked the lineup and readjusted the
defensive alignment prior to the game in hopes of jump-starting his
struggling club. But considering how good Astacio was, Dierker
might have to wait another day to evaluate the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Astacio struck out 10 batters and allowed only two runners to
reach scoring position. The performance was a clinic on changing
speeds, mixing pitch selections and locating pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the best game we've had pitched against us
this season,'' Bagwell said. ``Pedro had everything going. He had a
good breaking ball, and he certainly had his velocity. Obviously we
wanted to get more hits than we did, but the (opposing pitcher) has
some control over that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can hold Mother Nature partially responsible for this
one. Astacio was scheduled to pitch Sunday in San Francisco, but a
rainout pushed him back to Monday _ much to the Astros' chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made that breaking ball look like a hittable pitch, and it
really wasn't,'' Astros left fielder Lance Berkman said.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's performance was sufficient to win most games, but he
happened to be unlucky enough to draw Astacio as his mound
opponent. The Astros righthander, who has a 2.82 ERA over his last
three starts, allowed three runs (all in the first three innings)
on six hits in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the ballgame when I left, and as a pitcher that's
all you can ask for,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Yorkis Perez, Jay Powell and Joe Slusarski combined for 1
scoreless innings in relief.
</P>
<P>
   Astacio ranks among the National League leaders in run support,
but he didn't need much Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies had gone 21 innings without scoring before they hit
town, but it took only two innings to snap that spell Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-up, three-down inning in the first, Holt walked
the leadoff hitter, setting up Todd Helton's two-run homer off the
left-field foul pole _ 315 feet away from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Helton leads the NL with 34 RBIs, and his 10 home runs also rank
among the league leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty cheap,'' Holt said of Helton's opposite-field
homer. ``If that pole had been 316 feet away, the ball goes foul.
But it wasn't a good pitch on my part. I got a fastball up; he hit
it and got lucky. A few more inches and that ball is going foul.''
</P>
<P>
   But when a team is struggling like the Astros are _ five losses
in their last seven games and 14 in their last 21 _ the breaks are
few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies pushed the lead to 3-0 in the third when Mike
Lansing doubled and scored on Jeff Cirillo's fly ball into the
no-man's land in short center field.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Craig Biggio got a glove on the ball but couldn't
make the catch, drawing an error. Center fielder Richard Hidalgo
was able to throw to shortstop Bill Spiers for a force play at
second as Lansing scored.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo put the Astros on the scoreboard with his team-leading
10th home run, a bases-empty monster shot that landed on the
railroad tracks atop the left-center-field wall and bounced onto
Crawford Street, leading off the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo has six homers and 12 RBIs in the Astros' last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Astacio pitched four hitless innings prior to Hidalgo's homer,
and Spiers' bloop single in the eighth and Hidalgo's ninth-inning
hit off Cirillo's glove at third base were the Astros' only other
hits.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9728 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-WARNER-TRIBUTE-LADN     05-09 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-TRIBUTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S EISNER A NO-SHOW AT TIME WARNER CHIEF'S BASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE CARNEY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Despite their well-publicized corporate
feud, Walt Disney Co. boss Michael Eisner honored Time Warner chief
Gerald Levin at a black-tie dinner Monday night _ but he canceled a
personal appearance and sent a videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The no-show by Eisner, co-chairman of the Larry King Cardiac
Foundation benefit at the Regent Beverly Wilshire, and the feud
between Disney and Time Warner over cable broadcast rights set an
unusual backdrop to the gala.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, he's honoring Jeffrey Katzenberg,'' comedian Al
Franken quipped, in reference to Eisner's public dispute with
another media mogul, the K in DreamWorks SKG, who previously worked
for Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's giving him an organ donor card.''
</P>
<P>
   King introduced the video, saying, ``We have Michael Eisner on
tape, if Time Warner will let us show it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the video Eisner congratulated Levin on the honor, saying,
``I'm sorry that my own stress-filled life, as you can relate to
Gerry, has taken me to the East Coast when I'd rather be on the
West Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Levin said, ``You know what I'm doing when this
evening is over _ I'm going to Disney World.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin was diplomatic about the news that Eisner could not attend
the dinner, saying he was sure last week's dispute, in which Time
Warner Cable cut off the broadcast of Disney's ABC network for 39
hours, wasn't responsible for Eisner canceling his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael actually is a good friend I've known for many years. I
was looking forward to seeing him,'' Levin said. ``But no, there's
no connection to current discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner wasn't the only no-show. The event's other co-chairwoman
_ former first lady Nancy Reagan _ also couldn't attend, according
to King Foundation spokeswoman Linda Roth, because she stayed home
with former President Reagan, who is suffering from Alzheimer's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the corporate rivals was to be the centerpiece to
a testimonial dinner featuring other odd pairings _ conservative
columnist Arianna Huffington sharing the stage with Franken, the
left-leaning comedian, and feminist attorney Gloria Allred sampling
her dinner not far from Hustler publisher Larry Flynt.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,000-a-plate dinner raised money for the King Foundation,
which helps fund cardiac operations for patients who either can't
afford them or have inadequate insurance to pay for the lifesaving
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   King, whose CNN network is a division of Time Warner, created
the foundation in 1988 after he had quintuple bypass heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner pulled the plug on ABC's signal for a day-and-a-half
last week in a dispute over how much Time Warner would pay Disney
for the right to carry its cable programming. By law, the cable
company must carry the local affiliate, KABC (Channel 7), for free.
</P>
<P>
   The spat between the corporate behemoths went embarrassingly
public at 12:01 a.m. May 1, when ABC transmissions turned to static
for 3.5 million Time Warner customers nationwide. Shortly,
afterward a vivid blue and yellow slide appeared, in which Time
Warner told its subscribers to blame its rival: ``Disney has taken
ABC away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   And the bitterest pill for ABC was that the shutoff came during
a ratings sweeps period, when advertising rates are determined, and
when ABC had a chance to be the highest-rated TV network for the
first time in five years.
</P>
<P>
   After a 39-hour staring contest, Time Warner blinked when its
officials saw the fight was giving their company a black eye and
public opinion turned against them. They reached an agreement on
the morning of May 2 to extend negotiations between the two, and
ABC was coursing through the cables once again. The next day, the
Federal Communications Commission ruled that Time Warner had broken
the law by taking ABC off the air during a ratings sweeps period.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, speaking earlier Monday at the National Cable Television
Association meeting in New Orleans, continued defending his
company's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law should never have permitted this,'' he said of the
showdown. The system is ``just bad public policy, and we aim to
change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night after Eisner's video, Levin mentioned that he had
been at the New Orleans conference and jokes, ``We auctioned off
two of the Disney Channels while we were there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
