<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9729 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-CHANGES-HN     05-09 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CHANGES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Astros continuing to sputter and the season nearly 20
percent complete, they made a series of changes to their pitching
rotation, batting order and defensive alignment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After the dust settled, the Astros had a new look. Among the
changes:
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima is temporarily out of the starting rotation and will
miss his next scheduled start after going 1-5 with a 9.53 ERA in
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the end of the 1996 season, Craig
Biggio was not in the leadoff spot Monday. Roger Cedeno and Biggio
flip-flopped, with Cedeno hitting first and Biggio moving to No. 2
in the order.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, who has been spotty defensively in center field, was
shifted to right field, trading places with Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Tim Bogar, hitting .135, was told he will not start
for at least this week. Bill Spiers and Russ Johnson will play
short.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Gerry Hunsicker, manager Larry Dierker and the
Astros' coaching staff met Monday to discuss ways to improve the
club. The immediate result was more of the same. The Astros lost
3-1 to Colorado to fall to 12-19 overall and 3-10 at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said the moves were not a sign of panic, but he did
admit he was growing more concerned with the way the club was
performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly alarmed because we haven't put together one good
week,'' said Hunsicker. ``It starts with pitching. If the pitching
doesn't get better, we've got problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker stressed the move involving Lima was not permanent.
Lima, who won 37 games the last two seasons, has allowed 16 home
runs in 39 innings this year. In his last three starts, he has
given up 29 runs and 11 homers in 13 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Astros have a day off Thursday, they will be able to
skip Lima's turn in the rotation. Hunsicker said Lima will make his
next start May 16 in Milwaukee. Lima will be available to pitch out
of the bullpen later this week, but Hunsicker said he would rather
have Lima concentrate on working out his problems with pitching
coach Vern Ruhle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give Jose a chance to take a deep breath and reflect
on what's happened,'' said Hunsicker. ``He can work with Vern and
try to correct some things we've noticed he's doing. Jose took it
well. He knows we're in his corner. Plus, it's not like we're
banishing him to Siberia.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruhle said he and Lima will work on improving Lima's changeup,
his money pitch the last two seasons. Lima's changeup has been up
in the strike zone this season, one of the main reasons for his
inflated ERA and the eye-popping number of home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pitch he's always had success with, and he's been
inconsistent with it,'' said Ruhle. ``Right now, he's probably got
about 15 things going through his head, and I want him to
concentrate on one or two things to get some clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``We need to get him straightened out. He's
obviously in a rut. What we need for him to do better is relatively
easy, but it's been hard for him to do, and that's to throw the
ball overhand more. He's not that far off. We're not giving up on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima said he was not pleased with missing a start, but he
understood why the Astros are skipping him to work out his
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy, but there's nothing I can do about it,'' said
Lima. ``They're trying to help me get going again. Maybe it's a
good idea to step back and take a couple of days to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because I never thought it would come to
this point where I would skip a start, but they can do whatever
they want to do. They're the boss. I hope it helps. I didn't win 21
games (in 1999) by being lucky. Now everyone is turning on me. Not
management, not my teammates, but the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker called the switch involving Biggio and Cedeno ``more of
a psychological move than anything else.'' Cedeno is hitting .210
after going 0-for-4 Monday; Biggio is hitting .252 with one home
run and seven RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think Biggio is the superior leadoff man, and he has
been the best for the past few years,'' said Dierker. ``Both of
them are struggling right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio had been the Astros' leadoff hitter since the start of
the 1997 season, hitting first for 497 consecutive starts before
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a guy (Cedeno) who can steal 80 bases, so
I think it's a good move,'' said Biggio. ``I'm only going to run in
certain situations; Roger's going to run all the time. Whatever is
best for the team, that's all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me hitting leadoff and Roger hitting second is not the reason
we're losing. Hitting leadoff is probably what's best for Roger,
and I know I can handle hitting second because I've done it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said moving Cedeno from center to right was ``not
punishment or a demotion. Right now, we feel our best defensive
outfield has Richard in center field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will have another decision to make when Moises Alou
comes off the disabled list, likely Friday. Alou had been playing
right field before suffering a calf injury. Dierker said he would
talk to Alou and see if Alou wanted to stay in right field or would
be agreeable to playing left. If Alou stays in right, Dierker said,
Cedeno would move to left field.
</P>
<P>
   At shortstop, Bogar was benched after going 10-for-74 in 26
games. He will take extra batting practice during the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, they want me to take some time to get
more confidence in hitting and to get my swing back,'' said Bogar.
``I think it's temporary. Obviously, we're not doing very well as a
team, and some changes needed to be made. There are some big red
flags on the team, and I'm one of them. They're just doing what
they think is best for the team, and I don't have a problem with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``We're going to try to give Bogey a little break
and let him start over. Generally speaking, I prefer to go with
defense at that position, but he's lost right now.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
