<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBA     05-09 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BAD DAY ALL OVER DOOMS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Matt Herges allowed seven earned runs. That's how bad
a night it was for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Until a fourth-inning double by Arizona's Travis Lee, Herges
hadn't given up an earned run this season. He then gave up another,
then two more on a homer by Steve Finley and so on and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers began a 12-game, four-city road trip in the worst
possible way. They were absolutely bamboozled 15-7 by the
first-place Diamondbacks at Back One Ballpark on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona wracked starter Chan Ho Park (3-3) for nine hits and
eight runs, then pelted the previously untouchable Herges for seven
runs. Arizona tied a club record with 20 hits in an nine-inning
game, batted around three times in the first five innings and
flat-out put a whuppin' on the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I missed many pitches,'' said Park, who has a
12.66 ERA at BOB. ``They were swinging the bats good. A great day
for them. I have no idea (what went wrong).''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers yielded season highs in runs and hits for the second
straight night. They allowed 14 runs on 17 hits Sunday to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun,'' Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre said.
``It's not fun getting your (butt) kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   It began in disgusting fashion for the Dodgers as Park regressed
to points of last season. About the only thing that went well for
Park was he didn't walk seven batters, which he did in each of his
last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   The first four Arizona batters reached base and scored, the
final two coming on Lee's double. But the Diamondbacks weren't
finished in the inning. Pitcher Omar Daal had the first of his two
hits to drive in Lee for a 5-0 lead. It was the first of three
times Arizona scored five runs in an inning.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Park's problems, the Dodgers pulled within 5-4 on a
pair of two-run homers. Beltre's came in the second, his third of
the season and first since April 18. In the fourth, Todd Hundley
hit his seventh of the season, and his second right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Park melted again, and this time he didn't survive the inning.
Tony Womack homered to lead off the fourth, Jay Bell doubled and
Luis Gonzalez singled to put runners on the corners. Second baseman
Mark Grudzielanek momentarily stemmed the ambush when he made a
diving stop of Erubiel Durazo's sharp grounder through the middle.
Bell scored, Durazo was out and manager Davey Johnson had seen
enough of Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers starter lasted 31/3 innings, his shortest outing
since St. Louis' Fernando Tatis hit a pair of grand slams in one
inning last season to knock Park out after 22/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of ugly,'' Johnson said. ``Early on, Chan Ho
looked like he couldn't get his fastball where he wanted it and he
couldn't get the curveball over.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges continually said that even though he was off to a
remarkable start in which he hadn't allowed an earned run in his
first 19 innings, his good fortune would eventually even out.
</P>
<P>
   It did, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   Herges did nothing to cool the hot bats of Arizona. The first
four Diamondbacks he faced reached base via hit or walk. By the
time the inning was over, Lee had an RBI double, Andy Fox had a
run-scoring single and the Diamondbacks led 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it would come to an end, but I just wish it hadn't been
(seven) runs against the Diamondbacks, the team leading the
division,'' said Herges, whose ERA went from 0.00 to 3.00. ``The
floodgates were open and I didn't shut them.''
</P>
<P>
   It also brought on another situation. Arizona started seven
left-handers in the lineup and the Dodgers don't have a lefty in
the bullpen. Because of that, Johnson said he would look closer
into Mike Fetters' elbow injury and also think about recalling left
Onan Masaoka from Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you have a situational lefty and a long lefty,''
Johnson said. ``It's the same place we were a couple of months
ago.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
