</P>
<P>
   DELAY-TRADE _ After a bill-signing ceremony in the Oval Office
last month, President Clinton sidled up to an unlikely ally in his
fight to pass a decisive trade bill with China, the
administration's top foreign policy goal. ``We talked about what
each of us has to do and we gave each other some advice,'' said
Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the House majority whip and one of
Clinton's most vitriolic critics on Capitol Hill. With the crucial
vote just over two weeks away, DeLay finds himself in the
improbable role of the president's chief water-carrier and
potential legacy-builder in an all-out battle to grant China
permanent normal trading privileges. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRON-POLICY _ A draft proposal from the Clinton
administration to safeguard national forests from development would
bar building roads across nearly one-quarter of those lands but
would not immediately rule out future logging or off-road vehicle
activity. By Douglas Jehl.
