   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT4) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIGHTMAN-PHYSICS (Undated) _ A physicist-turned-writer looks
back on what he misses about science: the purity. Theoretical
physicists, and many other kinds of scientists, work in a world of
the mind. It is a mathematical world without bodies, without
people, without the vagaries of human emotion. By Alan Lightman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MILKYWAY-COLLIDE (Undated) _ Andromeda and the Milky Way are
speeding toward each other at more than a quarter-million miles per
hour. In three billion years, the two galaxies may slam together
head-on. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Items about Arctic and Antarctic species
being ever so similar; the effects of El Nino; blister beetles'
remarkable survival techniques. By Herny Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ULTRASOUND (Undated) _ Since the '70s, ultrasound has grown
up. Rather than simply glancing at the fetus, doctors today take a
series of measurements: the length of the fetus; the length of the
thigh bone; and the circumferences of the head and abdomen. They
check the four chambers of the heart and the structures of the
kidney and bladder. And now ultrasound is on the verge of yet
another revolution. The latest gadgets, though far from standard
use, create three-dimensional images of the fetus and may be used
to peer deep within the fetal brain, identifying fine points of the
developing anatomy never seen before. By Randi Hutter Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT2,3) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
