<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-SEXSLAVERY-0510-CO     05-09 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-SEXSLAVERY-0510-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PASSES BILL TO CRACK DOWN ON SEXUAL SLAVERY
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid a growing trend of trafficking in women for
forced prostitution, the U.S. House of Representatives voted
Tuesday to step up prosecutions and increase penalties to a maximum
of life in prison for what has become a global sexual slavery
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the legislation, which had languished on Capitol Hill
for several years, gives prosecutors new tools to combat the
problem and gives the U.S. State Department $95 million to prevent
its spreading by warning women in poor countries about the danger.
</P>
<P>
   According to recent CIA estimates, 2 million women and girls
from Asia, Latin America and the former Soviet Union every year are
lured by traffickers by promises of plane tickets and good jobs
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Once these women arrive in wealthier countries, they are kept as
prisoners in brothels and frequently ``bought'' and ``sold.'' Some
50,000 women and girls are thought to be brought into the United
States each year for involuntary prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Trafficking Victims Protection Act, perpetrators would
receive punishment ``commensurate with the penalties for kidnapping
and forcible rape,'' said Rep. Christopher H. Smith, R-N.J., a
chief sponsor of the measure, which passed on a voice vote without
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also offers protection to victims, including an offer
of temporary legal residence in the United States for illegal
immigrants who are willing to cooperate with prosecutors in
pressing charges against the pimps and traffickers. Currently, the
victims are frequently deported and the traffickers are not
punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation will put these offenders behind bars while
protecting the victim,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation has been introduced by a bipartisan effort
in the Senate led by Sens. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., and Sam
Brownback, R-Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Under current laws, prosecutions have been rare, both in the
United States and abroad. Some prosecutors say they have been
hampered by sentences that are too short. In cases brought recently
in Georgia and Florida, most of the penalties were no more than six
years, and some were less than two years.
</P>
<P>
   (Julia Malone's E-mail address is: juliam(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.cia.gov/csi/monograph/women/trafficking.pdf for the CIA
report on sexual slavery, ``Center for the Study of Intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c106:H.R.3244 for text of the
House bill.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
