<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-RESTAURANT-SMELLS-ART     05-09 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-SMELLS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., R.I.)  
 NOSING THE WAY TO THE KITCHEN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few weeks ago, I walked into Al Forno in
Providence, R.I., expecting a good meal. I got something else. I
left the lean, cool evening air and stepped into the restaurant's
foyer.
</P>
<P>
   It felt like I had stepped into another world.
</P>
<P>
   The earthy aromas of burning wood, yeast, roasting chicken and
herbs enveloped me. The restaurant smelled like food, and it
stopped me. I could not think of a single New York restaurant that
smelled so good. Or for that matter, one that smelled like anything
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few decades, aroma, especially in better
restaurants, has slowly disappeared. And now as more ambitious
restaurants open by the minute, an aroma-free environment has
become something of a norm. Powerful new ventilation systems in the
kitchen are partly responsible. But more than anything else, it's
because restaurateurs do not want the scents of food and cooking
swirling around diners, even if they have an open kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally you don't want odors out in the dining room,'' said
Tom Colicchio, the chef at Gramercy Tavern. ``When eating food and
enjoying food, your olfactory senses play a big part,'' he said.
``If you start to smell other things, it gets in the way _ it
detracts from the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crispness'' is the word many restaurateurs and designers use
to describe the kind of air they are after. And to get it, they
avoid absorptive fabrics, opting for gauzy curtains rather than
heavy, dense ones and hard-surfaced floors rather than rugs. Dining
rooms use neutral-smelling chemicals for cleaning, often at night
so any odors fade before the next service. A crisp room may not
evoke home, but it can make all the flavors in a meal easier to
comprehend, as each course announces its arrival to the diner's
nose.
</P>
<P>
   Modern ventilation systems help that along too. Fan-driven
kitchen exhausts have been around since the 1960s, but they have
become increasingly efficient over the years. Now, the fans above
the stoves are so forceful &UR;  &LR; that they pull air from the dining room
through the kitchen, actually creating a small amount of negative
air pressure between the two. Peter Bentel, an owner of Bentel &AMP;
Bentel Architects/Planners in Locust Valley, said that ``with
appropriate engineering, putting smells back into the dining room
is actually difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventilation must be powerful enough to suck airborne grease,
heat and cooking odors up ducts above the tenant spaces in the
building, at which point it is released into the air. With a New
York restaurant like Tabla, that means a 29-story climb. The
velocity of the air in the duct must also be powerful enough to
keep the grease airborne so that it does not stick to the duct and
become a fire hazard. Ideally, said Dominick DePinto, an owner of
Ambrosino, DePinto &AMP; Schmieder Consulting Engineers, a Manhattan
firm that has designed kitchen exhaust systems at the Royalton and
Caroline's Comedy Club, that velocity should be 100 feet of air per
minute.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly the romantic image of the hearth. But it may be why
the city itself has such a varied bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen aromas have changed, too. Before modern ventilation came
along, kitchens were hot, greasy, pungent dens. Jacques Pepin said
that when he was a chef in the 1950s and '60s, aromas distinguished
parts of the kitchen. ``When you went through the different areas,
you knew what people were cooking,'' he said. Cooking then employed
all the senses. Cooks, he said, could tell that a chicken was done
by the way it sounded in the oven. When the fat clarified and it
was nearly done, the sound of it roasting would change. It was said
to sing. Today's sterile, lab-like kitchens, Pepin lamented,
disassociate cooks from the food. Air conditioning cools kitchens
off, and exhausts remove the smell of food.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to enter many dining rooms blindfolded, though, you
would be more likely to guess that you were in a library or a
florist shop. And sometimes this is intentional. Some restaurants
go to great expense to import aromas.
</P>
<P>
   At Chanterelle, arrangements of flowers around the room are like
oversize atomizers. With them, said Karen Waltuck, an owner, they
want to bring an airiness, and a cool, clean quality inside. ``It's
almost a spa feeling,'' she said. ``It should make you relax but
feel pampered.''
</P>
<P>
   At Gramercy Tavern, which was designed by Bentel's firm, the
walls are coated with beeswax and there is a great deal of wood in
the furnishings, all so that there would be a ``wholesome'' aroma.
The intention, Bentel said, was to make diners feel as comfortable
as they would in the home of a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years the Monell Chemical Senses Center in
Philadelphia began studying more explicitly the relationship
between odor and appetite. Fifteen years ago, Dr. Marcia Levin
Pelchat, a sensory psychologist at the center, said taste and smell
were considered the minor senses. Today, scientists think that they
may be much more powerful and have much more influence on mood and
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   An aroma like beeswax, Levin Pelchat said, ``is associated with
craft and nature, and it does smell a little bit like honey, so my
guess would be that it would evoke an impression of naturalness,
the outdoors, or memories of natural things.'' Flowers, she said,
teeter between a good association, if it's mild enough, and a
distraction, like heavy perfume. ``If they evoke the memory of a
garden they can give the same feeling of freshness,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A controversial hypothesis, Levin Pelchat said, is that food
aromas may cause a release of insulin into the bloodstream,
resulting in a drop in blood sugar and possibly feelings of hunger.
Some responses to food, like salivation, are biological. But
reactions to most aromas are believed to be learned responses.
``You have to learn what is a food odor and what isn't, and you
have to learn what odors have to do with Mom and which ones have to
do with Grandmom,'' Levin Pelchat said.
</P>
<P>
   Aroma and memory are undeniably powerful. When I think of the
months I spent in Paris, I do not so much remember images of the
place I lived and the streets I walked. I recall the smells. There
was the sharp winy odor of the cafe in the morning that I noticed
from the street as I passed its open door. When I think of the
bakery where I worked, I think of the yeast and butter, tile and
apples, a confluence so distinct I can taste the pain au levain in
my head and I can smell the cool street air that came in with the
delivery man. Ask me the color of the tile, and my memory fails.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned from Providence, I began paying more attention
to what restaurants smelled like. The most aromatic place I found
was a street cart that offered chicken curry. The further up I went
on the restaurant scale, the more aromas diminished. Small bistros
tended to be heady blurs of herbs, meat and cigarette smoke. Some
had more specific bouquets. A stop at Le Gigot in Greenwich Village
one evening was like walking into a pool of caramelized onions. Woo
Lae Oak in Soho was a dense whiff of beef, vinegar and spices.
Daniel smelled of fabric; and I could smell the gin in my drink.
</P>
<P>
   What formal restaurants want to avoid, Bentel said, are
lingering aromas, which can cling to fabrics. This is often
controlled through design. In the banquet room at Eleven Madison
Park, for instance, metallic curtains were chosen for a glass wall,
so that aromas from one party would not linger to the next.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, chefs do not want to eliminate aroma from the
experience entirely. A few years ago, chefs began serving soup at
the table, ladling it into a warm bowl in front of the diner. It
looked impressive, but it also allowed the aroma of the soup to
blossom right under the diner's nose.
</P>
<P>
   Wylie Dufresne, the chef at 71 Clinton Fresh Food, once worked
at a restaurant in Paris where the chef would put a sprig of dried
thyme on a plate and light it on fire before it was sent out so
that the aroma would fill the dining room. The dish was nothing
more than roasted chicken with mashed potatoes, but, Dufresne said,
the effect could be seen on diners' faces as they followed the
waiter crossing the room like a tennis ball sailing across the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Such control turns the experience of dining into a slow sequence
of condensed sensual frames. The dining room at Peacock Alley,
which is sunk deep in the core of the Waldorf Astoria, is like a
secluded, aroma-free sanctuary. It is so neutral that when, on a
recent visit, the waiter set down a piece of bread on the plate, I
could smell the yeast in it. Subtlety has never seen such extremes.
Every dish thereafter had the same kind of spotlighted entrance.
</P>
<P>
   I had a similar experience at Jean Georges, where the minimalist
room is a perfect expression of that ``crispness.'' It makes a fine
environment for focused wine tasting. And somehow eases the
prospect of eating so many courses.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also something deadening and hollow about it. A
restaurant that does not smell of food or cooking cannot spark and
enliven all the senses the way a restaurant brimming with the
aromas of a kitchen can.
</P>
<P>
   Peasant, a new restaurant in Soho, has no electrical wiring in
its kitchen. All the cooking is done on a wood stove and in a
wood-fired oven in full view from the dining room. A ventilation
duct is also directed into the dining room, piping in garlic and
oil, new brick and young wood. The aromas echo from wall to wall.
With the kitchen showered in natural light from a glass roof, the
place has a soft blue glow and dark shadows. It could be cold and
austere. But the aroma of food gives it warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner is Lombardi's, a 95-year-old pizza shop with
coal-fired ovens. The aroma of the place is like worn leather,
something that can't be fabricated. It always smells the same,
always pleasant, of roasted tomatoes and sweet dough.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants with powerful ventilation systems do not harbor such
complex, aged blends. But many do still smell. And not always good.
While most aromas are sucked out, some linger. At Beacon in
Midtown, a wood-burning oven is the centerpiece of the kitchen. But
wood is not what you smell. When you walk in the door, you first
pass the bar. It smells like stale beer and a college dormitory. In
the back, by the kitchen, there is the aroma of grease. At Blue
Ribbon, a sushi restaurant in Greenwich Village, seaweed and old
fish meet you before you even enter the place.
</P>
<P>
   The aroma of food, in most cases, is pleasurable. It is what
seduces people as they cook. And for many people it is what spells
home. When I arrive at my door in the hallway and smell the cooking
of the woman who lives next to me, she doesn't know it, but it
always makes me feel like I am being welcomed home. Perhaps, as the
Monell scientists suspect, it is all learned. But it took me until
now to appreciate its importance.
</P>
<P>
   My dinner at Al Forno changed me. I can remember how the red
wine we drank smelled of spice and berries. I can still taste the
ricotta tart, redolent of almonds. I was not distracted by the
other aromas. I was embraced by them. They gave the place soul and
a deep, thrumming vitality.
</P>
<P>
   When I got home and took off my coat, I could still smell the
wood and smoke. I couldn't think of a better reminder of the
experience. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
