<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, May 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The spell of spring heat that has gripped much of the Midwest
and Northeast in the past several days will end Wednesday as a cold
front sweeps toward the Eastern seaboard. Thundershowers will
accompany the front as it moves from the west slopes of the
Appalachians early Wednesday to the East coast Wednesday night. A
few potent thunderstorms will erupt in the lingering warmth and
humidity from New York to North Carolina in the afternoon and
evening. Farther east, cool ocean air and patchy light rain will
cling to the east coast of New England. In the wake of the front,
breezes from the northwest will deliver seasonably cool air to the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather with little chance for rain will exacerbate drought
conditions from Texas to the lower Mississippi Valley. Meanwhile,
unseasonably cool air will spread across much of the West.
Scattered showers and mountain snow will linger in the Northwest.
Gusty winds will accompany the cooler air in California and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HEAT WAVE
</P>
<P>
   An official heat wave was declared in parts of the Northeast on
Tuesday where readings climbed to 90 degrees or more for the third
consecutive day. Reaching 90 for three straight days or more was
proposed in 1900 as a universal criterion for a heat wave, but the
definition ignores the typical summer heat in many areas. For
example, the average daily high in Dallas reaches 90 on June 6 and
stays at 90 or above until Sept. 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
