<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN BALLET THEATER: MEMORIES, BALLOONS AND SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It may be hard to believe but American Ballet Theater
is 60 years old, a milestone celebrated at the anniversary gala
that opened the company's two-month season on Monday night. It was
an event that married past and present and looked to the future.
``Variations on a Theme by Haydn,'' a subtle, formal and rich
ballet that Twyla Tharp has set to music by Brahms, received its
New York premiere.
</P>
<P>
   This look toward new creativity was balanced during the evening
at the Metropolitan Opera House by excerpts from the repertory and
some surprise guests, notably Alicia Alonso, the Cuban ballerina
who was one of Ballet Theater's earliest stars in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore, who was honorary chairman of the gala with Vice
President Al Gore (not present), was introduced by Caroline Kennedy
and Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who were introduced at the start
by Hamilton James, chairman of the company's board.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kennedy, Schumer urged strong support for the arts. Gore
offered her variation on the theme, broadening it into an
appreciation of ``the arts as part of our national heritage.''
``Swan Lake,'' in a new staging by Kevin McKenzie, the company's
artistic director, was represented by an excerpt from Act 2 and
started the dancing on the program.
</P>
<P>
   Company alumni made their appearance at the first intermission:
Donald Saddler, Miriam Golden and Annabelle Lyon had all danced at
Ballet Theater's debut in New York on Jan. 11, 1940, and took a
bow. Saddler, a choreographer and director in ballet and on
Broadway, paid tribute to Richard Pleasant, Ballet Theater's
founding director, and to Lucia Chase, the company's founding
patron and later co-director with Oliver Smith from 1945 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks, Alonso said, ``This was the first big classical
company in the United States and it was wonderful, we were all
together.'' Speaking of pioneering years for both the dancers and
the audience, she concluded, ``The most beautiful way to unite
people is through art.''
</P>
<P>
   Unity of a new sort was signaled when McKenzie stepped on stage
at the end of the evening to read a message from Mikhail
Baryshnikov, who withdrew all his productions from the company
after he resigned as its artistic director in 1989. Baryshnikov,
who has kept his distance from the troupe, sent his best wishes
``in honor of Lucia Chase and Oliver Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own remarks, McKenzie said, ``Sixty is too young to be
old and too old to be young.'' By past standards, it was a sober
and simple gala, keeping reminiscences and alumni to the minimum.
Nonetheless there was a festive close in a mass curtain call. Gold
and silver balloons rained down on the entire company and on the
guests, who included the British-born star Frederic Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   Tharp's ballet deserves special attention not only because of
its novelty but also because the rest of the familiar program was
unevenly danced. Terrific is the word for the men, who blended
style, artistry and virtuosity. With a few exceptions the women
were atypically off form.
</P>
<P>
   With 30 dancers, ``Variations on a Theme by Haydn'' is a big
ballet despite its relative brevity. Tharp keeps to the classical
vocabulary more than usual, with only a few quirky weight shifts
playing off ballet's centered positions.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, she has added her own sophisticated dimension to the
music, reflecting its emotional essence and classical form. This is
a ballet that perpetually retracts and expands, swelling into an
intense and frontal advance by the dancers that corresponds to
Brahms' grand finale.
</P>
<P>
   The changing patterns reflect the musical theme's celebrated
structure (AABB) and counterpoint, but there is too much going on
at once to view the ballet as a literal visualization of the score.
</P>
<P>
   Tharp tends to sacrifice details to a larger pattern. But strict
clarity is not the issue. The choreography makes each of the nine
variations an adventure: Each is unpredictable, impelled by the
energy that drives the entire ballet.
</P>
<P>
   It is a plotless work with dance as its subject and yet there
are episodes that imply courtships and a chase scene. The big lifts
are obvious, and the counterpoint in the choreography is present in
the contrasts among the five main couples and two pairs of
soloists, not just in the interaction of the principals and the
ensemble, often divided into units of four or eight pairs.
</P>
<P>
   Santo Loquasto's tunics and tights nonetheless color code the
corps in light green and the principals in tan. Jennifer Tipton's
lighting design is as fine as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Three couples stand out in the beginning, but it isn't long
before Susan Jaffe and Marcelo Gomes stand out as more equal among
equals. Julie Kent with Angel Corella and Paloma Herrera with
Vladimir Malakhov introduce the athletic partnering, and Jaffe
introduces the diamond motif in a lift that will recur. Irina
Dvorovenko and Maxim Belotserkovsky stood out in brief, fast solos
woven into the choreography's texture, and Sandra Brown and Herman
Cornejo darted in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Oksana Konobeyeva and Gennadi Saveliev as well as Ekaterina
Shelkanova with a brilliantly dancing Carlos Molina occupied the
middle ground between the ensemble and the principals. But Corella
and Kent had the stage alone for a playful courtship, full of
slides and swoons. Jaffe and Gomes, whose duets had a flourish, led
the finale, which somehow seemed disconnected from the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Ermanno Florio's conducting nonetheless could not be faulted
during the evening. Corella and Kent flowed elegantly through part
of Act 2 in ``Swan Lake.'' Malakhov and Amanda McKerrow seemed to
be dancing ``Giselle'' instead of George Balanchine's ``Tchaikovsky
Pas de Deux.'' Corella's bravura rightly wowed all in the
``Corsaire'' pas de deux with Jaffe, and Jose Manuel Carreno was
equally magnificent in ``Diana and Acteon'' with Herrera.
</P>
<P>
   Kent and Julio Boca led the finale of ``Theme and Variations,''
and Boca and Alessandra Ferri acted their way lustily through the
bedroom duet from Kenneth MacMillan's ``Manon.'' Nina Ananiashvili
brought down the house with her arm-rippling and idiosyncratic
``Dying Swan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
