<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-SURVEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONTINENTAL AND TWA FLY FRIENDLIER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Continental Airlines ranked highest among major
domestic carriers in overall customer satisfaction for both short
and long flights, according to a new study of consumer attitudes
released Tuesday. Houston-based Continental has finished first or
second in the survey five years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Trans World Airlines (TWA) finished a close second in the survey
of frequent flyers that was compiled by Frequent Flyer Magazine, an
Oakbrook, Ill.-based independent magazine covering the airline
industry, and J.D. Power and Associates, a marketing information
firm in Agoura Hills, Calif., near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines, which finished No. 1 among domestic carriers
in a recent academic study, was a distant third in the Tuesday
survey.
</P>
<P>
   In January the magazine, in a random mailing, sent
questionnaires to 25,500 of its 200,000 subscribers, asking them to
rate the last three flights they had taken. The results from the
6,079 who responded will be published in the magazine's June issue.
</P>
<P>
   The study ranked carriers on nine types of service _ on-time
performance, airport check-in convenience, quality of flight
attendants, size of seats including leg room, quality of boarding
gate personnel, convenience of scheduling flights, interior of the
aircraft including bathrooms and overhead bins, frequent flyer
program and quality of food.
</P>
<P>
   Rankings were determined for long-haul flights of 500 miles or
more and short flights under 500 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on Continental's overall top ranking, Gordon Bethune,
the company's chairman and chief executive officer, said at a news
conference here, ``We've become the most consistent, dependable,
reliable airline because of (our) people.'' And ``we are
competitive in our fares,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   On long flights, Continental ranked first in food service,
aircraft interior and check-in. It finished second in five other
service categories and third in on-time performance.
</P>
<P>
   TWA finished first in on-time performance, seating area,
scheduling and frequent flyer program.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest's flight attendants ranked at the top by a large
margin among survey respondents. Continental's came in second.
</P>
<P>
   On short flights, Continental finished first in six categories _
aircraft interior, food service, check-in, boarding gate staffers,
frequent flyer program and flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   In the flight-attendant category, Southwest tied Continental and
the Dallas-based carrier also had the best on-time performance.
</P>
<P>
   The study found more complaints about service this year than
last year, a result similar to that in the study released April 10
by researchers at Wichita (Kan.) State University and the
University of Nebraska at Omaha. That study showed a 130 percent
jump in airline customer complaints to the Department of
Transportation in 1999 over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Taylor, director of travel services for J.D. Power,
said the industry was ``doing pretty well'' considering the recent
boost in numbers of passengers. For instance, he noted that
Continental flights now are about 75 percent full, compared with 50
to 60 percent a few years ago. He said the increase in passengers
and the resulting jump in the number of flights had also created
more delays.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
