A0185 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-DANCE-ABT-REVIEW-SFCH     05-09 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-ABT-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THE BEST FOR ABT'S 60TH BIRTHDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By OCTAVIO ROCA  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK &LR;   &LR; _ Sometimes miracles happen, and there was certainly
something miraculous about the American Ballet Theatre's 60th
anniversary gala at the Metropolitan Opera House on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia mingled with exuberance, and respect for a glorious
past turned to excitement over a resplendent present. There were
memories recalled with deep affection, but most of all there was
dancing so magical that the future of American dance seemed as
bright and joyful as dance itself.
</P>
<P>
   There were short speeches at the start, including gala
chairwoman Tipper Gore's praise for the melting-pot diversity that
ABT has always boasted. Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the evening's
co-chair, spoke movingly of continuing her late mother's work on
behalf of this ballet troupe. Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., called
ABT ``America's company.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the dancing began with the Act 2 pas de deux from Kevin
McKenzie's new ``Swan Lake,'' with Julie Kent, Angel Corella and
the full corps de ballet. It was a breathtaking glimpse at a
production that is possibly the finest anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Kent's Swan Queen was a majestic, ineffable creature, with
Corella an impetuous Prince Siegfried. ABT's corps were stunning,
assured in their steps and sublime in their eloquent upper bodies.
Best of all, this was no meaningless dance out of context: An
entire emotional world came alive with dance and gestures that
always rang true.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda McKerrow and Vladimir Malakhov followed in George
Balanchine's ``Tchaikovsky Pas de Deux.'' There was immense charm
here, with Malakhov tossing off his pirouettes and almost casually
presenting, caressing and lifting into orbit the playful ballerina.
For her part, McKerrow managed to find the serenity at the heart of
Balanchine's whirlwind. It was a gorgeous sight.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures really rose, though, with the pas de deux from ``Le
Corsaire.'' Corella was the slave Ali, worshiping at Susan Jaffe's
feet. She was a model of Maryinsky  &LR; e &LR; paulement, all opulent line
and generous smiles. He was possessed: Not since Rudolf Nureyev's
prime have I witnessed such demonic speed, such seductive presence.
Corella is an incandescent, electrifying dancer who drove the
audience to a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   The program indicated that ``Theme and Variations'' was next,
but instead the Met's golden curtain parted to reveal Alicia Alonso
alone onstage, and the cheers were deafening. A trio of fellow
alumni from ABT's first season in 1940 _ Annabelle Lyon, Miriam
Golden and Donald Saddler _ had preceded her in a touching tribute
earlier, but it fell to the legendary Alonso to recall the
company's mission, its optimism and sense of adventure, its eternal
youth. ``We were so full of illusions,'' she said. ``We had the
beginnings of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, before the tears and cheers abated at the end of Alonso's
speech, familiar strains of Tchaikovsky rose from the orchestra
pit, and the company appeared in the extended finale from ``Theme
and Variations.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Balanchine ever create a more stirring ballet than this
masterpiece he choreographed for Alonso and Igor Youskevitch at
ABT? The ballet has gained speed over the years but has lost none
of its mesmerizing appeal. It looked stunning Monday night as Julie
Kent and a reckless, brilliant Julio Bocca led an ensemble that
could not be bettered in the world today.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just Act 1. The rest of the gala, save for a big
and unlovely Twyla Tharp ballet, continued with the mix of
exquisite technique and unabashed theatricality that is the mark of
ABT. Paloma Herrera, an unruly treasure of a classical ballerina,
was Diana to Jos &LR; e &LR;  Manuel Carre &LR; n &LR; o's Acteon in Nureyev's staging
of Vaganova's pas de deux. There was delicious spring in her step,
ecstatic musicality in his bravura. This was a ``Diana and Acteon''
that both brought back memories and made one see the dance anew.
</P>
<P>
   Bocca and Alessandra Ferri brought Latin passion and wild
abandon to the Act 1 pas de deux from Kenneth MacMillan's
``Manon.'' Nina Ananiashvili next brought out Michel Fokine's
devastating ``Dying Swan.'' It was very much a Soviet take, though
Ananiashvili's line was softer than Maya Plisetskaya was in this
ballet, and her arms rivaled Natalia Makarova's. Her phrasing was
seamless, her torso eloquent. Most of all, for all the superhuman
technique Ananiashvili showed, hers was a heartbreaking portrayal
of a ravishing creature facing the end.
</P>
<P>
   It was a miscalculation to close the gala with Tharp's
``Variations on a Theme by Haydn,'' a New York premiere but not a
great ballet. Still, McKenzie buoyed spirits by appearing before
the curtain. ABT's dynamic director thanked his predecessors, his
audience, his dancers. He then let the curtain rise on the entire
company. ``How lucky I feel,'' McKenzie said, speaking for ballet
lovers everywhere. It is a lucky age that boasts an American Ballet
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
