<HEADER>
A0186 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-ART-TATE-REVIEW-SFCHR     05-09 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-TATE-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POWERHOUSE OF ART IN LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH BAKER  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON &LR;   &LR; _ ``Danger: 650,000 volts'' reads a sign on the south
side of the Tate Modern, Britain's first true museum of 20th
century art, which opens Friday. That sign gives a fair idea of the
impact this London institution will have, both as architecture and
in its exhibition style.
</P>
<P>
   The colossal structure that houses the Tate Modern has been a
London landmark since it was built as an electrical power station
in 1947 by Giles Gilbert Scott, who is known most as designer of
the classic red British telephone box.
</P>
<P>
   The building is a great, grimy symmetrical hulk on the south
bank of the Thames, minimally striated with brickwork and vertical
windows, a towering square chimney at the center of its north
facade. Its style is best described as brutalist Art Deco.
</P>
<P>
   Turning this relic of heavy industry into a major international
art institution, which it is instantly recognizable as, has taken
five years and more than $220 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a building people knew,'' said Swiss architect Jacques
Herzog, who masterminded its conversion into a museum, ``but with
good reason it was not known as a people building.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the Tate Modern a grand meeting place, not just an
exhibition space, was part of the task given the firm of Herzog &AMP;
de Meuron, which is designing the new M.H. de Young Memorial Museum
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The de Young project is very, very different,'' Herzog said.
``With that lovely park site, it's the most beautiful project on
our drawing board at the moment. The Tate Modern building by
contrast is a tough, urban site that could be approached only by
yielding to its energy and trying to turn that to advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Herzog &AMP; de Meuron has succeeded to a degree that should give
visiting San Franciscans new confidence in the firm's
less-than-popular design for the de Young.
</P>
<P>
   Entrance to the Tate Modern building is down a wide ramp that
descends to the bottom of the Turbine Hall, a gargantuan interior
space _ 500 feet long, 115 feet high _ that housed the generators
of the long-decommissioned powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The industrial character of the architecture is immediately
apparent in a grid-work of massive steel beams, painted charcoal
brown, and high walls of brick, painted putty gray.
</P>
<P>
   Steel truss-work beneath the long skylight overhead, the slot
windows in the end walls and the illuminated ``light boxes'' the
architects have attached to the Turbine Hall's north wall cleanse
the enormous interior's factory-like, almost prison-like air,
rather than deny it.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is a little like looking into Piranesi's famous
etched fantasies of prisons: The imagination is somehow liberated,
despite the forebodings.
</P>
<P>
   The virtue of Herzog &AMP; de Meuron's approach here is its very
lack of preciousness. Steel looks like steel, wood like wood,
concrete like concrete. The wood gallery floors have been coarsely
sanded and left unvarnished. Hardware is minimal and starkly
functional throughout.
</P>
<P>
   The gantry crane that once served the power station remains high
overhead in the Turbine Hall as a tool for moving large-scale
sculpture such as the commissioned works by Louise Bourgeois that
now fill the east end of this space.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois is showing three huge rusted steel towers _ each about
70 feet high _ fitted with giant distorting mirrors and spiral
staircases inside and out. They are places intended as analogies to
the emotional outcome of different styles of mothering.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in view of their prominence, they are the least
convincing facet of the Tate Modern's extensive opening
presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois's one effective piece here is an enormous bronze
spider that looms, seemingly on tiptoe, on the central pedestrian
bridge across the Turbine Hall. Monstrously imposing when one is on
its level, the spider looks almost dainty when viewed from three
levels above, through the transparent wall that divides the
exhibition spaces from the Turbine Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Tate Modern has 84 gallery spaces in its current
configuration. ``Not one of the spaces in the original building was
suitable for use as a gallery,'' Herzog said. ``Every space needed
to be designed.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is divided into seven levels, the top two of which
offer magnificent views of London from within the two-story light
box the architects added to the roof of the building.
</P>
<P>
   By day, the building wears the light box like thick translucent
epaulets. Illuminated at night, the light box frees the building of
some of its mass and remakes the local skyline.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition rooms could not be more cleverly used than in
this opening set of shows. Four suites of galleries display the
Tate's permanent collection of 20th century art to an extent never
possible before. It is a startlingly rich collection, weighted
toward the art of the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than chronology, four themes have dictated the choice and
layout of objects in the yearlong opening presentation. They are
``Landscape, Matter, Environment,'' ``Still Life, Object, Real
Life,'' ``History, Memory, Society'' and ``Nude, Action, Body.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to lose one's thematic place in the network of
galleries. Entering a large roomful of works by Tony Cragg or
Joseph Beuys, for example, one finds the works on view so absorbing
in themselves that their curatorial purpose fades. This is
especially true of the grand, softly lit room displaying Mark
Rothko's somber ``Seagram Building'' mural paintings. But then,
Rothko's work seems never to want contextualizing.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, one roomful of minimal sculpture makes almost as
much sense in ``Still Life, Object, Real Life'' as another does in
``Nude, Action, Body.''
</P>
<P>
   What seem like redundancies or mistaken choices at first glance
almost always turn out to suggest a deeper, initially unnoticed
level of connection.
</P>
<P>
   A room containing three large abstract sculptures by Anthony
Caro makes an improbable but finally convincing hinge between
``Still Life, Object, Real Life'' and ``Landscape, Matter,
Environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're quite consciously trying to move away from the hierarchy
between classic modernism and contemporary work,'' said Tate Modern
director Lars Nittve. ``There has to be some relevance in our
handling of the classic stuff to what artists are doing now and
what life is like now.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening ensemble of exhibitions, capped by a more enigmatic
one titled ``Between Cinema and a Hard Place,'' succeed brilliantly
in productively shaking up even the professional critic's
expectations and prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying both to create a museum of modern art and
rethink what a museum of modern art is,'' said Nittve.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate success of these ambitions is a challenge to other
museums of 20th century and contemporary art around the world, even
New York's Museum of Modern Art, which for so long seemed to define
the 20th century canon.
</P>
<P>
   The only embarrassment of the grand Tate Modern vision is that
the Millennium Bridge connecting the museum with St. Paul's
Cathedral _ the first new Thames bridge since 1894 _ is not
finished. Queen Elizabeth dedicated the fragmentary span Tuesday
just the same.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
