u i BC-AUSTRIA-E.U.-530&AMP;ADD-     05-09 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-E.U.-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME EUROPEAN UNION MEMBERS READY TO EASE SANCTIONS ON AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ At least six of the 15 members of the European
Union have expressed a readiness to work toward suspending
sanctions imposed on Austria, raising hopes here that the measures
may be lifted within the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian officials identified the countries as Spain, Italy,
Ireland, Greece, Finland and Denmark. Hubert Vedrine, the French
foreign minister, confirmed that ``six or seven countries'' now
wanted to ``think over'' the sanctions imposed three months ago in
protest at the inclusion of Joerg Haider's rightist Freedom Party
in the government.
</P>
<P>
   France is not among those countries, and the determination to
set a moral standard for the European Union by making clear that
parties such as Haider's are not welcome in government remains
strong in Paris, Brussels and Berlin. But a less confrontational
approach to Austria now seems apparent.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph widely published here of a smiling Joschka Fischer,
the German foreign minister, holding an umbrella over the Austrian
foreign minister, Benita Ferrero-Waldner, as she stood beside
Vedrine at a European Union meeting on Sunday summed up the change
of mood. Only recently, French and German ministers had shunned
their Austrian counterparts at such gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions, which consist of downgrading relations with
Austria and crimp the activities of Austrian ambassadors, have
prompted heated debate in Europe because they represent an
unprecedented intrusion into the internal affairs of a member
state. Austria was punished despite the fact that Haider's
intermittent revisionist views and his party's anti-immigrant
bigotry have remained at the level of words rather than deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe is listening to us again, and that is the first, and
extremely positive step,'' Ferrero-Waldner, who is a member of the
conservative People's Party, said here Monday. At the same time,
she warned against ``over-optimism'' with respect to lifting the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium, facing its own problems with the rising rightist Vlaams
Blok party, remains the most vehement in its insistence that the
sanctions not be eased until the Freedom Party leaves government,
European Union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Chirac, the French president whom Haider has referred to
as ``a pocket Napoleon,'' is also reluctant to seek a compromise.
The German government of Gerhard Schroeder would certainly not be
the first to take a conciliatory step that might appear to condone
the rise of a rightist party in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 governments that have imposed the sanctions acted
individually but in unison, and it is likely they will continue to
do so. If they do retreat from their position while the Freedom
Party remains in government, they face the prospect that their
decision will be portrayed by Haider as a vindication and a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But maintaining the measures also has a growing price. Internal
opposition to the measures is increasing in some member states,
particularly Germany, and Central European candidates for
membership in the union, traumatized by long subservience to
Moscow, are not happy that a member state's sovereignty has been so
reduced.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Germany, the opposition Christian Democrats, who have been
vehement in their denunciation of the measures, have recently been
joined by some members of Schroeder's coalition partner, the
Greens. Christian Sterzing, a spokesman on foreign affairs for the
Greens, said the measures had been ``too hasty'' and that France
and Belgium had ``overreacted.''
</P>
<P>
   Joschka Fischer, the Green foreign minister, does not share
these views, officials said. But his ministry is deeply divided
over sanctions that were imposed with unusual speed and without any
clear idea of the circumstances in which they might be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Austria's proposal is that the sanctions, which include a
refusal to receive Austrian ambassadors at anything above
``official level,'' could be ``temporarily suspended'' while
international monitors, perhaps drawn from the European Commission,
kept an eye on the government.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said this idea would be studied before a summit
meeting of EU leaders on June 19. But Rudolf Scharping, the German
defense minister, said there was ``no plan'' to lift the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma over the sanctions has been accentuated by the
recent behavior of Haider. After stepping down from the leadership
of his party and adopting a quieter tone for a few weeks, he has
roared back throwing punches left and right. He has called
Schroeder an ``opportunist,'' restated his desire to become
chancellor and vowed to make his party, now the second force in
Austria, ``number one.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same times, party members have sharpened their tones. The
finance minister, Karl-Heinz Grasser, has said that if the
sanctions are maintained beyond the summer, Austria could block
reforms of the European Union needed to prepare the way for the
entry of new members. The party also appears to have persuaded the
coalition government to call a referendum on the sanctions in the
fall if the measures persist.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what such a referendum might achieve beyond
demonstrating that a large majority of Austrians, whatever their
opinion of Haider, think that the sanctions are unfair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
