<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUSSIAN-ANIMATOR-ART-     05-09 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-ANIMATOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANIMATOR'S OSCAR BECOMES A VICTORY FOR RUSSIAN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Russia, Canada, Japan, Calif.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YAROSLAVL, Russia _ When Aleksandr Petrov returned to his home
here from Hollywood last month with an Oscar tucked in his
suitcase, he was almost crushed on the platform at the Yaroslavl
train station by a crowd of friends, fans, television cameras and
flower-wielding officials.
</P>
<P>
   Taken aback, Petrov, a soft-spoken man of 42, referred all
questions to his wife, Natasha. It fell to her to make an obvious
point which, according to reporters present, went something like
this: ``Now you are falling all over us, but where were you before
when we needed you?''
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar ceremonies in March were held the same night that
Vladimir Putin was elected as Russia's second president. So it took
a day or so for the Russian press to turn its attention to Petrov
and his 22-minute film, ``The Old Man and the Sea,'' a strikingly
beautiful adaptation of the Hemingway book, literally hand-painted
on glass, which won the Oscar for best short animated film.
</P>
<P>
   Then the floodgates opened and Petrov was swept up in a backwash
of pent-up emotions as Russians seized on his Oscar as a victory
for a culture, a tradition and a pool of artistic talent that has
managed to survive despite the difficulties and setbacks of the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, thank you,'' said a woman with tears running down
her cheeks, as she clutched Petrov's arm after a special showing of
his films in Moscow at the House of Cinema, the epicenter of the
Russian film world. ``At last someone has shown that we are still
here, still working.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Yaroslavl, brushing the dust off equipment in his
tiny studio at the back of a dilapidated amateur film club, Petrov
is still trying to puzzle out how he ended up as a national hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the eyes of simple people, it is a victory for all of
Russia, something like a prize for football, or a sports prize,''
he said. ``Russia has gone through a long period when its authority
was weakened, and people feel bad about that. That's why any prize,
any victory revives them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me this was all unexpected,'' he went on. ``I accept the
Oscars with irony _ no, that's the wrong word; with understanding.
It is an exceptional prize, but it is not something on a state
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrov's Oscar reflects what is good and bad in Russian culture
today. On the one hand Petrov, widely acknowledged as the world
master of a rare and difficult animation technique and a filmmaker
who has been nominated for an Oscar three times, did finally win
the industry's top award, an honor that has eluded previous
generations of Russian animators.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand he received no financial support, public or
private, in Russia. The film, which took three years to make and
cost an extravagant $2.2 million because of its 70-millimeter Imax
format, was made in Canada, produced by Productions Pascal Blais, a
Montreal company, and sponsored by Japanese backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A prophet without honor in his own land,'' said Yulian F.
Nadezhdin, the cultural affairs reporter for Northern Region, the
main newspaper of Yaroslavl, an ancient Volga River city.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Yaroslavl had never even heard of Petrov, even
though his earlier films _ ``The Cow,'' ``The Mermaid'' and ``The
Dream of a Ridiculous Man'' _ had won awards in Russia. These films
have been shown in a local theater over the years, but the seats
were filled mostly with Petrov's friends. When he returned eight
years ago to the city of his childhood _ he was born in a village
outside of Yaroslavl _ city officials listened coolly to his
requests for assistance and turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it wasn't the right time; the country then was really in
a bad way,'' Petrov said. ``Even the big movie studios were
collapsing, so I can understand the reasoning of the city fathers.
For them, my requests were just empty noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the tune has changed. In Moscow a hesitant and clearly
nervous Petrov was applauded and feted by the capital's cultural
elite at the House of Cinema, introduced triumphantly by Russia's
other Oscar winner, Nikita Mikhalkov (``Burnt by the Sun,'' best
foreign-language film, 1995) and heralded with a telegram from
Putin, then the president-elect.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Petrov's hometown, acknowledging their neglect,
said they would try to help. ``They didn't promise any golden
mountains,'' Petrov said. ``But they said they would support me. We
shall see.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not need much room to make his films, just enough to
paint on backlit plates of glass that are wiped clean after each
painting is committed to film. Trained as a classical artist at the
Voronezh Arts School and later as a filmmaker at a Moscow
institute, Petrov long ago forsook brushes for his own hands: with
a few deft movements of his fingers, thumbs or even the heel of his
palm, he creates faces, hands, legs, trees, sky and the shifting
moods of a Russian lake during the spring thaw or a Caribbean sea
at sunset.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is fluid, lyrical, almost magical. ``It is like
sitting in a museum looking at a painting, and suddenly the
painting tells a story,'' said Bernard Lajoie, the Montreal
producer who decided in 1996 to back Petrov's production of ``The
Old Man and the Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Canadians finance the film, but they decided _
together with their Japanese backers _ to film it in a large format
that they thought would lend itself to the marine scenes that make
up most of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old Man and the Sea,'' scheduled for release in the United
States in September, is the first animated film to be produced for
Imax theaters, an experiment that initially made everyone involved
in the project uneasy. ``I was nervous and my producers were
nervous, although we didn't tell each other until the end,'' Petrov
said. ``I was worried that my fingerprints would show on the
gigantic screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Shooting the film for a large format added to the cost and
complexity of the project; laboratory expenses alone came to
$500,000, Lajoie said. Petrov _ with his wife; his 20-year-old son
and assistant, Dmitri; and his cameraman, Sergei Rechetnikov _
spent two and a half years in Montreal devoting themselves to the
agonizing process of producing the painted film frame by frame.
</P>
<P>
   To ease his task, Petrov's Canadian producers provided the
filmmaker with a specially designed computerized animation stand
that allowed him to see previous frames as he worked. But
otherwise, the rest of the work was done painstakingly by hand,
more than 29,000 frames _ or more accurately, complete paintings _
about 8 to 12 frames for each second of film. The sequencing was
first mapped out in pencil sketches, but the frame-to-frame
continuity is something Petrov kept in his head, or rather, in his
mind's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a very professional approach,'' he said. ``If I
worked for Disney they would have thrown me out a long time ago.
There is no discipline in my approach; I make the changes as I go
along.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
