<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUSSIAN-ANIMATOR-NYT     05-09 0191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-ANIMATOR-NYT </SLUG>
 
YAROSLAVL, Russia: I go along.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an industry addicted to hype and self-publicity, Petrov comes
across as a kind of antihero, all modesty and self-deprecation. At
the Oscars he spoke a few words of English before lapsing
apologetically into Russian. Once back in Russia, he seemed
literally stunned by the press attention and has been loath to use
his sudden celebrity to toot any horn, let alone his own.
</P>
<P>
   His hopes, like his complaints, are low key. He would like to
open a studio for local animators, although he is not sure who
would use it, except perhaps some of the children who attend
classes at the Sea Gull film club. He is taking his time before
committing himself to his next project, but he knows this much:
next time, he wants to stay in Yaroslavl.
</P>
<P>
   When he was working in Canada, some of his friends predicted
that he would end up staying abroad, like so many other Russian
artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to come home,'' he said. ``And I did. That
seems to mean something to people, that I returned because it means
there is something to return to. I hope it was the right
decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
