<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: WINNERS AND LOSERS IN DOT-COM BRANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLISON FASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much has been made of the need for dot-coms to generate
awareness of their names among computer users. Internet companies
are spending billions of dollars online, in print and on television
to establish their brands. Now comes a study that tries to identify
the winners and losers in the big branding struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was conducted in October and released in
mid-April by Greenfield Online, an Internet market research company
based in Wilton, Conn., surveyed about 3,400 computer users. Among
100 Internet names placed before the respondents, Microsoft.com has
the highest ``brand power,'' defined as a combination of rankings
in three categories: brand familiarity, the brand's ability to
affect the Internet landscape and the brand's perceived financial
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Following Microsoft.com in the survey were four well-known
dot-coms. In descending order, they were: Amazon.com, Netscape.com,
AOL.com and eBay.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of branding efforts, it's important to know if a site
is having a personal effect on an Internet user,'' said Mara
Shelby, vice president for client development at Greenfield, adding
that sites perceived by computer users as being fun and frequently
updated are more likely to be visited regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, as Shelby puts it, is to ``keep people coming back for
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The brands ranked No. 6 through 10 on the survey were more of a
mixture of old and new: IBM.com; Barnesandnoble.com; MSN.com, the
Microsoft Network; MSNBC.com; and Hotmail.com.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high overall brand-power rankings for Internet-based
companies, in the category of financial strength, the survey
respondents said they were more likely to invest in traditional
companies that have Web sites or sell products online than in pure
dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   The question the survey asked was, ``Assuming you had the money
to invest and are currently investing, how likely would you be to
invest in each brand at any time, for any reason?'' The only
Internet-based company to rank in the top five was Amazon.com. The
top five were: Microsoft.com, Amazon.com, IBM.com, WalMart.com,
Intel.com and Coke.com. (Intel.com and Coke.com tied for fifth.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have expected more offbeat dot-coms would be up
there,'' Shelby said. Internet-based brands fared better in the
other two categories in the survey. In fact, the same five
companies that topped the overall brand-power rankings were also
deemed the most powerful in familiarity and ability to affect the
Internet environment.
</P>
<P>
   The top five in familiarity were: Amazon.com, Microsoft.com,
AOL.com, Netscape.com and eBay.com. The top five in the other
category were: Microsoft.com, Netscape.com, AOL.com, Amazon.com and
eBay.com.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield sorted the data to prepare rankings of brands that
compete against each other in fields like books, credit cards, fast
food and content aimed at women.
</P>
<P>
   For example, among online booksellers, the Amazon.com brand
ranked highest, followed by Barnesandnoble.com and Borders.com.
</P>
<P>
   For credit card brands, survey respondents listed Visa.com
first, then Mastercard.com and AmericanExpress.com. In fast food,
McDonalds.com beat out Wendys.com, which led BurgerKing.com.
IVillage.com was ahead of Women.com in the women's lifestyle
category.
</P>
<P>
   Tying for the lowest ranking of the 100 brands were Haggle.com,
an online auction site, and Hillspet.com, which offers nutritional
advice and products for dogs and cats. The rest of the finishers on
the bottom were: Petopia.com; Virgin.com; Wingspanbank.com;
Sixdegrees.com; Furniture.com; Peapod.com; Fatbrain.com; and
PG.com, the Web site of Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to just be well known,'' said Mike Mulligan,
chairman and chief executive at Mapquest.com in New York, the Web
site that ranked 20th for overall brand power. ``It's also
important to have a brand that's readily understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a large extent,'' he added, ``your Web site is your
brand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
