<HEADER>
A0196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-WOMEN-GLIDERS-HNS &LR;      05-09 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-GLIDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENIOR CITIZENS TRY NEW HOBBY: HANG GLIDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is poetically appealing that Pat Calvert and
Barbara Sedgley hail from a town called Alta. As in altitude.
</P>
<P>
   A while back they were down at the hair parlor for their regular
Wednesday visit. Calvert was imagining how she might celebrate her
upcoming 75th birthday. Hang gliding, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara said, `Well, I'd like to do it, too,' but I didn't
think she would,'' Calvert recalls as the two old friends stand
atop a ridge of Mount Tamalpais 2,000 feet above Stinson Beach,
Calif. The distant strand would be their landing zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a husband and two sons, and they think we're insane,''
says Sedgley, 74. The pair have driven 150 miles from their homes
in Placer County hill country in hopes that the weather would
permit a takeoff. They had been canceled once by high winds.
</P>
<P>
   Calvert, the widowed mother of three, says one of her sons _
Robin Calvert, an actor living in San Francisco _ had facilitated
their aerial folly by arranging things with the San Francisco Hang
Gliding Center, which offers tandem flight instruction on Mount
Tam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a real good ride,'' she tells chief instructor and
flight coordinator Eric Mies. ``I don't want a grandma ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Mies says customers the ages of Calvert and Sedgley are rather
rare, though he once took up an 83-year-old man who was an
experienced aviator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical age group is the 40s and 50s,'' said Mies. He
figured most younger people can't afford the $175 fee for the 10-
to 12-minute ride.
</P>
<P>
   Mies and fellow instructor Andrew Whitehill set out to choose
their passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take the best-looking girl, and that's hard to decide,''
says Whitehill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which one of you weighs the most?'' asks Mies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why she does, of course,'' quipps Calvert.
</P>
<P>
   Neither woman seems intimidated by the adventure ahead, nor new
to the world of recreational aviation. Sedgley had ridden a hot-air
balloon in Napa and a sailplane north of Reno over Pyramid Lake.
Calvert, too, had gone gliding. Two years ago she soared in a
parasail, pulled by a boat over the waves of the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgley figures that even if something were to go awry, she
wouldn't experience fear in her final moments. She hadn't been
scared when she wrecked her motorcycle 10 years back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flew up and over the handlebars, and that's the last thing I
remember,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehill asks if either woman has had recurring dreams about
flying. Sedgley says she did. Hang gliding is ``like that only much
better,'' he promised. With the help of enthusiastic assistant
Stephan Spano, the women are methodically inserted into their
harnesses. Sedgley, the first to be outfitted, looks like a
rubber-clad gladiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying off a mountain? Why not?'' she says. ``It's better than
sitting around the house. . . . I don't knit. I don't do crochet.
So I go out and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvert, who is being suited up nearby, mutteres, ``I had no
idea Barbara was so adventurous.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitehill assures the women that his 63-year-old mother ``is
going to be jealous. She's been wanting to do this for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mies, who will be flying first with Sedgley, says he didn't know
if she would get a sled ride _ a straight coast to the beach _ or a
bit of a bouncier, longer coast to the coast. It will depend, he
says, on the wind and on how much stunt flying she could endure.
Plenty, it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   The pair make a run down a steep slope and, in very few steps,
are airborne. Lifted by generous winds, they promptly pop upward
and drift out across the green trees and brown grass of Mount Tam's
flanks and hollows. After coasting to a lower altitude, the hang
glider begins to make turns, dips and gentle spins.
</P>
<P>
   Spano, beside himself with the beauty of it all, has a ``When
Harry Met Sally'' moment. ``Oh, he's DOING stuff!'' he exclaimes.
``Oh, he's having FUN! Oh YES! Oh, THAT'S GREAT!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephan, could you help me?'' asks Whitehill, standing alone
and ignored with a hang glider on his back.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Whitehill and Calvert launch themselves into
Marin County airspace. ``Oh wow!,'' she exclaims as they rush away
from the ridge.
</P>
<P>
   In too little time both women are walking off the beach, still
wearing their flight harnesses and delighting in their shared
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful. It was flying like a bird,'' says Calvert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the red-tail hawks flying with us,'' says Sedgley. ``We
soared, and then he took some swoops and he dived. We hit a little
bit of turbulence a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I liked that feeling,'' Calvert replies.
</P>
<P>
   Would they do it again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' says Calvert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do some of the other things first,'' says
Sedgley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skydiving next,'' says Calvert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skydiving and bungee jumping,'' says Sedgley.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to be our age, you don't want to wait too long to
do things,'' says Calvert with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you get to this age and people are dying. People you
know. And you decide to go out and do something that will let you
know you're alive,'' says Sedgley.
</P>
<P>
   Bragging to their friends is one of the payoffs, she says.
``That's what makes you giggle inside,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   As they ride back up the hill, Calvert thanks Mies and Whitehill
for the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll remember this when we're old,'' she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
