<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0199 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MATH-TEACHING10-COX     05-09 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATH-TEACHING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GLENN COMMISSION BEGINS TO DRAFT REPORT
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Commission on Mathematics and Science
Teaching for the 21st Century began Tuesday to sort out suggestions
proposed by experts, advocates and the public on how to improve
teaching of those subjects in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Among the approaches rejected was a tongue-in-cheek proposal
that the final report begin, ``Americans are just too dumb to know
how bad they are'' at science and math.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real vote-getter,'' drawled one of the 32
commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will end up discarding about 30 percent of the
suggestions it has received in the past year, its chairman, John
Glenn, said.
</P>
<P>
   The former astronaut and Democratic senator from Ohio said that
the suggestions formed ``a classic bell-shaped curve,'' in which
moderate suggestions piled up in the middle and about one-third
represented either very liberal or conservative views.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll throw out the extremes and what we're left with are the
common-sense ideas,'' Glenn said. ``Sixty or 70 percent of the
comments have been right on target.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Jim Geringer of Wyoming, a former aerospace
engineer on the Glenn commission who is also chair-elect of the
Education Commission of the States, said he too expects a moderate
document to emerge in the final report, which is due in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our role to gather information and knit it all together,
not to invent math and science education all new,'' Geringer said.
</P>
<P>
   Commission members, who range from teachers to corporate
executives, struggled Tuesday to figure out how they could package
moderate suggestions in a report with enough sizzle to get read.
</P>
<P>
   Holding his hand at belt level, Glenn said, ``When I was a
senator I had a stack of reports on education reforms that was, no
kidding, this high.'' He said an aide would read each report and
give him a one- or two-sentence summary.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next four months the commission hopes to find a way
to sound the alarm about the poor quality of teaching and learning
in science and math and to suggest what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Its members have agreed on their diagnosis. Glenn put it this
way: ``When we see comparison after comparison that shows our
students dropping seriously behind other nations in math and
science, we know that eventually would mean that our people won't
have the best jobs in the world and we'd depend on other nations to
determine our standard of living.''
</P>
<P>
   But they haven't agreed on what to suggest as a cure.
</P>
<P>
   In groping toward a consensus on solutions, the commissioners
explored the benefits and drawbacks of several options this week.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many liked the idea of offering financial
incentives to 1 million teachers _ about a third of the public
school teaching force _ each summer to attend institutes or
academies at which they would study math, science and methods of
teaching those subjects.
</P>
<P>
   But other commissioners said that research shows that a
three-week or five-week summer course doesn't improve teaching
unless a district follows up by giving the teachers time to consult
weekly or even daily with each other during the regular school year
.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those countries where the kids learn more math and science
have national curriculums, but here we have 15,000 school
districts, each with its own curriculum,'' said Glenn. He noted
that his commission cannot issue orders to school boards.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Glenn said, ``One of our biggest challenges will be
convincing school board members to read our report.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Glenn Commission,
www.ed.gov/americacounts/glenn/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
