<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0200 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BRITNEY-SPEARS-MUSIC-     05-09 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITNEY-SPEARS-MUSIC-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITNEY SPEARS FROM SCHOOL GIRL TO COQUETTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Britney Spears is a tease. That's the gist of the title song
from her second album, ``Oops ... I Did It Again,'' due to be
released on Tuesday. After some introductory moans, the song tells
some poor sap that she didn't mean to make him think ``we're more
than just friends''; she temporarily lost her senses, but she
wasn't serious. The song is by no means an apology. It's a
near-boast punched home by the last line of the chorus: ``I'm not
that innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 18-year-old Spears it's also a carefully hedged bet, at
once knowing and deliberately vague. As the current queen of
teen-age pop, she's eager to grow up a little bit, yet she's not
about to alienate fans who are still in grade school. She's taking
her calculated step at a time when, across pop culture, the image
of the teen-age girl is up for grabs, drifting between girlish
innocence and adult desires.
</P>
<P>
   Things have moved fast in the mass-marketed portion of Spears'
adolescence. Her first album, ``... Baby One More Time,'' was
released last January; it ended with her singing ``The Beat Goes
on,'' declaring, ``We still dream of sharing our first kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, she always mentions how close she is to her
mother, with whom she has just collaborated on a book, ``Britney
Spears' Heart to Heart'' (Three Rivers Press/Random House). Sample
gush: ``I wanted to write this book so people could understand what
a special bond we have between us.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the album was shipping 12 million copies and Spears
was logging thousands of miles on tour, she quickly metamorphosed
from the pert parochial-school girl of her first video, ``... Baby
One More Time,'' into a coquette in hot pants and halter tops.
``Oops ...'' is a musical clone of ``... Baby One More Time,'' but
its video clip leaves high school behind. Spears makes her entrance
in three come-hither closeups: her unblinking eye, her glossy lips
and a pan up her torso, from thighs to chest, in a skintight red
suit. The clip ends with her on her back, writhing under the
camera's gaze.
</P>
<P>
   Spears is hoping to smoothly traverse a pop career's equivalent
of puberty: the no-fans'-land between the G-rated love songs of
teenypop and the sexually aware songs that could hold the attention
of an older, more lasting audience. Puberty is tough on everyone,
but in careers based on teenypop, maturation used to be the grim
reaper. Trying to have things both ways, Spears flaunts her body,
then insists she's only posing. In an interview in the current
issue of Rolling Stone, she says: ``I don't want to be part of
someone's `Lolita' thing. It kind of freaks me out.''
</P>
<P>
   If her actions contradict her words, she's not the only one
confused. Right now, there are no clear-cut expectations for a
teen-age girl coming of age. Sexual activity arrives early.
</P>
<P>
   A December 1999 study by the National Center on Addiction and
Substance Abuse at Columbia University found that among
15-year-olds, 38 percent of girls and 45 percent of boys reported
they had engaged in sexual intercourse. For some junior-high-school
students, doctors report, oral sex takes place as casually as a
good-night kiss. Yet young girls, experienced or not, still show
soft hearts; they flock to soft-focus romantic movies and squeal
for the unthreatening blandishments of the Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Pop culture is as divided on girls' roles as any other
indicator. It dispenses a range of images from sticky-sweet to
coyly flirtatious to lethal. Yet the majority of young women's pop
hits, which were once feared as recruiting jingles for vice, are
now far tamer than television and movies.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Spears looks downright prissy by comparison to
television's most vivid teen-age character, Buffy the Vampire
Slayer. Buffy, now a college freshman, is petite but intrepid as
she protects all of humanity from an endless menagerie of demonic
forces. She also has an acknowledged sex life, despite its tendency
to lead to apocalyptic consequences. Sarah Michelle Gellar, who
plays Buffy, turned foul-mouthed for ``Cruel Intentions,'' the
teen-age remake of ``Dangerous Liaisons''; the results were
ludicrous, but the film showed that Hollywood isn't afraid to
portray teen-agers like sleazy adults. In films like ``American
Beauty'' and ``Election,'' Hollywood also shows baby boomers
lusting after high-schoolers; moaning and swiveling, Spears comes
across like Angela Hayes (played by Mena Suvari) in ``American
Beauty.'' She acts like she's been around but in the clinch, she's
still virginal.
</P>
<P>
   Recording companies have been restoring stereotypes from the
1950s and finding that they sell. There's a renewed racial divide;
while young black women like Lil' Kim or Aaliyah are allowed to be
salacious or openly lewd, white ones are, at most, mildly
suggestive (like Christina Aguilera soliciting foreplay in ``Genie
in a Bottle'').
</P>
<P>
   While boys can be as decorous or punky as they choose _ even
N'Sync, on its new album, sings about cybersex _ teen-age girls are
expected to be mannerly again. Recording companies have been
scouring the talent contests, kiddie shows and hinterlands for
girls who'll seem like sisters or pals to their prospective
audience.
</P>
<P>
   They have come up with singers like Hoku, the 18-year-old
daughter of Don Ho, whose hit, ``Another Dumb Blonde,'' is pure
bubblegum gone feisty: she tells a boy who's ``not really
interested in my heart or mind'' that she's seen through him and he
can go find another pushover. Then she spends the rest of her album
promising to give the guy she loves anything he needs.
</P>
<P>
   M2M, the duo of the 15-year-old Marion E. Ravn and the
16-year-old Marit E. Larsen, are no less dulcet but slightly more
revealing. In their native Norway, they used to sing children's
music; on ``Shades of Purple,'' they wrote their own songs (in
English) with some professional help, and their vignettes of puppy
love hint at real junior-high-school ups and downs. They tell a
grabby date, ``Don't say you love me/ You don't even know me'';
they confront a friend who's trying to steal a boyfriend in ``Don't
Mess With My Love''; they reveal insecurity about their looks and
choices in ``Girl of Your Dreams'' and ``Mirror Mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears reveals glimmers of ambition on ``Oops ...'' She and her
producers clearly realized that her tight little voice is in the
same register as Michael Jackson's. Hoping to stir up ancestral
memories of blockbusters, they came up with freeze-dried versions
of the synthesizer orchestras on ``Thriller,'' and Spears clips
words like Jackson. (She has stopped trying to make her voice swoop
like Mariah Carey; that franchise has been taken over by Aguilera.)
Where Spears spent most of her debut album pining for a boyfriend,
``Oops ...'' starts with her acting a little tougher, fending
someone off in the title song, ``Stronger'' and ``Don't Go Knockin'
on My Door.''
</P>
<P>
   The older, more seasoned Spears is chafing _ mildly and with
premeditation _ against the constraints of being a nice girl. She
has a pierced navel now, and a little tattoo, and she talks back to
anyone who'd criticize her new wardrobe. In ``What U See (Is What U
Get),'' she tells someone, ``Now you think I'm wearing too much
makeup and my dress is too tight,'' then concludes, ``I can't be
nobody else and I like the way I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Her remake of the Rolling Stones' ``Satisfaction'' (with a
synthesizer arrangement out of Jackson's ``Billie Jean'') has new
lyrics that make it not an attack on commercialism or a sneer of
adolescent disgust, but the complaints of a picky shopper. ``When a
girl comes on and tells me how tight my skirt should be,'' Spears
chirps, ``she can't tell me who to be/ I've got my own identity.''
</P>
<P>
   With her crisply catchy, hitbound songs, Spears is seizing her
identity the way pop entrepreneurs want her to: as a consumer. She
can choose her skirt length and mascara; she can bump and grind and
pout. The freedom she wants is the freedom to package herself as
both a pop product and an object of desire. She'll have to grow up
some more to realize how many other ways a girl can assert herself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
