<HEADER>
A0203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-NOTES-ART-NYT &LR;      05-09 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 TV NOTES: `FRIENDS' and `X-FILES' RENEWALS; `MILLIONAIRE'; VH1 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With `Friends' Like These . . .
</P>
<P>
   The names have changed on both sides, but the negotiations
between NBC and the stars of its top comedy show are definitely
moving into Yogi Berra territory: deja vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   The network has less than a week to set its fall prime-time
schedule, and every prospective list of shows being drawn up this
week includes one Thursday night headed by ``Friends'' and another
in which that sitcom has gone away.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what NBC was forced to do four Mays ago, when
three co-stars of ``Seinfeld'' were holding out for $1 million an
episode. Now it's the six stars of ``Friends'' who are asking for
that price. The studio making the show is also the same, Warner
Bros., though every program executive from both the network and
studio has changed.
</P>
<P>
   One other factor is the same: NBC knows that even if it does not
conclude a successful negotiation with the stars, ``Friends'' will
not be going to another network. That was the case with
``Seinfeld'' too, because the network had a deal with Jerry
Seinfeld. In this case the network already has a deal with Warner
Bros. that ensures that no other network can buy the show out from
under NBC.
</P>
<P>
   So is there a real risk that ``Friends'' will not be back next
season? Few of those involved in the negotiations seem to think to.
As one senior executive put it, ``Nobody's walking around in a
panic over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees this is all about money, and money does not
usually kill deals when all sides have a vested interest in a
show's continuing. ``Friends,'' if not quite a ``Seinfeld,''
remains the strongest comedy on network television, both in terms
of ratings and critical appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, which had seen its ratings slide this season, clearly needs
the show. And Warner Bros., which would share the salary costs,
wants more episodes because it is making a fortune on syndication.
But perhaps neither network nor studio is desperate enough to pay
each of the six principal cast members $1 million an episode.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and Warner Bros. have reportedly pushed their offer into the
range of $600,000 each (the figure that the three ``Seinfeld''
co-stars ultimately accepted). The ``Friends'' actors, using the
leverage they know they have as the deadline of a new season
schedule draws near, are sticking to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The justification for the stars _ Lisa Kudrow, Courteney
Cox-Arquette, Jennifer Aniston, David Schwimmer, Matthew Perry and
Matt LeBlanc _ is that NBC was willing to play $1 million an
episode two season ago for the stars of ``Mad About You,'' perhaps
the biggest overpayment in television history. That series had one
disastrous season left.
</P>
<P>
   Far from making NBC more willing to pay however, the ``Mad About
You'' deal has left it gun-shy about paying so much. NBC would much
rather cite the ``Seinfeld'' precedent: the stars took the $600,000
an episode, and the show had one more year of huge ratings.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Seinfeld,'' there was some genuine concern from
NBC that a deal might collapse. But in this case the studio and
network seem convinced that the stars, who have not exactly lit up
Hollywood with their film work, cannot possibly turn down more than
$16 million each for a season's work.
</P>
<P>
   One senior executive predicted that the figure would reach
$700,000 each (that translates to a total of $16.8 million for each
actor for a 24-episode season) and that a deal would be reached,
possibly by Friday. NBC officially presents its schedule to
advertisers in New York on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is less clear for that other hit show held up in
negotiations with its star, Fox's ``X-Files.'' David Duchovny is
not holding out simply for money, but he has made clear that he is
less than thrilled about continuing with the show.
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny also has a lawsuit over payment for reruns pending
against Fox, which complicates any deal. Fox is in the same
position as NBC in trying to plan a new schedule without knowing
what to put in on Sunday nights at 9.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome is truly uncertain. The show's other star, Gillian
Anderson, is signed for another year. Duchovny may opt to work only
a partial season.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely outcome now: ``The X-Files'' will be back but
not for a full season. Anderson's character, Scully, may have a
different partner for much of the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Who Wants to Return?
</P>
<P>
   Looking to finish its season with yet another surge, ABC's ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' will stage a contest among past
big-money winners in the final week of the current sweep month.
Winners who took in at least $250,000 will be back in a tournament
starting on May 21. This time each contestant will split his
winnings with a charity.
</P>
<P>
   All three millionaire winners will be back, along with four of
the five who won $500,000. The rest of the spots will be filled
with $250,000 winners.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   For Graying Rock Fans
</P>
<P>
   As people move on with their lives, they tend to cling to the
musical tastes they had around age 30. Even as aging dogs learn new
tricks, they perform them to the same old score.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, VH1 has started a spinoff called VH1 Classic,
which features the videos of musical acts that appeal to an (ahem)
older audience: acts like the Rolling Stones, Michael Bolton and
Bruce Springsteen. The channel, whose debut was on Monday, is
currently available in only the 1 million homes that subscribe to
digital cable services. That number is expected to grow appreciably
in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   John Sykes, VH1's president, said that as popular music has
progressed, there has been less room for these baby-boomer acts on
VH1, which was conceived as a mellower, older sibling to the
brasher and louder MTV. But the definition of ``mellow'' has
changed considerably over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Where VH1 used to feature singers like Smokey Robinson and
Bolton, it is now a regular outlet for Metallica, the heavy-metal
group, and the Red Hot Chili Peppers, who have been known to
perform in the nude, save for strategically placed socks. Meanwhile
MTV is now a haven for the so-called boy bands _ teen-age idol
groups like 'N Sync and the Backstreet Boys _ and the harder, new
rock acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at MTV now, they've had to make room for a lot of
young bands,'' Sykes said. ``So a lot have moved on to VH1's
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Sykes said that VH1 Classic was essentially taking over VH1's
original mission and was intended to serve its original audience,
which, Sykes said, has grown underserved as it has grown gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge audience out there of Americans raised on rock
'n' roll and R&AMP;B who we think are ready and waiting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But can they still dance?
</P>
<P>
   _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
