<HEADLINE>
HOW I CURED MY BOREDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (Eds: Sunny Vanderbeck is chief executive of Data Return, which
runs Web software. ) By SUNNY VANDERBECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm 27, and I spent the first years of my life on a farm outside
Fort Worth, Texas. I've always been curious. One time, when I was
4, I wanted to get into a locked room. So I got a screwdriver and
took the doorknob off.
</P>
<P>
   As I reached third grade, it became clear it was time for me to
go live with my dad. Dads tend to be a little bit more structured,
a little less touchy-feely. Still, school bored me. I'd get
discounted on a paper because I didn't follow the procedure. And
I'd say to the teachers, ``But I got to the answer faster.'' They
didn't care. My attitude was, ``whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy my curiosity, I'd try things out. My freshman year in
high school, I was a member of ROTC. My sophomore year, I had a
mohawk. Later, I got early admission to the University of Texas at
Arlington. There were things I missed, like senior prom, but those
functions never held a lot of interest for me.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did college, it turned out. I remember writing PASCAL
computer programs that told you how much change _ pennies, nickels,
dimes _ you should return after a transaction. I was bored out of
my mind. So, like that Monty Python skit, I started thinking, ``And
now for something completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   I went to talk to the military recruiters. But none of the jobs
looked interesting except counterintelligence, and until you're
pretty senior in counterintelligence, you're basically a gofer. The
next day I realized I wanted to try to become an Airborne Ranger in
the Army. There aren't that many Rangers, and the washout rate is
tremendous. It sounded like an amazing challenge.
</P>
<P>
   After we had learned how to jump out of airplanes, we went into
the Ranger indoctrination program. These are basically three weeks
to see if you really want to be a Ranger or if you thought it
sounded cool. We crawled through the mud in the middle of the
night. We did push-ups until we couldn't push anymore and then
rolled over and did flutter kicks until we couldn't do any more and
then rolled back over and did push-ups.
</P>
<P>
   It was constant, incessant physical, mental and emotional
harassment. I wasn't bored anymore, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Because I had done hunting as a kid, they made me a sniper.
Sometimes we'd get on a plane at dusk, go do something in another
country and be back at dawn. I never shot anyone, though. It was
almost all training exercises. You get this mindset that ``I'm a
Ranger.'' Everything else becomes irrelevant. But by the end of my
time, I would look at my bunkmate and think, ``Is his life worth a
mission that may not affect the quality of life in the United
States?'' I wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   Ranger school prepared me more than anything else for what I do
now _ managing in the controlled chaos of the Internet. If you can
execute a mission under stress and motivate people who are worn
down, then getting a group of people _ who did eat today and did
sleep last night _ aligned around a common vision is not that
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   After the Army, I went back to college, but I dropped out again
to take a job at Microsoft. Then, Microsoft made a hard left to
respond to the Internet. That drove me and two colleagues to start
our company. Our venture capitalists were our American Express and
Visa cards.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft taught us to focus on the long term. Our stock is
worth about a third of what it was in March. But we know we're
building something. A stock price is like climbing up a ladder with
a yo-yo. If you watch the yo-yo, you'll miss the big picture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
