<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ART-1000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE AUCTIONS, EXHIBITS REDEFINE HOW AFICIONADOS APPRECIATE AND
BUY ART
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by ART-HOW TO and ART-WEB SITES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The august auction house Sotheby's is all but giddy with
anticipation at the prospect of putting up for sale one of the 25
surviving first printings of the Declaration of Independence. The
estimated value of this rare bit of parchment is between $4 million
and $6 million dollars, and the auction house has already set its
sights on June 29 as the auction day. But don't expect Sotheby's
Manhattan bidding room to be buzzing with potential buyers.
Instead, the company will conduct the entire sale in pristine
silence via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online, we are about to auction off the single most important
printed piece of paper in the history of the world,'' says David
Redden, vice chairman of Sotheby's. ``I would say that is quite a
significant vote of confidence in the arrival of the Internet to
the art market.''
</P>
<P>
   From New York's largest museums and toniest galleries on Madison
Avenue to the cubbyholes of local art on Main Street, U.S.A., the
Internet has become one of the art market's most important channels
of communication and commerce to a diverse audience of museums,
dealers, collectors, private sellers, teachers, curators and
patrons. Though no one has the temerity to predict that the Net
will replace the physical interaction between artwork and art
admirer, many see it as the art world's fastest-rising lieutenant
in its battle to democratize an elitist field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's thanks to the Internet that art is available to anyone
who can get to a computer,'' says William Bartman, executive
director of Art Resources Transfer, a not-for-profit gallery in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   This past year was crucial in crystallizing the art market's
arrival online, as dozens of Web sites sprang up, covering nearly
all the major players in the art scene. Now it's pro forma that
major museums and galleries, museum shops, art suppliers,
appraisers and auction houses have ``dot-com'' affixed to their
name. Even framers carry the cybertattoo _ FrameYourArt.com, for
example, runs a special giveaway of a $300 ``antique reproduction
serigraph'' just for sampling its site.
</P>
<P>
   The entire gamut, from mass-generated posters to priceless
Picassos, is up for grabs online. Ever since San Diego-based The
Art Cellar Exchange went online in 1994 as the country's first
fine-art brokerage house, a steady flow of paintings, prints,
photographs, drawings and ceramics has been sold through
cyberspace. Now the growth has advanced to warp speed. Visualize
just reported doubling its revenue, number of customers, and pieces
of art sold, all in just a three-month period.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is that for people with money who are
addicted to buying art at galleries or at auction but who might
live in Silicon Valley or someplace where their choices are
limited, the Internet has become their medium,'' says Uta Scharf,
vice president of auction sales of artnet.com. ``And the anonymity
of it doesn't hurt either.''
</P>
<P>
   In this new exploding virtual art market, Web sites mimic
real-life events with their attendant hype. Artnet.com, one of the
more important online art sales and auction sites, staged an
``Icons of the 20th Century'' Net show last fall. Gathering works
from numerous leading galleries, artnet.com put on display iconic
works by Picasso, Rothko, Dali and Warhol, along with pop-cultural
touchstone images of Marilyn Monroe, Muhammad Ali and Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became quite a big candy store for online buyers,'' recalls
Scharf.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no firm has taken advantage of recent technological
breakthroughs in transmission speed as much as the Intel Corp.. The
high-tech chip manufacturer launched ArtMuseum.net, one of the
Net's most true-to-life ``blockbuster'' exhibitions of fine art,
basing its virtual exhibitions on the holdings of three museums:
Amsterdam's Van Gogh, New York's Whitney Museum of American Art,
and San Francisco's Museum of Modern Art. For ArtMuseum.net's ``Van
Gogh's Van Goghs'' 72-painting exhibit, it produced a 3-D effect
that created the illusion of the viewer moving through and around a
Van Gogh work.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every major museum has an Internet presence through its
proprietary Web site. In one of the splashiest endorsements, New
York's Museum of Modern Art and The Tate Gallery in London will
come together to start a commercial e-business. But commercial
transactions are but one need the Net is providing. It's also
serving as a cheap and convenient source of information for
potential museum visitors. The Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth's
Web site, for example, averages 3,700 hits per day and acts as one
of the museum's primary information vehicles to new and old
patrons.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
