<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, May 10 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MCCAIN (Pittsburgh) _ Citing common goals and shared values
that transcended any of the bitterness between them, Sen. John
McCain at last endorsed Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday and pledged
to help the de facto Republican presidential nominee achieve what
he had wanted so badly for himself: a seat behind the desk in the
Oval Office. His announcement, which came immediately on the heels
of a 90-minute private meeting with Bush, heralded a new phase in a
rocky political relationship that went from remarkable amity in
December to extraordinary animosity in March and a tense, delicate
dance of reconciliation over the last month and a half. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: an early version has moved and will be updated.)
</P>
<P>
   MONT-ASBESTOS (Libby, Mont.) _ Libby, Mont., is reeling from the
medical, psychological and financial consequences of a 67-year-old
mining operation, which once provided desperately needed
high-paying jobs here in the vast stretches of northwest Montana.
Although W.R. Grace shut it down in 1990, the mine is being blamed
for scores of cases of respiratory illness and death from exposure
to the tremolite. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-AUCTION (Undated) _ Developments in the bidding on eBay for
a painting many speculate may be by Richard Diebenkorn, a
California painter known for his sublime use of color in abstract
and representational works. Plus a talk with the seller, known on
the Internet as ``golfpoorly.'' By Judith H. Dobrynski.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ After a night of
looting, the abandoned house of Foday Sankoh, the rebel leader
whose whereabouts remained a mystery Tuesday, had been stripped of
almost everything Tuesday morning. Looters had left gaping holes in
the brick walls where air-conditioners had kept out West Africa's
stifling heat, and they had absconded with every piece of
furniture, clothes and item of value. What the looters had chosen
to leave behind was perhaps a suitable metaphor for Sierra Leone's
present sad state. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL (Atlanta) _ Former Gov. Edwin Edwards of
Louisiana, on trial on corruption charges in Baton Rouge, was found
guilty Tuesday on 17 or 26 counts and in four of five riverboat
casino schemes. By Kevin Sack. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IRAN-MISSILES (St. Petersberg, Russia) _ As concerns
mount in the United States and Israel that Iran's secretive missile
and nuclear weapons programs could pose new threats in the region,
the case of Yuri P. Savelyev, a leading Russian missile scientist
who persisted in his efforts to aid the Iranians in the face of
official sanction, illustrates the behind-the-scenes cooperation
between the Russian and American governments to stem the flow of
missile technologies to Iran. But at the same time, it also reveals
the deep-seated resistance within the Russian military and security
establishment against abandoning Russia's ``strategic`` role in
cultivating clients and lucrative contracts for transferring
military science and technology. By Patrick Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BATTLEGROUND (Undated) _ Today the fight is over
digital music, but tomorrow the legal battle over copying
information via the Internet is certain to shift to video and
software. At stake in the coming information war is the power and
perhaps the very business of some of the world's largest media
companies. The software underlying the ability to copy information
via the Internet is evolving rapidly, setting the stage for a much
larger confrontation over the ability to freely and almost
instantly copy any kind of digital information _ music, video,
software or documents _ to any location on the globe. And the new
technology will make it more difficult, perhaps impossible, to stop
the worldwide sharing of data. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT14, and a graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
