<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-ARMENIANS-ART-     05-09 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-ARMENIANS-ART-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
85 YEARS AFTER MASS KILLINGS, TURKISH-ARMENIAN RELATIONS STILL
FESTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELAZIG, Turkey _ Groves of mulberry trees at lakeside resorts
are about all that remains from the days when this region was a
center of Armenian life.
</P>
<P>
   One of the gnarled trees used to stand beside a long-gone
Armenian Orthodox church. Now it shades Tahire Cakirbay, 66, as she
looks out over her fields and shimmering Lake Hazar below.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took the Armenians up there and killed them,'' Cakirbay
said, pointing to a hill above her. ``They dug a hole for the
bodies. My parents told me.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million Armenians lived in what is now eastern
Turkey until their community was shattered in an orgy of ethnic
violence that exploded 85 years ago this spring. Many aspects of
what happened then are still hotly debated, but here where the
killings took place, few people doubt they occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't teach it in school, but if you're interested there
are plenty of ways you can find out,'' said Yasemin Orhan, a native
of Elazig who graduated from the local university last year. ``Many
Armenians were killed. It's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Orhan said she had learned about the killings from her
grandmother. Here in eastern Turkey, the passage of several
generations has not been enough to wipe them from memory.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the country, however, most people know little
about the killings of 1915. Turkish textbooks refer to them only
indirectly. They stress that Armenian militants were rebelling
against the crumbling Ottoman Empire, and discount or ignore the
killing of hundreds of thousands of civilians after the abortive
revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Conflicts over how to deal with this episode have provoked a
worldwide propaganda war between Armenia and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Armenian lobbyists want foreign governments to declare that what
happened in 1915 was genocide. Some Armenian nationalists say that
if Turkey can be forced to concede this, their next step might be
to claim reparations or demand the return of land once owned by
Armenians.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish diplomats resolutely resist these efforts. They assert
that Muslims as well as Christians were killed here in 1915, and
that it is unfair to blame only one side.
</P>
<P>
   To most Turks, the events of 1915 seem distant, but in the
Armenian consciousness, they are a vivid and constant presence.
Awareness of what is simply called ``the genocide'' is acute in
Armenian communities around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Often it is accompanied by fierce anger at Turkey's
recalcitrance.
</P>
<P>
   This anger boiled over into violence during the 1970s and '80s,
when a group calling itself Commandos of the Armenian Genocide
mounted a campaign against representatives of the Turkish
government. It killed Turkish diplomats in the United States and
elsewhere, and bombed targets including the Turkish Airlines
counter at Orly Airport in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the battle has shifted back to the diplomatic arena.
Each spring, foreign leaders issue carefully worded commemorations
of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Last month President Clinton issued a proclamation recalling ``a
great tragedy of the twentieth century: the deportations and
massacres of roughly one and a half million Armenians in the final
years of the Ottoman Empire.'' He did not use the word
``genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year Turkey has greatly improved its relations with
Greece, but there has been little progress with Armenia. The two
countries feud over a variety of political issues, but the wound
that 1915 has cut into the Armenian psyche also plays an emotional
role in keeping them apart.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, some of the first efforts toward
reconciliation between Turks and Armenians have begun. One was a
conference of Turkish, Armenian and American scholars who met at
the University of Chicago to begin a joint inquiry into the events
of 1915.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most difficult paper I have ever written in my
life,'' one of the participants, Selim Deringil, a historian at
Bosporus University in Istanbul, said before presenting his
analysis of Turkish-Armenian relations. ``Venturing into the
Armenian crisis is like wandering into a minefield.''
</P>
<P>
   The scholars who gathered at Chicago plan to meet again. Another
group plans to open a series of conferences later this spring in
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   In a different kind of gesture, seven Turkish and Armenian
women, all in their 20s, have joined to plan a civic campaign aimed
at improving relations between their peoples. The group's first
project will be raising money to restore an Armenian church near
Van, a city in eastern Turkey that was once an Armenian capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of thing has never been tried before,'' said one of
the organizers, Safak Pavey, a Turkish journalist. ``We want to
give an example of unity between two peoples who lived together for
a long time but became alienated from each other. It's about
restoring a church as a way of restoring souls.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The area around Elazig is just one of the places where Armenians
were killed by Ottoman soldiers and Kurdish tribesmen during the
spring and summer of 1915. But because several foreigners were
living in the area and recorded what they saw, the killings here
are unusually well documented.
</P>
<P>
   One of the foreigners was a U.S. consul, Leslie Davis, who took
a trip around Lake Hazar, then known as Lake Golcuk, after the
massacres. ``Thousands and thousands of Armenians, mostly helpless
women and children, were butchered on its shores and barbarously
mutilated,'' he later wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Armenian houses, churches and schools in this area have long
since been destroyed or allowed to collapse. New villages have
sprung up along the lake. Residents picnic under the mulberry trees
that Armenians planted around their summer homes a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is still possible to find artifacts of Armenian life here. At
one antique shop near Elazig, $250 will buy a heavy copper serving
tray inscribed with the name of its former owner in distinctive
Armenian script.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, a couple of men were discovered digging at what
they believed to be a former Armenian cemetery. They were
apparently looking for gold that, according to local lore, was
often interred with wealthy Armenians.
</P>
<P>
   Nevzat Gonultas, manager of a telephone substation on the
lakeshore, is considered a local historian because his father spent
many hours telling him stories from the past. Like most people
around here _ although unlike their brethren in other parts of
Turkey _ he knows what happened in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people don't know because they don't live here,''
Gonultas said as he sipped tea on a recent evening. ``My father
told me that Turkey was weak at that time and the Armenians decided
to stage an uprising. Then the order came to kill them. Almost all
were killed. It wasn't a war, it was a massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish authorities do not accept this version, and many
Turks never hear it. A historical atlas issued by a leading Turkish
newspaper does not show that much of this region was under Armenian
rule for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   At historical sites in this region, signs and brochures often
discount or omit facts about the earlier Armenian presence.
According to one new travel book, ``guards are under instruction to
eavesdrop on tourist guides who might be tempted to tell another
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who seeks to learn about the events in 1915, however,
need only come here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This used to be an Armenian area, but now they're gone,'' said
a factory worker named Selhattin Cinar. ``Dead, killed, chased
away. Our government doesn't want to admit it. Why would you want
to say, `My yogurt is sour'?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0226 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FIGGIS-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      05-09 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGGIS-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY MADE MIKE FIGGIS' ANTI-TECH FILM POSSIBLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Figgis has never made easy, accessible films. Even his
best-known work, ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' centered on a suicidal
alcoholic and a prostitute. But with his just-released
``Timecode,'' Figgis uses state-of-the art digital technology to
play with our notions of storytelling, indeed, our idea of how a
film is created.
</P>
<P>
   Where events in most films unfold linearly on a single screen,
Figgis splits it into four quadrants, each devoted to one of four
cameras that simultaneously filmed an interlocking story from four
different perspectives in one improvised, uncut 93-minute shoot.
</P>
<P>
   To direct the audience's attention from quadrant to quadrant,
Figgis uses sound as a pointer, emphasizing the audio from one or
more of the screens at a time. It could drive you crazy, but in a
multitasking world, a multitasking movie seems logical.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the great things about the movie,'' said actor
Julian Sands, a long-time Figgis collaborator who plays a masseur
in the film. ``Your brain can handle multiple views much more than
you suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgis says he took a most unusual path in creating the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Its unusual structure started with his frustration over the
repeated, rapid obsolescence of so many of the software programs
and pieces of technology that he was using in making movies, music,
photography and writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years ago, I realized I couldn't keep
reprogramming myself,'' Figgis said. ``You work your way through
some project, then go to use the program on a new project and they
tell you it doesn't work anymore, but they have a newer, better
program over here that you can use instead,'' Figgis said.
</P>
<P>
   That reality belies what he calls ``the fantasy of digital
perfection,'' and only by seeing through the fantasy, he said, was
he able to create ``Timecode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a short period where I crossed a line in my own head of
understanding digital technology,'' Figgis said. ''One becomes
addicted to the idea that they have to be using software across the
board. My realization was that that was bull.''
</P>
<P>
   So Figgis went back to some of the analog tools that had served
him well before he became a techno-addict. He was already half
there, given his affection for such well-made analog possessions as
his wristwatch, fountain pen collection and Leica camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Photoshop (the powerful photo-editing software from
Adobe), but I wouldn't want to get rid of my Leica,'' said Figgis.
``These things function beautifully and don't have to be
continually updated. Functional equipment is fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   So he resurrected a most functional piece of equipment, the
sprawling artist portfolios that he calls his notebooks, and on
which he scribbles bits of dialogue, storyboards, musical
fragments, script ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Those notebooks are more accommodating of his polymathic
creative urges than a computer screen and, unlike most computer
programs, will still be easily accessible 10 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   He also began thinking about the capabilities of another beloved
old tool, a Super 16mm movie camera.
</P>
<P>
   Initially he thought about using two of those cameras to follow
a couple, telling their story through extended shots of as long as
20 minutes. Over time, his idea grew, to four cameras, four people
and unedited shots as long as an entire feature.
</P>
<P>
   But such a choice in artistic structure dictated other choices,
such as what camera he would use. Only one camera, a Sony digital
video model typically used for industrial videos, could run the
90-minute-plus shots needed for Figgis' idea.
</P>
<P>
   The structure also dictated Figgis' choice of scriptwriting
tools, because scriptwriting programs couldn't handle what Figgis
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you have to invent a system of tablature that lets you
write in quadraphonic,'' Figgis said. He dug out another very old
tool, musical staff paper, pasted sheets of it together, and broke
it into 95 bars, roughly one bar per minute of running time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the highest devices man ever came up with,''
Figgis said of the staff paper.
</P>
<P>
   Only staff paper could be broken up into four staves,
synchronized in time, just as the movie's structure demanded,
Figgis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I mapped out all the big beats,'' Figgis said, using different
colored pens to show what each main character was doing, and before
which camera. To Figgis, the result was more like a musical
composition than a movie screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   The actors then improvised their lines off that general
composition in a way that Sands said ''was like a jazz performance.
It was very loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen times over nine days, the very big band of cast and crew
riffed through that composition in tightly synchronized
performances. Eventually, Figgis settled on one performance, the
last, for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   None of this would have been possible without his digital tools.
But just as important were the non-digital tools, and a different
relationship with technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it a liberation that you don't have to do it all the
digital way,'' said Figgis. ``Why put your energy into competing
against something that's not broken? Why not put the energy into
something that's never been done before, like the little camera
that can be used to shoot an entire film?''
</P>
<P>
   Technology has many uses, Figgis said, but a creative person has
to keep it in its place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone over 30 has to deal with the paranoia of never feeling
like they're able to keep up,'' Figgis said. ``The train keeps
going faster. But I'm still going to write a script on paper. I
love it. I also have a really interesting relationship of equality
now (with technology). I deeply respect it. I'm so charmed by it
now.''!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
