HIP-HOP/R&AMP;B DJs HEATING UP AIRWAVES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``tha' Goodfellas'': Disc jockeys Romeo and Dejai are joined by
veteran sidekick Tito in this increasingly popular high-energy
hip-hop/r&AMP;b show. Along with music, listeners hear such segments as
``Sports Rap,'' ``Tito's Top 4 at 4,'' ``Two-Hour Traffic Jam'' and
``Who's World Is It?'' &QL; 
Where: KPWR-FM (105.9) _ Power 106. &QL; 
When: 3 to 7 p.m. weekdays and noon to 4 p.m. Saturdays. &QL; 
Typical segment: ``Ride Wit' Us,'' Kurupt; ``Thong Song,'' Sisqo;
``Big Pimpin','' Jay-Z; ``The Next Episode,'' Dr. Dre featuring
Snoop Dogg; ``I Wanna Know,'' Joe. &QL; 
Quote: ``Hip-hop has exceeded many people's expectations and is
rapidly crossing musical boundaries. Some of today's hottest
hip-hop artists are expanding their fame and fortune into fashion,
film and TV, thanks to roots in music.'' &QL; 
Off the air: While juggling acting and music opportunities around
their radio obligations, Romeo and Dejai are preparing to suit up
for their first season in the NBA Entertainment League. &QL; 
Background: Both natives of St. Louis, tha' Goodfellas never
imagined they'd dial up radio careers. The pair, both in their
early 20s, relocated to Los Angeles primarily to pursue careers as
recording artists, but figured they could make a living spinning
music while making music as well. Their Power 106 show began last
August. &QL; 
Appearances: Thursday and Friday nights at Florentine Gardens in
Hollywood; Saturday nights at Vesuvius in Hollywood. &QL; 
You'll like this if: You like Power 106, KKBT-FM (92.3) _ the Beat.
</P>
