<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0228 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-2004-HNS &LR;      05-09 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-2004-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN POSITIONS HIMSELF FOR 2004   
 &HT;     A News Analysis   
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican John McCain positioned himself for a
possible presidential bid in 2004 with his belated and begrudging
endorsement of presumptive GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated Republican challenger embraced the two-term Texas
governor just warmly enough to escape blame if Bush loses to Vice
President Al Gore in the presidential election in November.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain signaled that his hard-hitting populist insurgency is
merely sidelined _ and not scuttled _ by his defeat at the hands of
Bush's privately funded $68 million juggernaut in the GOP
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Senior McCain campaign aides say that they expect the three-term
senator from Arizona to seek the White House four years from now if
Bush loses the race in November.
</P>
<P>
   McCain promised to campaign ``enthusiastically'' for Bush to
help ``restore integrity and honor to the White House'' _ a task
that he said Bush ``can do that more than adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain offered his arms' length endorsement with the reluctance
and pained body language of an ailing schoolboy ordered to swallow
a bitter tasting remedy. He agreed with a reporter's
characterization that making the endorsement was like ``taking
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain rejected in advance any invitation to join Bush's ticket
as the vice presidential running mate who could rally the fractious
Republican party and broaden the ticket's appeal to the
middle-of-the-road independents and conservative Democrats who
flocked to McCain's candidacy in the early presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked that I not be considered for vice president of the
United States,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush replied: ``I take him for his word.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a reporter's question at a Bush-McCain news conference
during their fence-mending summit in Pittsburgh to elicit the word
``endorse'' from McCain, a 63-year-old former Navy pilot and
Vietnam prisoner of war who waged a hard-hitting challenge against
Bush, the 53-year-old son of former President George H.W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Only when asked why he had ``difficulty'' using the word
endorsement did McCain actually declare that he was endorsing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I endorse Gov. Bush,'' McCain repeated seven times in
rapid-fire succession, triggering laughter across his audience of
campaign staffers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Bush quickly seized the elusive political trophy, nonetheless
with the quip: ``By the way, I enthusiastically accept.''
</P>
<P>
   At their joint news conference, McCain and Bush said they agreed
on the need to overhaul education, the armed forces, the
health-care system and the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   As McCain put it: ``We're in agreement on a lot more issues than
which we are in disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet disagreements abound. Bush favors a larger tax cut than does
McCain, who says he wants to use the federal budget surplus to
paying down the national debt and strengthening Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes and McCain favors banning the unregulated,
unlimited soft money contributions that corporations, unions,
special interest groups and wealthy individuals give to political
parties to help get the message out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not give up on the reform agenda,'' McCain vowed with a
tone of defiance in his voice. ``I want to emphasize one more time
_ and I made it very clear to Gov. Bush _ I will continue to pursue
the issues of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest nationwide survey, a Gallup Poll for CNN and USA
Today, showed Tuesday that Bush leads Gore 35 percent to 28
percent, with 26 percent saying they had ``no opinion'' on the
candidates at this point in the race.
</P>
<P>
   William Schneider, a political scientist at the American
Enterprise Institute, says that McCain had to join forces with Bush
``to show Republicans that he is a team player so that if George
Bush loses, McCain can be the one that Republicans turn to.''
</P>
<P>
   Were McCain to continue to spurn appeals for party unity, he
would remain ``an anathema to Republicans _ an invader from Mars _
with no hope of ever becoming president,'' Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the University of
Virginia, says McCain's post primaries' defiance had already gone
too far.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is ``the worst loser'' since Sen. Eugene McCarthy,
D-Minn., carried his unyielding anti-Vietnam war crusade into the
tumultuous Democratic convention in Chicago in 1968, Sabato said.
The furor sullied the Democratic nomination won by Vice President
Hubert Humphrey and contributed to Humphrey's subsequent defeat by
Republican Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``With McCain we'll have to watch what he does _ not listen to
what he says,'' Sabato says. McCain must ``go all out for Bush'' or
he will bear some blame for any Bush defeat, Sabato warned, adding:
``If McCain is held accountable for Bush's loss in November, he's
toast in 2004.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-INTERNET-ART-2ndTake-     05-09 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ART-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: and old patrons. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There are a number of international visitors who certainly
wouldn't make a trip here without doing some advance research about
us, and these days they are doing that kind of research on the
Net,'' says Carri Ann Wantuchowicz, public information officer at
the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The individual Web sites for smaller galleries constitute yet
another tentacle reaching out to the art community, emitting a
snowballing amount of information. Fort Worth's William Campbell
Contemporary Art gallery has a link with artnet.com. After shelling
out a start-up fee of $3,500 and a $100 monthly maintenance cost,
Campbell is represented with a five-page site among artnet.com's
other galleries.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Flatbed Press and Galleries, which specializes in
fine art prints, etchings and woodcuts, has joined Guild.com, a
sprawling fine arts Web site. Flatbed discovered that if an
Internet customer is seeking, for example, the etching
``Self-portrait'' by Luis Jimenez and it is in Flatbed's
collection, that client can click on the Flatbed gallery link from
Guild.com or search out the Jimenez print by entering the artist's
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is most common is that someone will be looking for a
particular artist but never have heard of Flatbed, and they come to
Guild.com, ... and we will hopefully have a stock of that work,''
says Katherine Brimberry, co-owner of Flatbed Press and Galleries.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hype of Net boosters about the Internet's potential
to broaden appreciation for art, the Web's greatest impact on the
fine-art world has been strictly commercial. From the very low end
where eBay resides to the world of high-end auctions, covering a
price range of $500 to $10,000, hawkers of art all but smack their
lips at the selling possibilities online.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the sites catering to the middle ground, like
Visualize.com, seem to be making the most impact online. Visualize
makes available, for between $100 and $1,100, lithographs, silk
screens, photographs and engravings, all in original
limited-edition formats. ``We felt that for someone who wanted to
get something of enduring value, something more than a poster, but
wouldn't spend $10,000 _ and knowing how intimidating a gallery can
be _ well, there just wasn't any source for real quality (work)
that was affordable,'' says Abby Adlerman, president and CEO of
Visualize.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Net art market hasn't come close to rendering
obsolete the gavel-banging auction rooms, it has constructed its
own parallel bidding universe for newcomers to the auction world.
</P>
<P>
   Populist eBay was motivated to add the auction house Butterfield
&AMP; Butterfield to its corporate mix, in addition to staging online
fine-art auctions under the rubric of ``Great Collections.'' And
despite its 256-year, tradition-steeped history, Sotheby's has held
nothing back in its pursuit of the Internet, investing a reported
$40 million in two Web sites: sothebys.amazon.com, selling art
valued at up to $10,000, and sothebys.com for the ritzier market.
As early as 1997, Sotheby's was dabbling in the Internet to
advertise the future auction of the world's best-preserved
``Tyrannosaurus rex,'' nicknamed ``Sue.'' ``Sue'' ended up being
auctioned for $8.4 million to the Field Museum of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the T. rex wasn't actually sold on the Web site, the
mere fact that it was presented there brought more and more people
to Sotheby's.com,'' says Sotheby's Redden.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, and completely isolated from a traditional live
auction, Sotheby's first Internet auction offered various books and
manuscripts, some of which sold for $13,500 each, a landmark price
for an Internet sale. Sure enough, the Net auction sold a stunning
$90,000 worth of books and manuscripts. Emboldened by this success,
Sotheby's began conducting online auctions of items with values
ranging from $200 to as high as $100,000. In January, Sotheby's
registered its most successful sale with a rare, 16th-century,
illustrated edition fetching $88,000. On sothebys.amazon.com, its
leading item was a 1930s Lou Gehrig Yankees cap which, in April,
went for $56,650.
</P>
<P>
   Artists gain different rewards when their works circulate on the
Net. Boris Bally is a 39-year-old metalsmith whose most
commercially successful works are his furniture pieces made from
recycled traffic signs. He is currently one of the more than 1,600
artists affiliated with Guild.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love it,'' gushes Bally. ``It's such a great new way to
do business, allowing me both to be anonymous and a virtual
businessperson.'' Bally has added $20,000 worth of Internet sales
to his regular gallery-based business.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Bally's work had to be officially selected by
Guild.com's top juror. Bally then received a one-page placement on
the Guild.com site. Bally signed a one-year exclusive contract with
Guild, which took a 35 percent commission from every Bally work
sold through the site, a contrast to the 50 percent cut most
galleries charge.
</P>
<P>
   Bally discovered that what was paramount to Guild.com was that
in offering his works for sale online, he needed a healthy
inventory to turn around the orders quickly. ``I quickly learned to
be one of the people who could ship an item within a week as
opposed to my normal delivery time of four to eight weeks,'' says
Bally, whose ``transit chairs,'' composed of recycled ``stop'' and
``yield'' signs, have received enormous Guild.com-generated
publicity. The bottom line: Bally has averaged, during certain
holiday selling periods, at least one order a day of the $975
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most artists don't spend money on magazine ads, but we can act
as a catalog for them, a sales tool for their own site, helping the
artists to get their name out there, beyond the gallery market,''
says Reed McMillian, director of artists' marketing at Guild.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the obvious rewards, the Web revolution isn't an
unmitigated success. Not everything sells equally well on the Net.
Sculpture, furniture and large-ticket art items haven't generated
boffo business. And since very fine line-drawings don't reproduce
well on-screen, tremendous expertise is needed just to discern
their value.
</P>
<P>
   And the Internet does induce some artistic soul-searching, as it
suddenly becomes less a matter of artistic integrity than of mass
production and entrepreneurial savvy. ``It does make for a more
dramatic workday, as I could have a major order of six chairs that
has to be turned around in a month,'' says Bally.
</P>
<P>
   California-based artist Tim Schaible admits that selling his
work online could potentially influence the direction his art moves
in. ``It might curb my thinking in what kind of art I might
produce, perhaps steering me towards what is found to be very
popular, but I've always been comfortable merchandising my art
anyway,'' says Schaible, who derives a quarter of his annual income
from online sales.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0233 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-INTERNET-ART-3rdTake-     05-09 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ART-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: online sales. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And perhaps because the art is sold from a faraway site, there
are always questions about quality and authenticity. Visualize
engages in an expensive process of inspecting every art piece,
making sure a certificate of authenticity is included with the
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, if a person is going to bid $30,000 for a work of art,
he will need to have someone look at it, and if it's a rare gold
brooch sitting in someone's collection in Irkutsk, then it becomes
expensive and time-consuming to verify authenticity,'' says Kenneth
Linsner, a director of content for artstar.com.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of physically examining a piece of art
on-screen. No matter how sophisticated the image, it can appear too
jarringly unreal for buyers already wary of investing thousands of
dollars in something not seen in person. ``When you look at
anything visual on the screen and you say `Wow, I really like
that,' and when you read that it measures 48 by 60 by 98, you can't
really grasp that on the Net,'' says William Campbell, owner of
William Campbell Contemporary Art gallery.
</P>
<P>
   As for Internet auctions threatening the viability of the
standard live auction for the upper echelons of great works of art,
nothing duplicates being in the same room, witnessing the
masterpiece up close and very personal. ``Yes, when it comes to the
terribly expensive paintings, they must be presented properly in a
darkened room with a strong light gazing down on this glorious work
_ all the conditions that a client relishes, and that will not
happen with the Internet,'' says Redden.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such limitations, the Internet's encroachment into all
aspects of the art world seems a foregone conclusion. Ever on the
cutting edge, the Net helped ring in this past Black History Month
by staging a first-ever online sale of 100 works by
African-American artists through artnet.com. Sotheby's talks
confidently about assembling a combined live and virtual auction,
while Visualize predicts that soon a live salesperson will be able
to walk a customer through a site, completing a sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the road, you might have photographs of a
three-dimensional object _ like a piece of furniture _ and have it
revolve in space, seeing its insides, back and front, helping one
buy with an enormous amount of real knowledge,'' says Redden.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than presenting three dimensions, though, the Internet
also has the ability to allow patrons of an artist to engage the
painter or sculptor online while he or she is creating a work. The
French Web site nart.com (already the self-proclaimed record holder
for selling $1.2 million worth of fine art at the largest online
auction ever) already offers the opportunity to throw oneself into
a virtual gallery realm where artists are witnessed creating in
their musty workspaces.
</P>
<P>
   But after this whiz-bang tour of an artist's garret is over, one
is still left to absorb the Internet art market's newly created
commercial art ethos. Virtually overnight, the Net has altered ever
so slightly that hoary idea that the ``where'' of art display
directly affects how deeply art is appreciated and whether it is
purchased. Perhaps inevitably, the exploding abundance of art on
the Internet, while serving as a great leveler of price, also
serves as a trivializer of some quality. Though such concerns, say
Internet art champions, are more than offset by the Net's
underlying populist influence that is making art available and
affordable for almost everybody.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Marton is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
amarton(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0234 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ART-HOWTO-TEX     05-09 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-HOWTO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURCHASING POWER
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies INTERNET-ART) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It only takes a modicum of Web savvy to join the burgeoning
world of art auctions once reserved almost exclusively for
millionaire jet setters.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to get started. Log onto, let's say, artnet.com, a
popular site that, twice a week, has two sales (or batches of art
``lots'') opening and closing. Click onto the online auctions home
page, which will show on any given day four images representing the
auction site's recommendations of the day. To track down a specific
kind of item within these groupings of auctionable items, enter the
artist, medium, title or a key word to bring up the appropriate
item.
</P>
<P>
   Once you find the image of the desired art work, click on it to
enlarge it and also to receive any relevant information. Also
included is the auction house's price estimate of what the object
will command. What is not published is the ``reserve price,'' or
the minimum price the seller will accept.
</P>
<P>
   To the right of the image of the desired artwork is a clock
showing how many days, hours, minutes and seconds are left in the
auction. Also shown is the lot number for the object, its starting
bid and the dollar increments in which the bids must be made. To
sign up to bid, a participant must fill out a bidder registration
form, which includes all basic information plus, most importantly,
a valid credit card number. In filling out this registration, the
participant picks a user name or handle (say, ``artfreak''), and a
password. The participant will then receive a bidder ID number.
</P>
<P>
   So armed, you are ready to make a bid. Return to the lot page
containing the image of the work and, on the right-hand side of the
clock, in a bidding bar area, you then enter the user name, bidder
number and password followed by the prescribed bid indicated or an
``auto-bid'' _ a bidder's maximum amount. A pop-up window will
appear acknowledging the successful bid.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, you have the option of enrolling in artnet.com's
``lot watch,'' which allows you to monitor the bidding progress on
as many as 100 different lots at a time. It is also wise to
remember that for many online auctions, much of the action takes
place in the frenzied final five minutes, because veteran bidders
don't want to drive up the price against themselves throughout the
course of the auction.
</P>
<P>
   If yours is the winning bid, you'll be notified by e-mail. Once
artnet.com receives your money, the item will be shipped out from
the seller. You then have 48 hours to compare it to the description
and condition report initially published on the item.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew Marton
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
