   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BUSH (Pittsburgh) _ Amid a circus atmosphere, John McCain
endorses George W. Bush, but reiterates he's not interested in vice
presidency. Though he pledges to campaign vigorously for Bush,
personal relations between the two remain cool. By Jill Zuckman.
1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DESERT-SLAYING (Carlsbad, N.M.) _ Raffi Kodikian, who pleaded no
contest to killing his friend during an ill-fated camping trip in
the desert, will learn his fate soon. Kodikian faces up to 20 years
in prison, but insists he committed murder only after his friend,
in agony from dehydration, begged for death. By Brian MacQuarrie.
800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-OPINIONS (Boston) _ Massachusetts health institutions
agree to provide second opinions, based only on x-rays and medical
records, to affluent people overseas. It's the latest in
telemedicine and in the race for innovative ways to raise money at
academic medical centers. By Liz Kowalczyk. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   REUTERS-YANKEE (Boston) _ Reuters Group, the world's largest
financial information and news provider, is buying Yankee Group
Research, a telecommunications consulting and market research
company, for $72.5 million in cash, to boost its range of research
material. By Hiawatha Bray. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN (Boston) _ Three decades later, the moment
survives, frozen in time -- the single greatest hockey play ever.
By Dan Shaughnessy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
