<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-DOCOMO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S NTT DOCOMO BUYS STAKE IN DUTCH MOBILE PHONE COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ NTT DoCoMo, Japan's largest mobile phone company,
agreed Tuesday to acquire a 15 percent stake in the Dutch mobile
phone operator KPN Mobile for about $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is NTT DoCoMo's first move into Europe as part of an
expansion beyond Japan by its parent company, Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone. It also gives KPN Mobile, a unit of Royal KPN, a
powerful ally in the intense competition for Europe's mobile phone
market. NTT DoComo was the first to give customers the ability to
browse on the Internet using mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies are likely to team up to bid for Orange PLC,
Britain's third-largest telephone operator. Orange is expected to
be put up for sale by Vodafone AirTouch PLC, which must divest
itself of Orange as a condition of its $183 billion acquisition of
Mannesmann AG, the German telecommunications company that it bought
a few months ago. Analysts expect a fierce bidding war for Orange,
which is expected to cost about $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that we've become much more attractive for Orange,''
said Joop Dreschel, a board member of KPN.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes less than a week after merger talks between Royal
KPN and Telefonica of Spain collapsed, leading the Dutch telephone
company to reach an agreement with NTT DoCoMo.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the stake NTT DoCoMo is buying in KPN Mobile, the two
companies will become strategic partners, developing a team to
create next-generation mobile Internet services in Europe based on
NTT DoCoMo's i-mode technology, which creates a continuous mobile
Internet connection. The i-mode service became so popular in Japan
that NTT DoCoMo has curtailed new users from signing up.
</P>
<P>
   Keiji Tachikawa, the president and chief executive of NTT
DoCoMo, said that buying a stake in KPN is part of a larger overall
strategy to enter Europe. ``We have closely followed developments
in the exciting European mobile communications market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo's foreign alliance is part of a broader strategy by
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone to expand internationally. On
Monday, its NTT Communications Corp. subsidiary purchased Verio, a
leading Web site manager in the United States, for $5.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For Royal KPN, which has an alliance with Qwest Communications
International of the United States and which is partly owned by
BellSouth, the agreement with NTT DoCoMo will give the company an
advantage in bringing mobile interactive services to Europe that
are far more advanced than the current offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of KPN, which had risen close to 8 percent last week
after it confirmed it was negotiating with Telefonica, fell Tuesday
to 109.93 euros or $99.875 because of investor anxiety that KPN
will be forced to do several smaller deals rather than one
pan-European merger.
</P>
<P>
   KPN and KPN Mobile were advised by ABN AMRO and J.P. Morgan. NTT
DoCoMo was advised by HSBC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
