<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PUTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN'S PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vladimir Putin's gaudy inauguration Sunday as Russia's second
elected president offered a lesson about the speed and completeness
of the counter-revolution that doomed the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The symbols as well as the substance of Russia's first electoral
transfer of power represent an antithesis to the old Soviet ways.
The pomp and ceremony of Sunday's spectacle evoked the czarist
past. Vanished were the drab Leninist rituals of the Bolshevik
tradition. In their place, Russians witnessed a carefully
choreographed pastiche of a coronation. The legitimating rationale
of the new Russian state was on display in evocations of imperial
Russian power and appeals to national pride.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of the sprawling, confused country Putin must govern
is as different from the czarist past, however, as from the Soviet
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Most Russians realize that Putin was brought to power by
powerful financial and media oligarchs. If he is to create a viable
capitalist economy, he will have to establish and implement rules
that are the same for all players. Sad to say, there have been
credible reports that Putin has personally intervened to punish a
rival of the oligarchs who were his original backers and to allow
members of his inner circle to bend regulatory agencies to their
will.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the invisible hand of the marketplace will have to
compel Putin to abandon the rigged system of crony capitalism he
inherits. Nonetheless, when President Clinton arrives in Moscow for
a summit encounter June 4 and 5, he would do well to nag Putin on
the need to make Russia a place where both Russians and foreigners
feel their investments will be properly protected.
</P>
<P>
   Another reality obscured by the operatic staging of Putin's
inauguration is Russia's weakness in the world. The Kremlin has no
allies and cannot afford the price of being a world power _ or of
frightening would-be friends in the West.
</P>
<P>
   At their summit, Clinton should heed Russian anxieties about any
scuttling of the 1972 ABM treaty, but he should also warn Putin
that the West cannot embrace a Russian leader who is covered with
the blood of noncombatant Chechen civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
