<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER10-COX     05-09 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: MEDICINE DOWN THE HATCH
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two months after their bitter primary battle, John McCain
endorsed George W. Bush today and said he looked forward to
``enthusiastically campaigning'' for him. McCain, however, asked
not to be considered as a running mate. The Arizonan gave his
formal endorsement to Bush after a 90-minute private meeting in
Pittsburgh that ended with a public handshake. ``I endorse Governor
Bush,'' McCain said half a dozen times with a smile. ``By the way,
I enthusiastically accept,'' Bush said. The pair acknowledged they
still have differences, primarily over campaign finance reform.
But, said McCain, ``We are in agreement on more issues than we are
in disagreement.'' When a reporter asked McCain about aides'
remarks that the timing of the endorsement was like taking medicine
now rather than later, McCain replied, ``I think your
`take-the-medicine-now' is probably a good description.'' Behind
the scenes, McCain's aides were chafing at Bush's refusal in the
news conference to repudiate conservative broadcaster Pat
Robertson's statement last weekend that a McCain vice presidency
would be ``very dangerous.'' Asked about that, Bush simply said
that McCain is ``a friend of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   PROMOTING HARMONY _ AND HIMSELF
</P>
<P>
   The real story behind the John McCain-George W. Bush meeting,
according to the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, is the work done by
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, a Republican vice presidential
hopeful, to bring the two sides together in his home state. Elsie
Hillman, an ex-Republican National Committee member and longtime
Bush family friend, was among those pressing for the event, but
says Ridge did the heavy lifting. Though he has taken heat from
Christian conservatives for being pro-choice on abortion, Ridge
could get a V.P. boost from the summit's success.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY DAY IN TWO STATES
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska Attorney General Don Stenberg was trying to take the
first step today toward reclaiming Sen. Bob Kerrey's seat for the
Republicans, facing Secretary of State Scott Moore and two others
in the GOP prilmary. The winner is likely to take on popular
ex-Gov. Ben Nelson. Retired Nebraska Cornhusker football coach Tom
Osborne was expected to rout two opponents in a GOP congressional
primary. In West Virginia Gov. Cecil Underwood, who was elected to
his first term as governor in 1956 and to his second term in 1996,
was expected to easily win the GOP nomination for his third term.
At 77, Underwood is the nation's oldest governor. And in case
anyone's paying attention, there are presidential primaries in both
states. Al Gore and George W. Bush don't seem too worried.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE A POLITICAL ECUMENICAL COUNCIL
</P>
<P>
   Politicians of many stripes and faiths sat elbow-to-elbow in St.
Patrick's Cathedral for Cardinal John O'Connor's funeral. Some of
those present had differed with O'Connor's strong opposition to
abortion or his views on other issues. But differences disappeared
in a turnout by the Washington and New York political elite that
seemed almost like a state funeral. President Clinton and Al Gore,
a couple of Baptists, sat near the two George Bushes, the elder
Episcopalian, the younger Methodist. New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani,
a Catholic, was a row behind Hillary Clinton, a Methodist herself.
Also attending were New York Gov. George Pataki and nearly 40
percent of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE SECOND-SPOT PROBING
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who is heading up Al
Gore's search for a running mate, has met with Sens. John Kerry of
Massachusetts and Richard Durbin of Illinois, according to the
Boston Globe. The newspaper also quoted Gore spokesman Chris Lehane
as saying: ``I can't confirm or deny anything. ... I have no
comment on the process at all.''
</P>
<P>
   FEC SOCKED WITH LAWSUIT OVER DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   Third-party and other groups sued the Federal Election
Commission, contending it was allowing a partisan commission to
limit the presidential debates to the two major parties. Among
those suing in federal court in New York were the Libertarian Party
and the Committee for a Unified Independence Party as well as
voters from the Democratic, Republican and Green parties. The
Commission on Presidential Debates limits access to its nationally
televised debates to candidates with at least 15 percent support in
five national polls.This latest lawsuit is different from previous
ones because it's against the FEC, not just the debate commission,
said Steve Dasbach, national director of the Libertarian Party.
</P>
<P>
   129,000 TEXASN SIGN UP FOR BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan turned in an estimated 129,000 signatures to state
election officials in a bid to secure his place as an independent
candidate on Texas' November ballot. He said he's still seeking the
Reform Party's presidential nomination, but sought ballot status as
an independent as an ``insurance policy'' in case the party taps
someone else. In order to qualify as an independent, Buchanan needs
about 58,000 signatures from registered voters who did not
participate in either major party primary. Election officials must
verify the signatures' authenticity. Buchanan listed Houston
term-limits activist Clymer Wright as his Texas running mate.
Buchanan said Wright, an old friend, agreed to be listed on the
petitions as a ``stand-in.'' Buchanan gave no indication whom he
ultimately might pick as a vice presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   PEROT SEEN SITTING THIS ONE OUT
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party founder Ross Perot is not expected to address the
party's August convention in Long Beach, Calif., where lapsed
Republican Pat Buchanan is likely to become the third party's
presidential nominee. Perot's lop lieutenant, Russell Verney, said
Perot ``has a very tight travel schedule for business this
summer,'' but the Associated Press reported that senior party
officials say Perot has indicated he won't attend the convention or
make a statement in support of the nominee. That would be a first
since he founded the party in 1992. His absence could further
demoralize a party riven by fierce infighting for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   GOP GIVING INDIANA DEMOCRAT A SMOOTH RIDE
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had an unusual reaction to a recent primary election
in Indiana: They basically surrendered in their effort to knock out
first term Democratic Rep. Baron Hill. ``This is a not a targeted
race we're now looking at for the fall,'' said Jim Wilkinson, a
spokesman for the GOP campaign committee. As if to underscore the
point, the GOP issued a written statement that spoke
enthusiastically of its chances for victory in other Indiana
contests. It omitted mention of Hill's seat. The GOP had long
touted Hill as a potential victim, but congressional party leaders'
hopes soured when Kevin Kellems, a former aide to Sen. Richard
Lugar, lost the nomination. Some GOP strategists view the winner in
the primary, Michael Bailey, a longtime anti-abortion crusader, as
too much a one-note candidate to defeat Hill.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS DEMOCRATS JUST BEATING AROUND THE BUSH
</P>
<P>
   The once-mighty Texas Democratic Party, whose fabled leaders
Lyndon Johnson and Sam Rayburn once dominated not just the state
but the nation, has fallen on very hard times. Of today's 29
officials elected statewide in Texas, none are Democrats.
Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison faces only token Democratic
opposition in her re-election campaign this year, which is more
opposition than the party is providing in most statewide races. But
other than the most partisan Republicans, few Texans would argue
that Democrats are powerless or obsolete, particularly since the
party still controls the congressional delegation and the Texas
House. But as George W. Bush campaigns for the White House,
Democrats are consumed by a parochial, less glamorous agenda, such
as legislative races and preparing for the 2002 gubernatorial race.
And few elected Democrats are willing to make trouble for their
popular governor.
</P>
<P>
   GET TING THEM INTO THE VOTING HABIT EARLY
</P>
<P>
   A new group called Youth-e-Vote announced it'll offer
schoolchildren across the country a chance to take part in online
mock balloting for president, governor and members of Congress this
fall. ``By exposing students to the political process at a young
age Youth-e-Vote (will help) turn the tide of the so-called voter
apathy in this country,'' said Joseph Mohen, CEO of Election.com a
Long Island-based online voting company. Youth-e-Vote will mail all
U.S. schools information seeking to encourage them to register for
the student vote on its Web site, www.youthevote.net. Youngsters
can ballot on the Youth-e-Vote Web site between Oct. 23 and Nov. 2.
Results will be available the day voting ends.
</P>
<P>
   THE OUTER LIMITS OF SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Republican primaries, the George W. Bush campaign
trumpeted seemingly any and every endorsement, whether from the
governor of a large state or the secretary of a small sewing
circle. But last week, the Bush campaign took it to the outer
limits. Bush showed reporters a recent copy of the Weekly World
News supermarket tabloid. The front page featured a photo of Bush
standing beside an oblong, hairless space alien. The tabloid noted
that this same extraterrestrial had backed Bill Clinton in 1992.
And as Bush noted, his alien encounter was further proof of his
commitment to expanding the Republican Party's appeal. ``New faces,
new voices,'' he said as he held the front page high. ``It goes to
show I'm willing to reach across certain demographic lines.''
</P>
<P>
   CHUCKLE WITH GORE, BUT JUST A LITTLE BIT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore as the Terminator? In his dreams _ or in his cartoon
collection. Gore's official White House Web site now boasts some
favorite jabs from his personal collection of editorial cartoons.
In one, there's Gore, post-makeover, with wild new hair and a pair
of lungs in hand _ a reference to an interview in which he said
that to win a candidate has to ``rip your opponent's lungs out and
move on.'' ``Hasta la vista, baby,'' says a Terminator-esque Gore.
But the collection includes only five of the more gentle digs;
absent are the more-biting ones, including claims about inventing
the Internet or inspiring, along with wife Tipper, the book and
movie ``Love Story.'' Rival George W. Bush doesn't boast a similar
cyber-collection, but spokesman Scott McClellan said there are
about 30 Bush cartoons framed at the Governor's Mansion. The Gore
cartoon site: www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/OVP/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
