SAN FRANCISCO _  RISINGSTAR, RISINGSTAR1  _ The past year has been
an amazing one for restaurants in the Bay Area, with exciting new
places opening all over the map. What's made this explosion of
restaurants significant is the talent behind them _ the people in
the kitchen who turn out food that wows our palates and keeps us
coming back for more. &HT;    This year's Rising Star chefs include Alexander Ong, Mark
Zeitouni, Laurence Jossel, Victor Scargle and Jeffrey Amber.
 &HT;    Chef profiles in two takes with recipes, two sidebars.
 &HT;     By Karola Saekel, Kim Severson, Robin Davis, Miriam Morgan and 
 Tilde Herrera  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEW YORK _  &UR; JAMES BEARD &LR;  _ The temperature wasn't the only thing
sizzling here Monday. Bay Area chefs, wine professionals,
restaurants and cookbook authors swept through the prestigious
James Beard Foundation awards like a firestorm.
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _  &UR; SECRET-VEG &LR;  _ Pintxos chef Bernat Dones has
created one of the most enticing vegetable main courses I remember
eating _ it consists of paper-thin layers of celery root, squash,
eggplant and zucchini.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest installment of the regular column describing
what makes a Bay Area restaurant's dish a success, we'll tell how
to make it.
</P>
<P>
   With chef's secrets for success, recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Michael Bauer &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _  &UR; WORKING &LR;  _ 30-Minute Main Dish: Poached Salmon
with Asparagus Rice Pilaf; Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe: Mushroom Marsala
with Polenta; and Now &AMP; Later: Roast Pork Loin with Gingered
Carrots &AMP; Watercress.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes. &QL; 
