<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTBACON-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 BEST WAY: Cooking Bacon   By Andy Lax  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For better or worse, there are few foods that more
typify the hearty American breakfast than bacon. Despite _ or
perhaps because of _ its high fat content and savory smoky
qualities bacon retains a special place on the breakfast table.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But what is the best way to cook bacon to have it turn out both
crispy and meaty? We tested Applewood Farms Sunday Bacon five ways
to determine the best cooking method _ on the stovetop in a
non-stick skillet, in a cast iron skillet, baked on a wire rack,
baked directly on a rimmed cookie sheet, and microwaved.
</P>
<P>
   To microwave the bacon, we sandwiched it between layers of paper
towels. The paper towels absorbed most of the grease so the bacon
did not need to be drained after cooking. It remained flat and did
not shrink. However, both the microwaved bacon and the bacon cooked
in a nonstick skillet came out dry and didn't much please the
tasters.
</P>
<P>
   The oven-cooked bacon was baked in the middle of the oven at 500
degrees for 7 to 10 minutes. The bacon placed on a wire rack (set
over a rimmed cookie sheet to catch the grease) looked the best but
was limp and lacked the crispness needed for perfect bacon. The
bacon baked on the cookie sheet was the Food department's favorite.
It struck a good balance between crisp and meaty and did not shrink
substantially.
</P>
<P>
   The bacon cooked in a cast iron skillet was a close second.
Although it cooked somewhat unevenly due to curling and shrinkage,
it gained points for nostalgia value and tradition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   We found that baking bacon on a rimmed cookie sheet is best.
Preheat the oven to 500 degrees. Arrange the bacon on the cookie
sheet and place it in the middle of the oven. Bake for 7-10
minutes, or until cooked to the desired crispness. Transfer the
bacon to paper towels to drain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
