<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0255 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-RISINGSTARS1-SFCHRON &LR;      05-09 3394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RISINGSTARS1-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURENCE JOSSEL
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 STAR SEARCH: Bay Area Chefs Reach for New Heights   &HT;     By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It's a long road from being an assistant kindergarten teacher to
being a chef at a hot Bay Area restaurant. But what an interesting
road it's been for 30-year-old Laurence Jossel of Chez Nous in San
Francisco.
<P>
   The South African native had less than auspicious teenage years.
He moved to the U.S. with his family when he was 10, eventually
settling in Los Angeles. To his parents' dismay, he quit high
school to manage a bar. He worked a number of other jobs _
including the stint as a kindergarten teacher _ until he finally
decided to go to cooking school. He admits that he agreed to go
just to make his parents happy.
</P>
<P>
   But when he went to the California Culinary Academy at age 19,
he found his passion. ``When school was done for the day, I felt I
hadn't done enough,'' he remembers. So he'd sneak into additional
classes just so he could learn more.
</P>
<P>
   It's that enthusiasm for learning that makes his food so
exciting. Three-month-old Chez Nous, where Jossel is also
part-owner, serves small plates like pommes frites, gnocchi and
roasted quail. He keeps a strict emphasis on simplicity,
authenticity and seasonality in his dishes.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 years since he graduated from CCA, he has worked in a
number of restaurants in San Francisco and traveled extensively,
absorbing all of the experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Jossel credits a number of people with having a strong impact on
his cooking style. He worked with Gary Danko at the Dining Room in
the Ritz-Carlton San Francisco, appreciating what he called Danko's
``cerebral approach.'' He says Danko also introduced him to others
who influenced his style, like cookbook author Joanne Weir and
cooking instructor Madeleine Kamman.
</P>
<P>
   But it was when he was researching Greek food for the opening of
Kokkari that Jossel really saw his style begin to take shape. He
traveled to Turkey _ he couldn't get into Greece because of his
South African citizenship _ where he fell in love with the street
food.
</P>
<P>
   After eating what he describes as the best lamb, the best
yogurt, the best vegetables, he had an epiphany. ``Food has to be
honest,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That honesty is what he brought to Kokkari in the year he worked
there as sous chef, and it's the focal point of his straightforward
food at Chez Nous.
</P>
<P>
   He chooses dishes from a variety of cuisines because he likes to
change the menu all the time to keep himself interested. The
ever-changing menu also means he can offer his customers the best
of the season, like strawberry sangria.
</P>
<P>
   Jossel says it's too early to talk about what his next project
might be, but he thinks whatever it is would have the same
neighborhood appeal of Chez Nous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place was built for the neighborhood,'' he says. ``I like
it best when it's filled with the eclectic people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STRAWBERRY SANGRIA
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Jossel at Chez Nous changes his menu frequently, but
this simple drink is one of his current favorites. Try to use the
ripest berries you can find for superior flavor. If they're a
little under-ripe, add more sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 (750 ml) bottle soft-tannin red wine (Jossel uses an Italian
rosso)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound strawberries (about 2 pints), hulled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh apple juice
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup Triple Sec
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar (more or less depending on ripeness of berries)
</P>
<P>
   2 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a large pitcher. Stir until the sugar
dissolves. Cover and refrigerate at least 4 hours or up to one day.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the sangria into glasses, being sure to include some of the
strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a fork to eat the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 165 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 23 g carbohydrate,
0 &LR;   &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 9 mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; VICTOR SCARGLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Miriam Morgan &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
On a recent sunny spring morning, an elderly gentleman walked in
the door of Pisces, the new seafood restaurant in Burlingame, and
asked where he could buy a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ticket?'' asked the hostess near the door, getting ready for
the day's lunch service. ``Oh,'' she replied, ``this isn't the
train station any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The man's confusion was easy to understand. Pisces is located
right at the Broadway Avenue CalTrain stop _ and, in fact, was the
train station for decades. But now ticket vendors have departed and
the small historic building is where Victor Scargle is starting to
make some history of his own.
</P>
<P>
   In a space smaller than many home kitchens, he's turning out
stunning dishes like scallop foie gras salad, seared halibut with
morels, artichoke and eggplant puree, and ancho pepper grilled
corvina. His first tasting menu, which debuted at the end of last
month, features English pea soup with lobster fritter and white
truffle oil, and sauteed curried skate wing with boniato puree,
watercress and tamarind orange reduction, among other courses.
</P>
<P>
   At 27 years of age, Scargle is the youngest of this year's
Rising Stars, yet is already the executive chef of a destination
restaurant. A protege of Michael Mina, chef of Aqua in San
Francisco, Scargle helped open Aqua's sister restaurant in Las
Vegas before opening Pisces _ which is part of the Aqua group _
last year.
</P>
<P>
   He began his culinary career in his hometown of Aptos, making
cookies, taking children's cooking classes at the local community
college, then working in a restaurant to earn extra money while in
high school. He went on to the University of California at Santa
Barbara, majoring in economics, but found he'd rather be in the
kitchen than the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed the intensity of restaurant cooking, and I missed
watching people enjoy the food. That's really what I like,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   So Scargle returned to a kitchen, earning an apprenticeship with
Brian Bird at Fess Parker's Red Lion Resort in Santa Barbara. After
completing the year, he went to work with Robin Haas in Miami.
``That's where I learned all about tropical seafood and produce,
and Cuban influences,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He further honed his Nuevo Latino techniques by moving to New
York City and working with the renowned chef Douglas Rodriguez at
the ground-breaking Patria. From there, it was back to the West
Coast, and Aqua.
</P>
<P>
   Aqua's style, described as French/Californian seafood, has also
taken on Mediterranean and Asian influences under Mina's direction
_ which impressed Scargle. ``I learned how to take the best quality
products from different countries and use them to balance and
support the main ingredient,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After three years at Aqua, Scargle returned briefly to New York
_ ``sort of on loan,'' Scargle says _ to work at various
restaurants. At TriBeCa Grill, he presented daily American cuisine
specials, and learned about an entirely different style of food. He
also gained experience in the kitchens of the renowned Lespinasse,
Le Bernardin, Aureole, Gramercy Tavern Oceana and Park Avenue Cafe
_ and learned how to handle high-volume dining rooms. He also began
to realize how much diners appreciate a personal touch.
</P>
<P>
   At Pisces, he says, ``I like to go out and serve customers and
see their faces. The most important thing is making people happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings him back to pleasing customers with his cooking.
``I get inspired by what other chefs are doing, then I add my own
twist. Plus I look at what's in season, the weather, what feels
right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DUNGENESS CRAB CIOPPINO
</P>
<P>
   The stock may be made one day ahead and refrigerated until ready
to use. At Pisces, Victor Scargle adds the crushed shells from
three lobsters to the stock, which enhances its complexity. He
serves the cioppino with crostini spread with roasted garlic
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Shellfish Stock
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   20 shrimp shells
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 fennel bulb, trimmed, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   3 celery stalks, chopped roughly
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, chopped roughly
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, chopped roughly
</P>
<P>
   1 leek (white and light-green part), well rinsed, chopped
roughly
</P>
<P>
   Handful of parsley stems
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch thyme
</P>
<P>
   4 coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   4 white peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   Cioppino
</P>
<P>
   6 red bell peppers, deribbed and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   6 yellow bell peppers, deribbed and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   4 jalapeno peppers, seeded and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   20 vine-ripened tomatoes, cored and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1 head of garlic, separated into cloves, crushed (OK for the
skins to stay on)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pure olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Shellfish
</P>
<P>
   12 clams
</P>
<P>
   12 black mussels
</P>
<P>
   6 prawns (16/20 size)
</P>
<P>
   18 rock shrimp
</P>
<P>
   12 day boat scallops or 24 bay scallops
</P>
<P>
   Picked meat from 1 cooked Dungeness crab
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch basil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Make the stock:  &LR; Heat the oil in a large stockpot over
medium-high heat. Add the shrimp shells and sear them until they
turn red. Add the brandy and stir until it just evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomato paste. Reduce the heat to medium and cook,
stirring, for 2 minutes. Add the fennel, celery, carrots, onion,
leek, parsley, thyme, coriander, peppercorns and bay leaves. Cook,
stirring, until the vegetables begin to soften and turn glassy. Add
the white wine, turn the heat to high, and cook until the wine
nearly evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   Add the water, bring to a boil, and cook over medium-low heat
until the stock reduces by one-third to one-half. Strain the
mixture through a chinois or other fine strainer; discard the
solids and return the stock to the pot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Make the cioppino:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 350. Toss the peppers,
tomatoes and garlic with the olive oil. Spread the vegetables on a
large rimmed baking sheet or roasting pan. Season with salt and
pepper. Roast for 15 to 20 minutes, stirring once, or until the
vegetables are just tender.
</P>
<P>
   Add the vegetables to the shellfish stock. Bring to a boil,
reduce the heat, and simmer for 10 minutes. Puree the stock in
batches in a food processor or blender. If making ahead, cool,
cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To finish the cioppino:  &LR; Return the stock to the pot and place
over medium heat. When the stock simmers, add the clams, mussels
and prawns, and cook until the clams and mussels open. Remove the
shellfish and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Add the rock shrimp and scallops to the stock. Cook for 4
minutes. Return all of the shellfish and the picked crabmeat to the
stock. Add the basil. Heat through.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Remove the basil. Arrange equal portions of the
shellfish in wide soup bowls. Mound crabmeat in the center of each.
Ladle the hot stock over the shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 590 calories, &LR;   &LR; 40 g protein, 40 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 24 g fat (3 g saturated), 221 mg cholesterol, 446
mg sodium, 9 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; JEFFREY AMBER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Tilde Herrera &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager growing up in the Midwest, Jeffrey Amber would
never have imagined that his destiny would lie in a West Coast
kitchen. He saw himself as a poet so he went to the University of
Oregon as an English major.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1991 he left his academic life behind, landing in San
Francisco because he thought the city would be a more conducive
environment to develop his writing. To earn some money, he turned
toward the restaurant work that had always sustained him and
ironically, found it to be his true calling.
</P>
<P>
   Amber did not get much culinary inspiration growing up in Iowa.
His father, retired from the Air Force, was the ``king of the
barbecue,'' he says, and his mother, an administrative assistant,
was ``queen of Stouffer's frozen meals.''
</P>
<P>
   He supported himself by working in restaurants because he needed
an income while in school, beginning in a small family-run Italian
restaurant where he learned to make ravioli and sausage as an
eighth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, his natural ease in the kitchen allowed him to
drift in and out of many. ``I sort of goofed off for a long time,
cooking all kinds of different things. I never went to school for
it, it was just something that I could do. I could walk into any
kitchen and I could cook.''
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in San Francisco, he added more restaurants to
his resume, which reads like a laundry list. ``I've been everywhere
but nowhere,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In his early 20s, he took stock of his natural culinary talent,
his love for the intensity and instant gratification of cooking and
decided to get serious about it. He set goals for himself and got
in contact with some of the very best in the industry, ``people who
knew how to make art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Alfred (Schilling) who was making chocolates and I had
never done pastry. His stuff is very architecturally based. He was
doing wedding cakes when I met him, using live plants in the
wedding cakes which I had never seen before. I thought it was very
unique, very artistic. Really beautiful stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling taught him composition and presentation but it was his
next mentor who taught him discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to the point in San Francisco where I felt like I could
be a sous chef somewhere but I didn't have the resume,'' he says.
``So I went from restaurant to restaurant, putting myself out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd stay here for a month and there for a month, each time
thinking, `I don't want to be a sous chef here,' until I met Denis
(Soriano) at the Grand Cafe. He said, `You work here and I'll make
you a sous chef.''' Amber realized his resume was built on smaller
restaurants and he needed the experience and connections working at
a place the size of Grand Cafe would bring.
</P>
<P>
   While attending the opening of the W hotel's restaurant, XYZ, he
met Alison Richman, the opening chef. She asked him to join her
crew to strengthen their dinner service and he accepted even though
the food that was being served ``wasn't really my style.'' He was
getting ready to leave XYZ when he was offered the executive chef
position.
</P>
<P>
   He decribes his food as fun, a little flashy but sophisticated,
``colorful, very alive-looking food, very defined, composed,
architecturally based. Where you just knock it down before you eat
it but when it hits your table, you turn it around to show your
friends. That's the food I like to serve, little works of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Amber says he aspires ``to be someone like Gary Danko or George
Morrone, people who do extreme fine dining, where people come for
the food, to be wowed, there for the experience. That's what I'd
like to see _ dinner-only, fine dining. It's something I'd like to
evolve to. But you need to prove yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; PUMPKIN SEED-CRUSTED MONKFISH
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 acorn squash
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 spring (green) garlic bulbs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons roasted pumpkin seeds
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   10 cherry tomatoes, stemmed and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 eight-ounce monkfish fillets
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the squash:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Slice
the acorn squash in half, remove seeds and place the halves
cut-side up on a baking sheet. In the cavity of each squash half,
place 1 tablespoon butter, 1 tablespoon sugar and 4 tablespoons
orange juice. Season with salt and pepper. Bake for 30 to 40
minutes, until the squash is tender. Slice each half into 4
lengthwise sections.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the garlic:  &LR; Trim the leaf end of each garlic,
leaving 3 inches of green top, then trim 1/4 inch off the root
ends. Remove the first layer of skin. Bring the milk to a gentle
boil in a saucepan; season with salt and pepper. Add the spring
garlic and cook until it is tender.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the sauce:  &LR; Bring the stock and 3 tablespoons of the
pumpkin seeds to a boil in a saucepan; boil until reduced by half.
Add lemon juice and whisk in the remaining 5 tablespoons butter, 1
tablespoon at a time, until fully incorporated. Add the spring
garlic and cherry tomatoes, remove from heat. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To cook the fish: &LR;  Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Coarsely
chop the remaining pumpkin seeds, then toss with the nutmeg and
cinnamon. Season the monkfish fillets with salt and pepper. Heat
the olive oil in an ovenproof saute pan until almost smoking. Add
the monkfish and sear until light brown on both sides, turning
once.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the seed mixture on top of the fish to form a crust.
Place in the oven and bake for approximately 7 minutes, or until
the fish is just done.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Divide the squash slices between 2 large, shallow
serving bowls. Top each with a spring garlic bulb. Divide the sauce
and tomatoes between bowls and top with the monkfish fillets.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 895 calories, &LR;   &LR; 43 g protein, 67 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 54 g fat (28 g saturated), 166 mg cholesterol, 405
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 13 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MARK ZEITOUNI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Age: &LR;  29
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Restaurant: &LR;  Working at Fifth Floor temporarily, but shopping
for a new venture in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Style: &LR;  Subtle and influenced by French cuisine, but with
regional twists
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Recipe: &LR;  Blue Cheese and Watercress Pan Souffle
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I don't like to play with food too much. There's a fine line &LR; 
 &LR; between giving people interesting food and trying to show off &LR; 
 &LR; the really strong flavors of the products.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ALEXANDER ONG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Age: &LR;  32
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Restaurant: &LR;  Xanadu
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Style: &LR;  Restor-Asian (pan-Asian fusion)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Recipe: &LR;  Pan-Roasted Duck Breast with Spicy Mango Salsa
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Trying to get into the ``controlled chaos'' of the Shangri-La &LR; 
 &LR; kitchen, he ended up a dishwasher, ``but I wasn't about to give &LR; 
 &LR; up.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; JEFFREY AMBER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Age: &LR;  29
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Restaurant: &LR;  XYZ
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Style: &LR;  California French-inspired
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Recipe: &LR;  Pumpkin Seed-Crusted Monkfish
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I try to always be more creative, but keep a certain level
of &LR;   &LR; sophistication. We have a jewel box of a dining room and I
like &LR;   &LR; to fill it full of jewels.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; LAURENCE JOSSEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Age &LR; : 30
</P>
