<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-HERB-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 AT THE SOURCE: Seasonal Scent: Eatwell Farms' lavender crop 
 caters to a passionate market   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 WINTERS, Calif. _  Lavender, says Nigel Walker, is a wonderful mood
enhancer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He won't go quite as far as a friend who asked rhetorically,
``Who needs Prozac if there is lavender around?'' But he has
observed that ``these big, burly field workers sing more when they
tend the lavender.''
</P>
<P>
   There must be a lot of singing these days at Eatwell Farms, the
82-acre spread Walker and his wife, Frances Andrews, work in
Winters near Davis. On the farm, a full five acres are devoted to
the fragrant herb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lavender,'' admits Walker, ``is a passion of ours,'' and
despite friends' pessimistic warnings, the couple has found a
lively market for this, the most esoteric of their crops. (Diverse
fruits and vegetables, especially tomatoes, occupy most of
Eatwell's acreage.)
</P>
<P>
   Both husband and wife have farm blood in their ancestries. He
has a grandfather who farmed in the English Midlands, her's grew
peaches in Virginia, ``but both our parents had more sense than to
be farmers,'' Walker says with a chuckle. ``We both had proper
jobs, too.'' He worked for the BBC in his native Britain; Andrews
started her working life at Morgan Stanley in New York. She moved
west and took a job at Alice Waters' Cafe Fanny in Berkeley, then
at Full Belly Farms near her current home. The two met,
appropriately, at the Marin County farmers' market.
</P>
<P>
   Walker returned to college for a degree in horticulture, so
botanical names roll off his tongue with ease.
</P>
<P>
   He needs it to explain his lavender. There are early-blooming
Provence and Grosso, which are being harvested now _ the second and
third week of May is their peak season. Other lavenders come in
later, stretching the season into early summer _ Hidcote Giants,
Grapenhall, Seal, Super and more. All are fragrant, but each has
its own characteristics. Grosso produces the darkest purple
flowers; Super has the bushiest heads; short-stemmed Lavandula
angustifolia produces the most oil.
</P>
<P>
   Walker and Andrews hope to process some of the crop by drying or
using it in infused oils. For now, Eatwell's lavender is fresh,
sold at the Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market on Saturdays and tucked
into the 240 baskets of produce delivered weekly to subscribers in
San Francisco and the East Bay under a Community Supported
Agriculture program. ``It's a freebie,'' Walker says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   They have been surprised how many recipes use lavender as a
flavoring _ flans, custards, cookies, salads and savory dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Between the demands of the farm and their nearly three-year-old
twins, Andrew and Eric, cooking has not been a priority for the
farm couple. ``I don't spend much time in the kitchen,'' Walker
admits, and his wife chimes in, ``I certainly didn't marry you for
your cooking, darling; I married you for your accent.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Eatwell Farms is located in Winters (Yolo County). The &LR; 
 &LR; farm's products are sold Saturdays at the Ferry Plaza Farmers' &LR; 
 &LR; Market in San Francisco. The farm's phone number is (530) &LR; 
 &LR; 759-8221. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
