A0257 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-VEG-SFCHRON &LR;      05-09 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-VEG-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Paper-Thin Layers of Vegetables Make Milhojas 
 Pintxos' Signature Dish   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Spanish cuisine isn't necessarily known for its
vegetarian specialties, but any successful restaurant in San
Francisco _ especially one that attracts a young crowd _ has to
offer more than a basic plate of grilled vegetables.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So chef Bernat Dones uses his imagination. He's created one of
the most enticing vegetable main courses I remember eating. It's
paper-thin layers of celery root, squash, eggplant and zucchini.
The vegetables are moistened with a drizzling of basil oil and
topped with tomatoes and a creamy crumble of goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   It's a perfect dish for this trendy Mission District urban-chic
restaurant, which incorporates new and old elements. Modern blue
and yellow glass pendant lights hang over the tiled bar and
kitchen, and rustic pine floors provide a visual contrast to the
sleek molded wood chairs and the cool blue and yellow color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   With its sophisticated interior and innovative recipes, Pintxos
(pronounced PEEN-chos) does for Spanish/Basque food what the
groundbreaking Slanted Door _ just down the street _ did for
Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Pintxos, 557 Valencia St. (between 16th and 17th streets), San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; (415) 565-0207. Dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Slicing the vegetables. &LR;  It's important to cut them as thinly
as possible to get their distinct flavor. If not, the flavors don't
merge correctly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Dry sauteing the vegetables. &LR;  The paper-thin vegetables are
first cooked in a dry skillet to soften and brown them and
intensify the flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ A turn in the oven. &LR;  After layering the sauteed vegetables,
the casserole is baked, which further helps meld and intensify the
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VEGETABLE MILHOJAS WITH BASIL, TOMATO &AMP; GOAT CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound tomatoes, peeled, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, smashed
</P>
<P>
   5 fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound eggplant
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound kabocha or other autumn squash, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound celery root, peeled
</P>
<P>
   About 4 tablespoons Basil Oil (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound soft, fresh goat cheese (such as Montrachet), crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add
the tomatoes, garlic and basil leaves. Season with salt and pepper.
Saute for 1 minute. Remove the garlic and basil. Refrigerate the
tomato sauce for at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Using a mandoline, cut the eggplant into thin circles about
1/8-inch thick. Cut the zucchini into long strips, about 1/8-inch
thick. Cut the squash and celery root into 1/16-inch-thick slices.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat. Do not add
any oil. Sprinkle the zucchini with salt and pepper. Add to the
skillet and saute until just soft, about 2 minutes per side.
Transfer to a platter.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with the seasoning and sauteing about 2 minutes per side
with the eggplant. Transfer eggplant to the platter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the celery root with salt and pepper. Add to the
skillet and saute until barely soft, about 3 minutes per side.
Transfer to the platter.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with the squash, seasoning it with salt and pepper and
sauteing 3 minutes per side. Transfer to the platter.
</P>
<P>
   Using an 8 x 8-inch oven-proof glass pan, layer the vegetables,
beginning with enough of the celery root to cover the bottom of the
pan, followed by some of the eggplant, squash and zucchini. Drizzle
1 tablespoon of the basil oil over the top. Repeat the layering
process until all vegetables are used, using 1 tablespoon Basil Oil
between each complete set of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the tomato sauce over the vegetables. Sprinkle the goat
cheese on top. Bake until the cheese starts to brown, about 6
minutes. Drizzle with the remaining 1 tablespoon Basil Oil and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 370 calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 18 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 29 g fat (11 g saturated), 26 mg cholesterol, 266
mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BASIL OIL
</P>
<P>
   Any remaining basil oil may be refrigerated for up to a month.
Use in salads or as a flavoring for meats.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch fresh basil (about 70 leaves)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Bring a medium-size pot of water to a boil. Drop in the basil
leaves and drain immediately. Then plunge the leaves into a bowl of
ice water. Remove the leaves. Pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   Put the leaves in the bowl of a food processor. Pulse to chop.
Slowly add the oil. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1/2 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 125 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 1 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 14 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 1 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
