<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-DIPS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASTER'S CHOICE:   
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  With spring comes parties, picnic and barbecues.
And with all those get-togethers comes chips and dip.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week we gave you the results of a full-fat potato chip
tasting. This week, we've tasted onion dip to go with them.
</P>
<P>
   The panel sampled eight onion dips, two pre-made and six made
from mixes according to package directions. Overall, those made
from mixes ranked far higher than the pre-made versions found in
the refrigerator case. But only two dips had decent rankings. The
others had little onion flavor, off-putting colors or artificial
notes.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming favorite was  &UR; Mrs. Grass &LR;  (1.5 ounces, 89 cents
at Andronico's), which is made from a mix. It ranked very well.
Panelists described it as classic and just what they expected from
an onion dip. One panelist particularly liked the plump onion
pieces. All would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Safeway &LR;  (2 ounces, 99 cents at Safeway).
Panelists liked the flavor for the most part, but thought it was
too mild. One panelist described it as tangy; another thought it
was bland. All might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Campbell's &LR;  (2 ounces, $1.59 at Cala) came in third. Two
panelists thought it was too salty. One noticed the texture of
onions, but couldn't taste them. Others thought the onion flavor
was stale and artificial. One might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Granny Goose &LR;  (.375 ounces, 79 cents at Draeger's) came in
fourth. One panelist liked the flavor, but others described it as
too sweet, powdery, bitter and gummy. One would buy it; four would
not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lipton &LR;  (2 ounces, $1.49-$1.59 at many supermarkets) scored
fifth, just one point lower than Granny Goose. Panelists disliked
the oily mouthfeel and said it tasted more like mayonnaise than
anything (the dip is made with sour cream). None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Knorr, Marie's and Kraft but they scored
too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Shelley Handler, consultant and food writer;
Patricia Hart, nutritionist and dietician; Julia McClaskey, chef,
Dine in San Francisco; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
