<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Frozen North Produces Gold-Medal Ice Wines  Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; When your life revolves around eating and
drinking, there are some food and wine events you try never to
miss, like the Old Ebbitt Grill International Wines for Oysters
Competition. Nevertheless, the fourth annual matching of oysters
with white wine took place in November at the historic Old Ebbitt
Grill in Washington, D.C., without me.
<P>
   If you plan to be in the nation's capital this November, I
recommend the event. In fact, the competition is such a good way to
learn about pairing wine and oysters that it alone is worth a trip
to D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is simple. A gathering of wine and food
professionals narrows a field of 423 white wines from nine
countries down to a manageable 45 semifinalists. Then, a panel of
16 judges, most of whom profess an intimate knowledge of bivalves,
slurps and sips its way through the wines, accompanied by tiny
Olympic oysters, awarding 10 gold, 10 silver and 25 bronze medals.
For the true oyster lover, it's like dying and going to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever pried open a dozen fresh oysters while waiting
for the wine to chill, it comes as no surprise that Sauvignon Blanc
was the most oyster-friendly wine at the Old Ebbitt Grill taste
off. In fact, 9 of the 10 winners were Sauvignon Blancs, three of
them from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The grand champion medal went to Villa Maria 1999 Marlborough
Private Bin Sauvignon Blanc. First runner-up was Nautilus 1999
Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc; and second runner-up was Alan Scott
1999 Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc. New Zealand Sauvignons scored two
more golds for Grove Mill 1999 Marlborough and Giesen 1998
Marlborough.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top gold-medal winners were three California
Sauvignons, including Husch Vineyards 1998, Amador Foothill Winery
1998 Fume Blanc, Cakebread Cellars 1998 and _ for the first time in
the competition _ a sparkling wine, Domaine Carneros 1995 Brut.
</P>
<P>
   Why did New Zealand Sauvignon Blancs score big as
oyster-friendly wines? The natural bracing acidity of Sauvignons
from the Marlborough region and the flavors of fresh lime juice and
passion fruit perfectly complement the briny flavors of fresh
oysters.
</P>
<P>
   But Sauvignon Blanc was not the only wine to win medals at the
Old Ebbitt Grill. Winning wines were also made from Chardonnay,
Chenin Blanc, Pinot Gris, Pinot Blanc, Riesling and Viognier.
</P>
<P>
   All of the winning wines were served with 25 varieties of
oysters at the Oyster Riot, an annual event held at the Old Ebbitt
Grill.
</P>
<P>
   If you would like more information about the Old Ebbitt Grill
International Wines for Oysters Competition, call Tom Meyer or
Maureen Mavin at (202) 333-9180.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Internet Wine News &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest news for wine fans who shop online is the new
partnership between WineShopper.com and Amazon.com. Through the
partnership, California wine shoppers can access 1,400 wines
through WineShopper, the Napa-based Internet start-up, or discover
the expanding world of wine through Amazon, a leading e-commerce
retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides taking on Amazon as a strategic partner, WineShopper has
formed exclusive partnerships with some of the country's leading
wine and food publications, including Wine Spectator, Connoisseur's
Guide to California Wine and WineToday.com. Links are planned from
the partner's web sites to WineShopper.com.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wine.com, another Napa-based wine e-tailer, announces
that Tapestry, a line of wines from Australia's McLaren Vale, has
re-entered the U.S. market and will be available only on Wine.com.
Tapestry, from McLaren Vale's Merrivale Winery, was first
introduced to U.S. wine drinkers in 1993. Available through
Wine.com are Tapestry Cabernet Sauvignon 1996 and Shiraz 1997, both
priced at $25, and Chardonnay 1998, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vintage 2000 Bud Break &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 wine grape growing season seems to be off to a good
start. Newly opened buds are out along California's coastal regions
from Napa Valley to Santa Barbara and in Washington state and
Oregon. Chalone Wine Group reports that a normal bud break follows
an overall mild winter with adequate rainfall. Chalone Wine Group
includes Canoe Ridge Vineyards in Washington and Carmenet, Echelon,
Acacia, Chalone Vineyards and Edna Valley Vineyard in California.
New to the Chalone Wine Group is Jade Mountain, a specialist in
Rhone-style wines in the Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Q &AMP; A &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Red wine gives me a nasty headache,'' says Vickie Hindershot
of Santa Cruz. ``Can you suggest some reds that won't?''
</P>
<P>
   The likely evidence that links headaches with red wine are the
phenolics found in all wine, but in larger quantities in red wine.
Histamines are another culprit in red wines that can cause
headaches in some people. You might try taking an antihistamine
before drinking red wine, but for some people, antihistamines are
known to interact with alcohol. The lighter the red wine, like
Gamay or French Beaujolais, the lower the histamines, since skin
contact through maceration is less.
</P>
</TEXT>
