<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0261 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-USCHINA-TRADE-0510-CO     05-09 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCHINA-TRADE-0510-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON BRINGS IN FORD, CARTER TO HELP PRESS FOR OPENING UP
CHINA TRADE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton brought together the architects
of half a century of tortured U.S.-Chinese relations Tuesday to
endorse a controversial proposal to make China a fully credentialed
member of the global trading order.
</P>
<P>
   With former presidents Jimmy Carter and Gerald Ford at his side
_ and dozens of former diplomats and cabinet members looking on _
Clinton called on Congress to approve legislation that would grant
permanent normal trade relations (PNTR) to China.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would end the annual congressional debate over whether
to extend low tariff and other favorable trading benefits to the
world's most populous nation, and would compliment a landmark White
House agreement over the terms of China's entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who put human rights near the center of his
administration's foreign policy, said granting PNTR to China would
help promote democratization and wider freedoms in a country that
takes in one-fifth of the world's people.
</P>
<P>
   ``China still has not measured up to the human rights and
democracy standards and labor standards of America,'' Carter said,
speaking in the ornate East Room where he once held press
conferences and entertained fellow heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no doubt in my mind that a negative vote on this
issue in the Congress will be a serious setback and impediment for
the further democratization, freedom and human rights in China,''
Carter said. ``And I hope the members of Congress will vote
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   With both houses of Congress expected to take up the PNTR
proposal in two weeks Clinton fired off a broadside against its
opponents, saying they had aligned themselves with conservative
hardliners and military leaders resisting economic and civil
reforms in China.
</P>
<P>
   Although observers expect that Clinton will win the crucial
House vote, it is still likely to be close. Enough so, that the
president was determined no to let up on the bill's opponents _
many of whom are Democrats _ on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's against it in China? The people that run the state-owned
industries, and don't want to give up their control; the more
conservative elements of the military, who would like to have
greater tensions between ourselves and them, and between themselves
and the people of Taiwan,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is truly ironic, when you look at who's against this in
China, to see that some of the most progressive people in the
United States are basically doing what they want them to do in
opposing this agreement,'' Clinton said. ``For me, it is very
painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Those remarks prompted return fire from those who oppose PNTR
with China, either out of concern for that country's poor human
rights record, its potential as a U.S. military adversary or
because U.S.-China trade is already badly out of kilter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that somehow there are two sides to the Chinese
government and that the pro-American side will be damaged and that
the other side will now come to predominance is ridiculous,'' said
Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., who joined several of his colleagues
for a Capitol Hill news conference to oppose the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be real clear about this: the hardliners on this are in
the United States. The hardliners are the corporate bosses that are
in league with the political leadership in China so that they can
both make money,'' said Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't care about this country. They care about whether or
not their international corporate interests are going to advance,''
said Norwood, who is working to defeat PNTR. ``Both of these
hardliners will exploit labor. They will exploit labor in the
United States, and they'll exploit labor in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton countered such opposition Tuesday with an array of
seasoned firepower _ several dozen statesmen who played central
roles in the crafting of U.S. policy toward China.
</P>
<P>
   Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger _ whose secret
meetings with Communist Party head Mao Zedong led to U.S.-China
detente during the Nixon administration _ spoke in favor of PNTR,
as did James Baker, who served as Secretary of State when President
Bush visited Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping in 1989, several months
before Chinese troops opened fire on unarmed demonstrators near
Beijing's Tiananmen Square, killing hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the audience was former National Security Adviser, Ret.
Gen. Brent Scowcroft, who made his own secret visit to Beijing in
the weeks following the Tiananmen massacre, at a time when Bush had
officially suspended top-level U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending were former Secretary of State Warren Christopher
_ whose own human rights overtures drew a frosty snub from
officials in Beijing several years after the Tiananmen killings _
and former Secretary of State Alexander Haig, who defied U.S.
Ambassador to China James Liley and attended a Chinese anniversary
celebration in Tiananmen just four months after the bloody
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the lives of the people in this room, the last 50
years of America has unfolded,'' said Clinton. ``We want the voice
of this meeting to echo across the country, and to embrace the
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cast the issue in national security terms, saying that
to reject PNTR with China could strengthen the hand of hardliners
and militarists, perhaps increasing the likelihood of a U.S.-China
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's by far the most important national security vote that
will be cast this year,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   At is essence, though, the vote concerns trade.
</P>
<P>
   Last year China exported nearly $70 billion more worth of goods
and services to this country than it bought from American factories
and farms. Clinton claims that passing PNTR _ and endorsing China's
entry into the WTO _ would help level the playing field for U.S.
exporters to China. That, Clinton contends, would help to narrow
the trade gap and create new jobs for American workers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that PNTR and WTO membership would have the
opposite effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here because I want the Chinese to know the joy of Texas
products made by Texas workers,'' former Democratic Texas Gov. Ann
Richards told reporters at the White House immediately following
the event. ``From computers to agricultural products, we make the
best, and we want that billion-people market opened up.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
