<HEADER>
A0263 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      05-09 1546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: Salmon or Pork Loin Could Win Points With Mom   By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  You might remember poached salmon from wedding
buffets of days gone by. The poor fish was skinned, poached whole,
then rearranged on a huge platter with cucumber ``scales'' to try
to make him look like his former self, when he once got to roam the
open seas or his fish farm.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might be out of fashion, but poaching still is a very easy
and low-fat way to cook fish or poultry. All the fish needs is a
dip in a flavorful simmering broth or court bouillon; no oil is
used. It's also hard to dry out anything cooked in liquid, though
you still should avoid overcooking.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30-Minute Main Dish, Poached Salmon with Asparagus Rice
Pilaf, the fish is accompanied by a pilaf seasoned with lemon juice
and golden shallots. Asparagus pieces are folded into the pilaf
halfway through the cooking process to steam along with the rice.
</P>
<P>
   The Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe, Mushroom Marsala with Polenta, calls on
pregrated Parmesan cheese, preminced garlic and dried thyme for an
ultra-quick preparation. The creamy, vegetarian ragout is enlivened
with Marsala, which contrasts well with the crisp rounds of
polenta. If you like, serve it alongside wilted red chard or other
greens.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get a reservation for Mother's Day, impress your
mom with an old-fashioned homemade roast, like the Roast Pork Loin
with Gingered Carrots &AMP; Watercress. This dish has lots of clean,
bright flavors and makes a nice presentation with its springy
orange and green color scheme. The gingered carrots are both sweet
and spicy, a good complement for the juicy roast tenderloin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   POACHED SALMON WITH ASPARAGUS RICE PILAF
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 quart chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   2 large shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups basmati rice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound thin asparagus
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   4 salmon fillets (you can leave skin on), about 8 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   5 to 10 parsley sprigs or a few green onions
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the stock in a large, wide pot. Mince the shallots.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a Dutch oven. Add the shallots and saute
until tender, about 2 minutes. Add the rice and stir until all the
grains are coated with oil. Add 21/2 cups of the heated stock, the
lemon juice, 1/2 teaspoon salt and a few grindings of black pepper.
Stir and bring to a boil. Reduce to a simmer, cover, and cook 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add 4 cups of water to the remaining stock and bring to a boil.
Keep at a low simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Snap the tough ends off the asparagus and discard. Cut the
asparagus spears into 1-inch lengths, but leave the tips whole.
Zest the lemon and mince the zest (you should have 2 to 3
teaspoons). Reserve the rest of this lemon.
</P>
<P>
   After the rice has cooked 10 minutes, stir in the lemon zest and
asparagus. Return to a simmer, cover and cook until the rice is
tender, about 10 minutes longer. (Let stand, covered, for a few
minutes before serving.)
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze the juice from the reserved lemon into the heated stock
and add the vinegar, bay leaf and 1 teaspoon salt. Bring to a boil.
Submerge the salmon fillets in the liquid and poach until flaky but
still pink in the center of the thickest part, about 5 to 6
minutes. (If the fillets are not completely covered in liquid,
cover the pan.)
</P>
<P>
   Finely chop the parsley or thinly slice the green part of the
onions as garnish.
</P>
<P>
   When done, carefully lift the fillets from the broth. Place the
fillets over a bed of rice pilaf. Sprinkle with the parsley or
green onions.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 770 calories, &LR;   &LR; 55 g protein, 66 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 31 g fat (7 g saturated), 150 mg cholesterol, 380
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   MUSHROOM MARSALA WITH POLENTA
</P>
<P>
   You can find prepared polenta in a refrigerated case in the
supermarket. I used Santini brand polenta with good results.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound white or crimini mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   3 portobello mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons prepared minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 (35-ounce) roll prepared polenta
</P>
<P>
   About 1/2 cup pregrated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch chives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Marsala
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oven to 450 degrees. Position oven rack at top of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Clean and trim the mushrooms. Cut into medium dice.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the
garlic and thyme and saute until fragrant, about 1 minute. Add the
mushrooms and season with salt and pepper. Saute until tender,
about 6 to 8 minutes, stirring often.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the polenta into eight 1/2-inch-thick rounds (you will
have one third of the roll left). Arrange on a small buttered
baking sheet and place on the top rack of the oven. Bake 5 minutes,
then sprinkle about 1/2 tablespoon Parmesan on top of each slice
and return to the oven until brown and crisp, about 2 minutes
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the chives into 1/2-inch lengths. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Increase the heat to high under the mushrooms and stir in the
Marsala. When the mixture is almost dry, add the stock. Bring to a
simmer, then reduce heat and stir in the cream. Heat through, then
adjust sauce for seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the polenta slices to shallow soup bowls. Ladle the
ragout over the polenta; top with more Parmesan and the chives.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 475 calories, &LR;   &LR; 12 g protein, 31 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 32 g fat (19 g saturated), 105 mg cholesterol, 271
mg sodium, 7 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   ROAST PORK LOIN WITH GINGERED CARROTS &AMP; WATERCRESS
</P>
<P>
   If you would like to save part of this recipe for later,
marinate as directed, then seal, uncooked, in a plastic freezer bag
with some of the marinade. Defrost the meat overnight in the
refrigerator, then cook according to directions. Purchase fresh
watercress and cook more carrots to serve with the leftover roast.
</P>
<P>
   The Marinade
</P>
<P>
   4 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   21/2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   The Pork
</P>
<P>
   2 (31/2-pound) pork tenderloins, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches watercress
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches medium-size carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 large shallot
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   About 11/2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne
</P>
<P>
   Pinch allspice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Stir together the marinade ingredients, then add the pork and
refrigerate for at least 3 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the tenderloins from the marinade, pat dry. Season well
on all sides with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place a large saute pan over medium-high heat. Add enough oil to
cover the bottom of the pan completely, then heat until almost
smoking. Add the tenderloins and brown on all sides, but be careful
because the residual marinade burns easily.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the tenderloins to a large roasting pan, allowing
plenty of room between them. Fold under the thin end of each
tenderloin so the pieces are uniform in thickness. Roast for 30
minutes, or until the meat reaches at least 137 degrees
(medium/medium-rare) on an instant-read thermometer, inserted into
the thickest part of the pork. Remove from oven and let rest 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the pork roasts, cut the watercress stalks roughly in half
and arrange on a large serving platter.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the carrots and cut on the diagonal into 2-inch lengths.
Mince the shallot and ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1 tablespoon butter in a medium pot; add the ginger and
shallot and saute until tender, about 8 minutes. Add the carrots
and enough stock to just cover them, the cayenne, allspice and salt
to taste. Bring to a simmer and braise until the carrots are
tender, about 12 minutes. Discard all but 1/3 cup of the liquid,
then stir in the honey and the remaining tablespoon butter. Adjust
seasoning. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place the tenderloins on the bed of watercress and
surround with carrots, leaving a frame of watercress around the
outside of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 350 calories, &LR;   &LR; 57 g protein, 10 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 8 g fat (3 g saturated), 175 mg cholesterol, 166 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades vary &LR; 
 &LR; and are difficult to estimate. Variables include the type of &LR; 
 &LR; food, marinating time and amount of surface area. Therefore, &LR;   &LR; the
marinade is not included in this analysis. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
