<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Danko, Rodgers Win National Chef Awards   c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 NEW YORK _  The temperature wasn't the only thing sizzling here
Monday. Bay Area chefs, wine professionals, restaurants and
cookbook authors swept through the prestigious James Beard
Foundation awards like a firestorm.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the annual gala event honoring excellence in the culinary
industry, Gary Danko in San Francisco was named Best New Restaurant
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Rodgers of Zuni Cafe in San Francisco was awarded Best Chef
in California. The other nominees in that category were all from
San Francisco _ Traci Des Jardins of Jardini &LR; e &LR; re, Reed Hearon of
Rose Pistola and Black Cat, Michael Mina of Aqua and Nancy Oakes of
Boulevard. Menlo Park native Janos Wilder, now chef-owner of Janos
in Tucson, won for Best Chef in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Rubicon, where Larry Stone is the wine director,
received the Outstanding Wine Service Award. Stone, along with
Thomas Keller of the French Laundry in Yountville, was inducted
into the Who's Who in Food &AMP; Beverage in America.
</P>
<P>
   Kermit Lynch of Kermit Lynch Wine Merchants in Berkeley was
named the Outstanding Wine and Spirits Professional.
</P>
<P>
   Swan Oyster Depot in San Francisco was named a Regional Classic
and Drew Nieporent, who owns Rubicon in San Francisco and Tribeca
Grill and Montrachet in New York, among other restaurants, was
named Humanitarian of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   In other restaurant awards, David Bouley of Danube in New York
was named Outstanding Chef, and Charlie Trotter's in Chicago was
named Outstanding Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle took two journalism awards, which were handed out
earlier. Staff writer Robin Davis won Best Newspaper Feature
Writing Without Recipes for ``Sushi, American Style,'' which ran in
The Chronicle last December. Staff writer Kim Severson won for
Newspaper Feature Writing About Restaurants and Chefs. Her story,
``The Rise and Fall of a Star,'' profiling noted chef Jeremiah
Tower, ran in The Chronicle last September.
</P>
<P>
   In television awards, Bay Cafe, the cooking show on Bay TV
hosted by Joey Altman, won best local television cooking show or
segment.
</P>
<P>
   In cookbook categories, ``The Bread Bible,'' by Bay Area author
Beth Hensperger (Chronicle Books) won Best Baking and Dessert Book
award.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
