<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but
the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is
enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff
aims to change that. This round-up column will make practical sense
of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as well as offering
offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food news to put on your
plate. &HT;     
 FOOD IN THE NEWS: California Says No to Biotech Labels  By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; The blossoming movement to label genetically
altered food sold in California restaurants and grocery stores took
some recent hits in Sacramento, but activists say their battle is
far from over.
<P>
   In late April, the state Senate's powerful agricultural
committee voted down a proposal by Sen. Tom Hayden, a Los Angeles
Democrat, that would have required labels on all food products that
had genetically modified ingredients. The proposed law would have
carried a 30-day jail sentence or a $2,500 fine for violators.
</P>
<P>
   Food producers and other groups, including the California
Restaurant Association, argued that it would be almost impossible
to track the origin of ingredients in many food products.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns ranged from problems tracking the feed given to cows to
how to label dishes on restaurant menus. Because restaurants often
change suppliers and create dishes based on available products, the
pressure to verify every ingredient would force chefs to limit
their menus and add excessive costs to restaurant meals, says John
Dunlap, president of the restaurant association.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise of sorts was reached last week,(MAY 2), &LR;  when the
agriculture committee approved a version of the bill that requires
the state to simply  &LR; consider &LR;  whether the labels are needed and
how to best do it. The issue now heads to the other side of the
floor, where supporters will try to get it through the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been shifted from `you should do it' to `maybe you should
do it,''' says a disappointed Marc Lappe, director of the Center
for Ethics and Toxics, the advocacy group leading the fight. ``It's
a defeat for the principle of labeling our food.''
</P>
<P>
   He concedes the battle to get the labels will be a long one, and
the fact that the committee even agreed to ask the Department of
Food and Agriculture and Department of Health Services to study it
is progress, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Clinton administration announced several steps
meant to assure the public that genetically engineered food is
safe, including a more formal process for reviewing new products
and more testing to determine their effects. But it said mandatory
labeling for food containing genetically engineered products was
not necessary. The food industry, which argued that labels would
unfairly stigmatize biotech food, applauded the plan. Consumer
advocates criticized it and plan to fight for the labels through
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Drop That Mussel &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As sure as asparagus and artichokes signal the arrival of
spring, so does the annual Department of Health Services quarantine
on mussels.
</P>
<P>
   The quarantine, aimed at preventing paralytic shellfish
poisoning, bans the consumption of any mussels harvested by the
public on California's beaches. It does not apply to commercially
harvested mussels. Shellfish gathered for grocery stores and
restaurants must be certified safe by the state and are taken from
waters regularly tested for the toxin that causes PSP.
</P>
<P>
   The quarantine began May 1 and lasts until Oct. 31. Although it
does not apply to sport-harvested clams or scallops, people who
gather those types of shellfish are advised to eat only the white
meat and to throw away dark-colored organs or viscera before
cooking. And, the health department reminds us, don't harvest those
types of shellfish from beaches close to sources of sewage or
chemical contamination.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the health department's shellfish
information line at (510) 540-2605 or (800) 553-4133.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Kim Severson is a Chronicle staff writer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
COL. 2 of FOODNEWS (83358 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
