<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 STAR SEARCH: In the sea of young chefs, we've found five who
will  make a mark on the Bay Area dining scene  By Karola Saekel, Kim Severson, Robin Davis, Miriam Morgan and 
 Tilde Herrera  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; The past year has been an amazing one for
restaurants in the Bay Area, with exciting new places opening all
over the map. Small neighborhood spots have become destinations,
and splashier high-profile places have attracted diners in ever
increasing numbers.
<P>
   But what's made this explosion of restaurants even more
significant is the talent behind them _ the people in the kitchen
who turn out food that wows our palates and keeps us coming back
for more.
</P>
<P>
   They're not just the big names. Peeking behind the stoves, the
Food staff has uncovered five especially talented young chefs who
we bet will soon emerge as stars in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   Some have formal training; some don't. Their styles range from
straightforward and subtle to inventive and cross-cultural. But all
of them infuse their cooking with a love for what they do, and the
skills to excel at it.
</P>
<P>
   Their passion is on the plate _ and we're all the luckier for
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ALEXANDER ONG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Karola Saekel &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If Alexander Ong's classic culinary training needed to be honed
to a razor's edge, he got his chance in Florida, when the
Ritz-Carlton organization made him a 911 chef.
</P>
<P>
   Like a paramedic, the 911 chef rushes off at a moment's notice
to rescue a kitchen in dire need: When a sous chef is hospitalized
with bleeding ulcers, another is thrown in the slammer after an
altercation in a bar, or yet another walks out in a huff on the eve
of a convention. Pinch-hitting in these situations is a challenge,
Ong admits.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a life Ong would have liked to live forever, but ``it
was a chance to learn a lot about how America works and see a good
part of the country for a single guy.'' (He has since married
Kimberly Norton, whom he met in Florida and who is now his pastry
chef.)
</P>
<P>
   Ong already had a handle on how hotel kitchens work in other
parts of the world. The son of a professional couple in Malaysia,
he wasn't interested in an academic career. After graduating from a
Catholic high school, he headed for Kuala Lumpur and a job as a
banquet server at the huge Shangri-La Hotel. His ambition was to
get into the ``controlled chaos'' of the 600-cook kitchen. The chef
finally gave in to his pleadings and told the 17-year-old to report
to the kitchen the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got myself properly outfitted in chef's whites,'' Ong
recallstells &LR;  with a grin. ``The chef took one look at me and said,
`Now get out of that uniform and put on a dishwasher's shirt.' It
was humbling, but I wasn't about to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers couldn't understand why a son of the middle class
would want to be a menial laborer. `` `You could work in a nice
office,' they used to tell me.'' But he persisted. Three months
later, when a prep cook left, he got his chance.
</P>
<P>
   From then on Ong's career has spiraled ever upwards. Wanting to
work in the United States but not being able to obtain a visa _
``it's not like high-tech workers; cooks are a dime a dozen'' _ he
settled for a position in Bermuda. It wasn't a bad life _ good pay
undiminished by taxes, no rent and free food. With a British
Commonwealth passport, ``We could fly to New York in the morning,
shop in Chinatown, have two lunches and be back in our dormitory by
night.''
</P>
<P>
   But the work was uninspiring _ ``three-bean salad straight from
the can,'' he explains with a comic little shudder _ so he jumped
at an offer from the Atlanta Ritz-Carlton, later transferring to
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Always looking for new challenges, there followed stints at
Caesar's Tahoe, Orocco East-West Supper Club in San Francisco's
Richmond District, in friend Chris Yeo's Straits Cafe, at Stars and
briefly as opening chef at Le Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   When longtime acquaintance, restaurant entrepreneur George Chen
(who owns Betelnut, Shanghai 1930, Long Life Noodle Co.), invited
him into a new venture, Xanadu, he saw new opportunities. He helped
design the place and, with Chen, took a nonstop eating jaunt across
Asia, gathering ideas for the menu they call RestorAsian.
</P>
<P>
   Like the master of the mythical Xanadu (in historic reality,
Shang-tu), the restaurant embraces all the regions of Kublai Khan's
far-flung empire.
</P>
<P>
   Between these pan-Asian inspirations and Ong's classic French
training and Malaysian sensibilities, creating a fusion menu
slanted toward restorative combinations was a natural. But Ong
doesn't strive for an Asian version of a healthy-crunchy approach.
He doesn't get into Chinese herbalism and he asserts that yin and
yang are all very well _ up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food,'' he says, ``has to taste good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PAN-ROASTED DUCK BREAST WITH SPICY MANGO SALSA
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dark mushroom soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 star anise
</P>
<P>
   4 whole cardamom pods
</P>
<P>
   4 duck breasts, about 6 to 7 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apricot preserves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup whole-grain mustard
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   12 spears grilled or blanched asparagus
</P>
<P>
   Mango Salsa (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the marinade:  &LR; Stir the sugar into the warm water until
completely dissolved. Add the soy sauce, star anise and cardamom.
Let cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Add the duck breasts and let marinate for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sauce:  &LR; Meanwhile, combine the cranberries, apricot
preserves, mustard and coconut milk in a saucepan. Bring to a boil,
reduce heat and simmer slowly for a few minutes until the sauce
thickens and coats the back of a spoon. Let cool for about 8
minutes, then puree in a blender. Season with lime juice and salt.
Keep the sauce warm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To cook the duck:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Remove the
duck breasts from the marinade and dry on paper towels. Heat the
vegetable oil in a heavy pan until almost smoking. Sear the breasts
skin-side down for about 1 minute over high heat. Turn and sear the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the duck breasts to a roasting pan and roast until done
to your liking: about 10 minutes for rare meat, 13 minutes for
medium. Let rest 8 minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Place 3 asparagus spears on each serving plate.
Spoon equal portions of the sauce over the asparagus. Slice the
duck breasts on the diagonal and fan out over the asparagus. Place
a spoonful of Mango Salsa on each serving of duck. Pass the
remaining salsa at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (without sauce): &LR;   &LR; 255 calories, &LR;   &LR; 34 g protein, 2
g &LR;   &LR; carbohydrate, 11 g fat (4 g saturated), 142 mg cholesterol,
138 &LR;   &LR; mg sodium, 0 fiber. Note: The calories and other nutrients &LR; 
 &LR; absorbed from marinades vary and are difficult to estimate. &LR; 
 &LR; Variables include the type of food, marinating time and amount &LR; 
 &LR; of surface area. Therefore, the marinade is not included in &LR;   &LR; this
analysis. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SAUCE, PER TABLESPOON: &LR;  36 calories, 0 protein, 5 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 2 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 21 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MANGO SALSA
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 large ripe mangoes, peeled and cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 red jalapeno pepper, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cilantro leaves, cut in chiffonade
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Thai basil leaves, cut in chiffonade
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mint leaves, cut in chiffonade
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the diced mango and jalapeno in a bowl. Add the herbs to
the bowl and toss to combine. Season with salt and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 31/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 5 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 1 g carbohydrate, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 0 sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MARK ZEITOUNI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Kim Severson &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Some chefs are driven to nourish people. Others simply love food.
For Mark Zeitouni, it's all about art.
</P>
<P>
   That makes sense, since the 29-year-old protege of Fifth Floor
chef George Morrone spent much of his time in college studying fine
art.
</P>
<P>
   Zeitouni fell into cooking as a way to make a living while he
was doing something else. He started working in kitchens in high
school and continued while an art student at the University of
Florida. He eventually dropped out and decided to attend the
culinary arts program at Johnson &AMP; Wales University, graduating
magna cum laude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to see food as artistic medium,'' he says. ``You can
put a lot of creative energy into one day of being a chef. You
don't have to wait three months to sell a painting to get that
satisfaction of pleasing someone with your art. There's immediate
gratification.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of April, Zeitouni left his job as the opening chef
at Berkeley's French-styled Bistro Viola. This month finds him
helping his friend Philip Kaufman open Soleil in Palo Alto's Westin
Hotel and spending two weeks filling in for a vacationing Morrone
at Fifth Floor.
</P>
<P>
   Morrone has played a central role in Zeitouni's development as a
chef. Zeitouni worked under Morrone for three years, first at the
Delano Hotel in Miami Beach and later at One Market in San
Francisco. Zeitouni then spent a year in the executive chef slot at
Reed Hearon's Black Cat in North Beach before moving across the
bay.
</P>
<P>
   Zeitouni and Bistro Viola's owner, Pat Bryant agree that they
parted ways on good terms. The restaurant is changing to a more
neighborhood-style bistro, and Zeitouni wants a chance to further
develop and showcase his style.
</P>
<P>
   His food is subtle, allowing the focus to stay on the
ingredients rather than cooking style or cunning combinations. His
dishes are light on starch and highlight one or two elements _ the
broth in a baby vegetable pot-au-feu is not much more than lightly
seasoned stock perfumed with vegetables; grilled salmon is dressed
in the barest of outfits _ lemon vinaigrette, parsnip puree and
grilled asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've used the word feminine before,'' he says. ``I don't use
brash flavors. It's very French with interesting twists.''
</P>
<P>
   He loves cooking in the Bay Area because the emphasis is on
top-drawer ingredients. Vegetables' quality, for example, allows
them to be the highlight of a dish, rather than a supporting
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be just a carrot,'' he says, ``but it's this
beautiful, round, perfect baby carrot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BLEU DE CHEVRE &AMP; WATERCRESS PAN SOUFFLE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch watercress
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup + 1 teaspoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   8 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   8 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1 cup crumbled blue de chevre, or other blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 ripe tomatoes, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Trim off any yellowed leaves
and tough stems from watercress. Chop half of the watercress
(you'll need approximately 1 cup); set the remainder aside for
garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the 1/2 cup butter in a heavy-gauge saucepan. Add the
flour, cornstarch and salt and cook over medium-low heat, stirring
constantly, until the mixture forms a paste. Transfer to the bowl
of an electric mixer, and with the mixer on low speed, slowly add
the milk and egg yolks. Mix until well blended.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg whites until they hold stiff peaks. Fold the whites
into the batter, then fold in the chopped watercress.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the 1 teaspoon butter in a nonstick 6- or 8-inch saute pan.
Add the batter and cook over medium heat until the souffle is
slightly colored on the edges, similar to a pancake. Scatter the
crumbled cheese over the top, then place the pan in the oven for a
couple of minutes until the eggs set up and the cheese softens.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a serving plate; garnish with tomato wedges and
watercress sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 630 calories, &LR;   &LR; 24 g protein, 33 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 46 g fat (25 g saturated), 518 mg cholesterol,
1,313 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
