<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-1STLD-W     05-09 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WITNESS: REILLY `HAPPY AS A FOX' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: FIXES lede, changing papers' to paper's)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A newspaper consultant for Clint Reilly, who has
brought an antitrust suit to block the Hearst Corp. from buying the
San Francisco Chronicle, acknowledged Tuesday that when he filed a
sworn declaration saying that local publisher Ted Fang would need a
$50 million a year subsidy to successfully publish the San
Francisco Examiner, he included only the paper's costs and no
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Ingram also admitted that his declaration should have
said the Fangs would need a subsidy of ``up to'' $50 million per
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram, a former vice president of operations for the San
Francisco Newspaper Agency, which provides business operations such
as circulation, advertising, printing for the Examiner and
Chronicle, also testified that Reilly was ``happy as a fox in a hen
house'' when he learned that Hearst would offer a subsidy to the
Examiner's buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram's testimony opened the second week of trial before U.S.
District Judge Vaughn R. Walker on real estate investor and former
mayoral candidate Reilly's suit.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hockett, a lawyer for the Fang family, the
publishers of the San Francisco Independent who are seeking to buy
Hearst's Examiner, sought to show that the Fangs could successfully
publish The Examiner with a subsidy from Hearst of up to $66
million over three years.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly was an unsuccessful bidder for The Examiner. A Hearst
executive testified last week that Reilly had requested a subsidy
larger than the one offered to the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's attorney, indicated in his trial
brief that Reilly offered March 7 to buy The Examiner, seeking a
$200 million subsidy from Hearst during a six-year period.
</P>
<P>
   In cross-examination, Hockett asked Ingram about a Feb. 13
e-mail Ingram wrote after speaking with Reilly, who was then
negotiating with Hearst and had just learned that Hearst was
willing to give a subsidy to the Examiner's buyer.
</P>
<P>
   In the e-mail, Ingram said: ``I talked with Clint late last
night. He was happy as a fox in a hen house.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockett asked Ingram why was Reilly was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know much about foxes,'' Ingram replied.
</P>
<P>
   Hockett shot back, ``It's not because they're about to do
something good for the public, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Walker interjected that the question was argumentative, and
Hockett withdrew it.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which will decide the future of San Francisco's daily
newspapers, is scheduled to run through the end of this week.
Witnesses are expected to include Hearst President Frank Bennack,
Fang and Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst was expected to begin putting its defense case on
Tuesday, a Hearst lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends Hearst's plan to buy the morning Chronicle for
$660
</P>
<P>
   million and to sell its smaller afternoon Examiner to the Fang
family will
</P>
<P>
   give Hearst the only metropolitan daily newspaper based in San
Francisco, which he says would be an illegal monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly claims Hearst's proposal to sell The Examiner to the
Fangs for $100 and give them a subsidy of up to $66 million to
defray publishing costs is a ``sham,'' because the subsidy is
insufficient and The Examiner will fail.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto claims Hearst's purchase violates federal antitrust laws
and the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, a lawyer for Hearst, has argued that The Examiner
could not survive outside its profit-sharing agreement with the
Chronicle, and that because it is an economically failing
enterprise Hearst legally may shut it or sell it and buy the
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Halling also has denied that Hearst's sale of The Examiner to
the Fangs is a sham, and says Hearst is not required to give any
buyer a subsidy. Halling has said Hearst gave the Fangs a subsidy
to satisfy concerns of local politicians, who have said San
Francisco should have at least two daily papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs, who publish the free, three-times-a week Independent,
also have denied The Examiner deal is a sham.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony last week, Examiner publisher Timothy O. White said
he had offered San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown favorable editorial
treatment in return for Brown's support of Hearst's plan to buy the
Chronicle. Hearst put White on indefinite leave and is
investigating whether White violated journalistic ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Other testimony showed that The Examiner earned a $20.5 million
profit last year under its profit-splitting agreement with the
Chronicle. Hearst executives, however, testified that if Hearst had
to carry its full publishing costs outside the agreement it would
lose money.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, Hearst and the Chronicle Publishing Co. have had a
joint operating agreement under which they share printing,
circulation and marketing and all revenue from both papers. After
paying shared costs, they split the remainder, and each paper pays
the costs of its independent editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements are allowed under the Newspaper Preservation Act,
which was meant to keep alive newspapers that otherwise might fail
so communities could benefit from multiple editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, representatives of both Hearst and the Chronicle said
that one of the papers would likely fold if they were forced to
economically compete against each other.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was set to expire in 2005, but the Chronicle's
owners decided to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto has argued that Hearst abused its position in the joint
operating agreement to ward off other potential bidders for the
Chronicle and gain an unfair advantage buying the paper. Both
Hearst and the Chronicle have denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
   The trial on Reilly's suit is the nation's first on a challenge
to the breakup of a joint operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle is the nation's 12th largest daily newspaper, with
a circulation of 465,535. The Examiner's circulation is 108,986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
