<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0282 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-BRADY-HNS &LR;      05-09 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BRADY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DON'T MISS `GROWING UP BRADY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pure cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually nothing redeemable for the majority of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours of your life you will never, ever get back.
</P>
<P>
   What we're saying is, don't miss ``Growing Up Brady'' (9 p.m.
Sunday, May 21, WNYT Ch. 13), the behind-the-scenes drama about the
actors who made up that bunch of Bradys.
</P>
<P>
   The continued interest in and passion for ``The Brady Bunch''
serves as a perfect metaphor for the longings of baby boomers, as
fortysomethings ache to cleanse the unsavory memories of their
youths in the timeless fountain of wholesome, family-friendly
values.
</P>
<P>
   That's one possibility. More likely, ``The Brady Bunch'' adds up
to nothing more than a stupid sitcom that's managed to run ad
nauseam for the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a cynical time in the '70s,'' said Barry Williams,
still known today simply as Greg. ``The Bradys was out of step with
all of that. What we're experiencing now is a nostalgic look at a
time in people's lives that was nicer, more innocent, less
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia, that is, not for the lives we led, but the lives we
watched on TV. Williams, in a conference call with reporters,
cautions that ``The Brady Bunch'' isn't meant to be a philisophical
touchstone. Thanks for the heads-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important with `The Brady Bunch' ... to not make
it more than it is,'' Williams said. The actor _ who often referred
to the 1969-'74 show in the present tense _ said it was an
unpretentious, idealistic family sitcom with a light moral flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Embrace the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   If you have no experience growing up with ``The Brady Bunch''
(once part of ABC's tremendous Friday-night lineup that for a time
included ``The Partridge Family,'' ``Room 222,'' ``The Odd Couple''
and ``Love, American Style''), there's no reason to watch this
behind-the-scenes biofilm.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're of the right age group, or have seen the endless
reruns _ or the Saturday morning cartoon, or the television movies,
or the lesser spinoff series ``The Brady Wives'' and ``The Bradys''
_ this biopic is worth watching just to see:
</P>
<P>
   _ Greg make out with Marcia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan and Peter go on a date.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cindy and Bobby get married (calm down; it was during the
show's first year).
</P>
<P>
   _ Greg go on a date with his mother, Carol. (You da man!)
</P>
<P>
   _ What happened to Tiger _ and it's not good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cousin Oliver _ that insufferable late addition to the cast _
not mentioned for the whole two hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Greg make out with Marcia.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it: Your first reaction to the Greg-Marcia liaison is
``Iiicck _ they're brother and sister.'' (While some chronology and
minor facts were changed, Williams said the one piece of history he
really wanted to rewrite was the details of his relationship with
Maureen McCormick.) We just saw the characters, never bothering
with the actors playing them; this film breaks down the walls we've
erected between the Bradys and the real people.
</P>
<P>
   Williams served as co-executive producer on ``Growing Up
Brady,'' which is based on his 1992 book (subtitled ``I was a
Teenage Greg''). He calls the treatment affectionate yet honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a point of speaking to each of the cast members ...
about the nature of the project,'' Williams said. ``We're not
dealing with the characters in this movie; we're dealing with the
people. My movie picks up when the (TV show's) director yells
`Cut.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the movie is about as deep as the show, and makes no
attempt to slash and burn anyone. Some of the other main actors
cooperated on the project; McCormick, however, was notably absent.
</P>
<P>
   And after the two theatrical ``Brady Bunch'' movies that ripped
this eminently rippable show, you can understand the reluctance of
the original cast to being involved with any ``Brady'' project.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been so much goofing on `The Brady Bunch,' so much
spoofing ... I wanted to reassure (the cast) that was not this
story,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Notables in the cast-playing-the-cast include Michael Tucker
(``L.A. Law'') as the eminently patient executive producer Sherwood
Schwartz (the real Schwartz makes a cameo at the end of the film)
and Scott Lookalind, who plays his look-alike dad Michael Lookalind
(Bobby).
</P>
<P>
   The other original cast members are portrayed, although it was
disappointing not to see more screen time for the actress playing
Schenectady's Ann B. Davis (the maid Alice Nelson). As Robert Reed,
Daniel Hugh Kelly (``Oh Baby'') gets the most dramatic role: Reed
was a serious actor who was constantly upset by the series'
juvenile scripts, a gay man uncomfortable with kissing Henderson,
but a performer who always showed a genuine paternal affection for
his fellow cast members.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Growing Up Brady'' we don't see the actors playing the
actors; we finally see the actors who played Greg and Marcia and
Jan, Peter, Bobby and Cindy as people. While ``certain members are
intent on distancing themselves from the show,'' Williams said, he
embraces his fate. He will always be Greg Brady _ so why not make
some money off of it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful,'' Williams said. ``It would be looking the gift
horse in the mouth to say, `Gee, I had this great hit record, but I
don't want to sing it anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   After not one but two ``Partridge Family'' movies this season,
plus another ``Brady Bunch'' behind-the-scenes drama slated for Fox
on May 16, we don't want to hear the song of the '70s sitcoms too
much longer.
</P>
<P>
   But like ``Stairway to Heaven'' _ and those Kraft individual
slices in the back of the fridge _ it's comforting to know they're
there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
