<HEADER>
A0283 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-CONGRESS-NAT     05-09 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CONGRESS-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  By Alex Canizares
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 9 - A key House vote over whether to ease
sanctions on food and medicine trade to to Cuba and other terrorist
countries is expected to ignite ideological tensions today.
</P>
<P>
   The case against the 40-year-old sanctions against Cuba gained
momentum yesterday as the Senate Appropriations Committee passed an
amendment to exempt food and medicine from the embargo that bars
U.S. businesses from trading with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   A House version passed subcommittee last week, sending it to the
full Appropriations committee for what is expected to be a divisive
debate and a close vote. If it passes, it would go to the House
floor for a vote late next week.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of easing sanctions, including Representative J.
Joseph Moakley, Democrat of South Boston, argue a change is needed
in a policy, they say, harms Cuban people by denying them basic
agricultural goods and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 40 years, it is clear it hasn't worked,'' said the
bill's Senate sponsor, Senator Byron Dorgan, a North Dakota
Democrat. ``This embargo only hurts poor people and sick people.''
</P>
<P>
   The push among U.S. businesses eager to tap unopened markets to
ease sanctions against Cuba, Libya, Iran and other nations where
trade is probibited has intensified since a similar bill to the one
before the Congress was introduced last year.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill fell three votes short of passage in a
House-Senate conference last year when House Republicans removed
Cuba from the measure, despite heavy lobbying from the American
Farm Bureau and the United States Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders in the House Appropriations Committee said they
intended to kill the measure again, saying they opposed granting
concessions to Cuban leader Fidel Castro along ideological - rather
than economic -- grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone thinks poor people of Cuba will benefit from lifted
sanctions they are totally wrong,'' said the committee's chair,
Representative C.W. Young, a Florida Republican. ``I'm not prepared
to give Castro one inch.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Tom DeLay, Republican of Texas and the House
Majority Whip, sent letters yesterday urging other yesterday to
vote against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Appropriations Committee is the wrong venue for debating
this issue,'' DeLay said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   The provision, introduced by Representative George Nethercutt,
Republican of Washington, lifts restrictions on trade between U.S.
business and Cuba, Iran, Libya, Sudan and North Korea. It includes
a provision allowing the president to unilaterally cut off food and
medicine sales in areas where hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with Cuba?,'' said Moakley, who led a
fact-finding delegation of academics and cultural organizations to
Cuba last month and supports lifting the entire embargo. ``We trade
with China _ When you see every country trading with Cuba, that
kind of waters down your embargo.''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley, who is the ranking Democrat on the Rules committee that
would receive the bill before it goes to the floor for a vote, said
he would defend the bill from what he said would be a ``hard
fight'' there from Cuban-American Representative Lincoln
Diaz-Balart, a Florida Republican who is against easing sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsor, Representative George Nethercutt, Republican
of Washington is counting on at least 24 supporters from last
year's vote to vote for the measure. The committee's ranking
Democrat, Representative David Obey of Wisconsin, who voted against
last year's bill, would support the bill today, said spokeswoman
Kori Hardin.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
