<HEADER>
A0285 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SCHILLER-THEATER-$ADV     05-09 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHILLER-THEATER-$ADV14-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING SCHILLER STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH 
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To literate Europeans of the 19th century, the poet, playwright
and historian Friedrich Schiller (1759-1805) ranked right up with
Shakespeare, an idol he honored not only by conscious imitation but
also in a translation of ``Macbeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, even in his native Germany, Schiller's works for the
stage survive mostly as refracted through operas by Rossini, Verdi
and Tchaikovsky _ a mere handful of the dozens their revolutionary
idealism inspired. Over the last half century, ``Don Carlos,''
formerly a pillar of the classical German canon, has gone into
eclipse, even as the majestically flawed Franco-Italian epic by
Verdi has moved from the fringe of the repertory very nearly into
the center.
</P>
<P>
   Once a classic, now a footnote. And tomorrow?
</P>
<P>
   From May 16 through May 20 at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, a
brief run of the play by the Royal Shakespeare Company provides a
rare chance to take our Schiller straight. Straight, that is,
within the parameters of a production that Gale Edwards has
directed in modern dress, and a verse translation by Robert David
MacDonald that was described by one London critic as ``fleet,
colloquial but often remarkably resonant'' _ phrases of limited
application to Schiller's original. (Resonant his language is,
fleet it can be, colloquial it is not.)
</P>
<P>
   The production could prove a revelation for theater fans and
opera buffs alike. The case, it bears noting, resembles that of
Verdi's late Shakespearean masterpieces not at all. To know
``Otello'' and ``Falstaff'' is in some sense to know their
Shakespearean prototypes. To know ``Don Carlos'' through Verdi is
hardly to know the play.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the five principal characters in the stage version form the
constellation familiar from the opera. The icy, tyrannical King
Philip II of Spain, old enough to be the father or grandfather of
his historical counterpart and gnawed by private griefs and doubts.
Elizabeth of Valois, his virtuous queen, the pawn of royal
matrimonial politics, once betrothed (as in truth she was) to
Philip's high-strung son, Don Carlos, whose feelings for her remain
those of a desperate lover. The Marquis of Posa, the prince's close
friend, drawn fatally into the gravitational field of the king.
Princess Eboli, the king's mistress, enamored of the prince.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the action are the prince's deranged attempts to
recapture the queen's heart, and Posa's effort to win the prince
for his own, no less dangerous, cause: religious independence for
the Spanish-occupied Low Countries.
</P>
<P>
   The big political picture _ the thought police of the
reactionary church and state ranged against the upstart
libertarians of faraway Flanders _ is another constant carried over
from the play to the opera. But in the overall plotting, general
matters of style and tone and strategic use of spectacle, not to
mention countless minute particulars, the libretto Joseph Mery and
Camille du Locle fashioned for Verdi takes lordly liberties.
</P>
<P>
   With transparently ``operatic'' intent, they introduced a new
opening act, furnishing a brief idyll of bliss for Don Carlos and
Elizabeth before destiny tears them apart. They punctuated the
play's succession of mainly private scenes with big public episodes
(including a brutal auto-da-fe) and major opportunities for the
chorus. Cutting and pasting with abandon, they eliminated lesser
roles, not always improving the dramatic logic. Nor did they spare
the principal figures, either.
</P>
<P>
   En route to the opera house, Elizabeth (who to the prince's
chagrin is forever being referred to as his mother) lost the
children she has in Schiller's play, which perhaps renders her a
more plausible object of romantic devotion but no longer sharpens
the terms of her conflict between desire and duty. Less usefully,
they excised cloak-and-dagger absurdities in the final scene (Don
Carlos dresses up as his grandfather's ghost) in favor of a botched
trick ending of their own.
</P>
<P>
   We have yet to factor in the music, which paints a succession of
powerfully contrasting frescoes in an inexhaustible palette of
ravishing colors. Not only that. Verdi's genius for melody and
cadence means that each character has a personal voice _ a trait
foreign to the play, in which, by design, everyone speaks (as it
were) the same language.
</P>
<P>
   The consistency of tone in the play ``Don Carlos'' (ceremonious,
rhetorical, unsullied by the wit, grit and malapropisms that
energize Shakespeare) is one hint of many that its true home is not
the playhouse but the study. Schiller called ``Don Carlos'' neither
play nor tragedy but ``a dramatic poem,'' thus a medium less for
actors than for the voice of the poet. That voice, and it alone, is
Schiller's ``music.''
</P>
<P>
   The poem's genesis lasted some five years, yielding five acts
totaling 5,370 lines of blank verse _ the equivalent of three
full-length plays of Racine. (A prose version prepared by the
playwright exists.) The world premiere, in 1787 when Schiller was
not yet 30, was a triumph. Still, the advance publication of
drafted scenes (some with stage directions of all but novelistic
density), as well as a series of 12 open letters by the playwright
in response to criticism, are ample evidence that ``Don Carlos''
was a literary _ even philosophical _ phenomenon at least as much
as it was a theatrical one.
</P>
<P>
   A true son of the Enlightenment, Schiller abominated absolutism
and deified civil liberty. Virtually all he wrote _ ``Don Carlos''
emphatically included _ forms part of his lifelong manifesto
against tyranny in all its forms: personal, social, political and
ecclesiastical.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to perform the full text have been few. Huge cuts were
a necessity from the start, and while salvaging the plot is quite
easy, crucial qualities of the dialogue inevitably suffer.
Schiller's polished blank verse (often indistinguishable from his
friend Goethe's) sits curiously with the stuttering, jumpy movement
of the characters' thought. When speeches run long (and they often
do), it is not because a person has complicated new information to
impart but because that person is at a loss to seize a clear
thought from a blur of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   A spectator, or even a reader pedantically parsing the
ambiguities on the printed page, may well encounter the same
difficulty, further aggravated by mechanics of the plot. A flurry
of highly sensitive letters, amorous and political (anonymous,
misinterpreted, deliberately deceptive) generate no end of smoke.
The players' myriad naive or optimistic misreadings of others'
temperament or motives add that much more. Within the gloomy cloud
of unknowing, a simple, declarative sentence shines like a beacon.
``I need love.'' &QC; ``He thinks 'tis proven.'' ``She is false.'' ``The
king has wept.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of these lines is spoken by the prince early on, the
third by his father, deep into the drama. The second, summing up
the problem with Posa, belongs to Domingo, the king's Machiavellian
father-confessor, the last to Count Lerma, head of the royal
bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller's debts to Shakespeare take many forms _ literary
allusion, outright quotation and patterns of metaphor among them.
But most Shakespearean of all is his attention to subsidiary
players. In ``Don Carlos,'' the most imposing of them is the Grand
Inquisitor, an evil deus ex machina, 90 years old, blind and yet
still capable of crushing the proud Philip by superior intellect
and brute force of will.
</P>
<P>
   Two lesser dignitaries are the subjects of master portraits: the
military commander the Duke of Alba, whose iron-fisted rule of
Flanders the prince in his starry-eyed delusions proposes to
supplant with a tolerant regime of his own; and Lerma, captain of
the royal bodyguard, who finds ways to reconcile his loyalty to the
king with dangerous, unsolicited confidences to the prince.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
