<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0286 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SCHILLER-THEATER-$ADV     05-09 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHILLER-THEATER-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: the prince.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of others, Schiller offers quicker, still brilliant sketches:
the Duke of Medina Sidonia, the undisgraced admiral of the lost
armada; Don Raimond of Taxis, postmaster in chief, under whose
eagle eye no private correspondence is secure; the Marquesa of
Mondecar, who loves her bullfights and burning heretics. Eboli's
popinjay of a page comes in for a brilliant miniature.
</P>
<P>
   These are characters who leap off the printed page. From the
perspective of the study, the principals' jobs look much harder.
Don Carlos, Schiller's answer to Hamlet, caroms from self-pity to
mad elation, his heart forever on his sleeve; what triggers Eboli's
infatuation and Posa's self-sacrificial devotion is hard to fathom.
King Philip, whose emotional world collapses not quite as painfully
as Lear's, weathers his storms and knuckles under to the
Inquisition, sacrificing love to power.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen's impressive integrity does more to put others in
their place (the aged Philip among them) than to win admiration or
sympathy for herself. Spurned by the prince, Schiller's Eboli
negotiates the surrender of her virginity to the king with the
sangfroid of a geisha. Verdi's more formidable Eboli is Philip's
mistress from the start _ and has Arab-scented songs to sing that
make her much more alluring.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Posa, who has reminded some of Hamlet's schoolmate
Horatio, the beloved friend to whom the prince can bare his soul.
The resemblance, if granted, is rather strained. Horatio is a
witness, Posa a provocateur _ one, moreover, who to his own
astonishment captures the eye and heart of his friend's mortal
enemy, the king. The position is, of course, untenable.
</P>
<P>
   Verdi reconfigures Posa as the exemplar of friendship, virtue
and selfless tolerance. The character starts out that way in the
play, but royal favor goes to his head, and soon he is spinning out
of control, play-acting a betrayal of the prince in a suicidal
attempt to save him. In truth, though even the prince is fooled for
a while, the one Posa betrays is the king. Philip and Don Carlos
carry on over his corpse like rival widows.
</P>
<P>
   To the bitter end, Posa's mantra is humanity. Never does he
surrender the dream of a future when thought will be free _ a
future of which he elects his self-centered, undisciplined friend,
of all people, as architect. A German wit once called the character
``ein Prinzip im Trikot,'' a doctrine in tights.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been in the days of old-fashioned costume drama.
Can an actor in modern clothes turn him into flesh and blood? Soon
we will know.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, this ``Don Carlos'' could open the door for a later
and greater dramatic poem of Schiller's: ``Wallenstein,'' his epic
trilogy of the Thirty Years' War, a more challenging and more
purposefully chaotic proposition. Tim Albery staged the work's
belated, drastically cut professional British premiere (some three
hours out of seven), at the Pit, the Royal Shakespeare Company's
second London stage, seven years ago. ``In every sense a great
occasion,'' said The Guardian. ``A long slog,'' countered The Times
of London.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps now it is time for a full treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Do it, England. You have the actors, and Germany lacks the will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
