<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0290 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PENRY-JONES-THEATER-$     05-09 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENRY-JONES-THEATER-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A SURPRISE HIT IN 18TH-CENTURY GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) 
 (Editors: See also SCHILLER-THEATER) 
 By MATT WOLF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When Rupert Penry-Jones first started reading ``Don
Carlos,'' the Friedrich Schiller play that brings him to New York
this week, he was only three pages into it before he thought:
``This is too long, too wordy.''
</P>
<P>
   But after another 10 pages or so, as Penry-Jones, a 29-year-old
English actor, recollects it: ``I couldn't put it down. I thought:
`It's like a medieval soap opera. There's nothing frightening about
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been the best reviews to date of Penry-Jones'
career, as well as a surprise hit for the Royal Shakespeare Company
in a realm _ 18th-century German expressionism _ not often explored
by Britain's heavyweight theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Carlos'' will be presented by the RSC at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music's Harvey Lichtenstein Theater for five
performances beginning May 16, as part of the troupe's residency
this month at BAM. (The final offering, ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream,'' opens there May 21.)
</P>
<P>
   As the title character, Penry-Jones plays a young Spanish prince
during the Inquisition who is smitten to the point of Hamlet-like
derangement with Elizabeth of Valois, his father the king's third
wife. Cast as the queen is Josette Simon, the willowy English
actress who first gained attention in London about a decade ago as
the first black Maggie in Arthur Miller's play ``After the Fall.''
</P>
<P>
   History tells us that the real Don Carlos died in questionable
circumstances in 1568 at the age of 23. More to the point, the
actual Spanish prince was known for being not just mentally
unstable but physically deformed, in marked contrast to
Penry-Jones' good looks. ``Don Carlos is always played by a
handsome boy,'' said the play's director, Gale Edwards, laughing.
``That's the terrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has an extensive resume in musical theater and opera.
She is currently represented on Broadway by the new revival of
Andrew Lloyd Webber's ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' at the Ford Center
for the Performing Arts, while her London version of the same
composer's ``Whistle Down the Wind'' starts its third year on the
West End in July. Neither production received great reviews, to put
it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   According to Edwards, a 45-year-old Australian who has lived for
the last six years in London, ``Don Carlos'' illustrates far better
``where my heart is'' than do the Lloyd Webber shows. That
affiliation, she said, ``has been relatively recent and, in
percentage terms, is quite small compared with other work.'' She
has also directed Lord Lloyd-Webber's ``Aspects of Love'' in
Australia and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a classical director first and foremost,'' Edwards said.
``The gravity of most of my work has been classical theater; the
musical stuff is the flotation in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, why Schiller, a writer whose work, as Edwards
acknowledges, ``is obscure enough at the best of times''?
</P>
<P>
   She came to the play, she said, through opera, directing
Donizetti's ``Maria Stuarda'' for the English National Opera in
London in 1998. Edwards found herself steeped in Schiller _ and not
just ``Mary Stuart,'' on which Donizetti's 1834 opera is based.
(``Don Carlos,'' of course, has inspired its own opera, the Verdi
treatment of 1867.)
</P>
<P>
   Edwards read ``Don Carlos'' and reacted strongly to it. ``God,
this is a great play,'' she recalled thinking to herself. ``But
it's about 5{ hours long and very dense. There's probably a rather
brilliant three-hour play here.'' She ultimately took her proposal
to the Royal Shakespeare Company. Several years before, she had
worked there, directing a well-regarded production of ``The White
Devil,'' Webster's 1612 Jacobean classic. In choosing an
English-language text for Schiller's play, Edwards opted for an
existing translation _ by Robert David MacDonald, a Scottish writer
and director _ which she has trimmed.
</P>
<P>
   The Webster and Schiller plays, Edwards said, have much in
common, starting with a similar density, not to mention a shared
focus on bloodletting as well as issues of tyranny and injustice.
In the fall, she will return to the RSC to direct a third play,
Webster's ``Duchess of Malfi,'' in what Edwards regards as an
informal but identifiable theatrical triptych.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the three plays is concerned with a system threatened
by a free thinker, a free spirit,'' she said. ``And in each case,
the system wins. They are dark, bloody political stories _ as well
as three of the most difficult plays ever written, in terms of
carrying an audience through a labyrinthine plot and an incredibly
bleak view of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was with something approaching delighted surprise that
critics and audiences alike responded to ``Don Carlos,'' first in
Stratford last June and then in London in January. ``Theater at its
most theatrical,'' said Michael Billington in The Guardian. The
performances led Charles Spencer in The Daily Telegraph to praise
``the RSC at the very top of its form.'' Penry-Jones, he said,
possessed ``the brooding intensity of a heart-throb star.''
</P>
<P>
   Penry-Jones' portrait of the distraught prince follows
celebrated appearances at the National Theater in 1997 in Arnold
Wesker's ``Chips With Everything'' and at the Almeida Theater in
1998 as the tearful, anxious father in Edward Albee's ``Play About
the Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schiller production has also helped remind London audiences
of the authority of John Woodvine, the British stage veteran who
plays the unyielding Philip II of Spain .
</P>
<P>
   ``The narrative drive is certainly fantastic,'' said Woodvine
about Schiller's story, especially, he added, given that Schiller
``is probably known no more in England than in America.'' Beethoven
lovers, of course, know Schiller's ``Ode to Joy'' from the last
movement of the Ninth Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   So here he is, at 70, returning to a city in which he last
appeared on Broadway in 1981 in ``Nicholas Nickleby'' as Uncle
Ralph. ( Woodvine's wife, Lynn Farleigh, was seen earlier this
month in the first RSC production of its season at BAM, T.S.
Eliot's ``Family Reunion.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been wonderful for me,'' said Woodvine of his latest
role. ``There aren't too many parts this good for an elderly
gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
