<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CHAIRS-ANTIQUES-ART-$     05-09 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAIRS-ANTIQUES-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBJECTS THAT COULD FURNISH A PENTHOUSE FOR FRED AND GINGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RITA REIF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After the discovery was made in February, John C.
Waddell, a New York collector and retired businessman, said it was
like finding ``Tut's tomb beyond the attic door of a little
Monopoly house in Queens.'' It happened when a dealer came to the
house in New Hyde Park to buy valuables and, finding none, was told
to inspect the attic.
</P>
<P>
   There he discovered a long-lost American Modern treasure from
1938: the first plastic shell chair ever made. Actually, there were
two of them. The shimmering chairs with curvy clear-plastic seats
framed in tubular steel were handmade prototypes of Gilbert Rohde's
least-well-known and most innovative design. The chairs represented
a futuristic approach to furniture design, using Plexiglas, a new
acrylic plastic made by the chemical company Rohm and Haas, for
whom Rohde worked as a consultant. The chairs were publicized
during the 1939 World's Fair in New York but were never
manufactured because Plexiglas was taken out of commercial use by
the federal government and diverted for windshields of military
aircraft when war broke out in Europe that year.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell and other American Modern enthusiasts had known of the
existence of the chair for decades, but only from photographs. ``No
one knew whether the chair had been produced or whether the
prototypes had survived,'' Waddell said. No one realized that two
such chairs were hidden away in an attic of a sister-in-law of
Rohde, probably since he died in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell was among the first to be told of the discovery and
within days bought one of the chairs. The other was bought by Mark
McDonald, a New York dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Now both chairs are on view in New York. Waddell's in ``American
Modern, 1925-1940: Design for a New Age,'' an exhibition of 175
objects at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, 120 of which are gifts
Waddell has made to the museum or has promised to make in the
future. The show, which remains through Jan. 7, 2001, was organized
by the museum and the American Federation of Arts and will travel
nationally through 2002. McDonald's chair is on display at his
Gansevoort Gallery in the West Village.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell's gifts to the Metropolitan Museum have left many empty
spaces in his New York apartment. But this will not end his
collecting of American Modern objects. ``I intend to keep buying as
long as I can afford it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he would sorely miss the Rohde chair because ``my
favorite is always the last piece I bought.'' But there are many
other rare pieces that will also be missed: a 1927 desk with a
stepped form, inspired by a skyscraper, by Paul Frankl; a 1934
stainless steel and Bakelite triangular coffee pot and creamer from
a service by Helen A. Hughes Dulany; a boldly graphic 1928
``Step-On-It'' penny scale by Joseph Sinel and a sleek cone-shaded
floor lamp by Walter von Nessen, also from 1928.
</P>
<P>
   The lamp was Waddell's first American Modern acquisition 25
years ago, when he had no idea he would start a collection of that
genre. ``I don't think anyone has a fully formed agenda when they
begin buying in a new category,'' he said. The American Modern
appealed to him because he had tired of the French Art Deco
furnishings he owned. ``Everything seemed a bit over the top,'' he
said. At the time, he was also buying American and European
photography of the 1920s and 1930s. The 500 images he collected
were valued at $2.7 million when they were acquired by the
Metropolitan Museum in 1989 from Waddell. The Ford Motor Co. paid
$1.8 million toward the purchase and Waddell donated the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell concentrated intensely on the American Modern collection
in the 1990s, especially after he retired in 1994 as president and
chairman of Arrow Electronics, the world's largest distributor of
electronic components. Two years ago he began talking with J.
Stewart Johnson, a consultant on design and architecture to the
Department of Modern Art at the Metropolitan Museum. ``I decided
that the collection belonged there,'' Waddell said. ``It was the
Metropolitan Museum that did the industrial shows in the '20s and
'30s. Those landmark exhibitions dignified the material,
popularized it and encouraged designers to work with American
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Industrial designers are well represented in Waddell's
collection, beginning with the European-born Americans Frankl and
von Nessen, who led the way in the 1920s. By 1930, American-born
designers had moved into high gear in Manhattan, streamlining,
chroming and glamorizing the newly colorful vacuum clearers,
radios, dinnerware and furniture. Norman Bel Geddes produced the
show's most iconic object, the red-white-and-blue-striped
``Patriot'' radio, manufactured by Emerson in 1940. Donald Deskey
made the black Formica and aluminum tables in the exhibition, which
were designed in 1932 for Radio City Music Hall and look elegant
enough for a palace.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he had always appreciated the urban character of
American Modern but had decided to focus on how New York was
reflected in the objects after he saw Waddell's collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I became more aware of his objects, the exhibition became
more and more a show about Astaire and Rogers,'' Johnson said.
``The people who lived in those Manhattan penthouses, they had made
it; they had arrived. That was the wonderful mystique of Manhattan,
its towers and its skyline. And John Waddell's objects bore that
out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-REAGAN-COLDWAR-NYT &LR;      05-09 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-COLDWAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT REAGAN'S ALMA MATER, HIS ROLE IN ENDING COLD WAR IS
COMMEMORATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   By ELLEN ALMER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Ill. _ Before ``The Gipper'' and the Oval Office, Ronald
Reagan washed dishes in a women's dormitory at the small college
here.
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, from his childhood home in Dixon, the 17-year-old
future president followed the pastor's daughter, on whom he'd had a
crush, and made his way to Eureka College, situated amid the
cornfields of central Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Depression, Reagan spent four of the best years of
his life at Eureka, according to both local legend and his daughter
Maureen Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, thousands on this campus of 500 students gathered here
under white and yellow tents to dedicate a new garden commemorating
a visit Reagan made here in 1982, when he proposed that the United
States and the Soviet Union begin reducing their nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The Ronald Reagan Peace Garden, which commemorates the end of
the Cold War, contains a bronze bust of the former president and a
five-by-four-foot piece of the Berlin Wall. The garden is planted
with tall, white tulips called ``Maureen'' tulips, specially chosen
to honor the former president's daughter, who has become her
father's representative here in the six years since he was
diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``This school was the first love of his life,'' Ms. Reagan said
recently as she walked across the campus.
</P>
<P>
   In the years following his graduation in 1932, Reagan, first as
a movie star, then as California governor, and finally as
president, visited the campus 14 times, attracting thousands of
people for events as ordinary as library dedications and the annual
Pumpkin Festival Parade.
</P>
<P>
   By making the disarmament proposal as part of a commencement
speech here in 1982, ``he gave them a presidential legacy,'' said
Ms. Reagan. ``He knew that's what he was doing. It was a gift only
a president could give.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan supposedly modeled the speech, which many say marked the
beginning of the end of the Cold War, after the famous ``Iron
Curtain'' speech Winston Churchill gave in 1946 at Westminster
College in Fulton, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   But critics such as Frances FitzGerald, author of the recent
book ``Way Out There in the Blue: Reagan, Star Wars, and the End of
the Cold War,'' discount the importance of the Eureka speech,
saying that Reagan's goals were far from noble, and that he was
basically forced into the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks by
anti-nuclear activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was a wonderful speech,'' FitzGerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it would seem almost impossible to tarnish the 41st
president's image at Eureka College, where his presence is felt not
just in the Ronald Reagan Museum, replete with mementos such as his
college diploma, movie posters and jelly beans; or in the imposing
Ronald and Neil Reagan Physical Education Center (named for Reagan
and his older brother, who also attended the school).
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one senses Reagan's stamp on the student body, from the
buzzing campus chapter of the Young Republicans club to the
well-groomed students who stroll the campus in button-down shirts
and ties. The former president finds his way into the curriculum,
as well; recently, a group of students on a school-sponsored trip
to Ireland visited Reagan's ancestral home in County Tipperary.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's name also brings in healthy endowments; 20 students
here are Ronald Reagan Fellows, who attend Eureka on full four-year
scholarships and participate in all-expenses-paid internships all
over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, over iced tea, Ms. Reagan regaled some of
those students with stories of horseback riding with her father at
Camp David and her own trips to Africa as an ambassador for her
father.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Ronald Reagan fellows is Jared Hansen, a 20-year-old
junior who first learned of Eureka College in the eighth grade,
while writing a history paper about Reagan. This summer he will
intern for a former Reagan Supreme Court nominee, Robert Bork, a
former federal judge who is now a legal scholar with the American
Enterprise Institute, a public policy research think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so fond of this school, he came back so many times, and
that weighs so much on people's minds,'' Hansen said of Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Other students mentioned Reagan's reputation as a campus rebel;
during his freshman year, he gave a rousing speech in the college
chapel that eventually led to the resignation of the college
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people feel that it was here he first discovered his
political voice,'' said Dr. Junius Rodriguez, an associate
professor of history at the college.
</P>
<P>
   His presence in the town is felt in subtler ways. Reagan Drive
cuts through a neighborhood near the college, and the public
library contains nearly a dozen biographies on him and his wife,
Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez likes to joke that the telephone prefix in heavily
Republican Eureka _ 467 _ spells out ``GOP'' on the phone pad.
</P>
<P>
   On her way across campus, Ms. Reagan said she could understand
her father's affinity for the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel just like dear old Dad, I don't ever want to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
