<HEADER>
A0305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-McCAIN-COX     05-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-McCAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush, McCain reach truce, sort of
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH, Pa. _ They huddled for 90 minutes in the opulent
splendor of the 84-year-old Westin William Penn Hotel. Then Gov.
George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain emerged not quite
buddies but straining to prove, publicly at least, that they are
not enemies, either.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the feisty war hero who scared Bush in the early rounds
of the GOP primary with a spirited fight, finally endorsed his
once-bitter rival, but McCain likened it to taking medicine.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush called McCain ``a good man, a man of good
judgment,'' but he declined to repudiate the Rev. Pat Robertson's
recent statement that McCain would be ``very dangerous'' as vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the most that Republicans anxious for unity could
hope for. Tensions between the Bush and McCain camps have simmered
since the two fought it out during the primaries. Mistrust lingered
right to Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   McCain recently threatened to pull out of the meeting. But,
eager to put hostilities behind him, McCain relented after a Sunday
telephone call from Bush. McCain reportedly considered canceling
again after word of Sunday's phone call leaked out Monday. Before
the weekend, the two had spoken twice by telephone since McCain
suspended his campaign March 9.
</P>
<P>
   To capture the White House, Bush needs the 4.5 million
independents and Democrats attracted to McCain by his dramatic
personal story and his calls for government reform. That political
reality has forced the victor to keep communications open with the
man he vanquished _ to the irritation of Bush loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta pollster Whit Ayers, a Republican not working for either
camp, said the meeting should help both men. He called McCain's
decision to endorse Bush ``the right thing for him to do, for his
political future and for Governor Bush's.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said categorically Tuesday that he has no desire to be
Bush's running mate. Bush said, ``I take him for his word.'' McCain
has not ruled out another bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers said he thought Bush was planning to reach out on his own
to independents and Democrats. ``Anything he can do to help open
those doors is useful, and that's why a joint appearance is
helpful,'' Ayers said. ``At the same time, there's a limit to the
amount of influence that anyone who did not win the nomination can
have on the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McCain and his advisers are aware of the danger of
overplaying his hand and seeming to want too much. Governor Bush is
a good politician. Senator McCain is a good politician. My guess
is, after all the bobbing and weaving and maneuvering, it'll all
come out OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men were eager to show that they want to move ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``To look back with anger or any rancor would be a mistake for
me and for Governor Bush,'' McCain said. ``I hold no rancor.''
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by reporters, McCain horsed around a bit, repeating the
word ``endorse'' over and over again to dispel any notion that he
reluctantly backed Bush. But when asked by one reporter whether the
endorsement amounted to taking his medicine now rather than later,
McCain said: ``I think your `take-the-medicine-now' is probably a
good description.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain said he looks forward to ``enthusiastically
campaigning for Governor Bush for the next six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stressed his own commitment to reform and said he and
McCain agree on issues such as education and overhauling the
military. Bush adopted the ``-- eformer with -- esults'' mantra
after McCain trounced him in the New Hampshire primary. Bush also
said he hopes McCain would ``play a key role'' in this summer's GOP
convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him point blank he made me a better candidate,'' Bush
said. ``He waged a very good campaign. He put me through my paces
and, as a result of the campaign, I stand better prepared to become
president.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain was careful to say that he and Bush still disagree on
some key issues. McCain remains committed to campaign finance
reform and continues to call for a ban on soft money _ the
unlimited, unregulated cash that flows to political parties. Bush
backs banning such contributions from corporations and labor unions
but not from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The two side-stepped questions about Bush's proposed five-year,
$483 billion tax cut. McCain attacked the plan during the
primaries, saying it wouldn't do enough to pay down the federal
budget deficit or shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans portrayed the McCain endorsement as a big
boost for Bush _ ``Today is a bad day for Al Gore,'' said former
GOP presidential contender Gary Bauer, who had endorsed McCain _
the Democrats tried to downplay it.
</P>
<P>
   At a Pittsburgh news conference after what they called the
Bush-McCain ``peace accord photo op,'' Democratic National
Committee officials handed out compact discs containing bad things
McCain had said about Bush during primary season.
</P>
<P>
   Included among McCain's greatest hits against Bush was this one
from Grand Rapids, Mich., on Feb. 20: ``Governor Bush is a Pat
Robertson Republican who will lose to Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore tried to rain on Bush's big day by reminding a Washington
audience that McCain recently returned to South Carolina to say he
believes the state should no longer fly the Confederate flag over
its Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, McCain, like Bush, said that's a decision
for the state to make. McCain now says his position at the time was
born of political expediency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking to the Anti-Defamation League, said of the issue
Tuesday, ``It is wrong to remain silent about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore will be in Dallas tonight for two fund-raising events for
the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Jena Heath at jenah(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
