<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VICTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS TEARFULLY RECALL VICTORY OVER NAZIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Every other day of the year, Alexander Grigorinsky, 87,
is just another poor old Russian pensioner, living alone and
forgotten in a run-down communal apartment in a Moscow suburb.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, he was a hero one more time, as Russia celebrated
its victory over Nazi Germany in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Donning the light blue beret of a Soviet paratrooper and his old
medal-bedecked uniform, Grigorinsky joined 5,000 other veterans in
a parade through Red Square. Then, his hand resting on the cane he
has carried since his second gunshot wound, received one terrible
day in Hungary in 1944, he ambled around Moscow's Gorky Park,
looking for old buddies from his unit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he found two.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there were none.
</P>
<P>
   But it was OK. Tuesday, everyone wanted to greet Grigorinsky,
congratulate him, and listen to his story. Among them: a young
paratrooper with his arm still in a sling from the wound he
received fighting rebels in Chechnya; four tourists from China;
three Russian skateboarders; an exchange student from Ghana; and
finally, several men and women in their 70s and 80s, veterans from
another paratrooper unit, who sat him down at an outdoor cafe where
they all sang old war songs and drank to victory.
</P>
<P>
   This is the magic of Victory Day in Russia, a holiday that more
than any other in this often sad and struggling land brings people
together, and, for a day, makes old people happy. Even the
competing parade of thousands of Communist supporters denouncing
the poverty that has hit Russia since the demise of the Soviet
Union did little to darken the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem an ironic legacy for a war that claimed the lives of
an estimated 27 million Soviet soldiers and civilians; few Russian
families were untouched by the horror, tragedy, and privations. But
the victory in what is known here as the Great Patriotic War is
also remembered as the Soviet people's finest hour, the most
unifying moment of a 20th century otherwise marred by recurrent
hardship, repression, and stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only Russian national holiday with a human note,
because almost every family has something to mourn for,'' said
Sasha Popov, director of the American Studio of the Moscow Art
Theater, whose grandfather was killed in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Day in today's Russia is also a day of reconciliation,
when political battles take a back seat to the festivities, perhaps
the one day in Russia when violent history combines with the
turbulent present to produce a mellow brew.
</P>
<P>
   As watchful snipers surveyed Red Square, President Vladimir V.
Putin took in the parade of veterans, whose rows of medals
glistened on new gray suits provided by the government for anyone
who no longer had a uniform. The veterans were joined by
fresh-faced cadets and units that have fought in Chechnya, as well
as goose-stepping honor guards outfitted with World War II-era
uniforms, weapons, and standards.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was flanked by his predecessor, Boris N. Yeltsin, who in
the early 90s, looking to make a break with the Communist past,
eliminated much of the military pomp of this day, and in 1995 built
a gate to Red Square that made it impossible to repeat the massive
shows of military force that paraded past the Kremlin in Soviet
days.
</P>
<P>
   They stood on a podium under the mausoleum of Soviet founder
Vladimir Lenin, whose name was tastefully covered by a green
banner. Mikhail Gorbachev, the last Soviet president, whose reforms
helped dismantle Communist rule in Russia, stood by, as did Marshal
Dmitry Yazov, one of the men who tried to oust Gorbachev from power
in a failed 1991 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Even Josef Stalin, long discredited in mainstream Russia as a
bloody dictator, made a cameo appearance. Stalin's heroic status as
the mastermind of victory in 1945 has eroded as the reverent Soviet
view of his leadership has given way to a critical assessment. But
Putin, who has played heavily on patriotic themes, started his
address with the words Stalin used 55 years ago: ``Happy holiday,
dear brothers- and sisters-in-arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin leaders since Stalin have always sought to exploit the
victory for their own political message, and Putin Tuesday was no
exception when called on Russians to draw on the spirit of World
War II to ``build a strong and prosperous country, to raise high
the Russian flag of democracy and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the marshals clapped as they watched the veterans dance and
sing. Yeltsin wiped his eyes, and later put on glasses. Putin wiped
his eyes, too, though it could have been because of the very stiff
wind.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. Moscow time, Russia's three major networks observed a
moment of silence. Across Moscow, red banners hung from buildings
and lampposts, and huge posters honoring the war dead declared
``Remember Them By Name,'' and ``Into the Third Millennium Without
War.''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the banners may have seemed out of place for a
country that is bogged down in a war against rebels in Chechnya.
But most people in Russia see Chechnya as a righteous struggle
against bandits and terrorists. Many probably agree with Putin, who
lauded the soldiers who were ``writing new chapters in Russian
military history'' and said the Nazi's defeat will be ``a warning
to those who see terror and violence as their main weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No force can conquer the Russian arms and army,'' Putin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
