<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frequent fliers vote Continental No. 1
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continental, TWA and Southwest airlines fly highest when it
comes to passenger service quality, according to an annual survey
of frequent fliers.
</P>
<P>
   The trio ranked 1-2-3 for both long-haul and short-haul flight
quality in the survey by Frequent Flyer magazine and J.D. Power and
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines, which last year tied with
Continental for third on short flights, was deemed below average in
both categories this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are genuinely perplexed because customer service is a top
priority for Delta, and we have made considerable improvement,''
spokesman John Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Delta, which handles 80 percent of passengers at
Hartsfield International, was among the top four airlines in the
Department of Transportation's primary service measures for 1999.
It recently finished second in a survey of consumer perceptions by
the Harris polling organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Frequent Flyer/J.D. Power survey uses a range of service
measures to establish an industry average in each category, then
ranks carriers that finish above it. Below-average carriers are
listed but not ranked.
</P>
<P>
   The most important factors are on-time performance, airport
check-in processes, flight attendant courtesy, and seat space and
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Results are based on 6,079 flight evaluations submitted by ``a
national sample of representative frequent fliers,'' 54 percent of
whom reported some type of flight problem, according to the
magazine and J.D. Power.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that 25 percent of frequent fliers use the
Internet for travel planning and that about half of those buy
tickets online.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
