<HEADER>
A0323 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELL-DEAL-FOLO-COX     05-09 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-DEAL-FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth: TV coming next year
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BellSouth Corp. has promised that its new satellite service will
create thousands of jobs while reshaping the way customers use
their televisions.
</P>
<P>
   As the deal with GE Americom was formally announced Tuesday,
BellSouth vowed to deliver its Americast service next year, putting
the company in head-to-head competition with a host of cable and
satellite providers already in the market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to hundreds of channels of television, the service
will eventually offer e-mail, video on demand, video games and the
chance to make purchases over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a forward shift in how people watch TV and what they
they use TV for,'' said Bob Frame, president of BellSouth
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The set-top box allows downloading of movies or other programs
that can be watched later, rewound and paused. If you hook the
set-top box to the Net via a phone or high-speed line, you can
watch television and interact with a related Web site. For example,
you'd have a Braves game on and link to the site that sells
merchandise. That hook-up also lets the television serve as a
gateway to the phone, so if you have Caller ID, the screen might
flash the number of an incoming call.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth expects to package this with its other services, said
Frame. ``One company, one call, one bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Even limited to the Southeast, the deal could be a boon to $25
billion-a-year BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   It will extend BellSouth's entertainment offerings throughout
the region, giving the company a chance to deepen its bonds with
customers even as telecommunications competition heats up.
BellSouth would like to use digital television as part of a package
including phone service and Net access.
</P>
<P>
   Without endorsing the estimate, BellSouth officials did not
object to reports that they expect to reap about $3 billion a year
from the service in the Southeast. That figure represents a large
portion of the money already spent on digital television, which
means BellSouth expects to take business from others while the
overall market also grows.
</P>
<P>
   The company is confident of winning a large market share, Frame
said. ``I think 25 to 30 percent is certainly doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based telecom analyst Jeffrey Kagan endorsed BellSouth's
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts BellSouth in a very strong competitive position,''
he said. ``The more customers they can tie up with a telephony and
entertainment bundle, the harder it will be for competitors to woo
them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have given the plan mixed reviews, some expressing
skepticism about BellSouth's ability to lure customers from
entrenched satellite providers like DirecTV and EchoStar's Dish
network.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly MediaOne, metro Atlanta's largest cable company,
is blase about the threat. ``We saw this coming five or six years
ago,'' said Reg Griffin, company spokesman. ``We feel as if we are
in a much better more competitive position now.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver-based MediaOne has spent $400 million upgrading its
network here. The company, which has agreed to be acquired by AT&AMP;T,
can now deliver its high-speed offerings to about 40 percent of the
1 million homes passed by its lines.
</P>
<P>
   But MediaOne has a different approach than BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne wants to give customers the option of high-speed
Internet access and digital entertainment _ but not via the same
device, Griffin said. ``Our customers tell us they want those
services, but they want them independent of each other. The serious
user wants the Internet on the desktop or the laptop, while the
rest of the family may be watching television.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the specter of entrenched competitors, BellSouth counts
on its reputation _ as well as the new technology wrinkles _ to
carve out a solid share of the entertainment market.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has declined to talk about how much it will charge for
the new service. Current Americast customers pay an average of $54
a month, more than most satellite services charge.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth may not have to undercut competitors to do well,
said Schaffer Hilton, partner in technology at Deloitte &AMP; Touche
Consulting. ``I think the BellSouth brand name carries a lot of
weight in the nine-state region. I would hope they'll be more
aggressive in pricing than the existing satellite providers, but
you can ride on the BellSouth brand name a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for new technology is growing, he said. ``Five years ago,
it was more of a technology looking for a place to happen. Now, a
broader number of consumers don't think this is a stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth intends to have its own technicians install the
equipment, including the 30- by 20-inch dish that will receive
signals. If the venture does well, BellSouth will need customer
service representatives, sales staff, marketing help and
supervisors, in addition to installers, Frame said. ``If we execute
our business plan, there will be literally thousands of jobs
created.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth now delivers its Americast service in 11 metropolitan
areas using either high-speed fiber lines or signals transmitted
from a few antennas in high places. But fiber is costly to install
and has been placed in only a portion of BellSouth territory. And
the wireless signal can be checkmated by hills, buildings and
trees. BellSouth says Americast has been enthusiastically embraced
where offered, but the company can claim just 120,000 takers for
the limited offering.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, BellSouth can use satellites to make Americast
available to 14 million households _ more than 90 percent of the
people in the nine states where BellSouth is the dominant local
phone company. Even more enticing, the satellite service also
dangles the possibility of expanding beyond the Southeast to 50
million households ranging from Texas to Wisconsin and east to the
Atlantic, Frame said.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite deal is the third big-ticket move by BellSouth
since its failed bid to buy Sprint in October.
</P>
<P>
   After taking some heat from analysts, BellSouth has this year
announced a multibillion-dollar tracking stock for its Latin
American investments and a giant wireless alliance with SBC
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Around BellSouth, rivals were growing ever larger, and the
company appeared headed for irrelevance, said analyst Marc Bacurin
of J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co. ``Even six months ago, the impression
everybody had of BellSouth was that things were passing them by.''
</P>
<P>
   While viewing the satellite deal as positive, Bacurin said he is
surprised that BellSouth seems ready to ratchet back its support
for digital subscriber lines, high-speed technology capable of
using some copper wires.
</P>
<P>
   Still, BellSouth and other regional phone companies have had
trouble delivering DSL to much of the market, and satellite
offerings don't preclude work on DSL, Bacurin said. ``It shows that
they are thinking about strategic alternatives, as opposed to a
year ago. They are not going to go down without a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
