<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-HOUSE-COX     05-09 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-HOUSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A digital home sweet home
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Digital technology, which has fueled the revolution in business,
data transmission and communication, is expected to soon change
households and the way we relate to one another in daily life.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech engineers and computer specialists, in a year-long
project, are now examining this future, live and in color.
</P>
<P>
   Their laboratory is a digitally equipped frame house on 10th
Street, dubbed Aware House, that will be a discrete focal point for
their research.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our goals is to discover technology combinations that
can unobtrusively enhance lifestyle in the home of the future,''
said Nikil Jayant, director of Tech's Broadband Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Special attention will be paid to the needs of infants and older
citizens and of families in general, Jayant said.
</P>
<P>
   On display during a recent open house were several special
projects for the special groups, including unique ways to monitor
infants and a system to monitor an older person remotely _ either
across town or on another continent by means of an ``always on''
broadband connection to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The digital watch on seniors, called Aging in Place, builds on
the assumption that older people, even though they are becoming
dependent, do better if they can remain in their familiar home as
long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research suggests that as we grow older the comfort of
familiar surroundings is better for us than being uprooted and
placed somewhere else, however well-meaning,'' said Beth Mynatt, an
assistant professor of computing who will pay special attention to
research on Aging in Place.
</P>
<P>
   Mynatt's research will consist of interviewing seniors and their
children or caregiver to see what families desire to know, and what
levels of information seniors care to share.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far we established one fact _ nobody wants a video camera
in the bathroom,'' Mynatt said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities, however, include cameras on stairs, and
other watchful devices that keep track of security, eating habits,
socialization, and taking of medication.
</P>
<P>
   Systems could be programmed to alert loved ones, police, doctors
or others automatically if things go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   With infant monitoring, the baby's room would be provided a
special edition of the ``smart shirt,'' developed first for
military use by Sundaresan Jayaraman and his Tech team in the
School of Textile and Fiber Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The garment, a wearable computer that the Defense Department
would use to monitor the well-being and
</P>
<P>
   whereabouts of the troops in the field, can be put to peacetime
uses too _ such as to monitor body functions and
</P>
<P>
   protect against sudden infant death.
</P>
<P>
   The specially wired house allows the parent or caregiver to
receive audio or data reports on the infant or sick child
automatically wherever he goes around the house.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's cry or other hints of distress would be picked up by
the snug-wired garment and piped into the
</P>
<P>
   room where the caregiver happens to be, but only to that room if
he so chooses.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the baby garment would be waterproof, Jayaraman said.
</P>
<P>
   That garment could also be adapted for use by others in the
house who are ill or need special monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   As with many of the other applications of technology in the
house, the study will examine not just how things work in the hands
of real people, but how people take to them, and what precisely
they expect from them, the scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human challenge with this technology is as much a
challenge, if not more, than the technological challenge,'' said
Gregory Abowd, an associate professor of computing.
</P>
<P>
   Abowd's classrooms have been minilaboratories in the use of
digital video and audio, as well as data retrieval, in the service
of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   He is a member of the research team at Aware House.
</P>
<P>
   And so is Thad Starnes, a developer and devotee of the unique
wearable computer, whose researchers will be testing a device that
could replace the basket full of remote controls around the living
room.
</P>
<P>
   The special device, which could be worn about the neck or
attached to a shirt like a pendant, would be able to
</P>
<P>
   control lights and electronic equipment with discreet hand
movements instead of by button pushing.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the research will be to find out what use ordinary
people have for the new technology, Starnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Other features of the house to be studied will be the ``smart
floor,'' a system that can track the movements of individuals by
their footsteps around the house, so that anyone can know their
whereabouts at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Other technologies will tag personal items like glasses,
wallets, keys and other items that have a habit of
</P>
<P>
   getting lost, and help the forgetful individual locate them
instantly at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The study in the 5,000-square-foot three-story house is funded
by a combination of federal funds and private corporate support.
</P>
<P>
   This includes a $700,000 grant from the Georgia Research
Alliance for the design and construction of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
