<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-F22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    F-22 production will remain in Marietta
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin will not move final assembly of the F-22 fighter
from Marietta to Fort Worth, Texas, a decision that preserves more
than 1,000 Cobb County jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace giant had been quietly considering such a move
since last winter, when it consolidated management of all aircraft
programs at its fighter plant in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   But in a memo to Marietta workers and at a Washington news
conference, executives said Tuesday no move is planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the last few months, we have reviewed results from
several previous studies of F-22 production plans, including
options for moving final assembly,'' Marietta plant chief Tom
Burbage said in the memo. ``The financial implications of these
studies do not support a change in current plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, there are no plans to move F-22 final assembly from
our facility in Marietta.''
</P>
<P>
   The company didn't say how much it would cost to shutter F-22
facilities in Marietta, but U.S. Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), in a
statement hailing the stay-put decision, pegged it at more than
$500 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,200 of the 7,500 jobs at the plant are tied to the
decade-old F-22 program, with most of the rest linked to the C-130J
cargo plane. The company has spent millions building not only an
F-22 assembly line in Marietta but also specialized testing
facilities and an administrative and engineering complex.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the idea of moving the work to Fort Worth has
cropped up periodically as the company has fought to contain costs
in the controversial program, slated to move from development to
production next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth plant already makes midfuselage sections of the
F-22. Lockheed Martin looked at consolidating all its F-22 work in
Fort Worth to cut long-term overhead costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News last week reported that members of the
Machinists union at the Fort Worth plant, just coming off a strike,
believed their plant was in line to get the F-22 final assembly
work.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin officials issued Tuesday's memo in part to quell
the continuing speculation.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a move concerned the Machinists union at
Marietta and Georgia members of Congress. Both have helped Lockheed
Martin protect the F-22 program in Congress and would take a dim
view of any shift of work to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   F-22 funding in the fiscal 2001 defense budget cleared an
initial hurdle Tuesday when the Senate Armed Services Committee
approved the Air Force's request for an initial production lot of
10 planes. The committee also was expected to add funding for two
C-130Js to the four requested by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
