</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-EARTHLINK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sprint increases EarthLink stake
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprint Corp. said Tuesday it would increase its investment by
$431 million in EarthLink Inc., an Atlanta-based Internet service
provider .
</P>
<P>
   After the stock purchase of 26 million additional shares, Sprint
has a 26.7 percent interest in the ISP.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint originally owned 29 percent of EarthLink, though that
percentage was cut in half when EarthLink issued additional stock
after Apple Computer invested $200 million in January. EarthLink
merged with Atlanta-based MindSpring earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The long-distance telephone carrier had been expected to
increase its holdings to its previous level and had until Aug. 4 to
exercise that option. Sprint purchased the shares for $16.58 each _
that's 2.5 percent below EarthLink's closing price Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bodes very well for EarthLink,'' said Frank Gristina, an
assistant vice president and research analyst with Atlanta-based
Robinson-Humphrey. ``It's a good move for Sprint and a signal they
want to move into other markets. You'll see more and more
traditional companies trying to expand into Internet markets.
Rather than try to build quality brands in-house, which can be
expensive and distracting, many are finding it's easier to look
outside. Sprint's interest in the company is an extra vote of
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink Chief Executive Officer Garry Betty said the timing of
the investment was auspicious. ``Because of this we are able to do
some things from a contractual standpoint that will be positive for
both EarthLink and Sprint.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty said most people don't realize that EarthLink is Sprint's
consumer Internet offering. He said the two companies were partners
in Sprint's ION (Integrated On Demand Network), which will begin
rolling out in July in selected markets and nationwide next year.
Betty also said that there would be additional branding
opportunities with Sprint including EarthLink wireless service
slated to roll out sometime this summer.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink said Sprint's investment will boost its cash reserve
64 percent to $1.1 billion. Betty says he plans to use the money to
continue building EarthLink's customer base.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of use of the cash, we still feel we have to scale up
to become a stronger alternative to America Online. We'll do both
selective and opportunistic acquistions and internal marketing to
work toward that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty would not specify what companies or partners EarthLink
would consider combining with. ``There are still some properties
that are attractive,'' he said, ``and we will augment our growth
that way if the financial terms are right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gristina said EarthLink has always been very careful about its
acquisition spending, trying never to spend more than $400 per new
subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they need to keep a little war chest to continue to
market at their current rate and have a little breathing room,'' he
said. ``EarthLink has always focused on the cost of acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   However, with a multimillion-dollar cash infusion from Sprint,
the company may be able to spend more to acquire the subscribers
Betty says it has to have to go after AOL. AOL has about 22 million
subscribers; EarthLink, the second-largest ISP in the country, has
3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this will enable them to do a rebate program with a
computer reseller,'' Gristina said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
