<HEADER>
A0327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TEXTILES-COX     05-09 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXTILES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Textile proposal stands to boost state
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia yarn and fabric companies should get a significant boost
from a new textile trade agreement that's poised to become law.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the U.S. House of Representatives passed a bill to
liberalize trade with Caribbean nations and give struggling areas
of Africa greater access to U.S. markets. The Senate is expected to
approve the measure this week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill expands apparel trade with 48 sub-Saharan African
nations and 25 Caribbean nations. Garments made in those countries
with U.S. yarn and fabric can enter this country without duty or
quotas.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for some Georgia manufacturers that have
watched the steady exodus of apparel operations to other countries.
In a sector marked by dwindling jobs due to technology and overseas
competition, the new trade bill could create 63,000 U.S. textile
jobs, said Roy Bowen, president of the Georgia Textile
Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia is going get a large share of that,'' Bowen said. The
new jobs will come across the board, from production to marketing
and management. About 40 percent of the state's textile companies
are involved in the apparel business, Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate vote is timely this week, as the state association
held its annual meeting at the Cloister on Sea Island.
</P>
<P>
   Yarn spinners and fabric makers will benefit the most from the
bill, said Roger Chastain, president of the American Textile
Manufacturers Institute and chief operating officer of Greenville,
S.C.-based Mount Vernon Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain predicted that, with the agreement, demand for U.S.
fabric will at least double over the next eight years. The trade
bill, if approved, would take effect in October.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the bill lays the groundwork for a showdown on trade
with China. The House is expected to decide the week of May 22
whether to grant China permanent normal trade status. If the House
approves the measure, Senate passage is likely.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say permanent normal relations with China are
essential to assure the U.S. benefits from China's likely admission
to the World Trade Organization. The textile industry has been
aggressively fighting China's entry into the WTO, fearing increased
competition from Chinese apparel makers.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean measures of the new trade bill could help offset
any damage done if China is allowed into the WTO, said Kay Norwood,
a textile analyst with Wachovia Securities. She warned Georgia
industry leaders Tuesday that China's entry is almost certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fabric manufacturers need to make friends south of the border
(in the Caribbean and Mexico), developing joint ventures, alliances
and relationships with garment makers to assure a market for their
fabrics,'' Norwood said. ``Inaction at this point means you're
giving up future business.''
</P>
<P>
   Boosted by the North American Free Trade Agreement, thousands of
mills churn out clothing in Mexico, for example. Less than a year
after NAFTA was passed in 1994, apparel imports from Mexico
surpassed apparel imports from China, Norwood noted.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Caribbean measures of the bill are viewed generally
as positive, the African portion presents some risks.
</P>
<P>
   China has said it would use the proposed free trade with
sub-Saharan Africa as a way to smuggle its goods into the United
States. ``Because there are no trade restrictions between Africa
and China, the elimination of quotas from Africa would give China
free access to the U.S.,'' Norwood said. ``This would be a disaster
because China could flood our markets with no controls
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said the positive effects of the African measure are
unclear, because the group of 48 countries accounted for less than
one half of 1 percent of apparel imports into the United States
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill creates incentives for growth in Africa's embryonic
textile and apparel industry. Clothing made in Africa from African
fabric would be allowed to rise from 1.5 percent of total U.S.
imports to 3.5 percent over eight years, boosting African exports
of those products from $250 million in 1999 to an estimated $4.2
billion in 2008, according to the International Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   African nations where the gross domestic product is less than
$1,500 a year per capita, all but six of the total, also would
export to the United States quota-free for four years, even when
they use fabric from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has been in the works for about six years, Chastain
noted. During that time, many in the textile industry fought to
stop the legislation, arguing it would cost American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
