<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CIO-MANAGEMENT-ART-NY     05-09 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIO-MANAGEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF INFORMATION OFFICERS RISING TOWARD THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, H. John Lochow felt as though the word ``techie''
were practically branded on his forehead. As a computer systems
manager at AT&AMP;T Capital Corp. and at CNA Insurance Cos., and later
as the chief information officer for a succession of corporations,
he says, he was never allowed to run other departments, let alone
serve on high-level management teams at these businesses.
</P>
<P>
   For him, things have turned out well. But Lochow's lurch up the
corporate ladder is not an isolated case. In corporate America, an
increasing number of chief information officers _ basically, they
are the folks in charge of the computers _ are amassing greater
power as top bosses and company boards realize how crucial their
expertise is in staying ahead of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Lochow (pronounced LUCK-oh) got his chance to break loose from
the techie label last year. Opportunity called in the form of a
mini-crisis at his current employer, Tech Data Corp. in Clearwater,
Fla., a giant computer distributor that was growing so fast it
could not hire enough people to keep up with orders. Its warehouses
were bulging with products that could not be shipped.
</P>
<P>
   Lochow, whose main responsibility until then had been to
maintain the smooth functioning of the company's computers in 35
countries, believed he was the man to break the logjam. So he asked
Tech Data's chief executive, Steven A. Raymund, to put him in
charge of the company's supply division. After all, he told
Raymund, he had already turned around the information technology
operations to make them more efficient, and at no additional cost
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   He got the assignment and threw himself into it with tasks like
picking apart and mapping every process that Tech Data used in its
warehouses to receive and ship its products.
</P>
<P>
   He emerged a hero: Within three months, Tech Data had almost
doubled its shipments and had trimmed back inventory. Now Lockow
reports directly to Raymund, and earlier this year he was given
responsibility for managing yet another department, the one that
assembles the company's products.
</P>
<P>
   Lochow clearly savors his new role at Tech Data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now my responsibilities cross many lines of business,'' he
said. ``Before, I felt like I was up against a glass ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by Egon Zehnder International, an executive
search firm, found that companies are increasingly looking to a new
generation of chief information officers to be business
strategists, and that these ``new'' CIOs spend at least half their
time outside the information-technology department on efforts like
developing and incubating new prospects for electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that 15 percent of new chief information
officers now serve on the boards of their companies and 70 percent
are on their companies' high-level management teams. Those numbers
are up sharply from a decade ago, industry specialists say, when 0
percent and 10 percent would have been more likely figures.
</P>
<P>
   The information officers are reveling in their elevation from
backroom tinkerers with fancy titles to strategic thinkers on an
equal footing with corporate presidents, chief operating officers
and chief financial officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the third generation of CIO now,'' Lochow said. ``The
first generation was made up of techies, like data center
directors. And although the second generation was more vocal in
terms of becoming part of corporate planning, its members were
still one level below directly reporting to their chief executives.
Now, however, thanks to the Internet, CIOs are moving directly into
corporate decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive recruiters say the trend is the inevitable fallout of
the Internet revolution, which has recast the dynamics of the
marketplace of almost every industry overnight and forced companies
to react with equal speed or face extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that companies would say, `Find us a CIO who
will take care of our computer systems,''' said S. Ross Brown, who
is the director of the high technology and telecommunications
recruiting practice at Egon Zehnder. ``But now they're calling to
say, `We need a CIO who can help us define our whole way of doing
business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Those new responsibilities require new duties, of course,
including spending more time with both the corporate brass and
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia Claudio, the chief information officer at the Farmers
Group, the subsidiary of Zurich Financial Services that is based in
Los Angeles, says her new travel schedule takes some getting used
to. In March, Claudio spent three days crisscrossing Indiana to
meet with more than 60 sales agents, something that chief
information officers like her would never have done five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't look to me as just being a CIO,'' she said. ``I'm
expected to bring wisdom, to understand all aspects of our
business, as well as not work in isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Claudio joined Farmers two years ago, she said, her job
at a former employer was focused entirely on the information
systems. But now she is asked almost daily for her views on
questions like whether to increase the company's sales staff and
how to sell multiple products to existing customers.
</P>
<P>
   Because technology now touches every corner of almost every
company's business, Claudio said, chief information officers are
probably better prepared than other top managers to assume new
responsibilities _ including the mantle of chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of quite a few situations where this has already
happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Zilvitis, the chief information officer of Gillette
Co., says his expertise is sought out because technology touches
every aspect of Gillette's operations, even product design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to be involved in change management in everything I
do,'' Zilvitis said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not as though CIOs are on an unstoppable march to the top
at every corporation in America, of course. One school of thought
is of the opinion, in fact, that as a group they retain a
detail-oriented mentality that can miss the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bernard, who founded his own consulting firm in New York,
for example, believes that for all the changes wrought by the
Internet, too many chief information officers continue to
``worship'' technology, while ignoring both the strategic and the
customer-service aspects of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue for CIOs and their staffers is that no one has
articulated to them how much their jobs have changed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some do grasp those changes, of course, and are leveraging their
new stature to shop themselves around.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hjelm left his job as chief information officer at Federal
Express in January to become chief operating officer at Zoho Corp.,
an Internet vendor in Sunnyvale, Calif., that caters to hotels and
casinos.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years at Federal Express, Hjelm said, he had become
tired of endlessly reinventing the giant company's computer systems
and yearned for a more expansive role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to try something different, as well as be a part
of the Internet economy,'' he said. ``Now, I'm creating something
new, as well as an entire business model in an industry that's ripe
for it. That's why a lot of chief information officers like me are
leaving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
