<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0330 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-KIDS-ALLERGIES10-COX     05-09 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ALLERGIES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    conni
 &HT;    Jennifer Brett desk:4097 home: 770-590-5938 page: 888-644-8803
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Food allergy awareness week: Nothing to sneeze at
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Campbell remembers with a grimace the day he had to eat his
lunch all alone.
</P>
<P>
   The self-imposed exile was necessary. Several of the
10-year-old's friends had peanut butter sandwiches in their
lunches, and Jeff is so allergic to peanuts that the smell is
enough to make his lips swell and his skin break out in hives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the lunch lady if I could be moved,'' said Jeff, a
fourth-grader at Crabapple Crossing Elementary School in
Alpharetta, Ga. ``I had to sit by myself, and I was mad.''
</P>
<P>
   That was last year. This year, Jeff says he usually has no
problem at lunch because his friends are sensitive to his allergy.
Mindful of children like Jeff, the school's cafeteria serves no
peanut products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not going to take the risk,'' said Principal Sonia
Terry, who said the school has not served peanuts for at least
three years. ``Every now and then we'll get a delivery (of peanut
products) and it's stopped at the loading dock.''
</P>
<P>
   That might sound extreme, but consider this: According to The
Food Network, a Fairfax, Va.-based organization that has declared
this week ``Food Allergy Awareness Week,'' between 100 and 200
people die each year from food allergy-related reactions. The
organization says there are an estimated 30,000 emergency room
visits a year because of severe reactions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, for example, a 13-year-old middle school student in
Kentucky died after having an allergic reaction to nuts in
chocolate candy she ate at school. And schools in Pennsylvania,
Iowa, New Jersey, Connecticut, Maryland, Illinois, Massachussetts,
California and New York City have banned peanuts from the cafeteria
because of students with severe allergies.
</P>
<P>
   In response to concerns, school officials throughout the metro
area say they use a variety of means to ensure that children with
food allergies don't accidentally eat an item that might cause a
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, students in the Gwinnett County, Ga., use meal
cards. When the cards are swiped, the computerized cash register
alerts the cashier to a child's food allergy, so the cashier can
police what's on the child's tray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some parents give photos of their children to the people at
the register,'' said Laura Nurse, manager of community and media
relations.
</P>
<P>
   At Jeff Campbell's school, Terry credits parents like Jeff's
mother, Susan Campbell, for making everyone in the school aware of
food allergies. Jeff and other students with allergies have
emergency health care procedures posted on the school clinic's
bulletin board. The clinic also stocks EpiPens, medical devices
used to administer epinephrine to a child having an allergic
reaction. Parents bring the EpiPens for their children, and must
present doctors' notes before the clinic can accept them.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who has also placed an EpiPen in Jeff's lunch box, is
pleased with Crabapple Crossing's response but wants to spread her
message of education and awareness. She is a member of the Food
Allergy Network.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta school systems typically don't set rigid
food-allergy policies governing every cafeteria, but allow each
school to deal with whatever allergies or dietary needs the
children there may have. ``There is no districtwide policy,'' said
Barbara Gilbert, food service director for DeKalb County, Ga. ``...
If we are aware a child is allergic to a specific thing, we will
make a special meal. We will work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   When an allergy requires more specialized meals _ such as an
allergy to wheat _ students must bring lunches from home, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb County school cafeterias offer varied menu choices to
accommodate allergies. Children who can't drink milk can have
juice, and children who can't eat a peanut butter sandwich can
choose a turkey sandwich instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lunchroom managers and parents are always in communication
about what the child's needs are,'' said Daphne Hanks, food
nutrition services area coordinator for the system. ``We try to be
as flexible as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Turner, food nutrition coordinator for the Cherokee
County, Ga., school system, said cafeteria workers keep lists of
children with food allergies and monitor them as they proceed
through the lunch line. They also display signs that signal, for
example, the brownies being served that day include peanuts or
walnuts. Even with the signs, children with food allergies often
quiz cafeteria workers to make sure they don't eat something that
could cause a reaction, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids know to ask,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cookies that contain peanuts are served separately from cookies
that do not, Turner said. The cafeteria will also prepare special
dishes for children with food allergies _ broccoli without cheese
sauce for a child who is allergic to milk products, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Food allergies affect not only the cafeteria but also policies
on classroom snacks a parent may bring in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just give out candy indiscriminately,'' said Paul
Kraack, spokesman for the Clayton County, Ga., school system.
Parents must tell teachers what treat they'd like to bring.
Teachers will ask the parents to bring an additional item if the
proposed treat would cause a reaction in someone.
</P>
<P>
   In high schools, students with allergies pick a buddy in each
class who knows how to administer epinephrine in the case of an
allergic reaction, Kraack said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Minar's daughter Lauren, a fourth-grader at Mountain Park
Elementary in Lilburn, Ga., is allergic to peanuts and other nuts.
Minar feels comfortable sending Lauren, 9, to school because of
school policies that set aside a ``peanut-free zone'' in the
cafeteria and require staff to be aware of allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren also knows to read labels and not to sit near anyone
eating peanut products.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Raymond, assistant principal at Mountain Park, said about
20 of the school's 600 students have allergies. EpiPens are kept in
classrooms, the clinic and the cafeteria. Anyone who comes into
contact with an allergic child knows about the allergy and
emergency plans in case of a reaction, Raymond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody kind of looks out for these kids, including the
children,'' he said. ``The children at our school know they don't
sit next to someone with an allergy if they're eating something
(the child is allergic to).''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff, the Crabapple Crossing student, said his friends plan
their lunches to avoid problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year if I make a new friend, I say I'm allergic to
peanuts and if it's possible try not to bring any peanut products,
because if they do I won't get to sit with them,'' Jeff said.
``They'll say OK.''
</P>
<P>
   AVOID THESE
</P>
<P>
   Eight foods cause 90 percent of food-allergy reactions: milk,
eggs, peanuts, other nuts, fish, soy, shellfish and wheat. Symptoms
of a reaction include hives, abdominal cramps, vomiting, diarrhea,
swelling of the mouth or throat or difficulty breathing. The most
severe type of reaction, anaphylaxis, is sudden and can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Food Allergy Network
</P>
<P>
   BE A FRIEND
</P>
<P>
   Children can help their friends with food allergies stay safe by
following some simple guidelines:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't share your food with food-allergic friends.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Learn what your friend is allergic to and help your friend
avoid it by reading ingredient labels and asking questions when
eating in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wash your hands after eating, especially if you've eaten
something to which your friend is allergic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Remind your friend to always carry medication if prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't let your friend go to the bathroom alone, especially if
the friend is not feeling well.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If a reaction occurs, call 911 immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Food Allergy Network
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Brett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
