u f BC-REUTERS-YANKEE-BOS &LR;      05-09 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUTERS-YANKEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REUTERS GROUP BUYS BUSINESS RESEARCH FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Slumping demand for technology stocks came as bad news
to Primark Corp. which had planned to sell shares in its Yankee
Group technology research subsidiary. But along came Plan B, in the
form of the British media company Reuters Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters has agreed to pay $72.5 million for Boston-based Yankee
Group, part of a campaign to build up Reuters as a major provider
of business research and consulting services. The deal was
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is going out and building new businesses for
Reuters in the corporate information market, which globally is a
$15 billion industry,'' said Brad Hanson, CEO of Reuters
Enterprise, the unit that will acquire Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   As for Primark, the agreement offers an attractive alternative
to an IPO in bearish times. ``The capital markets are not
particularly amenable to IPOs of small companies right at this
moment,'' said analyst Peter Appert of Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Primark acquired Yankee Group in 1996 for $34 million in cash
and up to $31 million in additional performance incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Primark estimated that the deal with Reuters will
generate a $35 million pretax gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the current conditions in the IPO marketplace,'' said
Primark chairman and CEO Joseph Kasputys, ``the cash sale of 100
percent of the Yankee Group is more advantageous than our
previously announced plans for an initial public offering of
approximately 40 percent of its equity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Group's chief executive, Berge Ayvazian, agreed. ``I'm
extremely pleased,'' said Ayvazian, who will remain at the helm.
``The IPO marketplace has become very unfavorable. . . . You can't
throw IPOs out and watch them fly anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   With the deal, Primark will extract itself from the technology
information business. The Waltham, Mass. company sold its TASC
military information unit to Litton Industries for $432 million in
1997. Its remaining stable of companies, including MarketEye,
Disclosure, and A-T Financial Information, focus on economic and
financial news and research.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters, meanwhile, is eager to get into the tech research and
consulting business. Last year, it acquired Tower Group of Needham,
Mass., which specializes in the application of information
technology to financial services companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic strategy here is that the market research sector is
very large,'' Hanson said. ``It's a multibillion-dollar global
industry. It continues to grow at 15 to 20 percent per year.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank's Appert agreed that the Yankee Group acquisition
is good business for Reuters. ``It's a great business, very
profitable, and has grown very, very consistently over the years,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters' American depository receipts closed down $4.9375 at
$99.4375 Tuesday on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Primark fell 13 cents
to $25.3125 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
