<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0335 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE11-COX     05-09 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wary gardener battles hostile takeover attempt
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ Weed war is hell. I learn that anew each year
during high-weed season, and the lesson always disappoints. You
see, I love ``weeds.'' That is, I love some, including the lovely
and talented Queen Anne's lace, long tall mullein, wild potato vine
_ and can you believe anyone would consider horsetail an
undesirable?
</P>
<P>
   But like everything else in the garden, a weed's rise or fall
depends on whose taste rules the plot. It's not a weed if you say
it's not. As a longtime defender of ``weeds'' and ``trash trees,''
such as mimosa, I thought these disparaged ones recognized my
friendship and never would get totally loose in my space. Wrong.
Along came sow thistle, as hostile as dwarf bamboo, that cultivated
plastic grass.
</P>
<P>
   Sow thistle reminds me of what a newspaper friend, an editor,
used to say to jokingly belittle us ungrateful writers: ``No matter
how much you do for a reporter, it will always hate you.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering all I've done for thistle and many other weeds _
giving them homes among the Japanese maples, the hollyhock, ginkgo
and the rest of my intentional ornamentals _ I couldn't believe sow
thistle acted out the way it did. It had to be hate.
</P>
<P>
   That was my reluctant conclusion the other day when I saw two
lines of this dandelionlike plant (yes, dandelion is one I've
always sheltered, too) growing on each side of a row of
twice-blooming cherry trees. The thistles had shot up to at least a
foot in a matter of days, their soft, reddish stems fattening up by
the minute. Clearly, this was a hostile act.
</P>
<P>
   I could not let such disrespect go. I launched my counterattack,
pulling the weeds out, roots, stems, leaves and all, benefitting
from a recent rain, striking while the earth was cool and wet. What
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like a good weed battle to bring out the
primitive in a gardener. I like to display the vanquished until
they dry up and disappear. I have hung clumps of unwanted bamboo in
the Y of trees and shrubs, condemning the ripped-out reeds to
drying and brittling, doing everything but crying out for merciful
death.
</P>
<P>
   Some ancient trait in me asserts that this public display warns
all that come after: Grow here, and the same will happen to you. I
know, I know. If that really worked, I would be weedless in
McCaysville and everywhere else I have gardened for, lo, these five
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I do it, hang an unwanted weed out to dry.
</P>
<P>
   The sow thistle made such a wonderfully willing victim. So named
because pigs (and some humans) love to eat it, this plant, unlike
some thistles, has a stem unprickled enough to handle without
gloves, my way to garden. Like the dandelion, it produces yellow
flowers and fuzzy-haired seeds that ride wind and water to faraway
places, reproducing by the zillions.
</P>
<P>
   In my garden, a colony had developed underground, popping up in
rows much like cane bamboo, flanking the cherries as if preparing
to close in for a weedy kill. Sometimes growing as high as 6 or 7
feet, they just might have the strength to commit such mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   I beat them to the punch, ripping out and laying out all the
plants on the rocks they grew next to, rocks that I had placed
there to outline the cherry-tree plot. My prize display is a huge
specimen stretched atop a slab of quartz that measures some 4 feet
long. During its tenure on the slab, the thistle has had its root
dirt bathed away by showers.
</P>
<P>
   Even on warmish, blue-sky days, the gray-white slab is cool to
the touch. Thus, it will take days for the sow thistle to dry up,
readying itself for its ultimate return to the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the message to others remains out there. A weed here,
and there, and over there, too, can be beautiful. But don't try to
hog all the space.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail him at leemay(at)att.net.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
