<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MIAMI-POLITICS-525&AMP;AD     05-09 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-POLITICS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAGG  
</HEADLINE>
  
 AFTERMATH OF ELIAN RAID LEAVES MIAMI BITTERLY DIVIDED   By RICK c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For such a small boy, Elian Gonzalez has had a large,
far-reaching impact on the government of a city that was his home
for a mere five months. Mayor Joe Carollo, a Cuban-American
incensed by a federal raid to seize the child, has virtually remade
city hall, and the Miami city government is, more than ever,
distinctly Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo, who fired City Manager Donald Warshaw after he refused
to fire Police Chief William O'Brien after the armed raid on the
house of Elian's relatives on April 22, has named Carlos Gimenez, a
Cuban-American who was the city's fire chief, as city manager.
</P>
<P>
   The move came just a little over a week after Raul Martinez,
also a Cuban-American, was named to replace O'Brien, who resigned
in anger, as police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Miami now has a Cuban-American mayor, city manager and police
chief, as well as a Cuban-American majority _ three of five _ on
City Commission. While Cuban-Americans mostly supported Carollo's
actions, some residents here wonder if such a preponderance of
power is good for the already sharply divided city.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few days, Anglos, blacks and some Hispanics have
pelted City Hall with bananas, a symbol of what many here see as
Miami's ``banana republic'' government, and have begun a petition
to remove Carollo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of people here are concerned and outraged because
they believe the city of Miami has lost its balance and
equilibrium,'' said Arthur Teele Jr., Miami's only black city
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Teele, like many here, said Carollo's government seemed willing
to exclude all but Cuban-Americans at a time when passions were
running high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to talk about healing when you are widening the
gap,'' said Teele.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent development in Miami's chaotic political
landscape, a Miami-Dade County Circuit judge lifted a temporary
injunction Tuesday that had prevented Carollo from removing
Warshaw. That cleared the way for the Cuban-born mayor's
appointment of the Cuban-born Gimenez.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw, who was appointed by Carollo two years ago, said the
mayor had subjected him to a ``humiliating public execution.'' Each
man accused the other of misdeeds, but Circuit Judge Steve Levine
ruled that Carollo, under the city charter, could fire the city
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But in Miami, it is the impetus for all these drastic changes in
city government that has some residents angry.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor sided with the city's exiles against the federal
government in the custody battle to keep Elian in the United
States, after the child was found floating on an inner tube off the
coast of Fort Lauderdale on Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo demanded, in the days after the raid that returned Elian
to his father, that Warshaw fire O'Brien, who had refused to tell
Carollo about the raid on the house because he was afraid the mayor
would tip off demonstrators and create chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw refused to fire O'Brien, a 25-year police veteran, and
he himself was fired by Carollo on April 27.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien resigned the following day, saying he could no longer
work for the ``divisive'' and ``destructive'' Carollo.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Gimenez and Martinez said they wanted to get on with doing
their jobs. ``We need to put this whole episode behind us,'' said
Gimenez.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he was proud to be a Cuban-American police chief,
``but more proud to be just the chief of police.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few days, many outside the Cuban community have
reacted harshly to the exiles' protests of Elian's removal by
taking part in counter-demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Many feel they have no voice in a government that, to them,
seems to be by, of and for Cuban-Americans, and are angry at the
exiles' protests in which the American flag was flown upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Miami ``defines diversity and division now,'' said
Susan MacManus, a political science professor at the University of
South Florida. ``It's not surprising, but it is disheartening to
non-Cubans. There could be long-term negative consequences because
people feel they are not being represented.''
</P>
<P>
   Gimenez is not seen as a pure political appointee, but as a
capable administrator who is respected inside and outside city
hall, said James Corey, a political science professor at the
University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the ins and outs of this city's government,'' Corey
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, where more than 60 percent of voters are
Cuban-American, it is inevitable that political appointees will
reflect the community, pointed out some political experts.
</P>
<P>
   It is the timing, at such a sensitive time, that seems unwise to
the critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a purge to get rid of all the Anglos in the
city,'' said Max Castro, a senior research associate at the Dante
B. Fascell North-South Center at the University of Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
