<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0346 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-ELIAN-TV-COX     05-09 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elian media coverage in Atlanta expected to be a circus
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It should look like the media circus has come to town
when the Elian Gonzalez hearing takes place in Atlanta on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the TV weaponry sure to be employed on the narrow
downtown streets in front of the 11th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals
_ more than a dozen satellite trucks, banks of cameras aimed at the
courthouse doors, endless feet of cable snaking along the sidewalks
_ TV largely left this story a couple weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   So its arrival on Thursday is likely to be a one-day performance
_ just long enough to capture images of 6-year-old Elian's Miami
relatives, expected to attend the hearing; the lawyers for both
sides; whatever demonstrators are present; and developments from
inside the camera-free courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The major network news anchors are not scheduled to come to
Atlanta. Only the cable news networks are expected to report live
outside the courthouse. Other networks will report during their
morning shows and evening newscasts, and beefed-up local newscasts
will break in as events warrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drives the story for us are the images, and thus far the
images haven't changed,'' said CBS correspondent Byron Pitts, based
in Atlanta. ``All the networks will be there, they'll all do
stories, but I think there's a belief, as far as TV is concerned,
that it's drawing to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, this is a network TV soap opera,'' Pitts added,
``and while some episodes are more interesting than others, you
still have to cover every one. If this was a soap opera about a
60-year-old star having a baby, (Thursday's hearing) would be her
going for a sonogram.''
</P>
<P>
   With 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez out of camera range since federal
agents took him from Miami on April 22, TV coverage has fallen off
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   In April, 243 segments on the Gonzalez case appeared on
broadcast network morning shows, and 22 segments on afternoon and
evening newsmagazines, according to Kansas-based NewsTV
Corporation, which monitors coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But so far this month: only 9 segments have aired on morning
shows, and one segment on the newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 media credentials were granted inside the 136-seat
courtroom, picked from a lottery of about 45 media outlets, said
Norm Zoller, Circuit executive. WSB, which didn't get a lottery
credential, is paying two interns to camp out overnight in line for
when the public is admitted, first-come first-serve, beginning at 7
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Short of something unexpected, the most compelling image
Thursday is likely to be the departure from the courthouse of
Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not be able to read the judges, but we'll be looking
for any type of emotion or reaction from (the relatives),'' said
Sharon Fain, southeast bureau chief for Fox News, which is flying
in its New York booker to round up key players for its primetime
talkshows.
</P>
<P>
   At CNN, Thursday is merely ground zero for a story it has
covered from the start, whether there are compelling visuals or
not. Executives compare it covering a critical day at the U.S.
Supreme Court, which also bars cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a climatic moment in what's been a half-year saga,'' said
Keith McAllister, managing editor for national newsgathering.
``We're just going to do our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
