<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A REBEL LEADER'S DISAPPEARANCE, THE STORY OF A FORGOTTEN PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)  (See also SIERRA-LEONE-RESPONSE, SIERRA-LEONE-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make one-time purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ After a night of looting, the abandoned
house of the brutal rebel leader Foday Sankoh had been stripped of
almost everything on Tuesday morning. Looters had left gaping holes
in the brick walls where air-conditioners had kept out West
Africa's stifling heat, and they had absconded with every piece of
furniture, clothes and item of value.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the house, seven bodies, most of them Sankoh's
bodyguards, lay stiff in the bush and gutter. Inside, the looters
left behind only some garbage and scraps of paper.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were pages from an original copy of the 10-month-old
peace accord and an original copy of a document in which Sierra
Leone's president granted Sankoh _ the man responsible for a terror
campaign that left thousands of men, women and children killed or
maimed _ ``absolute and free pardon.'' That allowed him to live,
join a power-sharing government, form his political party and,
eventually, participate in presidential elections. At least that's
how the peace process was supposed to go.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it came undone. And so, Foday Sankoh, the legendary
survivor, a jungle fighter with barely a primary school education,
a failed commercial photographer, a cashiered corporal of Sierra
Leone's army, has succeeded in turning his small country into a big
problem for the world.
</P>
<P>
   He has humiliated the United Nations. He has embarrassed the
West, including the Clinton Administration.
</P>
<P>
   And now, after a confrontation outside his house on Monday, in
which his bodyguards killed at least four civilians while 75 U.N.
peacekeepers watched helplessly, he had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Had he vanished into the bush? Did a rival militia kidnap him?
Was he even alive? The U.N. force said it did not have him, and did
not know his whereabouts. In the confusion Monday, U.N.
peacekeepers fled from the compound and apparently did not return
in time to see what happened to Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are anxious to find a way of contacting Mr. Sankoh for
reasons that I think are clear to all,'' David Wimhurst, the
spokesman for the U.N. force, said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons related to the fact that 498 U.N. soldiers and
civilians being held hostage by Mr. Sankoh's men.
</P>
<P>
   In the confusion, the United Nations is trying to sort out what
it can do to restore order. Thousands of fresh troops from Jordan,
India and Bangladesh are expected to arrive sooner than originally
planned to operate under the U.N. flag. In addition, Washington has
sent a military team to Nigeria so that two Nigerian battalions can
be deployed here as a West African force.
</P>
<P>
   That came a mere week after the Nigerians left Sierra Leone and
Sankoh seized on their departure to attack the U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   The streets of Freetown remained tense on Tuesday, as British
paratroopers evacuated hundreds of Europeans. The paratroopers, who
arrived on Monday, were not expected to take part in the U.N.
force, though many could be seen on Tuesday operating checkpoints
and patrolling near the U.N. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the capital, Nigerian and Guinean soldiers for the
United Nations abandoned the junction town of Masiaka, about 35
miles east of here, after they ran out of ammunition, Wimhurst
said. Sankoh's loyalists were thought to be advancing toward
Freetown. Kamajors, traditional hunters who have been allied with
the government, as well as members of a military junta that briefly
controlled Sierra Leone in 1997, could be seen heading east out of
the capital.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.N. force began losing its grip on the country in recent
days, the country's main militias have re-emerged, recreating the
sense of lawlessness and anarchy that long pervaded Sierra Leone.
New alliances appear to have formed, most significantly between the
government and the 1997 junta, which was allied with Sankoh until
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 junta is made up of former soldiers and headed by Lt.
Col. Johnny Paul Koroma, who, like Sankoh, was a member of this
power-sharing government. Most residents of Freetown, particularly
those living around Sankoh's abandoned house, seem convinced that
Koroma had captured Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Koroma's house on Tuesday morning and afternoon _ where
young men dressed in sweats carried automatic rifles and walked up
and down a staircase above which hung a sign that read ``Peace'' _
men talked of waiting for arms supplies from the government so they
could go fight Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Koroma was too busy to talk, his aides said. But his personal
bodyguard, Hiroshima Bomb, who wore a skirt and a tanktop over
chest muscles of steel, and a necklace of ammunition rounds,
explained the new alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fight the RUF,'' Bomb said of Sankoh's organization. And of
the government that he had tried to topple only last year, he now
said: ``It's my father, my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens next to Sierra Leone will depend in great part on
whether Sankoh is alive or dead.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Sankoh's ruined house on Tuesday, one local man, Michael
Kamara, 50, said Sankoh's involvement was essential to resolving
the nine-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to express himself to the people,'' Kamara said. But
what if he were dead? ``Peace will take its course,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power and wealth to the people,'' read a poster in front of
Sankoh's destroyed house.
</P>
<P>
   It was with that message that Sankoh began a civil war from the
bush in 1991. The message struck a chord. Sierra Leone, rich with
diamonds, had long been controlled by a corrupt elite made up of
Lebanese businessmen and urban Sierra Leoneans. Many of these
Sierra Leoneans were descendants of the freed slaves who gave the
capital its name and formed a privileged class.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh represented the rural dispossessed.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Sankoh, who is in his 60s, seemed driven by a drive
for power. His ally, Charles Taylor, a guerilla fighter who
terrorized Liberia into making him its president, provided the
overall strategy: Target civilians and make their suffering so
great that they will make you president just to stop the suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Sankoh's group began committing the atrocities that
defined this war: chopping off people's hands and arms. Belgian
colonialist had done that decades ago to rule their colony in
central Africa, the Congo. But Sankoh infused the strategy with a
contemporary significance: his men cut people's hands because they
had used them to vote in 1997 for the current president, Ahmad
Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
   No hand, no more vote, his men said, as they chopped off limbs
with machetes and axes.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Sankoh did not believe in elections, preferring
the military option. Since the peace accord was signed in July, he
delayed laying down his weapons and obstructed peacekeepers from
deploying, especially in the diamond district, where his men kept
digging. Now it is believed they are better financed and equipped.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Mr. Sankoh's gutted house, in a second-floor room
designated ``confidential office'' and ``out of bounds to all,''
self-motivational messages decorated the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three kinds of people,'' read one of them. ``Those
who make things happen. Those who watch things happen. Those who
wonder what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, if he is alive, certainly sees himself belonging to the
first category, and has gambled that the international community
will fall into one of the others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
