<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0360 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CARLSON-DANCE-ART-$AD     05-09 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARLSON-DANCE-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A TOUR OF TABLEAUS, YOU MOVE, THEY DON'T 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM HARRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The choreographer and performance artist Ann Carlson has a knack
for astonishing audiences with simplicity. Downtown dance mavens
still oh and ah when recalling ``Visit Woman Move Story Cat Cat
Cat'' (1987), in which the voluptuous 5-foot-tall performer danced
naked while clutching a tiny kitten, vividly recreating the image
of Koko, the 300-pound female gorilla who learned to communicate
through sign language, and her pet kitten, All Ball.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of a series of dance works Carlson made in which
animals became her partners. And then there was the time in 1992
when she transformed the forbidding black-box theater at Dance
Theater Workshop into a gleaming white cube for an evening of
dances called ``Etihw,'' white spelled backward, that dealt with
purity, blindness and the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson, 45, has repeatedly based dances on ``what if''
scenarios _ often incorporating nontraditional performers _ while
exploring issues of community, femininity and mortality. In the
process, she often breaks down the barrier between performer and
spectator while redefining what constitutes performance. Carlson is
a conceptual artist who uses gesture, text and humor to break your
heart. As Jennifer Dunning wrote in The New York Times in 1998, ``
Carlson has an extraordinary gift for connecting the real and the
imaginary in ways that leave their mystery vibrantly intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson's new work will stretch the boundaries of dance
performance once again. ``Night Light,'' presented by Dancing in
the Streets in association with the Kitchen for eight performances
beginning on Wednesday, is a nighttime walking tour through the
Chelsea neighborhood of Manhattan. Eight guides _ people who live
or work in Chelsea _ will lead groups of 15 to several locations
where they will happen upon tableaux vivants in which historic
photographs taken at those sites will be reconstructed by dancers.
The dancers don't move, the audience does, but then again, ideas
about stillness have long been a part of Carlson's choreographic
vocabulary. For reservations and location, call the Kitchen at
(212) 255-5793, Extension 11.
</P>
<P>
   There will be seven tableaus in all, although no single tour
will visit every site. Included are images of three women in towels
at a Turkish bath, based on a photograph from 1904, priests leaving
General Theological Seminary carrying suitcases (a recruitment
advertisement from 1955), a murder victim and an 1895 Alice Austen
photo of a young woman selling newspapers on the corner of Sixth
Avenue and 23rd Street in Manhattan. (The reconstructed ``vendor''
will be on the same corner.) Austen, an amateur photographer who
took about 8,000 images, is considered a precursor of documentary
photography. Carlson, with the help of two photo researchers and
the Museum of the City of New York, scavenged through thousands of
images before settling on these.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many issues in each photo,'' Carlson said. ``I
don't have a photographic background and it's been interesting to
learn about what photos are staged or not staged _ in one sense,
they are all staged _ and what the archives hold. You fall into
this abyss of whose history we are talking about when you look at
the archives. What gets kept? What gets remembered? It's very
difficult, for instance, to find historic images of people of
color. The photos also reveal issues of class. My concern is how do
you talk about that and not be didactic?''
</P>
<P>
   On one level, ``Night Light'' is a timely examination of
gentrification and displacement, of how one industrial section of
New York _ not accessible by public transportation _ has become one
of the centers of the contemporary art world. Dozens of galleries
have transformed garages into sleek exhibition spaces. And it's not
uncommon to bump into tour groups wandering through the galleries
on weekends. At the same time, Carlson is winking at herself as
part of this privileged, hipster world. Her portrait, taken with
the videographer Mary Ellen Strom, her partner of the last 10
years, was included in the recent Catherine Opie show at Gorney
Bravin Lee on West 26th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of ordinary people and their extraordinary stories has
been a recurrent element in Carlson's work. She burst onto the New
York performance scene in 1986 with ``Sloss, Kerr, Rosenberg and
Moore,'' a nine-minute dance for four real-life attorneys. The
performers were confined to a rectangular area taped on the floor
and never looked at one another. Through their wild gesticulations,
Carlson hilariously captured the competitive and insecure world of
corporate life. Other pieces using nuns, security guards and
basketball players have followed.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson, who grew up in Park Ridge, Ill., graduated magna cum
laude from the University of Utah with a bachelor's degree in
dance. She earned a graduate degree at the University of Arizona
before moving to New York in 1984. Specifically, she came hoping to
work with Meredith Monk, a multidisciplinary artist she had read
about but had never met or seen perform. She auditioned and did not
get into the troupe at first, but in 1986 she did join Monk, who
subsequently insisted that Carlson leave to pursue her own muse.
Today, Carlson lives in Stuyvesant Town with Strom and their three
adopted children, 7-year-old twin boys and a daughter, 6.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two years, ``Night Light'' will be recreated in
Boston, Chicago, Portland, Ore., and Riverside, Calif. In each
city, the presenter will pick the neighborhood for the tours, and
Carlson will then do the photographic research. Meanwhile, she is
presenting a new solo at the American Dance Festival in Durham,
N.C., on June 11 and 12, a companion piece to ``Grass/Bird/Rodeo,''
a triptych of solos she performed in February at grade school P.S.
122. In that piece, Carlson tries to demystify the choreographic
process by telling stories about the work and taking questions from
the audience before each section.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Night Light' is looking into a moment that is gone,''
Carlson said. ``I loved the idea of seeing these two-dimensional
photos brought back into three dimensions. I'm recreating these
images in a gray scale _ these ghostly images in a full-toned
world.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
