<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0367 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-GEORGIA-COX     05-09 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GEORGIA-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush backs Barnes' education plan
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Judd
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's conversation with teachers at High Point
Elementary, one of Fulton County's most culturally diverse schools,
was going fine. The Republican presidential candidate's questions
and the teachers' answers closely followed the event's theme: the
importance of educating all children, regardless of their
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush asked about Georgia's new education reform plan.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was silence. Then, nervous laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you don't want to tell me,'' Bush said finally, ending
an awkward moment.
</P>
<P>
   High Point's principal, Linda Sumpter, explained that she and
her staff weren't sure yet what to make of Democratic Gov. Roy
Barnes' education plan. The measure mandates smaller class sizes
and increased testing to measure student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of sitting on hold,'' Sumpter said, ``waiting,
being diplomatic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I suggest you be diplomatic,'' Bush said, laughing. Increased
accountability, he added, ``shouldn't trouble anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's endorsement of Barnes' education plan was the only
surprise during the Texas governor's tightly scripted campaign
visit to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh earlier Tuesday, Bush received the endorsement of
a former GOP rival, U.S. Sen. John McCain of Arizona. In Atlanta,
he wanted to mark National Teachers Day by emphasizing his
commitment to public education. To make sure no one missed the
point, Bush's staff covered a wall of the High Point library with a
banner that read, ``No Child Left Behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he came to High Point, off Glenridge Drive in Sandy
Springs, because of its diversity. About 40 percent of its 700
students are Hispanic, and about one-third take classes for
children for whom English is a second language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a school that's not afraid of standards and expectations
and measurement,'' Bush told Sumpter and the eight teachers who
joined him for a 30-minute roundtable discussion. ``The
accountability system you use here shows you are improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaching children who live in homes where English isn't spoken
is crucial to ensuring that ``America's promise extends its reach
to every single family in our country,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, he said, he responded to proponents of an English-only
policy with, ``Why don't we have English-plus? We respect other
languages. Plus, we respect somebody else's culture. I think it's
important for our society.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he told parents gathered outside the school _ in Spanish
_ that their children need to learn English.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they're here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Vice President Al Gore, who is seeking the
Democratic presidential nomination, called reporters in Atlanta to
dispute Bush's commitment to education. ``He can talk the talk,''
said spokesman Todd Webster. ``But if you look at his proposals and
plans, they're much different that the rosy picture he is
painting.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush's visit, High Point's diversity was on abundant
display. A sign in the school lobby welcomed the candidate with,
``Bienvenidos, George Bush.'' And two of the teachers Bush spoke
with were Hispanics who now work with children who, like them, had
to learn English in school.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Bush arrived, just before 4 p.m., most of the
Hispanic students had headed home on school buses. The majority of
the children who greeted his motorcade were white and, judging by
the BMWs and sport utility vehicles their parents parked nearby,
upper middle-class.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were first-grader Emily Nault and third-grader Ryan
Williams. They stood near the school's front door, holding a
hand-lettered poster that said, ``Welcome, Governor Bush'' in red,
white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it's the only time I'm going to see him,'' said
Emily, 7. Asked what she knew about Bush, she answered, ``He's the
governor of Texas. He has a brother that's the governor of
Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   After Ryan whispered to her, she added, ``His father was
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, 9, was more interested in the controlled chaos surrounding
the candidate's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the secret agents,'' he said. ``And the camera
people.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
