<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-JUDGE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge blasts Lewis prosecutors
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Torpy
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A judge scolded prosecutors Tuesday after learning
that Atlanta police had destroyed investigative notes in the Ray
Lewis murder case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find troubling the destruction of handwritten notes,'' said
Fulton County Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bonner ruled that police did not exhibit ``bad faith''
in destroying notes of witness interviews and therefore she would
not exclude any prosecution testimony or reports. She did order
prosecutors to make some of their witnesses available to defense
attorneys for them to interview.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony, defense attorneys pointed out that lead
investigator Ken Allen, in some of his notes that survived, had
written partial quotes, such as: ``Ray and Shorty at corner'' and
``pull off victim.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the finished report, Lewis was pulling a participant of
the fight into a limousine. There is nothing mentioned about anyone
being pulled off a victim.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner noted that the ``discrepancy was material and
substantive,'' adding ``If there's a lot more like it, it will
matter to the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner also chided prosecutors for not telling police to keep
their notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much longer or how often the district
attorney's office can get away with not being specific enough'' and
not telling investigators to turn over their notes, Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   If a defense team opts into the discovery process, the
prosecutors ``shall produce for the opposing party any statement of
any witness that is in the possession, custody or control of the
state ...,'' according to state statute. The process was
established so a defendant would not be blindsided with new
evidence during trial.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Elizabeth Baker told the judge
``it's regrettable there was a lack of communication'' between
police and prosecutors but noted that a recent Georgia Supreme
Court ruling said officers don't have to maintain notes.
</P>
<P>
   In McGee v. State, the state high court said the landmark
federal Brady v. Maryland ruling ``does not require that agents of
the state retain rough notes made in the course of their
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, defense attorneys are eager to obtain raw notes to
find such discrepancies. Allen said he destroys notes because they
become ``very messy.'' The Lewis case is his second homicide.
</P>
<P>
   The motions hearing is expected to be the last before jurors
come in Friday to answer questionnaires. Jury selection begins
Monday. Lewis and co-defendants Joseph Sweeting and Reginald Oakley
are charged with murder in the Jan. 31 stabbing deaths of two
Decatur men in a Buckhead street fight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
