<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0371 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN-GUIDE-COX     05-09 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-GUIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elian whirlwind about to greet Atlanta police
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The spotlight will be trained on the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals Thursday when three judges hear arguments on
whether 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez will be allowed to apply for
asylum to the U.S. against the wishes of his Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the drama will unfold outside the courthouse along
Forsyth Street, where hundreds are expected to protest and
pontificate why the young castaway should or should not be allowed
to remain in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban Americans _ both local and from Miami _ are expected to
flock to the courthouse as early as 8 a.m. Most want Elian to stay
in the United States, with or without his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Other demonstrators _ such as the North Atlanta chapter of the
national group Fathers Are Parents Too _ will conduct a news
conference to talk about fathers' rights. FAPT is in favor of Elian
returning to Cuba with his surviving parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primacy of parental rights should take precedence over
politics,'' said Tony Zizza, vice president of FAPT's North Atlanta
chapter. ``We expect about 100 people to attend Thursday. The main
thing we want to talk about is that fathers should have the same
rights as mothers do when it comes to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Other protests are planned across the country this week.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever views and political leanings rumble outside the
courthouse Thursday, the Atlanta Police Department believes it is
ready. It has even set up separate areas for protesters with
opposing views.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're no strangers to protests,'' said Maj. John Woodard, who
heads the police precinct that covers downtown. ``We'll have
several officers from the precinct, as well as several officers
from the Special Operations Section, out there. There will also be
officers from Special Operations on standby in case things get out
of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of the department's Spanish-speaking officers have
been reassigned to deal with demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrian traffic will be prohibited in the immediate area
surrounding the courthouse. Several streets bordering the building
will be blocked off. The city's motorcycle units will patrol the
area, redirecting traffic, said Woodard and Deputy Chief Wesley
Derrick.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is scheduled to begin about 9 a.m. and is expected
to last less than an hour. About 100 seats are available to the
public on a first-come, first-served basis. Doors open at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the group espousing the parental rights of fathers
is Chicago-based attorney Jeffery Leving. The lawyer, whose mother
is Cuban, also represents Manuel Gonzalez, one of Elian's great
uncles and the eldest brother of Lazaro Gonzalez, the great uncle
who kept Elian in Miami for five months.
</P>
<P>
   Leving was retained by Manuel Gonzalez after Juan Miguel
Gonzalez wrote a letter to U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno asking
her to give custody of his son to Manuel Gonzalez, who also lives
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole things has divided the Gonzalez family,'' Leving
said. ``This should never have been about politics. It's all about
a father's rights to his child.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
