A0375 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-BEGALA-DELAY-NYT     05-09 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-BEGALA-DELAY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS PLAY THE VENGEANCE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for use in papers of Wednesday, May 10)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By PAUL E. BEGALA    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The congressional Democrats' racketeering lawsuit
against Rep. Tom DeLay, the House majority whip, is wrong,
ethically, legally and politically.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which charges DeLay with extortion, racketeering and
money laundering in his aggressive fund-raising for Republican
candidates, represents everything I hated about the politics of
personal destruction as it was waged against President Clinton.
Those of us who decried the abuse of the legal system for partisan
ends then now have a moral obligation to condemn the legal pursuit
of DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seems to lack merit. G. Robert Blakey, the legal
scholar who assisted in drafting the Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations Act, said that the statute was intended to
police business and criminal behavior, not political fund-raising.
``This is the kind of case that gives RICO a bad name,'' he told
The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   By going after a Republican leader, the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee is doing Republicans an enormous favor: shifting
attention from the GOP's pathetic record on gun control, Social
Security, the patients' bill of rights and other issues that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, DeLay has met with lobbyists in his Capitol office, where
they were allowed to write their own special interest legislation
themselves (``because,'' he said, ``they have the expertise'').
</P>
<P>
   But while the conduct he is accused of may raise ethical
questions, it isn't criminal. Maybe it should be, but until
Congress toughens campaign finance laws, politicians will seize
every advantage they can. And if there is a question about criminal
conduct, we have a perfectly competent Justice Department to decide
if there's a case to be made.
</P>
<P>
   If I were still running Democratic campaigns, I would
undoubtedly be troubled by reports that DeLay has a scheme to swamp
my candidates with unlimited, undisclosed money, an outrageous new
tactic. But the answer is: Run to the press and call on reporters
to investigate. Run to the voters and tell them about any secret
schemes. But don't run to the courthouse to file a suit that
equates Tom ``the Hammer'' DeLay with Sammy ``the Bull'' Gravano.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee was pursuing its nasty business against DeLay, House
Republicans were busy using hearings to torment current and former
White House aides. The former deputy White House counsel Cheryl
Mills, now a private citizen, spoke for many of us when she
addressed the GOP members harassing her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could spend your time making the lives of the individuals
you serve better,'' she said, ``as opposed to tearing down the
staff of a president with whose vision and policies you disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats sue Republicans. Republicans investigate Democrats. As
I watched the president, the first lady, innumerable staffers and
too many honest cabinet officers bankrupted by right-wing attempts
to carry their partisan warfare into the courtroom and the
committee room, I wondered how the cycle would ever be broken.
Payback is a natural human emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Well, here is how it ends: I'm going to say what too few
Republicans of conscience were willing to say that their party
wrongfully harassed the president and those around him; my party
should drop the suit against DeLay and return to talking about
issues. If we do that, we're more likely to win. And I know we'll
be more deserving of victory.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul E. Begala, who served as counselor to President Clinton
from 1997 to 1999, teaches government at Georgetown and is co-host
of ``Equal Time'' on MSNBC.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
