A0376 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-GILBERT-MICROSOF     05-09 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-GILBERT-MICROSOFT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BETTER BREAKUP THAN AT&AMP;T'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for use in papers of Wednesday, May 10)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By RICHARD GILBERT    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ As Microsoft's lawyers present proposals for
far less radical changes than splitting the company in two, it is
tempting to look at Microsoft and see AT&AMP;T. The breakup that
Microsoft is trying to forestall, but that the Justice Department
and 17 states have asked a federal court to order, seems
reminiscent of the antitrust settlement that divided AT&AMP;T into a
long-distance telephone network and a group of local phone
companies. But the appearance is deceiving _ and not just because
the companies themselves are different.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has made a persuasive case for ending
Microsoft's monopoly in computer operating systems, and it made a
compelling one in the 1980s for breaking up the regulated telephone
monopoly. But the government can do this job better: its proposal
for Microsoft does not create the same innovation-stifling
conditions that were imposed on telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T breakup did what was intended: it opened competition in
the telephone business and quickly gave consumers lower
long-distance prices and new services. But it also brought an era
of micromanagement of telecommunications by a federal court.
</P>
<P>
   It is now the computer industry that needs to be invigorated
with competition, and we have already found that merely setting
down rules to restrain Microsoft's conduct is not enough. The
company signed a consent decree in 1994 agreeing to forgo certain
restrictive arrangements with computer equipment makers. But in
practice, these rules did little to change the company's
exclusionary conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's plan for breaking up the company allows
the marketplace, not the courts, to decide where the industry will
go next. The architects of the government's plan have carefully
avoided including the ``line of business'' restrictions that put
boundaries on what services the Baby Bells and AT&AMP;T could offer.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the two new companies created from Microsoft would be
prohibited from offering the identical products sold by the other
company, and they would be barred from recombining through merger.
But nothing in the government proposal prevents either company from
developing a new product that competes with a product offered by
the other. The operating system company could develop a new word
processing or spreadsheet programs. The applications company could
develop a new operating system.
</P>
<P>
   After the AT&AMP;T judgment, Judge Harold Greene arbitrated disputes
for more than a decade on matters like whether the Baby Bells could
provide data, video and voice-mail services. The stream of requests
for waivers of provisions in the judgment clogged his court and
threatened to strangle technological and commercial progress.
Eventually, Congress restructured the industry with the 1996
Telecommunications Act.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows with any certainty what the next big change will be
in the computer industry, or from where it will come. It is
important to allow innovation to flow from any source. Microsoft
argues that the government's proposed remedies to curb its
monopolistic behavior would curb its innovation.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, the breakup it spells out would let the computer
industry itself _ within a new framework of competition _ decide
the future of technological development.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Gilbert teaches economics at the University of
California at Berkeley and was chief economist in the Justice
Department antitrust division from 1993 to 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the OPED
package and other features. &QL;
</P>
