<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW-COX     05-09 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush has quite a lot to be relieved about
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He looked like a man with a load off his mind, which he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great,'' George W. Bush said of his
long-awaited meeting earlier in the day in Pittsburgh with his
chief Republican rival, Sen. John McCain. The Texas governor was
kicking back with some lemonade after an afternoon session with
educators at High Point Elementary School here.
</P>
<P>
   ``John knew, for example, I was interested in reforming Social
Security. He wanted to hear the passion in my voice. He wanted to
know I was as committed to Social Security reform as he is,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has not yet laid out the full details of his Social
Security plan, said ``the initial step for reform'' could be
accomplished in the first years of the next administration. McCain
(R-Ariz.), Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.) and others have spoken of
getting a bipartisan commission's report on the president's desk by
2001, and Bush said it would be a priority.
</P>
<P>
   They'd talked about campaign finance reform as well, Bush said,
but while he said McCain ``understands I have a desire to reform
the system,'' Bush's response seemed to suggest the passion
regarding that issue was still in the other voice.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has accused Bush of hiding his plans for
Social Security and challenged him to a debate devoted to the
issue, but Bush insisted he would lay out his plan ``on my terms,
on my timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You notice the last couple of weeks the vice president has
been spending a lot of time talking about me. I'm talking about me.
I kind of like it that way. We've got two of us talking about me,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the meeting to smooth his strained relations with
McCain was something Bush likely was glad to have out of the way,
his greatest relief has to come from the polls, which have him
leading in the Midwestern states considered key to this year's
election and comfortably ahead in the South.
</P>
<P>
   As good as the news has been, these are the slow days before the
conventions. While Gore has taken some shots at Bush, the heavy
artillery hasn't been deployed yet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked his impression of Democratic Rep. Patrick
Kennedy's suit against his fellow Texan, House Majority Whip Tom
Delay, charging that Delay's strong-arm tactics with lobbyists
amounted to extortion. Wasn't it likely Gore's campaign would try
to hang Delay around Bush's neck?
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be. Probably. But I don't think that's going to work. I
think America's going to look for something better than that in the
campaign,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it's like in your state Capitol here, but
they're making some reforms. Barnes is a Democrat, you've got a
bunch of Republicans over there, and I know they're squabbling over
some aspects of the reform package, but they're making progress. We
did the same thing in Texas. ... Washington is full of rancor,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the party switching disputes of the past weeks, some
Republican legislators might not be as upbeat about the spirit of
cooperation under the Gold Dome. But it's interesting that we now
have two presidential candidates citing Georgia as an example of
how to do things right.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
