<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0381 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SCFLAG-DEBATE-COX     05-09 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCFLAG-DEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No consensus on flag debate
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Columbia, S.C. _ Today on one of South Carolina's newest
holidays, Confederate Memorial Day, the state House continues
wading through 40 more amendments on a bill that would remove the
controversial Confederate battle flag from the dome of the
Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   On its first day of formal flag debate Tuesday, the House found
no consensus as it debated for nearly six hours. It passed just one
amendment _ a proposal similar to a Senate plan that black House
members have said they will not support.
</P>
<P>
   While other state offices will be closed today to observe the
new holiday, the General Assembly and Gov. Jim Hodges plan to work.
The House reconvenes this morning.
</P>
<P>
   The House debate is being watched closely throughout the Deep
South, where the controversy over Confederate symbols is spreading.
Creation of Confederate Memorial Day, in fact, was part of a
compromise last month that also created a holiday honoring slain
civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   As debate on the flag began Tuesday, a handful of flag
supporters gathered outside on the Statehouse lawn and waved their
deep red Rebel flags.
</P>
<P>
   Cool-headed debate on the floor evoked comments on race
relations, the Civil War, honor and the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Becky Meacham-Richardson, a Republican flag supporter
from Fort Mill, proposed a nonbinding statewide vote on the flag.
The House tabled her amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought, really, that we were a government of the
people and by the people and for the people,'' Meacham-Richardson
said from the House well, ``not a government of the NAACP, by the
NAACP and for the NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
launched a tourism boycott of South Carolina Jan. 1
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP lacks support for its boycott, according to a new
Gallup poll. The same survey showed fewer people see the
Confederate flag as a symbol of Southern heritage.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 U.S. adults were questioned and 65 percent
opposed the boycott, 27 percent supported it. According to 59
percent of the respondents, the flag represents Southern pride. In
1992, 69 percent of poll respondents said it was a symbol of Dixie
pride.
</P>
<P>
   The House also tabled a plan supported by the Democratic caucus
to remove the flag and replace it at the Confederate Soldiers
Monument with a bronze likeness of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, especially black House members, supported that
compromise, pushed by former House speaker Robert Sheheen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lacks a flag ... I think this is an insult,'' said Rep.
Bill Cotty (R-Columbia), a member of the House Judiciary Committee,
which proposed a plan similar to what the Senate approved.
</P>
<P>
   The committee plan, offered by Cotty and the first one
considered, was defeated in a close vote.
</P>
<P>
   If the House agrees to change the bill sent to it, the Senate
could accept it, send it to a conference committee where members
from both chambers would work out differences, or it could amend
the bill again and send it back to the House, which then only would
have the option of approving or rejecting the measure.
</P>
<P>
   If Hodges calls the General Assembly back into special session
because the House can't settle on a plan, Sen. Glenn McConnell _ a
chief architect of the Senate compromise _ said that might be a
waste of time. The chambers could vote to adjourn, then be dragged
back by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect if this debate drags on, the chances of the flag
staying at the dome, because of the lack of common ground, will
probably grow,'' McConnell said. ``I say that because I don't know
of anywhere else we in the Senate really can go now.''
</P>
<P>
   Flag supporters say they'll counter the NAACP boycott with a
boycott of Michelin and other prominent South Carolina-based
companies calling for the flag to come down. Farmers, commuters and
truck drives will be urged to buy tires from other companies, said
Jerry Creech, chairman of the Southern Heritage Coalition. Drivers
will be asked to send their tire bills to Michelin's headquarters
in France and ``tell them to stay out of South Carolina's
business.''
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) O N T H E W E B : Discuss the South Carolina flag
controversy: www.accessatlanta.com/community/forums/
</P>
<P>
   Flag opponents: www.getinstep.com
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Heritage Coalition: www.kudzumedia.com/schc.htm
</P>
<P>
   Sons of Confederate Veterans: www.scv.org
</P>
<P>
   NAACP: www.naacp.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
