<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      05-09 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO CROWD'S DELIGHT, GORE TRIES BORSCHT BELT, WITH A TWANG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., D.C., S.C., Minn., Mich., Ohio, Ill., Pa., Mo.)   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore goes Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the nation's political attention seemed focused on
Sen. John McCain's endorsement of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for
president, the notably unethnic, Southern Baptist vice president
said the heck with it and tried out a Borscht Belt routine before a
largely Jewish audience here.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose family comes from Tennessee, told the
Anti-Defamation League that a sub-genre of music was proliferating
in Nashville _ the Jewish country-western song.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 on the hit list, he said, was this: ``I was one of the
chosen people _ until she chose somebody else.'' No. 3: ``The
second time she said `Shalom' I knew she meant goodbye.'' No. 2:
``I've got my foot on the glass, now where are you?''
</P>
<P>
   And No. 1, which the vice president sang with a soft lilt and a
twang: ``Mommas, don't let your ungrateful sons grow up to be
cowboys when they could very easily just have taken over the family
business that my own grandfather broke his back to start and my
father sweated over for years, which apparently doesn't mean
anything now that you're turning your back on such a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience roared and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks, the vice president really wanted to get in
on the McCain-Bush act.
</P>
<P>
   He has been struggling for weeks against the presidential-level
attention paid to McCain who, despite suspending his presidential
campaign, remains enormously popular and has been absorbing much of
the available political oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore, who has been lagging in the polls behind Bush, is
still overtly courting the independent-minded voters who were
attracted to McCain's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of the Bush-McCain meeting Tuesday, Gore had held a
private visit with McCain in Washington. And today, his little
humor routine aside, he used his speech to about 450 members of the
Anti-Defamation League to try to draw a contrast between McCain and
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming the two Republicans, Gore said it was wrong not
to condemn the Confederate battle flag flying over the South
Carolina statehouse. Bush has said repeatedly that it is up to the
state to decide whether to bring it down. McCain said the same
thing during the Republican primaries, but last month he voiced
regret for not having spoken out against the flag, saying he was
afraid that such a stand could have cost him votes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Tuesday of the flag controversy: ``We know it is wrong
not only to support it but to find it impossible to summon the
moral courage to speak out about it. It is wrong to remain silent
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's remarks allowed room for McCain's reversal but not for
Bush's continued refusal to condemn the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech was an official one as vice president, and the
league is a tax-exempt organization that cannot endorse political
candidates. But Gore's speech was certainly a political one,
designed to paint Bush as an extremist and undermine any impression
that McCain's endorsement might make Bush more acceptable to
independents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Independent voters are definitely on Gore's mind. Much of his
campaign since he secured the Democratic nomination has been geared
toward swing voters in battleground states from Pennsylvania, Ohio,
Michigan, Illinois and Missouri. And just as he has been wooing
McCain supporters, he has also been going after the backers of
Jesse Ventura, the independent governor of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Ventura was at the White House this morning for
a pep rally in support of permanent trade relations with China, and
Gore singled him out for thanks, among others, as did President
Clinton. Gore had also had Ventura and his wife to his home in
Washington last month for a private dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The gateway topic for Gore to cozy up to both McCain and Ventura
has been overhauling the campaign finance system, and campaign
aides said they expected the vice president to explore the topic
publicly with both as the campaign progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Gore's speech to the Anti-Defamation League poked
fun at his own obvious differences with his audience, he still
hoped to convey his commitment to their causes. ``I feel right at
home here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His commitments included support for a national law against hate
crimes. This amounted to another dig at Bush, who critics have said
failed to shepherd through such a law in Texas. In a speech that
extolled the virtues of tolerance, he sprinkled his comments with
references to famous Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freud once spoke about the narcissism of slight difference,
just as Einstein taught that the most destructive power known on
earth is within the smallest state we know _ the inside of the
atom,'' Gore said. ``The smallest differences sometimes unleash the
most horrific violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also won applause when he used the Hebrew phrase, ``Refua
shlayma,'' to wish a complete recovery to Abraham Foxman, the
league's national director, who recently had bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Howard Berkowitz, national chairman of the league, said
that the league had been concerned that both candidates were
injecting too much religion into the campaign. ``We want to make
sure that one candidate doesn't out-religion the other,'' he said,
citing Bush's comment that Jesus was his favorite philosopher.
``These things are better left in private,'' Berkowitz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
