<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-METHODISTS-COX     05-09 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Gay issues, guns take center stage
</P>
<P>
   By Gayle White
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland _ United Methodists entering the convention center
here today are braced for a gay rights demonstration that is
drawing activists from across the country, including Yolanda King,
daughter of slain civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the quadrennial General Conference of the United
Methodist Church are expected to vote Thursday on whether to keep
the church's prohibition against performing same-sex blessing
ceremonies and ordaining sexually active homosexuals to the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates spent part of Tuesday morning debating another
emotionally charged issue, gun control. After a discussion of
whether to include handguns, they voted by a 3-1 ratio for a
resolution calling on the U.S. government and other governments
where United Methodists are a presence to outlaw ``ownership by the
general public of handguns, assault weapons, automatic weapon
conversion kits and weapons that cannot be detected by
traditionally used metal detection devices.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, North Georgia delegates huddled around
their bishop, Lindsey Davis, for a pep talk and strategy session on
what to expect today as Soulforce, a gay rights coalition, stages a
vigil outside the meeting hall. ``I would encourage you to not be
nervous about it,'' Davis said. ``Stay calm and loving and
gracious, just as you always are.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishop told the delegates that the presence of security
guards and Cleveland police, already increasingly visible, will
probably be even greater today.
</P>
<P>
   North Georgia's 26 delegates favor keeping the bans on same-sex
ceremonies and gay ordination, said Tom Jackson, a lay delegate
from Athens. ``It was a litmus test for being elected to the
conference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The General Conference legislative committee responsible for
handling gay and lesbian issues has recommended maintaining the
status quo in the denomination's Book of Discipline, with the
addition of an admonition not to ``reject or condemn'' homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a more conservative General Conference,'' said
the Rev. Martha Forrest, district superintendent of the
Atlanta-College Park district and a candidate for bishop later this
summer. ``I feel fairly confident that the Discipline will remain
the same on same-sex unions and ordination.''
</P>
<P>
   While the North Georgia delegates discussed their response, at a
hotel several blocks from the convention center Tuesday afternoon
several dozen people attended a workshop sponsored by Soulforce.
Demonstrators are planning to block the taxi ramp to the convention
center today, and its leaders have negotiated terms of possible
arrest and punishment with Cleveland police.
</P>
<P>
   Arun Gandhi, grandson of Mahatma Gandhi, who is participaing in
the demostration said he believes he is doing what his grandfather
would have done _ but said, ``It will take many such instances to
bring about change.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Marlan of San Jose, Calif., co-chair of the Soulforce
event, admitted in an interview Tuesday that the group has little
hope of persuading delegates to change the denomination's position
on sexuality issues this week..
</P>
<P>
   ``We see our role as being able to bring public attention to
what's going on,'' he said. ``Delegates have their minds made up in
a lot of ways. We know that. In a way, what we're trying to do is
plant seed for 2004. We will be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
