<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-ETHIOPIA-ART-NYT     05-09 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-ETHIOPIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. GROUP IN AFRICA SWITCHES FOCUS TO ETHIOPIA-ERITREA CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea _ A United Nations Security Council delegation
visiting Africa has abruptly shifted its attention from the crisis
in Congo to the Ethiopian-Eritrean border, where hundreds of
thousands of troops on both sides are preparing for imminent war,
Western intelligence reports say.
</P>
<P>
   With the crisis in Sierra Leone hovering over both regional
problems, the Security Council decided in the past 24 hours to
intervene in the Horn of Africa conflict, hoping to prevent an
outbreak of fighting along the border. As the three crises have
come together in the past week, the Security Council's unusual
field trip to Africa has become more eventful, complicated and
immediately purposeful than any members had imagined, officials
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the trip was planned,'' said Richard C. Holbrooke, U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations and the leader of the council
delegation, ``Congo was the No. 1 crisis in Africa. By the time we
got here, it had dropped to No. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuttling back and forth Tuesday between Ethiopia's capital,
Addis Ababa, and the Eritrean capital, Asmara, the council members
were urging Prime Minister Meles Zenawi of Ethiopia and President
Isaias Afwerki of Eritrea to consider seriously the consequences of
reigniting what one diplomat called ``the stupidest war in
Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks began on Monday night and are expected to continue through
Wednesday. Because of the high tension between the two countries,
the council's chartered Boeing 737 cannot fly directly between
Addis Ababa and Asmara, but has to detour over Djibouti and the Red
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, Ethiopia and Eritrea have battled sporadically over
inland border territory at a cost of tens of thousands of lives.
With a peace agreement brokered by the Organization of African
Unity almost within reach, negotiations broke down last week in
Algiers. After reports that more troops, equipment and medical
supplies were being moved to the border, the British and French
ambassadors on the Security Council delegation proposed visiting
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of us succeeding are very small,'' Holbrooke said.
``Our sole objective is to get the OAU talks restarted. The U.N. is
not going to replace the OAU in the Horn. But maybe the Security
Council's support will encourage the two parties to talk instead of
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unacceptable that two of the poorest countries on earth
_ one with 16 million people facing famine _ should bring their
troops to the border to prepare for war. It's senseless. Completely
senseless. The last war resulted in 50,000 deaths, and this could
happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said after Wednesday's talks, ``I was sitting there
listening to these two highly articulate, intelligent men on the
edge of a war over trivial differences in the midst of a famine''
in Ethiopia, ``and I thought: This is one of the saddest things I
ever saw in international affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the problem between Ethiopia and Eritrea _ led by
two men who were once allies, until Eritrea effectively won
independence from Ethiopia _ has been the last of three pacts that
together form a peace package. It covers the technicalities of
pulling back troops and restoring property along the disputed
border.
</P>
<P>
   The French ambassador, Jean-David Levitte, said in an interview
Wednesday that remaining problems could be solved by arbitration.
He said he emerged from a session with Meles of Ethiopia taken
aback by the casual way in which these countries seem to be gearing
up for war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Meles, `When you start a war you think you will
achieve results fast,''' Levitte said. ``But that could be a
miscalculation. That's exactly what happened when the war started
in 1914 in Europe. On both sides, the French and the Germans and
their allies, were convinced that after a few weeks, there would be
a victory _ and a victory on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, I said, `When you start a war you never know,''' Levitte
added. ``The result of this miscalculation in Europe was, four
years later, millions of dead people and an end to a possible
positive role for both countries for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at reports on preparations for war on the border,
Levitte said that he is reminded frequently of World War I, and he
said that he pointed that out to Meles. ``You have, face to face,
two armies entrenched,'' he said, ``and it will be very, very
bloody, because first will come the planes and the guns, then
infantry from Ethiopia will fight to get more land and thousands of
young Ethiopians will be killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer of Meles was absolutely incredible,'' Levitte said.
``He said: `No, there is a difference. We poor countries cannot
afford long wars. We have not enough money to buy arms in
quantities to maintain the war effort for a long period.' He
implied that having made the effort to equip an army, he wanted a
fast return on the investment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
