<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0388 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-RANDYJOHNSON-COX     05-09 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RANDYJOHNSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson's harnessing huge talent in 7-0 start
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix, Ariz _Randy Johnson regrets a lot of it now. The years
he led the league in walks. The aimless rages. The senseless nights
when he kept throwing as hard as he could until his arm went as
limp as his Spinal Tap 'do. He went nearly half his career, he
admits now, without knowing how to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   It seems impossible to believe now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, every athlete wants to be successful. To what
extent? Some more than others,'' Johnson said. ``Once again, that
word complacency comes in there. I'm really never satisfied with
anything that I do. I took some lumps when I was younger and have
kind of come into my own.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm feeling I'm right where I want to be right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell the National League about it. Where he is, is 7-0 with an
absurdly low 0.93 ERA, facing Los Angeles and ace Kevin Brown
tonight, trying to extend the game's finest spring campaign since
Pedro Martinez, then in Montreal, won his first seven starts in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will find what baseball has seen over the season's
first five weeks. The Big Unit, now 36, not only is the most
dominating pitcher over the last half-decade; he somehow is still
traveling an upward gradient.
</P>
<P>
   If he did not comprehend the pitcher's art until he reached 30,
then this is his payback. And the payback, as former teammate Bret
Boone said, is ``a freaking titanic struggle, like it always is.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson emerged from April with the best showing in baseball
history. He is the third pitcher to win six times during the month.
Vida Blue did it in Oakland in 1971, and Dave Stewart did it in
Toronto in 1988. Neither came close to Johnson's minute ERA, made
up of six earned runs in his first 58 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire guys like Randy and Roger Clemens because they
dominate,'' Blue said. ``I'll take the power pitchers. I know there
are guys like Greg Maddux, but I like the guy who blows you away.''
</P>
<P>
   That scouting report is dying a long death. Johnson continues to
run up double-digit strikeout counts _ 131 times, second only to
Nolan Ryan's remarkable 215 _ but the Unit's reputation for
traditional pitching has expanded. Working a two-seam fastball into
his repertoire over the past two years, Johnson still can reach 100
mph with his four-seamer and then throw a 93-mph two-seamer that
sinks. He finishes the show with his unworldly slider; it is a
slicing wonder, which on April 20 struck out Colorado's Brian
Hunter swinging as the ball bounced under his back foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person seeing it on TV can't really get the picture,'' said
Diamondbacks catcher Damian Miller, who usually handles Johnson's
starts. ``You can't explain how absolutely nasty it is. It's
ridiculous. When he's pounding that 98-mile-per-hour fastball in
and then he throws that slider, it's stupid is what it is. It's
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   So are Johnson's numbers. He leads the majors in wins, ERA,
innings, complete games (4), shutouts (2), strikeouts (76) and
lowest batting average allowed (.156). All of that follows the 1999
Cy Young season, in which he set personal bests for complete games
(12) and innings (271 2/3) while leading both leagues with his
career-high 365 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   With his second Cy Young, he joined Pedro Martinez and Gaylord
Perry as the only men to win the award in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can sit here all day and I can rattle off all kinds of
little things that made me a better pitcher today than five or six
years ago,'' Johnson said. ``Just going through failure and
learning how to deal with it from a maturity standpoint, and then
also from a personal standpoint, in not trying to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I failed a lot in this game. Heck, in Seattle in '92,
I lost eight straight games. And I think that was my first step in
analyzing my mechanics and wind-up, learning a little more about
pitching. Then I met Nolan Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he credits a 1993 meeting with Ryan and subsequent
lessons on the wind-up from coach Tom House, Johnson remains
essentially self-taught. He learned to throw his insidious slider
on his own, as he did the new two-seamer. Nothing really is
responsible for his evolution as a complete pitcher but his own
will. He can't even talk like a power pitcher anymore
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't work on trying to strike people out. I'm just kind of
letting them,'' he said. ``I'm more concerned with going out there
and throwing as few pitches as possible, not only in the game but
in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me a great deal of pride to be able to get a
double-play ball instead of striking three guys out. Not only is it
easier on my arm, but the team isn't out there as long, either.''
</P>
<P>
   He has done far more for the Diamondbacks than give them a
pretty good chance every five days. Johnson rode lead on a flock of
acquisitions during the winter of 1998-99, as free-agent outfielder
Steve Finley and right-handed starter Todd Stottlemyre linked up
with two trade additions, outfielders Luis Gonzalez and Tony
Womack, since converted to shortstop. Third baseman Matt Williams
and second baseman Jay Bell already were here.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent 100-win season in 1999 and the fastest division
championship by an expansion franchise hardly are random events.
The D-backs opened play Tuesday with the best record (22-10) in the
NL. Johnson's late-career improvement is emblematic of an
experienced roster that is thriving with players in the latter
stages of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``From center field, it's awesome,'' Finley said of watching
Johnson pitch. ``The guy hardly ever misses the mitt. You don't
think of control with a guy 6-10, plus going 98, 100 miles per
hour. And then, every once in a while, that pitch gets away, which
always plants in a hitter's mind that when you're that big, you're
not going to throw every pitch right where you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   That unspoken menace transcends the mere heater at the neck. It
reaches into the opposing dugout, where a manager is forced to play
with one hand tied behind his back. Johnson has allowed lefties a
.182 average over his career, and many accomplished hitters _ Larry
Walker, the retired John Kruk _ would just rather not face him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're able to negate two or three quality left-handed bats
on a bench, that's a big advantage for us,'' Arizona manager Buck
Showalter said. ``We've had a few times, where Randy needs relief,
we'll bring a left-hander in behind him because you don't want all
those left-handers (on the other bench) coming in late in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   His routine tonight will be unchanged: two hours of clubhouse
quiet with some music lulling Johnson almost into a trance. Nobody
talks with him but, as he says, laughing, ``Nobody talks to me
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me if it's hard to catch him,'' Miller said.
``Well, when you first start, it's a little different, but once you
get a handle on the physical side of it, going out every fifth day
with him is more mentally challenging for a catcher, just to keep
him calmed down. He gets caught up in the emotion a lot and can be
very intense out there. I've learn the last two years that that's
my biggest job.''
</P>
<P>
   Controlled rage has helped deliver Johnson from a 49-48 pitcher
over his first five seasons to a 118-40 one since 1992. Back
surgery in 1996 not only extended his career but improved it, as
Johnson has given more effort to physical conditioning since then.
</P>
<P>
   Quick starts guarantee little. Martinez went 10-8 after winning
his first seven starts in 1997 but still won his first Cy Young.
McDonald went 7-7 in 1994 after his 7-0 start, finished 23-23 in
three subsequent seasons and, beset by a series of shoulder
problems, hasn't appeared in the majors since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is a different species. He has surpassed Sandy Koufax's
career win total, by two, as well as his strikeout total, by 372,
in 16 fewer innings. He also never has pitched better than right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been up to me to go out and take it a step further and be
consistent with it and become more of a pitcher,'' Johnson said.
``I'm enjoying where I am now, believe it or not. A lot of people
think it doesn't appear that I'm enjoying this. But deep down, I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
