u s BC-ROCKER-BALK-COX     05-09 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-BALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road trip starts badly for Rocker
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ They nibbled on his ears for most of nine innings Monday
night. But the crowd at Pro Player Stadium toasted John Rocker when
it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 14,024 were hoping for Rocker, the Braves closer, to
mess up when he came in to face the Marlins in the bottom of the
ninth. He obliged, balking in Florida's winning run in a 3-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd erupted. With glee.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's journey into South Florida's diverse landscape _ the
first of what may be a tumultuous seven-game road trip _ opened
with lots of security watching the area around the Braves' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Rocker signs carried in by fans (``RocKKKer,'' read one)
were confiscated while the teams were warming up.
</P>
<P>
   Six uniformed security staffers surrounded the Braves' bullpen
on the field and in the stands. Miami-Dade cops had a heavy
presence. There was also a large security force in plainclothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, because there is a potential for any possible
protest or actions by Mr. Rocker or anybody else,'' said M. Bruce
Schulze, stadium director.
</P>
<P>
   This was the start of what could be a volatile road trip for
Rocker, whose comments in Sports Illustrated offended many racial
and ethnic groups. South Florida's diversity was apparent Monday
night by the number of Venezuelan flags being waved whenever Braves
first baseman Andres Galarraga came to bat.
</P>
<P>
   But the evening was a success for all concerned. No one was
arrested, nothing was thrown on the field and no one mooned Rocker
like one citizen did in Los Angeles last week.
</P>
<P>
   There was a mixture of Braves and Marlins fans near the bullpen,
who debated with one another while the insults were flying in
Rocker's direction. His only reaction to the fans was to reach up
and autograph hats for a number of spectators.
</P>
<P>
   When Rocker began warming up as the Braves were batting in the
ninth, John Kloss and Chuck Snapp, both of Hollywood, Fla., tried
to get a chant going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redneck,'' they yelled when Rocker threw a warmup pitch.
``Racist,'' they yelled again. ``I went back and read that magazine
article last night and it made me angry all over again,'' said
Kloss, a computer programmer. ``The things he said were totally
ignorant. And his attitude since he came back has been atrocious.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
