<HEADER>
A0390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      05-09 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: AT&AMP;T WIRELESS HOLDS THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN with SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors who missed out on the biggest-ever U.S.
initial stock offering last month need not worry or hurry. Shares
of AT&AMP;T Wireless Group are back down to their offering price and,
judging by Tuesday's trading pattern, they may not be heading back
up again any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the shares _ which track the performance of AT&AMP;T's
wireless telecommunications business _ closed at $29.50, unchanged
from Monday. Since dipping below it briefly on Monday, the shares
have rarely strayed from their offering price.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly flat line on the wireless unit's stock chart resulted
from a strong show of support from the investment banks that
underwrote the $10.6 billion offering. In general, it is considered
bad form on Wall Street to allow a client's first-time stock
offering to quickly fall below its initial price without putting up
a fight.
</P>
<P>
   But traders said it was not clear how much longer the price of
AT&AMP;T Wireless would hold steady because there are no concrete rules
on how far the underwriters must go in providing support against
selling pressure. In after-hours trading, the stock slipped to $29.
</P>
<P>
   Traders at a few big investment banks said that Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co., one of three lead underwriters, was buying a lot of stock back
at the offering price Tuesday on behalf of the syndicate of
underwriters, which included almost every major investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12 million shares of AT&AMP;T Wireless changed hands
Tuesday for a total of about $360 million. Goldman Sachs officials
declined to say how much of that buying the firm did or to discuss
why the firm was buying back the stock.
</P>
<P>
   But traders and investment bankers at other firms said that
Goldman clearly felt obligated to prop up the stock because it was
such a lucrative, high-profile deal and because AT&AMP;T wields such
clout on Wall Street. A lesser deal that had performed early on as
AT&AMP;T Wireless did probably would not have received as much support,
they said. The wireless stock rose as high as $36, a gain of more
than 20 percent, in its first few days of trading before it began
to sink.
</P>
<P>
   Most prospectuses explain that the underwriters may purchase
shares in the open market to stabilize the stock price ``above
independent market levels.'' Underwriters also establish what they
call ``penalty bids,'' parameters set to discourage individual
investors from reselling, or ``flipping'' shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a fair amount of syndicate stabilization,'' said a
telecommunications stock trader at one Wall Street firm who, like
several of his peers, asked not to be identified. He said that
there are no concrete rules on what banks must do to stabilize a
new issue but that syndicates usually disband once a new stock
appears stable at a particular price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if they stop supporting it, it goes to $25, right?''
said the manager of a large mutual fund that owns shares of AT&AMP;T
wireless, on condition of anonymity. ``So maybe it goes to $27. I
think it was just priced high to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a dollar to put into wireless, I'd buy Nextel, or
Voicestream or PCS,'' the manager added, referring to the stock
symbol for the shares meant to track Sprint Corp.'s wireless unit.
``But I think over the next six months, the AT&AMP;T shares can support
this level. The stock's not a short and the company has a good
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Liu, an analyst at CIBC World Markets, said that some
institutional investors were turning their attention to other
wireless investments, like Sprint PCS, which recently announced
surprisingly strong subscriber growth.
</P>
<P>
   Before the AT&AMP;T Wireless offering, Liu said, ``The underwriters
were telling investors that this is a name you have to own. Now,
clients are asking, `Why do I have to own this name?'''
</P>
<P>
   Liu, one of the few Wall Street analysts who has not been
recommending the new AT&AMP;T stock, said investors also were concerned
about the lukewarm endorsements it received from analysts at some
investment banks that were involved in the underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   An executive close to AT&AMP;T said the company was not buying the
wireless shares on its own. AT&AMP;T's treasury department, however,
has traded the company's shares on the open market before,
according to people close to the company. While companies generally
disclose large plans to repurchase their own shares, a person close
to AT&AMP;T said Tuesday that the company would not have to make an
immediate public announcement were it to join the effort to support
the wireless shares.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the prospectus for the wireless offering refers
obliquely to the potential for ``repurchases by AT&AMP;T of shares of
AT&AMP;T Wireless Group tracking stock for the account of the AT&AMP;T
Wireless Group.''
</P>
<P>
   An AT&AMP;T spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
