<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0392 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LA     05-09 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY TIRED OF CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sigi Schmid is tired of talking about it. The Galaxy players are
tired of talking about it. It's just a waiting game now.
</P>
<P>
   Is Mexican striker Luis Hernandez coming? Is any Mexican player
coming?
</P>
<P>
   The Hernandez rumors started during pre-season. It seemed like a
wonderful idea at the time. Former Galaxy striker Carlos Hermosillo
returned to Mexico, leaving a vacant foreign allocation spot on the
Galaxy's roster. It was perfect, making even more sense because
Hernandez wants to come to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a potent front line Cobi Jones, Clint Mathis and
Hernandez together. It's scary on paper, probably scarier in
person.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out it's so frightening that Major League Soccer
probably will never let it happen.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the robbery takes place, this is why the long
delay.
</P>
<P>
   MLS insists that San Jose and New England each are due foreign
allocated players before the Galaxy even though the only foreign
allocated player on the Galaxy's roster is Mauricio Cienfuegos, who
was allocated in 1996, MLS' inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that MLS wants to sign and assign Hernandez to Los
Angeles, San Jose and New England can wait. It's like holding the
top two choices in a draft. If the Galaxy wants Hernandez, they
have to give away something to get the next allocation. And if they
don't want that allocation now, too bad, they may have to take it.
</P>
<P>
   In talking to team officials, it appears MLS is asking for far
too much from the Galaxy. As many as three starters have been
mentioned, including Roy Myers, Clint Mathis, Joey Franchino and
Greg Vanney. With the Hernandez signing looming, MLS is asking the
Galaxy to make a few players available for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, coach and president of soccer operations, is too smart
to give up that much for a player who will only be here a third of
the time, especially if it's Hernandez, a standout who could miss
plenty of action on Mexico's World Cup qualifying team.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy (5-0-3) is unbeaten, one of MLS' top teams, so why
make any drastic moves for a part-time player, even if he's as good
and as coveted as Hernandez?
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the MLS says so. That's what this may come down to.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, after Schmid finally says to leave his team
alone, that it is fine the way it is, MLS can step in and force his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN Magazine writer Jeff Bradley, calling the Galaxy mess the
``Dispersal Draft,'' said it best last week: ``MLS' Mission Control
is saying `we're not going to let the coaches and GM's cost us the
chance to get a gate attraction like Hernandez. We're not just
going to allow undefeated Los Angeles to load up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   MLS has stepped in before.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami last season, coach Ivo Wortman benched Carlos
Valderrama. With Valderrama unhappy, MLS told Wortman to make a
trade. Wortman didn't like what other teams were offering, so he
held out. MLS grew impatient and re-assigned Valderrama to Tampa
Bay, essentially stealing him from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   This will probably happen to the Galaxy. At some point, when MLS
is ready to sign a Mexican player and assign him to L.A. to
increase a fan base that is already tops in the MLS, it will come
at a huge cost. It will be a theft.
</P>
<P>
   To get Hernandez, the MLS will make the Galaxy spread the wealth
it has worked for since 1996. This Galaxy team was built on great
draft choices players like Vanney, Franchino, Mathis, Sasha
Victorine and Kevin Hartman and trades that brought Danny Pena and
Myers to L.A. But that means nothing to MLS.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid can't even protect them. That's what's wacky about this
league. How can you build a team for the future when someone else
can tear it down?
</P>
<P>
   The single-entity concept was created so that owners would
invest in the league, control player contracts, but allow
individual teams to operate autonomously within their markets. When
did that change? And when did the MLS become every team's general
manager? This is why Galaxy players are upset. This is why Galaxy
defender Danny Pena said last week he has no respect for the MLS'
front office.
</P>
<P>
   No one argues that Hernandez will be a great fit in L.A., but
it's too bad he may come with controversy, because some of the
luster will be lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
