<HEADER>
A0398 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL-720(     05-09 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER LOUISIANA GOVERNOR CONVICTED OF RACKETEERING AND
CONSPIRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Calif.)   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After a picaresque career lived at the edge of the
law, Edwin W. Edwards, the former governor of Louisiana, was
convicted Tuesday of racketeering, conspiracy and extortion charges
related to the awarding of state riverboat casino licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, 72, who served four terms in office and survived two
previous criminal trials without being convicted, was found guilty
by a federal court jury of 17 of the 26 counts against him,
including the most serious racketeering and conspiracy charges.
</P>
<P>
   His son Stephen also was convicted of multiple counts, as were
three other co-conspirators who were charged with being middlemen
between the Edwardses and several businessmen seeking casino
licenses. Two defendants _ a prominent state senator and a member
of the state's gaming board _ were acquitted of the relatively
minor charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who is rarely at a loss for words, was prohibited by a
judge's gag order from discussing the verdicts in detail on
Tuesday. But in brief comments to reporters outside the courthouse
in Baton Rouge, he thanked family members who supported him during
the trial, which lasted more than four -months, and he vowed to
appeal. A high-stakes gambler known for hosting $10,000-ante poker
games in the Governor's Mansion, Edwards then acknowledged that his
luck might finally have run dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese have a saying that if you sit by the river long
enough the dead body of your enemy will come floating down the
river,'' he said, his voice calm and measured. ``I suppose the feds
sat by the river long enough, and here comes my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a Democrat, could be sentenced to more than 200 years
in prison and fined millions of dollars. A forfeiture hearing to be
held on Wednesday could cost Edwards a substantial amount of cash
and property as well.
</P>
<P>
   After being indicted in November 1998, Edwards joked that if he
was sentenced to the maximum possible term he did not expect to
serve it all. Tuesday, he was less cavalier as he faced the
prospect of what he called ``a very large, long prison term.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that it has ended this way,'' Edwards said, shaded by
a canopy of oaks, ``but there is the system. I've lived 72 years of
my life within the system. I will spend the rest of my life within
the system. Whatever consequences flow from this I'm prepared to
face.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I will try to maintain the same demeanor of
confidence and support that I've had in the past three years as all
of this began to unfold. And in due course, whatever comes,
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who was the only defendant to testify during the trial,
showed little emotion as he listened to the verdicts. His wife,
Candy, 35, who kept a front-row seat through the trial, broke down
in tears as the first guilty verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors, who succeeded where their predecessors had
not, suppressed their glee in public. Most walked sternly from the
courthouse without speaking to reporters. But some allowed
themselves a wee smile. ``Look at my face,'' said Eddie J. Jordan
Jr., the U.S. attorney in New Orleans, who oversaw the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards still faces a trial in June on federal fraud charges
that he helped a failed insurance company evade millions of dollars
in state payments.
</P>
<P>
   The jury received the casino case on April 24 after a long and
captivating trial highlighted by the playing of wiretap-generated
audiotapes and the testimony of former Edwards friends who turned
state's evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   Among the star witnesses was Edward J. DeBartolo Jr., the former
owner of the San Francisco 49ers, who secured a plea bargain by
agreeing to testify that he paid Edwards $400,000 in exchange for
his help in winning a casino license for a DeBartolo partnership.
DeBartolo was forced to turn over control of the football team to
his sister because of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors outlined a series of five distinct schemes in
which Edwards and his son demanded substantial payments _ nearly $3
million in all _ in exchange for his assistance in procuring the
coveted casino licenses. Some of the extortion schemes took place
during Edwards' final term in office, which ended in 1996, while
others occurred after he stepped down but still held influence over
legislators and gaming regulators.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He was found guilty of the broadest racketeering and conspiracy
charges, and of involvement in four of the five schemes. Stephen
Edwards was convicted on 18 of 23 counts. Andrew Martin, a former
top aide to Edwin Edwards, was convicted of all six counts against
him; Cecil Brown, a longtime Edwards friend and business partner,
of four counts; and Bobby Johnson, another Edwards friend, of nine
counts. State Sen. Greg Tarver and Ecotry Fuller, the gaming board
member, were acquitted of charges that they helped Edwards
illegally obtain a confidential report for DeBartolo.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Edwards was circumstantial, because even the
hundreds of hours of audiotape never captured him making an
explicit demand. But the testimony of his former friends and
several suggestive conversations caught on the tapes apparently
were enough to persuade the jury. The tapes revealed him talking
about splitting up proceeds that he maintained he never received
and brainstorming schemes to launder money.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were surprised that Edwin, who has always been
so smart, let them get so much information on him,'' said Bernie R.
Pinsonat, a Baton Rouge pollster. ``They had tapes in his office,
tapes in his house, and they obviously nailed him. Regardless of
what happens from here on out it is the end of an era.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who by his own count has been investigated by 22 grand
juries, first escaped conviction in 1985 when a federal jury in New
Orleans deadlocked while considering charges that he took payoffs
to help his patrons win state hospital licenses. He was retried and
acquitted the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution clearly had stronger evidence in this year's
case, including the tapes and the witness testimony. It also
benefited by trying the case in Baton Rouge, where jurors are
considered more conservative than in New Orleans. All but one of
the jurors was white, a significant factor given that Edwards
strongest support always came from black Louisianans.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the verdicts were rendered, the defense team had
been handed at least one significant cause for appeal. Last
Thursday, after two days of investigation and legal hand-wringing,
U.S. District Court Judge Frank Polozola dismissed one of the 12
jurors, a white man known only as Juror 68. The verdicts, thus,
were returned by a jury of 11, and defense lawyers have assumed
that the dismissed juror was resisting the majority's arguments for
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The judge did not explain the dismissal, but Louisiana
newspapers have reported that the juror asked to be dismissed. The
newspapers, including The Advocate in Baton Rouge and The
Times-Picayune in New Orleans, reported that the juror sent
Polozola a note saying, ``I am being very intimidated because of
how I may feel. There is such an awesome responsibility with the
lives of people in our and my hands that I am trying to erase some
doubts but can't seem to forget them in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   After the juror was dismissed, defense lawyers asked for a
mistrial and were rebuffed by the judge. The time devoted to
dismissing the juror, when combined with other delays, meant that
the jury deliberated for only about seven of the 12 work days it
had the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
