<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0400 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ASSESS-2     05-09 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: PEACEKEEPING MISSION IN SIERRA LEONE SUFFERS FROM MANY
WEAKNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SIERRA LEONE, SIERRA-LEONE-RESPONSE) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The flaws in the U.N. peacekeeping mission in
Sierra Leone reach back to decisions supported by the Clinton
administration last year, when there was a rush to end the civil
war and dispatch an international force that would bring what some
call ``peace on the cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   The formula for the peace deal known as the Lome accord, which
the administration helped forge with an assist from the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, worked this way: The rebel leader, Foday Sankoh, was
released from death row and given a prominent role in a new
government on the understanding that his men would put down their
weapons, in a setting with U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration, haunted by the memory of 18 American
soldiers killed in Somalia on a U.N. mission, and mindful of 14
Belgians slaughtered in Rwanda, made it clear to Congress that it
would not send American forces to Africa again. Britain, the former
colonial power in Sierra Leone, similarly did not offer to send in
troops as peacekeepers there. Nor did or any other European
country.
</P>
<P>
   Washington also repeatedly told African leaders that, although
the United States was not prepared to risk its own people in
Africa, it cared about the troubled continent.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of that support, a peacekeeping force was formed,
crafted from a hodge-podge of nations whose armies had never worked
together, and who were given minimal equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council also did not give the peacekeeping force
the means to patrol the borders of Sierra Leone, through which,
according to experts on Africa, the rebels could continue trading
diamonds for weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission, like that of most U.N. peacekeeping forces, was
essentially to police a peace agreement, and not to plunge into the
fray. The problem was that they were sent to monitor a very fragile
peace.
</P>
<P>
   When the arrangements started to collapse, Britain sent several
hundreds paratroopers to the airport at Freetown on Monday, but
insisted they had the sole task of evacuating foreigners, while the
United States announced it would help transport 700 Bangladeshi
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials now say that Sankoh was never
interested in peace _ although it had enough trust in him for
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to meet him when she visited
the country last October.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its European allies have not offered
troops for the planned peacekeeping operation in Congo, either,
where 500 monitors are scheduled to deploy with the protection of
about 5,000 troops. Diplomats at the United Nations say that this
mission is now in question.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. peacekeeping department itself has already been going
through a series of inquiries after the world body failed to stop
the slaughter in Rwanda and to halt the killing of Muslims in the
Bosnian town of Srebrenica in 1995. A former Algerian foreign
minister, Lakhdar Brahimi, was appointed in March by Secretary
General Kofi Annan to look into the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robust peace enforcement is beyond the capacity of the United
Nations,'' said J. Stephen Morrison, the director of Africa
programs at the Center for Strategic and International Studies.
``The Security Council does not have the stomach for it,
contributing countries don't want to put their troops under other
commanders and then have to answer questions at home when their
troops get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   By backing such a weak force in a volatile country like Sierra
Leone, Morrison said, the Clinton administration was hoping for
``peace on the cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate within the administration and among other members of
the Security Council is now focused on whether to reinforce the
crippled force in Sierra Leone or to come up with a regional force,
led by the Nigerians, administration officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The tide is turning toward a regional force, and officials said
they hoped that would be the result of the meeting held Tuesday in
Abuja, Nigeria, of leaders from the region.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the session in Abuja, the leaders of nine African states
said they were considering deployment a West African force, led by
the Nigerians and known as Ecomog.
</P>
<P>
   Such a force had been in Sierra Leone before the Lome accord of
last July, and if it returns it would be a signal that regional
forces are viewed as better suited to enforcing the peace than
inexperienced U.N. troops, several administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of a regional body that controls the Ecomog force
said on Tuesday they would convene the 15 member countries'
ministers of defense and chiefs of staff on May 17 to consider
sending the troops back.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The logic of regional forces, according to administration
officials, is that each region looks after its own trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, NATO intervened in Bosnia and Kosovo; the Australians went
to Timor last year, and the West Africans may be poised to enforce
the peace in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, with its experience in Sierra Leone, was considered key
to a solution in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   But after Nigerian soldiers suffered casualties and were nearly
defeated by the rebel Revolutionary United Front in January 1999,
the Nigerian government told the United Nations, the United States
and Britain that it was going to pull out its troops if it did not
win increased financial support, an administration official said.
There was reluctance by the British and the administration to fund
the Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
   When the United Nations decided to send a peacekeeping force to
Sierra Leone, Nigeria _ like the United States _ said it did not
want its troops to serve under the U.N. commanders.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the Nigerian troops had left by early last week, the
moment when administration officials now say Sankoh's forces
decided to test the will of the U.N. force by taking Kenyan and
Zambian soldiers hostage and stripping them of ammunition and
armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   By last week, when the rebels struck, the U.N. force was still
3,000 soldiers short of the full 11,000 complement set up in
February. Recruiting non-African countries to send their soldiers
was particularly difficult, with the Indians, the Bangladeshi and
the Jordanians being the main non-African countries to offer men.
</P>
<P>
   After U.N. troops started arriving early this year _ six months
after the peace accord was signed _ the Indian commander of the
force, Gen. Veejay Jatley, told administration officials that the
organization in New York was so chaotic that he did not know what
troops were coming, or which country they were coming from, until
they arrived, one of the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jatley sent the new peacekeepers into the hinterland where the
rebels were still killing civilian Sierra Leoneans. ``This was good
to visibly demonstrate the peacekeepers were there but not good if
they got into a shooting war,'' an administration official said.
The peacekeepers were often intimidated, surrounded by rebels and,
according to Human Rights Watch, the peacekeepers did not intervene
to stop rapes, abductions and killings that were occurring close to
where they were.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
