<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
AS McCAIN ENDORSES BUSH, HE SHUNS VP JOB 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Smoothing out a rough spot in the Republican
presidential campaign, Sen. John McCain endorsed George W. Bush on
Tuesday and said he would ``campaign enthusiastically'' for the
Texas governor but was not interested in being his vice
presidential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Their private meeting and subsequent joint news conference ran
about as smoothly as the Bush campaign could have hoped, given
McCain's prickly personality and deep displeasure at some of the
dirt Bush dished his way en route to wrapping up the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Bush's stiffest competition for the nomination, did not
use the word ``endorse'' in his initial statement, and when asked
if he were endorsing Bush, McCain answered tersely: ``Yes.'' When
questioned further about whether he had a problem with the semantic
point, McCain repeated six times: ``I endorse Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way,'' Bush said, ``I enthusiastically accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain clearly came to no meeting of the minds in their
90-minute meeting on the Arizona senator's call for outlawing
unlimited, unregulated ``soft money'' in campaigns. But both men
emphasized that their agreements on public policy outnumbered their
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Each hoped the meeting put an end to speculation about McCain as
a Bush running mate, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked his advice about the vice presidency,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked that I not be considered for vice president of the
United States,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take him for his word,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Bush's choice for a running mate has begun to
focus on Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, whom Bush said McCain had
specifically mentioned. But McCain said the list of prospects was a
long one, including a few of the limited number of senators who
backed his presidential bid, such as Sen. Fred Thompson of
Tennessee and Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The body language of the event, in which Bush seemed to stand as
close as possible to McCain, indicated that the moment was more
important to the governor than the senator. Bush acknowledged as
much with his wish that McCain's backing send a signal to the
senator's supporters in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who think John is not only a great
American but a person who's got a good, solid agenda for the
future,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent national polls show that if McCain ran as an independent
presidential candidate, which he has said he will not do, he would
get about one quarter of the popular vote and force Bush into an
even closer race with Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the ``single most important reason'' for giving Bush
his formal backing is that the governor ``is the most qualified
person to be president of the United States. He has the vision, he
has the knowledge and the experience to carry out the mission of
maintaining the United States' supremacy, both militarily and
economically, in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's clear that Governor Bush's philosophy, his ideals
and his ability to articulate a vision of the future is the major
reason why he should be president of the United States and not Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee quickly issued a release
recalling some of McCain's more caustic comments about Bush during
the heat of the late winter GOP campaign, including: ``If Governor
Bush is a reformer, I'm an astronaut.'' Also on the DNC list was
McCain's view earlier in the year that Bush would ``lose to Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   In part of his opening statement, McCain seemed reserved in his
evaluation of Bush as national leader and was restrained in his
choice of words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that it's very important that we restore integrity
and honor to the White House,'' McCain said. ``I am convinced that
Governor Bush can do that more than adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed on his timing and frame of mind in finally offering
Bush formal backing, McCain replied, using a reporter's phrase: ``I
think your `take the medicine now' is probably a good
description.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said she took McCain's comment as
a joke, but the senator's advisers said that he had finally decided
it was time to get the long-anticipated event behind him. Until the
weekend, McCain had not intended to endorse Bush immediately after
their meeting.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a glitch in the proceedings, it was Bush's refusal,
in answer to a reporter's question, to repudiate the view of
religious right leader Pat Robertson that McCain was so emotionally
rash that he would be ``dangerous'' as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, without reference to Robertson, said only that McCain is
``a man of good judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also indicated that he would spend more time working to
keep Republicans in control of the House and Senate than in
boosting Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the two men did not discuss a specific role for McCain
at the Republican National Convention this summer, nor did they
apparently discuss other joint campaign appearances. Bush said he
wanted McCain to have ``a key role'' at the GOP convention. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
