<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Wis., Mich.)  
 McCAIN BACKS BUSH BUT WON'T BE ON TICKET  
(EDS: Updates throughout with fresh quotes, additional background,
analyst comment; story now in 2 takes; note byline change.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Citing common goals and shared values that
transcended any of the bitterness between them, Sen. John McCain at
last endorsed Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday and pledged to help
the de facto Republican presidential nominee achieve what McCain
had wanted so badly for himself: a seat behind the desk in the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to enthusiastically campaigning for Governor
Bush for the next six months,'' McCain said at a news conference
here that was attended by more than 100 members of the news media,
a reflection of just how unpredictable and closely watched the
interactions between the Arizona senator and the Texas governor had
become.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that it's very important that we restore integrity
and honor to the White House,'' McCain said. ``I'm convinced that
Governor Bush can do that more than adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by McCain, which followed his private
90-meeting with Bush, heralded a new phase in a rocky political
relationship that went from remarkable amity in December to
extraordinary animosity in March and a tense, delicate dance of
reconciliation over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, McCain's formal endorsement of his one-time
adversary allowed Bush to lay claim to a unified party, to put an
important piece of unfinished business behind him and to reach out
to independent and swing voters with the blessing of McCain, who
had held a potent allure over that group in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Bush and McCain and political analysts said just
how much work McCain would do on Bush's behalf _ and just how
thoroughly the wounds of a lacerating primary season had healed _
remained unclear. McCain's often tepid demeanor and restrained
language at the news conference only heightened those questions.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated several times that his support for Bush did not
alter or diminish his commitment to an overhaul of campaign funding
laws that was more sweeping than the plan favored by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He did not actually use the words ``endorse'' or ``endorsement''
until reporters pressed him to make sure they understood correctly
what was going on. At that point, McCain made something of a comedy
routine, saying: ``I endorse Governor Bush. I endorse Governor
Bush. I endorse Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   And when one journalist asked McCain if his actions Tuesday _ an
almost inevitable obligation for any politician wishing to remain
loyal to his party _ were like swallowing a dose of necessary
medicine sooner rather than later, McCain answered, ``I think `take
the medicine now' probably is a good description.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides chose to interpret the ambiguous remark as an
example of the senator's sometimes deadpan humor, and it did not
diminish their conviction, shared by many Republican operatives,
that the Texas governor had accomplished something important
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also made clear Tuesday that he had told Bush what he had
been saying publicly for some time: that he had no interest in the
vice presidency. But he and Bush said they had discussed other
strong candidates for the job, including Govs. Tom Ridge of
Pennsylvania, Christie Whitman of New Jersey, Tommy Thompson of
Wisconsin and John Engler of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting McCain's endorsement, Bush heaped praise on him,
providing a stark contrast to some of the dismissive remarks that
he and his aides had made about McCain after Bush effectively
secured the Republican presidential nomination in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   And he cast their acrimonious exchanges during the primary as a
beneficial experience that prepared him for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him point blank he made me a better candidate,'' Bush
said, referring to their meeting in a room of the Westin William
Penn hotel here. ``He waged a really good campaign and put me
through my paces. And as a result of the campaign, I stand better
prepared to become the president, which is exactly what I intend to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   And McCain said that it made no sense to revisit the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to look back in anger or with any rancor would be a
mistake,'' he said. ``It would harm me. It would harm Governor
Bush. And it would harm those who supported me in this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the tone of his remarks suggested that his and his aides'
ire over some of the negative tactics used by Bush and his
supporters during the primaries had not dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   That anger was rekindled Tuesday when Bush dodged a question
about whether he would repudiate a statement by the evangelist Pat
Robertson two days ago that choosing McCain as a vice president
would be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' said Rick Davis, who had managed
McCain's campaign. ``I don't think there's a Republican around who
doesn't think Pat Robertson's comments Sunday were outside the
mainstream of our party. What's the harm of saying that?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said that McCain's eventual endorsement of
Bush was never really in much doubt, in part because the senator,
seen as something of an untameable maverick in his own party,
needed to show his political peers that he could follow the loyal,
polite course. That would be particularly critical if Bush loses
and McCain seeks to become the party's nominee four years from now.
</P>
<P>
   But the road leading to this point was bumpy, and it was not
clear until Monday that Tuesday morning's meeting, scheduled a
month ago, would bring the waiting to an end. McCain's prior
statements that he would support the party's nominee fell short of
a formal seal of approval and fueled speculation, which Bush's
aides were eager to quell, about what was taking so long.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Brookover, a Republican strategist, said Tuesday's meeting
should give voters more of a sense of Bush's leadership abilities.
``What people want to see in a president and a presidential
candidate is the ability to forge forward through difficult times
and an ability to reach out and work with many people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the two men's aides, Bush did not offer McCain
anything concrete in exchange for his support. And one McCain
supporter said efforts by the aides to hammer out a document
detailing joint policy goals had failed.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's aides have let Bush campaign officials know that
the Arizona senator would like a prominent speaking role at the
Republican National Convention, and the Bush campaign has indicated
interest in making that happen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of the meeting, both McCain and Bush acknowledged
that they still have policy disagreements, although they declined
to linger on them. During the primaries, for example, McCain
repeatedly asserted that the size of Bush's proposed tax cut might
jeopardize the health of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   And McCain's vision of overhauling the campaign finance system,
for example, includes bans on unregulated donations to political
parties from both corporations and individuals; Bush does not think
individual contributions should be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, McCain said, ``I want to assure people that supported
me in the primary that I will continue to pursue this agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to both politicians said there had not yet been any
discussion about specific ways in which McCain could or would
bolster Bush's campaign efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But several Republican strategists in Washington said that
McCain would probably wind up doing a great deal and that his tone
Tuesday simply reflected the difficulty of accepting that it was
finally time to cede the stage to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went from huge media star and man-of-the-moment to having
to fall back in line,'' said William Dal Col, who managed Steve
Forbes' campaign for the Republican nomination. ``But it'll get
better and better as time goes by, and if he wants to run in 2004,
the smart thing for him to do is be as energetic and pro-Bush as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Warfield, who was the press secretary for the 1996
presidential campaign of Bob Dole, acknowledged that McCain was
``flippant and unconventional'' in delivering his endorsement but
that his manner did not change ``how important it really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, in the immediate aftermath of McCain's defeat,
there was furious speculation that he might run as a third-party
candidate,'' Warfield said. ``As recently as last week, there was a
poll that showed McCain, in a hypothetical three-way race, with
more than 20 percent. Any time you get endorsed by someone with
that kind of star quality is a very good day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
