 (ATTN: Calif., Mich., Neb., Pa., Texas)  
 POWER ARRAY PUSHES THE CHINA TRADE BILL  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two former presidents and an array of senior
officials from Democratic and Republican administrations rallied
Tuesday with President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore at the
White House to urge Congress to approve a landmark China trade
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a ceremony in the ornate East Room, Clinton
intensified his lobbying in advance of the House vote, now likely
on May 24 or May 25, to grant China permanent normal trading
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Congress votes against it, they'll be kicking
themselves in the rear 10 years from now, because America will be
paying the price,'' Clinton told scores of invited dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Statesmen, scholars and military chiefs, including former
Secretaries of State Henry Kissinger and James Baker III, whose
public service spanned nearly 50 years in some cases, stood with
Clinton in warning of the consequences of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A negative vote in the House or Senate would be catastrophic
to American agriculture, electronics, telecommunications, autos and
countless other products and services,'' said former President
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the measure, which would allow American companies to
benefit fully from a market-opening agreement that would pave the
way for China to enter the World Trade Organization, say it would
sacrifice lawmakers' influence over Beijing's record on human
rights and religious freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Carter acknowledged that China had fallen short
in those areas, but cautioned against rejecting the measure.
``There's no doubt in my mind,'' Carter said, ``that a negative
vote on this issue in the Congress will be a serious setback and
impediment for the further democratization, freedom and human
rights in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between Clinton and the former presidents in turns at
the microphone, Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential
nominee, appeared reluctant to give his full-throated endorsement.
His words sounded support. But his subdued tone suggested the pains
that Gore has taken to avoid alienating a pivotal ally, organized
labor, that opposes the accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is right for American jobs, it is right for the cause of
reform in China, and I believe it will move us closer to the strong
and stable world community that we all seek to create,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   With just two weeks left before the vote, the White House and
its allies on Capitol Hill say they are still 10 to 15 votes shy of
the 218 needed for passage. About 30 Democrats and roughly as many
Republicans remained officially undecided, and the presentation
Tuesday was aimed at pulling both camps down off the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said opponents _ an unlikely coalition of liberal
Democrats and conservative Republicans _ were unwittingly doing the
bidding of the measure's foes in China, the owners of state-owned
enterprises and reactionary military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is truly ironic when you look at who's against this in
China to see that some of the most progressive people in the United
States are basically doing what they want them to do in opposing
this agreement,'' said Clinton, who may visit a Democrat's district
in Minnesota or Ohio on Friday to champion the proposed lower
tariffs for American farmers.
</P>
<P>
   In their own news conferences, opponents warned that normalizing
trade relations would only reward China's bellicose government.
``Regardless of the administration's trade objectives, the reality
is that China prepares for war,'' said Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to sway uncommitted lawmakers, Reps. Sander M. Levin,
D-Mich., and Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., announced a bipartisan plan to
create a commission to monitor Chinese human rights and require
protection against a surge in Chinese imports.
</P>
<P>
   One undecided Republican, Phil English of Pennsylvania, said,
``This will make my decision a lot easier.'' But Rep. Dick Armey,
R-Texas, the majority leader, said provisions on labor and imports
would cost Republican votes on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But without some sort of bill to address labor and human rights
issues, Rep. Robert T. Matsui of California, a top Democratic vote
counter, said, ``this will be a real problem for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
