<HEADLINE>
PEROT MAY SKIP HIS REFORM PARTY'S CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ross Perot, the founder of the Reform Party and its
presidential candidate in 1992 and 1996, probably will not attend
this year's convention of the party, which is expected to nominate
Pat Buchanan for president, an aide said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty clear that if Buchanan is the nominee that Perot
will not attend the convention or support the nominee,'' said the
aide, a party official and Perot ally who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Perot did not return a phone call seeking comment, but another
of his key supporters, Russell Verney, said, ``He has a very tight
travel schedule for business this summer and no definite plans have
been made one way or the other with respect to appearing at the
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Perot aide who spoke on condition of anonymity said that
supporters of Perot felt that Buchanan's positions on social
issues, including his opposition to abortion and gay rights, were
contrary to the Reform Party principles against government
involvement in private matters. Taking positions on either side of
those issues, the aide said, would deflect attention from the
causes that led to the formation of the party, including its
support for campaign reform and its opposition to some
international free-trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to comment on the likely absence of Perot from the
convention, Scott McConnell, a senior policy adviser to the
Buchanan presidential campaign, said: ``Though Buchanan did not
endorse Perot in 1992 or 1996, he has great respect for him and
remembers fondly the battles against NAFTA and the WTO, in which
they were side by side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Perot does want to attend the convention, the welcome mat
will be out for him,'' McConnell said. ``If he chooses not to come,
we fully respect his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a will-he-or-won't-he aspect to Perot's
own candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   When Verney was asked whether there was any chance that Perot
might enter the presidential campaign later, he answered, ``No _
the window is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gerry Moan, chairman of the Reform Party, said that ``I
still think there's an outside chance he'll be there. We hold out
hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-ABACHA-NYT &LR;      05-09 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ABACHA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS LOCATE MORE MONEY BELIEVED LOOTED FROM NIGERIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Investigators pursuing what the Nigerian government
says is billions of dollars looted from the West African country
during the rule of its late leader, Sani Abacha, have found $630
million in Luxembourg bank accounts connected with his sons.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which has now uncovered more than $1 billion
in European accounts in the names of the Abacha family or
associates, has embarrassed officials in Switzerland and set off an
investigation of Credit Suisse, one of the country's two biggest
banks, where part of an additional $654 million in Nigerian money
was found.
</P>
<P>
   The latest amounts disclosed had been put in eight bank accounts
at the Luxembourg office of M.M. Warburg &AMP; Co., a private bank, in
the names of Alhaji Sani Mohammed and Abba Mohammed Sani,
Luxembourg officials confirmed. These names were falsely used by
two sons of Abacha, Mohammed and Abba, said a lawyer for the
Nigerian government.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts have been frozen, according to Jean-Paul Frising,
the deputy prosecutor in Luxembourg, and documents verifying the
accounts have been sent to the Nigerian government, which now must
ask that the money be returned.
</P>
<P>
   That request will be made before the end of the month, said a
lawyer for Nigeria's new democratically elected government, which
claims that Abacha embezzled more than $2 billion, much of it
through the nation's central bank, during the five years he
controlled the African country. He died in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for Abacha-related money also turned up more than $300
million in England last month. The money was originally transferred
there to pay Russian firms for building the Ajaokutu steel factory
in Nigeria, but found its way into the Abacha family accounts. That
money is being disputed, with a Geneva financier claiming the money
on grounds that the Russians had signed the debt over to him.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss authorities have been conducting an extensive
investigation because the money found in the country, which is the
most since Ferdinand Marcos, the former Philippine dictator, hid
$550 million here, cannot be returned without proof that it was the
product of illegal acts.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Geneva officials charged a New Delhi businessman
with fraudulently using some of the money to repay Russian
construction companies.
</P>
<P>
   That was followed by the indictment of an Abacha associate,
Abubakar Bagudu, in London on April 26 on charges of money
laundering, fraud, corrupt management and involvement in a criminal
organization. This was in connection with the Ajaokuta steel
venture and with two sales of vaccines, in 1995 and 1997, to
Nigerian health agencies, which allegedly netted $66.6 million.
Some $25 million of this illicit money is frozen in Geneva at the
Banque du Gothard and Credit Agricole, according to legal papers.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual procedure, an investigating magistrate, Georges
Zecchin of Geneva flew to London where he indicted the Nigerian at
the Swiss embassy. Bagudu, the Abacha associate, who ran an
import-export business in Nigeria, had traveled to Switzerland
twice last year to answer questions, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bagudu maintains that any money in Switzerland is the proceeds
of lawful business activities, and that he had settled Lagos'
claims last summer in a civil lawsuit. However, when it appeared he
would not come to Geneva to be charged, the Swiss magistrate went
to England. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
