<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 FORMER CHAMP STADLER DROPS OUT (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By JIMMY BURCH AND CHARLES CLINES
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Craig Stadler withdrew yesterday from the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic because of a rib injury, becoming the third
former champion to drop out of the tournament since practice rounds
began Monday at the Four Seasons Resort.
</P>
<P>
   Stadler, 46, ranks 40th on the PGA Tour money list ($472,462)
this season and finished second in his most recent event, the Shell
Houston Open (April 27-30). Stadler won the 1984 Nelson and has
finished 11th or better eight times in his past 15 appearances at
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Stadler's departure came one day after Nelson officials learned
that Ernie Els, the 1995 champ, and Fred Couples, the 1987 winner,
had withdrawn because of back injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Stadler's place in the 156-player field will be taken by
alternate Steve Gotsche.  &QL; 
Fancy footwork
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price displayed some quick feet upon arrival at the course
yesterday. And it had nothing to do with running to avoid
intermittent showers, which interrupted practice rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Price joined locker room attendant Martin Oribhabor in
what could best be described as an impromptu, soft-shoe dance
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an African greeting dance,'' said Price, who grew up in
Zimbabwe. Oribhabor, a native of Nigeria, said the two countries
have similar customs because of their proximity in Africa. Price
and Oribhabor routinely greet one another with the dance during
Nelson week.
</P>
<P>
   If Price is in contention during the weekend rounds, Oribhabor
said they will reconvene for the ``jumbo'' dance, which is designed
for good luck. They performed the ritual before the final round of
the 1991 Nelson, which Price won.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the real dance,'' Oribhabor said. ``This other was just
a welcome. Hopefully, it's a warm-up for bigger things to come.''  &QL; 
Early-bird Tiger
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods avoided the crowds yesterday during a practice round
at the Cottonwood Valley course. Woods joined Casey Martin, a
former Stanford teammate, on the tee at 6:30 a.m. They finished at
9:20 a.m., well before most fans arrived. Woods declined interview
requests after his round but said he would answer media questions
today.
</P>
<P>
   For Woods, it marked his second early start of the week. He
played at 7 a.m. Monday with Aaron Baddeley, an Australian amateur.
He plans to make another early start today. Woods' group is
scheduled for a 7 a.m. start on the TPC course in the Gold Pro-Am.
 &QL; 
Kickoff ceremony
</P>
<P>
   Byron Nelson and his wife Peggy were among the officials and
dignitaries who helped kick off the 2000 GTE Byron Nelson Classic
at a ceremony conducted about 12:15 p.m. yesterday while light rain
fell.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was moved from in front of the Nelson bronze
statue, that is the centerpiece of the Nelson Plaza adjacent to No.
1 tee, to under an awning near Byron's Room, a restaurant just in
front of the statue.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who took part in the ceremony were Irving mayor Joe
Putnam, tournament chairman Patrick McEvoy Jr. and Four Seasons
Resort general manager Craig Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson gave a short speech, and said the tournament that's named
after him is ``the best thing that's happened to me, what with what
the Salesmanship Club does and my association with all the pros.''
</P>
<P>
   The sponsoring Salesmanship Club of Dallas raised $5.9 million
for its charities from last year's tournament.  &QL; 
A more upright Duval
</P>
<P>
   David Duval was working to improve his posture during his
practice session Monday and said he'll be aware of the need to
stand taller this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I start slouching over too much,'' he said. ``I
don't know how long I've been doing it. It's something that could
be from day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   By standing up more, Duval said his swing is on a more level
plane.  &QL; 
Watch that hook
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach, among the
participants in yesterday afternoon's Skins Game, said as he gets
older, he has begun to play more golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf has a lot of aspects to it _ chipping, putting,
driving,'' said Staubach, who sports a 16 handicap. Staubach said
he isn't close to mastering any of the aspects, but said if he has
a strength it's probably his driver. He hit some impressive drives
on the practice range, but was worried what he would do on the
first tee.
</P>
<P>
   He soon found out and had the gallery to the left scrambling
after he hooked his drive.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard Colonial officials Dee Finley and Scott Corpening
worked the Nelson locker room yesterday, trying to secure
additional commitments for the May 18-21 event in Fort Worth.
Deadline for Colonial commitments is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez visited players on the
driving range. Rodriguez spent time chatting with Davis Love III
and Hank Kuehne, among others.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
