<SLUG> BC-BKN-MVP-VOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HICKMAN EXPLAINS VOTE FOR IVERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Fred Hickman's mind, Allen Iverson simply answered the
question better than Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   But no way did the CNN/SI anchor figure he'd be questioned so
much about it Tuesday, trying to justify what turned out to be the
vote that ruined O'Neal's chances of becoming the first NBA Most
Valuable Player to win the award unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that bothers me is that some people see this as
a vote against O'Neal, and it's not,'' said Hickman from his home
in Atlanta. ``Shaq's one of my favorite players. This is simply a
vote for Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main criterion is: What does a guy do to lift his team? I
had it down to Shaq, Iverson, Gary Payton (of Seattle), Tim Duncan
(of San Antonio) and Kevin Garnett (of Minnesota).
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the vote very seriously. I do as much homework and take
as much input as I can. It's a long agonizing process for me. But
to me, when you look at the Sixers without Iverson, I see a really
bad team. And the Lakers without Shaq are still a pretty good club
that makes the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to an MVP vote, you can't really compare a
center to a backcourt man. They're in different systems. They're in
different conferences. I can't argue with anyone who votes for
Shaq. He's just No. 2 on my ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickman says that Michael Jordan's seemingly annual MVP award
selection ``took everyone off the hook for a few years,'' but
Hickman did vote for Karl Malone of Utah the year he was a
semi-surprising winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past several years, there is no clear-cut No. 1 or
No. 2 guy now that the league has shifted. There are many quality
players. You have to do your homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickman doesn't feel hung out to dry by the league, which
handles the voting procedure by members of the media. He says he
usually is one of the last to send his ballot back and has been
voting ``for years in a number of categories.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact Hickman, who put up his explanation on the CNN/SI
Web site Tuesday afternoon, had to answer to some two dozen or more
media members Tuesday was quite ``mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them who rousted him up early Tuesday was Dr. Dre of the
urban-rap L.A. radio station The Beat, who then playfully roasted
Hickman for his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK, they're fans like everyone else,'' said Hickman.
``I don't mind (answering to my vote), but I had no idea I'd be
singled out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
