<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, BASEBALL IS MAKING A PITCH FOR EXCITEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Baseball fans thrilled to the exploits of
Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa two seasons ago, when the sluggers took
aim at the sexiest single-season record in the sport, Roger Maris'
61 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   They staged an epic battle that ended with both not just
breaking the previous mark, but shattering it. McGwire finished
with a staggering 70, and Sosa was close behind with 66.
</P>
<P>
   The 70 homers gave McGwire the record and the victory in the
individual battle, but the real winner was the game of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The two were credited with reviving interest in a sport still
licking its wounds from the 1994 players' strike that wiped out the
World Series. It was cool to watch baseball again. Even casual fans
followed the progress of Mac and Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the home run has almost become passe. There's
so many hit that the latest tape-measure shots are greeted with a
yawn, the ``half the guys in baseball are on pace to hit 50''
updates elicit a so-what shrug.
</P>
<P>
   A recent ESPN.com poll asked if there are too many home runs hit
these days. More than 60 percent said yes.
</P>
<P>
   So it again falls to two players to save the game, but this time
the two players are the very antithesis of McGwire and Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it's Pedro Martinez and Randy Johnson who could take
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and Johnson couldn't be any different from McGwire and
Sosa. They are skinny pitchers, not bulky sluggers. Their job is
not to hit balls over fences, but to keep hitters from doing it.
</P>
<P>
   However, their feats are perhaps even more incredible than the
1998 home run exploits of McGwire and Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of offense, when even middle infielders hit
opposite-field homers with regularity, Martinez and Johnson are
dominating the game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is 7-0 with a 0.93 ERA and 75 strikeouts in 58 1/3
innings for the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who lost one start to rain, is 5-1 with a 1.22 ERA and
67 strikeouts in 44 1/3 innings for the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hasn't lost since Aug. 31 last year. He's 10-0 with a
1.59 ERA and 124 strikeouts in 96 1/3 innings during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has lost once since Aug. 31, falling last Saturday
despite pitching a six-hit, one-run, one-walk, 17-strikeout game
against Tampa Bay, losing 1-0 to Steve Trachsel. Martinez is 9-1
with a 1.04 ERA and 138 strikeouts in 86 1/3 innings during that
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both dominating power pitchers with control,''
Mariners starter Aaron Sele said. ``That's a tough combination.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa had more than a thrilling home run chase in
'98. They also sparked considerable debate as to who was the better
player.
</P>
<P>
   Was it McGwire, who hit the most homers? Or was it Sosa, who had
a better average _ .308 to .299 _ and more RBI _ 158 to 147?
</P>
<P>
   The debate is the same for the two pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Is it Johnson? An imposing 6-foot-10, he's more intimidating. He
can also help himself with the bat; he's batting .273 and has a
five-game hitting streak. His fastball is perhaps a tick faster,
and his slider is deadly. His ERA is lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad he's on our side,'' Diamondbacks manager Buck
Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Is it Martinez? His changeup gives him more weapons than
Johnson. His control is a bit more precise. He's better at changing
speeds. His fastball tops out in the upper 90s. His ERA going back
to August is better than Johnson's and he has more strikeouts,
despite pitching in the league that employs the designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Who's better?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take either one of them,'' Sele said. ``If I can have
both, even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has both. In this era of mind-numbing home run numbers,
that's something everyone should be thankful for.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
