<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-SKINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMITT SMITH TOPS FOES IN SKINS GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Emmitt Smith has achieved plenty in his professional
life. Three Super Bowl rings, four NFL rushing titles, a Super Bowl
MVP award and an NFL regular-season MVP selection.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's got something else: bragging rights on at least three
golfers who are competing in the GTE Byron Nelson Classic this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys running back, playing in the first of two groups in
yesterday's Celebrity Skins Challenge, won three skins during his
seven holes against John Daly, 1998 U.S. Amateur Champion Hank
Kuehne and Tommy Armour III, taking home $5,000 for Potter's Home
Church, his charity of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did OK,'' Smith said. ``I had a good time and hit
some good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   He did more than hit a few good shots. Getting a stroke on each
hole against the pros in his group, he made a net birdie on the
par-4 No. 3, a three-hole carry for $1,500. He made net par on the
par-4 No. 4 as well to pick up another $1,000, then got a little
help on the par-4 No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   After no player won the skin on 18, the group went to a
chip-off. Smith went first, running his chip within 15 feet. The
other three then played at the same time, all purposely blasting
the ball 100 yards over the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured they would pull some junk like that,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith did it all with a new driver _ a Taylor Made that Kuehne
gave him on the driving range.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets done with football, he definitely has a future in
golf,'' said Kuehne, who earned $3,000 with a birdie on the par-3
No. 17. ``It's a lot of fun playing with Emmitt. He's such a good
guy. And his game is really good.''
</P>
<P>
   In the group behind Smith's, Paul Stankowski of Flower Mound
earned $5,500 for his charity, doing it all on the par-4 No. 18.
After his group, including Nick Price, defending Nelson champion
Loren Roberts and former Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach all
pushed on the 18th _ which had a three-hole carry _ Stankowski won
the chip-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all had pretty lousy chips,'' Stankowski said.
``Mine somehow just ended up the closest.''
</P>
<P>
   Staubach had a chance to win the hole in regulation after
hitting his second shot over the green and chipping to within five
feet. With his extra stroke, his putt for a net birdie stayed just
outside the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot tougher than football,'' Staubach said. ``In
football, I could make a bad pass and other players could make up
for it. I could have made up for my whole day at the end. All I had
to do was make a 5-foot putt.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
