<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY CLEARS HURDLE IN STADIUM BID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH _ The Los Angeles Galaxy Tuesday cleared a major
hurdle in its quest to move from the enormous, 96,636-seat Rose
Bowl into cozier quarters on the campus of California State
University Dominguez Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Those quarters a 30,000-seat soccer-specific stadium have yet to
be built, but the Finance Committee of the California State
University Board of Trustees gave its unanimous approval to the
concept at a meeting at Long Beach State. The full board is
expected to approve the plan this morning.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the Galaxy, which has been talking about
leaving the Rose Bowl since October of 1998, could be playing in
its new stadium by April 2002, said Tim Leiweke, the team's
president. The Galaxy has played at the Rose Bowl since Major
League Soccer's inaugural season of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The vote) indicates there is interest in going ahead with
good faith negotiations,'' Leiweke said. ``We're a lot closer now
(to moving) and it's nice to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the Galaxy move, it will have an immediate financial
impact on the Rose Bowl, but Leiweke and Rose Bowl General Manager
Darryl Dunn said they are negotiating a deal to have international
soccer matches and events too large for a 30,000-seat venue played
at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a conversation with Tim Leiweke two days ago,'' Dunn
said. ``They still would like to have a future with the Rose Bowl,
but their intention is to go beyond the Galaxy and be more active
as far as international games.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the number of matches played there, the deal could
actually work in the Rose Bowl's favor. Dunn said the stadium makes
more money from events that draw more people. Since the Galaxy
averages less than 20,000 fans per game, it's in the Rose Bowl's
best interest to bring international matches to the stadium. Many
of those matches draw crowds in the range of 50,000-70,000 Dunn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potentially it's a better deal,'' Dunn said. ``I think it
makes a lot of sense from our perspective because our history of
international soccer here is unparalleled.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl is the only stadium in the world to have served as
host for the Olympic soccer gold medal match as well as the men's
and women's World Cup championship matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people that are in the stadium, the more money we
make,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke said he would also negotiate with the Los Angeles
Memorial Coliseum if he couldn't reach a deal with the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium plan put forth Tuesday by the Galaxy and James E.
Lyons, president of Cal State Dominguez Hills, calls for several
ambitious renovations on a portion of the Carson campus that is now
occupied by a velodrome that was used for bicycle races in the 1984
Olympic Games. The location occupies 85 acres of property on the
western portion of the campus.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy and its owner, billionaire Philip F. Anschutz,
operating under the formal name of Anschutz L.A. Soccer, want to
add several improvements to the site at a total cost of $85
million, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for:
</P>
<P>
   A 30,000-seat soccer stadium;
</P>
<P>
   A 12,000-seat tournament tennis stadium;
</P>
<P>
   Fields and support facilities for the United States Soccer
Federation's National Training Academy;
</P>
<P>
   Locker rooms, weight rooms, offices, video rooms, a gymnasium,
pool and track;
</P>
<P>
   Housing for as many as 240 people.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's approval of the plan was a necessary step in Leiweke's
quest to have the U.S. Soccer Federation move from its current
headquarters in Chicago to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing we have to do is win the bid for the USSF to
move here,'' Leiweke said. ``They have 12 proposals, but we
understand we're one of two favorites.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is enthralled with the proposal. Steve Meiche, head
of the Southern California Velodrome Association, said he may file
a lawsuit. Meiche said his organization currently leases the
velodrome from the university and has a contract to do so through
2003. Meiche said many neighbors of Cal State Dominguez Hills also
are upset with the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think everyone in the area is going to play along,''
he said. ``The vast majority of the people I've talked to are
opposed to this. There's been no community forums to discuss this
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is seeking community input, Lyons said the
university has the final say about how the land is used.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem is going to be the issues of concerts, soccer
and soccer violence,'' he said. ``Some members of the community
will be asking, `What do you do to guard against it?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But, we're not putting this out to a public referendum and
asking them to vote on it,'' he said. ``I'm trying to broker the
best business and education deal that I can for the university.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
