<SLUG> BC-DESERT-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKER DESCRIBES EVENTS LEADING UP TO KNIFING OF FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, N.M. _ Three days of desperate, haphazard hiking
through the parched stream beds and treacherous mountain trails of
Rattlesnake Canyon had brought David Coughlin to a final night of
retching pain and fatal resolve, his best friend said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the knife,'' Coughlin asked Raffi Kodikian, who described
the scenario in dramatic, tearful testimony from the witness stand
at Eddy County District Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `No, I'm not going to do this,' '' Kodikian recalled.
``He grabbed me and said, `Stop (expletive) around. You know
they're not coming . . . Put it through my chest.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian said he complied with his friend's desperate plea,
piercing his lung on the first attempt. The second thrust, he said,
struck its mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the knife in his heart,'' Kodikian said. ``I asked him
if he was still in pain, and he said no, and he smiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Coughlin died on the desert floor. Within hours,
Kodikian was rescued by park rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The gripping testimony was the first time Kodikian, 25, has told
his story in public. Although he described it as a mercy killing,
Kodikian has pleaded no contest to second-degree murder for
stabbing Coughlin, a 26-year-old man from Millis, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Chief District Judge Jay W. Forbes has presided over the
sentencing hearing, and could deliver his sentence as early as
Wednesday after hearing from the final two witnesses. Kodikian
faces a maximum of 20 years in prison, but the judge could also
make him free man by placing him on probation instead.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian's plea avoids a jury trial by placing his fate in
Forbes' hands, but it also preserves his right to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian's emotional, detailed recounting of a nightmarish visit
to Carlsbad Caverns National Park _ in which a planned overnight
stay last Aug. 4 turned into a fatal, four-day ordeal _ did not
allay skepticism among park officials and law officers here.
</P>
<P>
   During a recess, Mark J. Maciha, the National Park supervisor
who spoke with Kodikian at his campsite shortly after being found,
said he remains baffled by several things he saw on the bottom of
Rattlesnake Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``From day one, I've tried to put myself in their perspective,''
said Maciha, who testified for the prosecution Tuesday. ``I've just
found too many things to resolve in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   First, Maciha said, Kodikian seemed alert when the rangers found
him, despite spending four days in the desert with no food or
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as coherent as I was,'' Maciha said.
</P>
<P>
   Other puzzling elements: the pair's decision to camp in a
shadeless stream bed, and that Kodikian had enough strength to
cover his friend's body with rocks weighing as much as 70 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a substantial amount of energy to move those rocks,''
Maciha said.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian testified that he had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do it,'' Kodikian said of his makeshift tomb. ``I
wanted his parents to be able to ID him. If I left him uncovered,
the buzzards would have torn him apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by Chief Deputy District Attorney Les
Williams, Kodikian maintained that killing Coughlin was not an act
of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what he needed, yeah. I recognized the situation,''
Kodikian said. His motivation, Kodikian added, was ``keeping my
friend from going through 12 to 24 hours of hell before he would
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kodikian's description of his state of mind, a
neuropsychologist who examined him extensively after his arrest
said Kodikian was suffering from a temporary mental disorder at the
time, caused by the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying for the defense, Dr. Thomas Thompson, said he also
noted that Kodikian has difficulty processing visual and spatial
information, even under normal circumstances. Inside the canyon, he
said, Kodikian likely could not align himself with geographical
landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   For Kodikian, walking into Rattlesnake Canyon was ``a disaster
waiting to happen,'' Thompson said. The topographical map he bought
at the park's visitors center, he added, might as well have been
``a text in Greek.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian's strong verbal-related intelligence probably made him
dangerously overconfident, Thompson testified. Faced with what
appeared to be a hopeless situation and a friend begging for death,
the doctor said, Kodikian ``would have had no ability to rise above
the situation and see it any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sheriff A.M. ``Chunky'' Click, who has questioned Kodikian's
statements from the beginning, said what he saw of Tuesday's
testimony did little to change his skepticism. When asked during a
break whether he believed Kodikian's version of events, Click
replied: ``There's only one person who really knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian's account, delivered directly to Judge Forbes,
portrayed a pair of young men who detoured to Carlsbad, en route to
California, to view the world-famous caverns here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were basically just looking for a bed,'' Kodikian said of
their 24-hour permit to enter the park's back-country.
</P>
<P>
   But when they awoke Aug. 5, the men could not find the trail
back to their car, Kodikian said. They spent a day vainly searching
for the path and ended back at camp _ baffled, tired, and out of
water.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, they climbed to the top of a ridge, but could not
find the place where where they believed they had seen headlights
on a road the night before. That exhausting trek, Kodikian said,
led only to more frustration, dehydration, and creeping thoughts of
suicide as buzzards circled overhead.
</P>
<P>
   As they returned to camp, Kodikian testified, they saw mirages
of water at an abandoned ranch, and tried to drink their own urine,
strained through a baseball cap, he said. The next day, Aug. 7, was
as mentally and physically exhausting as any he has endured,
Kodikian said.
</P>
<P>
   The pair became convinced that park authorities had misplaced
their permit and were not searching for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no hope that anyone knew we were down there,'' Kodikian
said. Coughlin even tried to cut Kodikian's wrist in a failed
attempt to begin a joint suicide act, Kodikian testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally and physically I was destroyed. I didn't know if I
could go through another day like that.'' At the same time, he
testified, Coughlin's condition deteriorated rapidly, vomiting
uncontrollably. ``He spent the whole night on his hands and knees,
throwing up,'' Kodikian said.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn, he added, the excruciating end-game began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
