<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA HOUSE DEBATES OPTIONS FOR MOVING REBEL FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ On the tense opening day of what may be the
final debate over flying the Confederate battle flag on the
Statehouse dome, an all-white majority of the South Carolina House
of Representatives appeared to be willing to accept a compromise
that would move the flag to a Confederate monument in front of the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The final vote on the proposal, which passed the state Senate
last month, will probably come Wednesday. But in a preliminary
vote, 72 of the 120 House members accepted an amendment that on
July 1 would move a smaller version of the flag to a pole in front
of the Capitol's main entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the flag, all but 11 of whom were white
Republicans, succeeded in passing a proposal that would make the
flag more prominent, raising the size of the pole to 30 feet from
the 20 feet proposed by the Senate, and illuminating it at night.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the body's deep racial divisions, none of the
House's 26 black members supported the amendment. Many black
members already opposed the Senate's proposal, saying that it kept
the Confederate flag in a position of prominence, and were even
more vehemently against the idea of making the flagpole taller and
lighting it up. The National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, which is conducting an economic boycott of the
state over the flag, also opposes the plan to move it to the
Confederate Soldier's monument.
</P>
<P>
   Black members, joined by many white Democrats, did support two
plans that were voted down by the majority: one to put a bronze
relief of the flag on a granite slab near the monument, and the
other to fly the flag on an ``avenue of flags'' adjacent to the
Capitol along with a series of other flags that have flown over
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   White supporters angrily denounced the bronze-relief plan as an
``insult'' to their heritage, and mustered the votes to defeat it
on a vote of 65-43.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War was a big part of the history of the state, not
a small part, but huge,'' said Bill Cotty, a Republican from
Columbia. ``But this tombstone monument type of bill, you might as
well lower it down and give it perpetual care. You're saying, bury
that baby, get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 40 white members were opposed to moving the flag at all,
and one member, Jake Knotts of West Columbia, said he would prefer
that the Confederate flag fly above the United States and South
Carolina flags.
</P>
<P>
   Black legislators, all of whom are Democrats, said it was clear
that the Republican leadership of the House was doing everything
possible to make the flag extremely prominent once it comes down
from the dome, making the entire exercise of moving it essentially
meaningless. They said that putting a symbol of slavery at the
entrance to the Capitol was nearly as offensive as flying it on
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``They voted down every suggestion we made to put it in
historical context, and they're just trying to ram it down our
throats,'' said Todd Rutherford of Columbia. ``If they try to pass
this without any of our votes tomorrow, it will once again be a
case of the great white fathers knowing what's best for the
African-Americans of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of the House, David Wilkins, said it appeared that
the House was moving toward the 30-foot flagpole provision, which
he supported. But he said Republicans in the House would not bear
all the weight of moving the flag; they will not support it in a
final vote if Democrats, and particularly black members, remain
opposed, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
