<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT CHALLENGES BOSTON POLICE HIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In yet another assault on one of the last vestiges of
Boston's affirmative action efforts, a federal lawsuit was filed
Tuesday challenging the police department's practice of bypassing
white applicants to hire lower-scoring minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed by Bradley J. Donahue, 31, a white man who
applied for a job as an officer, says a 1973 federal consent decree
that required the police department to give preference to
minorities is no longer valid because more than 30 percent of the
city's uniformed officers are black or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   After each entrance exam, the state's personnel administrator
provides the police department with a list that includes the name
of one minority officer for every white officer, regardless of
their test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courts around the country have said over and over again that
straight quotas are no longer constitutional,'' said attorney
Michael C. McLaughlin, who represents Donahue and who successfully
fought to overturn racial quotas at the city's three exam schools.
``It's fundamentally divisive. Granting benefits because of race or
holding someone back because of race is no different than racial
profiling.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed in US District Court comes just five months after
Boston Police Commissioner Paul F. Evans announced he was scrapping
a 19-year practice of promoting lower-scoring minority officers
over white officers.
</P>
<P>
   That shift came in response to a ruling last year by Suffolk
Superior Court Judge John Xifaras, who said that race should not be
a factor in police promotions.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a federal judge ruled that eight white Boston police
officers who were bypassed for promotion in favor of eight blacks
with the same test scores could proceed with their suit against the
state's personnel administrator.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1998, a federal appeals court ruled that the Boston
public schools use of race in admissions to the prestigious Boston
Latin School was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin said the 1973 consent decree that settled a
discrimination complaint by minority police officers came at a time
when the Boston Police Department wasn't hiring minorities, who
then comprised about 2 percent of the force.
</P>
<P>
   But McLaughlin says times have changed and now whites are being
discriminated against by the old affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high moral ground of the old quotas is gone,'' said
McLaughlin. ``They're all falling one by one. The fundamental issue
here is if (Donahue) should get in on merit, then he should get in.
And if they are using a quota against him, it should stop. He just
wants to make sure he's treated fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Mary Jo Harris, who represents the police department,
said the department's hiring of officers is controlled by the
consent decree, which is supposed to remain in effect until the
level of minority representation on the force reaches parity with
the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet,'' said Harris, adding that as of January
about 30 percent of the department's 2,400 uniformed officers were
minorities, about 5 or 6 percent shy of the overall percentage of
minorities in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Harris also noted that a federal appeals court upheld the
consent decree in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are one party among a number that are bound by the consent
decree,'' Harris said. ``Our legal obligation is to examine the
list in the order Civil Service gives it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The list provided to the police department by Civil Service
contains an equal number of minority and white officers and a
series of codes that reveal whether they have been given a
preference because they are minorities, veterans, disabled
veterans, or the children of officers who were killed in the line
of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue, who lives in Boston and commutes to his job as a police
officer in West Yarmouth, received no preference and wasn't hired.
He scored a 92 on the 1997 entrance exam and 96 on last year's
test.
</P>
<P>
   At least one minority officer who took the test with Donahue in
1997 and scored a 76 was hired, according to McLaughlin, who
complained that he's been unable to determine the scores of other
officers because the department has refused to disclose information
he has requested.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also names the City of Boston, Evans, James J. Hartnett
Jr., the state's personnel administrator, and a number of other
state officials.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that Donahue has been denied equal protection
under the law and his rights have been violated and urges a judge
to order the Boston Police Department to hire him as a student
officer and stop giving preference to minority applicants.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin said he will argue that the consent decree is no
longer legal and it makes no difference whether the proportion of
minority officers on the force is now representative of the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to go back to simple merit principles,'' McLaughlin
said. ``The consent decree was upheld in 1992, but I do not believe
it will be upheld now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
