<HEADER>
A0426 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-EBAY-AUCTION-670&AMP;ADD-     05-09 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-AUCTION-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 AFTER QUESTIONS ARISE, A HIGH-PROFILE eBAY DEAL IS POSTPONED  
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man who put a painting up for auction on the Internet for 25
cents and ended up making a $135,805 sale acknowledged Tuesday that
he concocted part of the story he used to describe the work and
said he would let the buyer out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bidding closed on Monday, speculation that the vivid
abstract work, which bore the initials ``RD,'' was by the
California artist Richard Diebenkorn set off a frenzy, though the
description never said who had painted the work.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth A. Walton, a lawyer in Sacramento who used the Internet
name ``golfpoorly'' in offering the painting on eBay, said he would
cancel the sale to Rob Keereweer of Nieuwkoop, the Netherlands,
which is legally binding, if experts determine that the canvas is
not by Diebenkorn and the buyer wants out.
</P>
<P>
   Walton, far from being a married homeowner who cleaned the
painting out of his garage to please his wife, is single and has
sold a raft of paintings on eBay, where he also uses the Internet
name ``advice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a heck of a ride,'' he said. Since The New York
Times reported the sale, he added, ``I've had people ringing my
doorbell, calling me late at night and calling my family.''
</P>
<P>
   But Walton said that he had not faked the painting or added the
signature. He said he was only trying to raise cash to finance his
new law practice by reselling works he bought cheaply at estate
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Walton and Keereweer spoke by phone Tuesday evening and, after
Walton acknowledged that he had ``made up a little story to go with
the painting,'' the two decided to put off the transaction
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will bring in an expert opinion from the outside before
finalizing the deal,'' Keereweer said from his home in the
Netherlands. ``Both he and I want to be sure. If it is authentic,
then we will proceed _ that's a fair deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton, who using the name ``advice'' is currently listing four
other paintings in eBay auctions that close on Friday, has run into
trouble selling art over the Internet before. Last summer, he
offered an unattributed Impressionistic work that bore a signature
``P. Gray,'' but again made no claims for its authorship. Thinking
it was by Henry Percy Gray, a California painter known for his
oak-laden landscapes, Michael Luther, a Nebraska businessman,
agreed to pay $7,600 for it, sent a check and received the
painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amateur painting; it was garbage,'' Luther said.
``We put a black light on it and the signature swam on the paint,''
indicating that it was added long after the painting itself was
completed. ``I wrote a letter saying I'd sue, and he e-mailed me
back saying that he was an attorney and that he would fight back.''
</P>
<P>
   Luther has not filed suit, however. ``I've forgotten about it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such tales _ especially those involving sums like $135,805 _
certainly illustrate the perils of buying art online, but some
lawyers said that Walton probably stands on solid ground if Luther
sues. ``The definition of fraud on the Internet is no different
than in the offline world,'' said Susan Crawford, an expert in
e-commerce law at Wilmer, Cutler &AMP; Pickering in Washington. A party
who feels wronged in an auction on a site like eBay, which does not
vouch for the authenticity of sellers' merchandise, can prevail
legally only if the seller makes materially false statements in the
item's description, several lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   When he offered the painting signed ``P. Gray,'' Walton said he
did not make up a story. He bought the work at an estate sale, he
said, and made no changes to it. ``I absolutely never added a
signature to a painting _ that's totally untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether or not, in the case of the $135,805
painting, the fact that Walton is not married and does not have a
child who put a hole in it _ things he said in his offer _ is
material information that affected the decisions of potential
buyers. ``It looks like he was intending to confuse people,''
Crawford said, ``but it would be up to a judge.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Walton, 32, insisted that he had, as he said online, bought the
work at a garage sale in Berkeley. At the time, in the mid-'90s, he
was a law student at the University of California's Hastings School
of Law in San Francisco. ``I can't remember what I paid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walton also said that he has never sold anything as potentially
valuable as the painting bid on by Keereweer, which ``golfpoorly''
had described as a ``great big wild abstract painting'' that he
kept in his garage because his wife would not allow it in the
house.
</P>
<P>
   The 33 paintings he has sold on eBay since March 30 as
``advice'' fetched a total of $5,766.62, with the biggest price
being $697 for a what he described as a ``FINE Impressionist Oil _
Nude Bathing Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bidding on the four items currently on the site, a
painting he described as an ``OUTSTANDING ESTATE OIL _ ARABS ON
HORSEBACK,'' has gone highest, $1,100 Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Walton said he has made something of a hobby going to estate and
garage sales on weekends to search out paintings because he is
trying to raise money to start a private law practice. Until about
six months ago, he worked at Kronick, Moskovitz, Tiedemann &AMP; Girard
in Sacramento, but he said he left because he wanted to work in
copyright, intellectual property and trademark law, an area related
to his brothers' employment in the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to start a law practice and it's tough,'' he said.
``I don't come from a family with money, and I spend my time on
weekends going around to estate sales and buying paintings,'' he
said. ``I can find these paintings for $20 to $30 a pop and put
them up on eBay and get $300. If you think that's nefarious.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton declined to say how much he has made this way. He has
used the name ``advice'' on eBay since November 1998 and
``golfpoorly'' since last August. Because records for eBay sellers
are accessible for only 30 days, it is impossible to determine a
total for Walton during that entire period.``I made not that much
last year and this year it's more,'' Walton said. He said that no
one other than Luther had attempted to return a painting.
</P>
<P>
   Keereweer, a managing director of a software company who turns
43 next week, said that he had discovered eBay about seven weeks
ago. Since he began collecting art about 15 years ago, he has
focused on American and European art from 1900 to 1960, and owns
works by Arshile Gorky and Franz Kline, among others. But since he
had the first of two sons four years ago, he said, ``it's hard to
find the time to go to auctions and galleries.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend told him of eBay. ``I started to look for things,'' he
said, ``and I have bought seven or eight things,'' including works
by Leger, Alex Jawlensky and Mondrian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't received them all yet, but what I bought was OK,''
Keereweer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
