<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD, CARTER JOIN CLINTON IN SUPPORTING CHINA TRADE BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Flanked by a bipartisan cast of elder statesmen,
President Clinton Tuesday warned that failure by Congress to
approve permanent normal trade relations with China will only end
up hurting the United States economically.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we vote for this, 10 years from now we will wonder why this
was a hard fight,'' Clinton said at a White House event attended by
former Presidents Ford and Carter and former Secretaries of State
Henry Kissinger and James A. Baker III. ``And if Congress votes
against it, they'll be kicking themselves in the rear 10 years from
now because America will be paying the price.''
</P>
<P>
   The president brought out the all-star group as he intensified
his effort to convince lawmakers to ease trading relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote on the China trade bill scheduled for later this
month is expected to be close, with many members of the president's
party opposed to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest tally by the Reuters news agency, 161
House members have said they were supporting or leaning toward
voting for the trade measure, 57 votes short of the 218 needed to
clear the 435-member House. Ninety-seven lawmakers said they are
undecided and 163 have indicated they are opposed to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The trade measure is expected to pass the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is opposed by human rights advocates and
organized labor, who fear that American jobs will be replaced by
cheap Chinese labor.
</P>
<P>
   However, business and agriculture interests have backed an
improved trade relationship, saying it will open up a lucrative
overseas market to their products.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton and others have argued that the trade deal would be
a boost to the U.S. economy. The president said that even if
Congress doesn't approve the deal, China still will join the World
Trade Organization, which will ease its ability to trade with Japan
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition of unions to the trade pact has put Vice
President Al Gore in a difficult position because he is relying on
organized labor's members and money to help in his presidential
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore showed up at the White House event and stood with
Clinton to strongly endorse the China trade pact, arguing ``it is
right for American jobs. It is right for the cause of reform in
China and I believe it will move us closer to the strong and stable
world community we all seek to create.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on their experience with China over the past decades,
the former presidents and Cabinet officials acknowledged human
rights abuses in China. But they said the United States would be in
a better position to encourage change in China by trading with the
huge Asian powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooperative relations with China are in the American national
interest,'' said Kissinger, who helped engineer President Nixon's
trip to China _ a seminal event that helped thaw relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who noted that he first voted for a China trade agreement
as a House member in the 1940s, said the measure's defeat would be
``catastrophic, disastrous to American agriculture, electronics,
telecommunications, autos and countless other products and
services.''
</P>
<P>
   And Carter, who has championed human rights issues around the
world, noted that most Chinese human rights advocates approve of
better trade relations between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``China still has not measured up to the human rights and
democracy standards and labor standards of America, but there is no
doubt in my mind that a negative vote on this issue in the Congress
will be a serious setback and impediment for the further
democratization, freedom and human rights in China,'' said Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who served as secretary of state in the Bush
administration, noted that over the years there has been bipartisan
support for improving trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush was unable to attend the White House
event, although administration officials were quick to note that he
backed the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
