<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0436 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BRITISH-MUSIC-$ADV14-     05-09 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-MUSIC-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO KEEP THE SUN FROM SETTING ON BRITPOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release, Sunday, May 14) 
 By JODY ROSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though England has long since come to terms with the political
reality of its empire's demise, remembered glory still haunts the
national imagination and reverberates in the country's popular
culture: in the flag-fluttering pomp that greets royal weddings, in
the blaring jingoism of the tabloid press, in the chants, to the
tune of ``Rule Britannia,'' which rumble down from the terraces of
soccer stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Yearning for the grandeur of England's yesteryear exists even in
the youth-obsessed realm of pop music. English pop has its own
version of a venerated imperial heyday: the mid-1960s peak of the
British Invasion. On the one hand, the era is a symbol of British
cultural triumph: the moment when the Beatles, the Kinks, the Who
and other seminal bands stampeded onto the American charts and
established London as the home of the pop zeitgeist.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the music itself that resonates with modern Britain's
fondest and most sentimental self-image. Its wonderfully rich mix
of psychedelia and Victoriana, of fuzz-toned rock guitars and
French horn fanfares, of visionary anthems and quaintly provincial
evocations of village greens, conjures a fairytale England in which
the boundlessly sunny present and the charmed past magically
coexist.
</P>
<P>
   For a few years in the mid-1990s, the English pop scene was
consumed by the desire to relive that hallowed musical era.
Guitarists sprouted mop-top hairdos, Union Jacks were hoisted above
drum-risers and a wave of young bands flooded the airwaves with
records whose jaunty, tuneful Anglicisms self-consciously invoked
the legacy of the '60s greats.
</P>
<P>
   Flaunting classically English pop qualities _ wry lyrics,
winsome melodies, exaggerated cockney-inflected vocals _ the trend
was a defiantly Anglocentric rebuke to the grunts and macho poses
of the American grunge bands that were dominating guitar pop: the
chiming, cheery sound of the empire striking back.
</P>
<P>
   The movement, christened Britpop, swept up English pop culture
in a whirl of music-inspired patriotism. When American bands
resuscitate old styles, it is usually to make fashion statements.
But the flag-toting fervor of the Britpop revival was something
more serious. Against a backdrop of domestic uncertainty _ a
floundering British economy, anxiety about joining the European
Union, political weariness after nearly two decades under
Conservative government _ Britpop offered an image of cultural
renewal, promising not merely to resurrect the giddy cool of
swinging London circa 1966 but to recapture some deeper lost
essence of British greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Half a decade later, England has conspicuously abandoned the
Britpop cause.
</P>
<P>
   The music press long ago declared the movement dead. Most of
Britpop's upstarts have disappeared, dropping off the radar when
their borrowed riffs and blokey histrionics fell out of fashion.
Britain's latest guitar pop favorites strike different postures:
quavering earnestness (Radiohead, Travis), Americana obsessed
(Gomez), techno-savvy (Beta Band) or, in the case of the reformed
ex-Britpop torchbearers Blur, a bit of all three.
</P>
<P>
   But traditionalist stalwarts remain. Two veteran Britpop bands,
Oasis and Supergrass, are currently in the United States, touring
behind new albums steeped in English pop classicism. Now several
years removed from the peak moment of Britpop hysteria, the records
provide insight into why the movement flared and fizzled, and are a
study in Britpop's limitations and possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Oasis was Britpop's marquee act.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the scowling, leering Gallagher brothers _ the lead
singer Liam and the guitarist-songwriter Noel _ the band arrived on
the British charts in 1994 with a bombastic sound and a grandiose
aspiration: to be ``bigger than the Beatles.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Britpop groups like Blur, Pulp and Gene embraced the
literate, arty aspect of the English pop tradition, Oasis offered
visceral pleasures: crunching guitars and the catharsis of soaring
choruses. In Liam Gallagher, the band had a bona fide rock star,
who put across his brother's often meaningless lyrics with gruff
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``(What's The Story) Morning Glory?,'' Oasis' second album, sold
15 million copies, but the band never managed a Beatles-like
conquest of global pop. Its third record bombed, and the recently
released fourth, ``Standing on the Shoulder of Giants'' (Epic
EK63586), a collection of rhythmically turgid, mid-tempo retro-rock
songs, finds Oasis slipping into wearisome self-parody.
</P>
<P>
   The root of Oasis' problem is the same misapprehension that
vexed so many of its Britpop compatriots: a failure to comprehend
the urbanity of classic English pop. The music of the British
Invasion might sound quintessentially English to today's listeners,
but its creators were cosmopolitan seekers, who assimilated a range
of influences _ in particular black American music _ into their own
very personal styles.
</P>
<P>
   Oasis professes devotion to the Beatles, but the band's gloss on
its heroes is shallow. Though it endlessly cribs the Beatles'
mannerisms _ announcing the gravity of its ballads with stately
``Hey Jude''-like piano chords, even co-opting famous Beatles
lyrics _ Oasis has absorbed none of its idols' zeal for musical
exploration. The Gallagher brothers traveled far on the momentum of
their bluster, but with ``Standing on the Shoulder of Giants'' the
band reaches the same dead end as a hundred Britpop lesser-lights:
worshiping vapidly at the altar of the past, Oasis consigns itself
to present-day irrelevance.
</P>
<P>
   Supergrass, a rugged trio from Oxford, never dared to dream
Oasis-size dreams of rock glory. But its musical ambitions have
always been vast. When the band first appeared in 1994, playing
funny, taut songs that combined the stuttering tenacity of the
Manchester punk legends the Buzzcocks with the wit of songwriters
like Ray Davies of the Kinks, Supergrass quickly gained a
reputation as Britpop's lovable clown princes. But even the band's
most cartoonish songs, like its breakthrough single ``Caught by the
Fuzz,'' were constructed with orchestral intelligence _ every burst
of feedback, guitar overdub and background vocal was witty, telling
and exact.
</P>
<P>
   On its third album, ``Supergrass'' (Island 314-542 388-2), the
band's promise is splendidly realized. Augmenting its power trio
line-up with keyboards and a small string section, the
singer-guitarist Gaz Coombes, the bassist Mick Quinn and the
drummer Danny Goffey have made an almost epic album, integrating a
riot of influences into an organic and highly eccentric
contemporary variation on classic British guitar pop. Avoiding the
pratfalls of their peers, Supergrass treats Britpop not as an
ideology or a kind of connoisseurship but as an approach to
songcraft. The result is one of the best English pop records in
many years. (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Supergrass has a command of a variety of pop styles, which it
moves between with easy virtuosity. The band plays passages of Sly
and the Family Stone-inspired funk, dreamy guitar arpeggios that
sound like Pink Floyd, rave-ups in the style of glam-era David
Bowie; it changes tempos and time signatures like a '70s
progressive rock band and sings lonesome high-harmony parts that
recall Brian Wilson's Beach Boys.
</P>
<P>
   But Supergrass has such a strong musical personality and such a
lucid sense of purpose that the record never feels like pastiche:
every arrangement and production flourish is made in the service of
a song. The stunning album opener, ``Moving,'' is a case in point.
The song starts out with Coombes crooning, accompanied only by
guitar and strings, erupts into a churning, manic R-and-B chorus,
then morphs into a lush Philadelphia soul-style ballad.
</P>
<P>
   But this stylistic hodgepodge feels just right: each musical
passage gives its accompanying lyric the perfect coloration, and
the listener feels the overarching mood of road-bound resignation
in the loping bass line that nudges the song through its wistful
fade.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Supergrass'' is, unmistakably, a record in the Britpop
tradition, it never indulges in genre cliches. When Oasis tries to
spike its new album with psychedelia, the group trots out shopworn
trippy motifs _ walls of echo and guitar reverb, sitar drones,
woozy keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   Supergrass' psychedelia, like the Beatles', grades into the
baroque; it is intrinsic, textural, symphonic _ an accumulation of
sonic details, bristling beneath unusual melodies, that reward
solitary listeners with sharp ears and a good set of headphones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supergrass'' is the album that the mid-'90s Britpop movement
promised but never delivered. Smart, inventive, melodically rich,
rambunctious yet subtle, ambitious but totally unpretentious, it
distills the best qualities of classic English pop and makes an
emphatic argument for the idiom's continued vitality. Half a decade
after the musical patriots packed up their flags, Supergrass has
given England a reason to wave them. ``Britpop'' is dead; long live
Britpop. &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
