 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CLINTON-SCHEDULE-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 7,
about communities that invite visits from President Clinton
misidentified the Arkansas town where Clinton attended a wedding on
Saturday. It was Subiaco, not Fayetteville.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NJ-DEBATE-NYT (moved on Monday, May 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, May 8,
about the first debate by New Jersey's four Republican candidates
for United States Senate misidentified the county represented by
one of them, State Senator William L. Gormley. He is from Atlantic
County, not Ocean County.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the year in which another candidate,
Murray Sabrin, ran for governor as a Libertarian. It was 1997, not
1993.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ACTORS-AD-STRIKE-NYT (moved on Monday, May 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, May 1,
about a strike by actors in television and radio commercials
misspelled one striker's surname and referred incorrectly to his
comments about the pay disparity between cable and network
television. The actor is Frank Simons, not Simmons. He said he
would have earned $40,000 if his commercial had run as often on the
networks as on cable. He did not say that that occurred.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TONY-NOMINEES-NYT (moved on Monday, May 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, May 8,
about the Tony Award nominations referred incorrectly to the
previous occurrence of multiple nominations for a single director
in different categories. Michael Blakemore, with two such
nominations this year, was similarly nominated 10 years ago, but
the most recent case was that of Michael Mayer, nominated last year
for both the musical ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' and the
play ``Side Man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
