<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JANUS-FUNDS-NYT &LR;      05-09 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANUS-FUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCELERATING GROWTH HAS FORCED JANUS TO CLOSE THREE FUNDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Colo., N.Y.)  By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Popularity has its complications.
</P>
<P>
   Under an onslaught of money from investors, Janus said Tuesday
that it would close three funds, including the $42 billion Janus
Worldwide, the nation's largest fund with an international bent.
The closings would become effective Wednesday. (Existing
shareholders would still be able to add to their positions.)
</P>
<P>
   The move, a year after the company shuttered the popular $35.4
billion Janus Twenty, means that nearly half of Janus' 15 equity
funds would be closed to new shareholders. Such closings are a
common practice in the industry to keep the assets in any given
fund from growing too large to be effectively managed.
</P>
<P>
   The last 16 months have brought great success to Janus, the
Denver mutual fund company known for its aggressive stock-picking
style. Last year, 28 cents of every dollar invested in mutual funds
went to Janus, according to the fund tracking firm AMG Data
Services, and the growth has only accelerated of late. In the first
four months of this year, the firm's equity funds took in $31
billion more, nearly equaling the company's inflows for all of last
year and propelling Janus from the 20th biggest mutual fund concern
at the end of 1998 to the fifth at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   That was so much money that several managers requested the
closings, which, by Janus policy, is within their discretion. ``It
will slow the flows,' said Stephen Stieneker, a Janus spokesman.
``We hope it will allow us to continue the performance our
investors expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Fidelity and Vanguard, which offer a diverse slate of
funds covering dozens of sectors and investment styles, Janus made
its name by offering relatively few funds largely focused on
aggressive stocks, and by making some prescient bets in the
technology and telecommunications sectors.
</P>
<P>
   The focused approach has meant that several of the same stocks
appear in the portfolios of different Janus funds, so if one Janus
fund is closed, investors may find a similar investing style in
another offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``For investors, you need to keep in mind that you're getting
somewhat similar exposure,'' said Christine Benz, a senior analyst
at the fund tracking firm Morningstar. For the company, ``the
challenge is that they'll need to develop the other parts of their
product line.''
</P>
<P>
   Janus added a value-oriented fund this year and two sector
funds, one focused on technology and one on health stocks, at the
end of 1998. The health fund, Janus Global Life Sciences, was one
of those closed Tuesday, along with the $8 billion Janus Olympus.
The technology sector fund was closed earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   While Janus executives consider how best to handle their growth,
they also must navigate an even more delicate situation _ Janus'
impending spinoff from its parent company, Kansas City Southern
Industries. Janus executives, including Tom Bailey, the founder and
chief executive, have criticized Kansas City Southern's plan to
package Janus along with its three other financial holdings into a
subsidiary called Stilwell Financial. Janus executives would prefer
to be spun off as a separate company.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern executives have rejected that suggestion,
and they expect the spinoff to proceed as soon as they receive
regulatory approval. Still, the future of Janus will remain with
Janus, say Kansas City Southern officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy has been that you don't change a winning
formula,'' said James R. Jones, a former chief executive of the
American Stock Exchange and current member of Kansas City
Southern's board of directors. ``It's an industry with a lot of
strong personalities, and they speak their mind,'' he said of the
Janus officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-00 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
