<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000509.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-09 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: BLAIR DEFIANT
</P>
<P>
   In his first speech since his most significant setback in three
years in office, Prime Minister Tony Blair said he would not change
his government's program to suit his critics. ``Come fair weather
or foul, we intend to stick to the course we have set out,'' he
said in an uncompromising address to the Periodical Publishers'
Association. In elections last week, Blair suffered the loss of
nearly 600 local council seats and the indignity of seeing Ken
Livingstone, whom he opposed, become London's first elected mayor.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: MURDER INQUIRY SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Commission, a watchdog group set up under the
April 1998 Ulster peace accord, dismissed as insufficient a police
investigation of the murder of a prominent Catholic rights lawyer,
Pat Finucane, and called for an independent inquiry. A Protestant
paramilitary group claimed responsibility for the 1989 murder, but
the family and civil liberties groups say they have evidence of
collusion between the killers and the Royal Ulster Constabulary.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: ARMY PULLBACK
</P>
<P>
   British army bases in Londonderry and South Armagh and a
military camp close to the Irish border are to be closed, and
several observation towers in Belfast are to be dismantled, said
Sir Ronnie Flanagan, chief of the Royal Ulster Constabulary. The
steps follow an announcement by the Irish Republican Army
permitting international inspection of its secret arms dumps.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: 3 EX-COMMUNISTS CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   Three former members of East Germany's Politburo went on trial
for manslaughter in the shooting deaths of four people trying to
flee across the Berlin Wall between 1984 and 1989. Herbert Haeber,
69, Hans-Joachim Boehme, 70, and Siegfried Lorenz, 69, are accused
of not speaking out in the Politburo against the killings of people
trying to escape to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: BERLUSCONI WINS
</P>
<P>
   A Milan appeals court overturned a bribery conviction against
Silvio Berlusconi, a media tycoon and leader of the center-left
opposition. Berlusconi, whose victory in regional elections drove
former Prime Minister Massimo d'Alema to resign, was cleared on one
of four bribery counts. The court overturned three others because
the statute of limitations had elapsed. He still faces trials on
other charges of bribery and false accounting.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MORE MAD COW DISEASE
</P>
<P>
   Officials announced that they had detected yet another case of
mad cow disease, this time in the northwest Manche region. The cow
and a herd of 141 other cattle were slaughtered and burned. The new
case brought to 17 the number of new cases discovered this year,
suggesting France is on the way to far exceed last year's total of
30 cases.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES: EX-NATO CHIEF ARRIVES
</P>
<P>
   Javier Solana, the former NATO secretary-general, arrived in
Manila representing European nations concerned over the welfare of
10 mostly European hostages being held by Muslim separatists.
Solana said he was there to observe and offer support, not to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: PLEA ON TORTURE
</P>
<P>
   China has been urged by a United Nations body in Geneva to
investigate allegations of torture and to take steps to ensure such
acts are punished. The U.N. Committee Against Torture also urged
China to end administrative detentions, in which inmates lack legal
protection.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: NO SURRENDER
</P>
<P>
   A day after Sri Lanka rejected a cease-fire offer from the
separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, Deputy Defense
Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte told Parliament, ``We will never give
Jaffna to LTTE.'' The Tigers have taken two crucial army bases
since April 22 in their quest to control the northern Jaffna
Peninsula. Ratwatte said 358 soldiers were killed and 349 are
missing in action in the recent battles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELSEWHERE IN THE WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: STRIKE HITS ENROLLMENT
</P>
<P>
   The number of high school graduates seeking admission to the
Autonomous National University, Mexico's most important institution
of higher learning, has plummeted in the wake of a student strike
that paralyzed the campus for nearly a year. Before the strike
began last spring, 78,000 students took the entrance examination.
After the strike ended this spring, only 41,000 applicants took the
same test.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO: NEW FIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda accused each other of continued attacks in
Kisangani, only a day after they agreed to a cease-fire and to
evacuate the city to make way for United Nations peacekeepers. Each
nation supports rebels fighting Congo's government, but twice now
they have clashed in Kisangani, an important strategic city. Rwanda
says Uganda fired 70 mortar shells at Rwandan positions overnight.
The Ugandan military said Rwandans fired first. No one was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SELF-APPRAISAL
</P>
<P>
   Israelis believe the typical Israeli to be characterized by
chutzpah, ``directness without politeness,'' materialism and
loudness, according to a poll by the newspaper Yediot Ahronot. But
only 20 percent of those surveyed said they considered themselves
typical. The newspaper also found that while half the Jewish
population consider themselves ``very Zionist,'' some 20 percent _
mostly young people _ do not consider themselves Zionist at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
