A0447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-09 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES FROM AROUND THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEDY OPPONENT IN TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   Jack E. Robinson III, the ill-fated Republican challenger for
Edward M. Kennedy's Senate seat, faces some new adversity that may
be potentially fatal for his campaign. As of 5 p.m. Tuesday, the
Massachusetts secretary of state's office had certified only 5,122
of the 10,000 signatures Robinson needed by that hour to officially
qualify to run. So unless he has some 5,000 signatures stashed out
there that can readily and unquestionably be certified, he has
failed to make the ballot, said Secretary of State William F.
Galvin. ``It's very much up in the air whether he will make it or
not,'' Galvin said. If he does not, Galvin added, it would mean
that Massachusetts Republicans had failed to field a U.S. Senate
candidate for the first time since senators were first elected by
popular vote, back in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson offered no explanation for what happened to his
signature-gathering effort or his campaign in general _ a campaign
he had sworn to continue despite a raft of damaging accusations and
incidents, ranging from traffic troubles to bad behavior toward
women.
</P>
<P>
   SWITCHING TO DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear yet whether it is a real trend, and if so why,
but the conversion of Southern Republicans to the Democratic Party
may be spreading. It began last month with two South Carolina
legislators. Then a few days ago, a Georgia state representative,
Randy Sauder, who represents the Atlanta suburb of Smyrna, became
the first Georgia Republican in 16 years to switch to the
Democrats. Another Republican state legislator, Buddy DeLoach of
Hinesville, is becoming an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Sauder, who switched just before the filing deadline to prevent
any Republicans from running against him, said he was disappointed
in the Republican Party's rigidity on issues like education.
Republicans vowed to run one of their own against him as an
independent candidate. Over the past few decades, those switching
parties in the South were mostly Democrats turning Republican.
</P>
<P>
   EYE ON 2004 RACE?
</P>
<P>
   Though this year's presidential primary season is not officially
over, a coming fund-raiser in Georgia is already stoking
speculation about races four years or so down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Next Monday, Jeanne Shaheen, the Democratic governor of New
Hampshire, will be the beneficiary of an event in Atlanta _ a bit
south of Concord _ that planners hope will raise at least $25,000
for her re-election.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the hosts, as well as one of the contributors, will
be Georgia's governor, Roy Barnes, a first-term Democrat who is
beginning to win national attention for his policies on improving
schools and limiting sprawl. Robert S. Kahn, Barnes' chief of
staff, says his boss was simply supporting a fellow Democratic
governor, not pocketing a chit to be cashed later, in time for New
Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary in 2004 or 2008. ``The only
election he's interested in, other than legislative elections, is
his own re-election,'' Kahn insisted.
</P>
<P>
   The event is being organized by Michael Coles, a prominent party
fund-raiser and Barnes ally who met Shaheen while working for Vice
President Al Gore in New Hampshire last winter.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH Davenport, Iowa
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE Arlington, Va.; Jacksonville, Ark.; Dallas; Burbank,
Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
