<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MOCKINGBIRD-ACTOR-NYT     05-09 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOCKINGBIRD-ACTOR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO KILL A MOCKINGBIRD ACTOR RECALLS THE MAKING OF A CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM THORNTON   The Gadsden (Ala.) Times   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GADSDEN, Ala. _ The ghost of Atticus Finch was at work this
week, in the eyes of students at Westbrook Christian School.
</P>
<P>
   As the mysterious Boo Radley once more kept watch over Jem,
Scout and Dill, students watched the screen expectantly, their
heads leaning forward, some hiding their faces in excited dread.
Adults looked on as well, familiar smiles playing on their faces as
the child actors of almost 40 years ago brought to life Harper
Lee's classic novel.
</P>
<P>
   Then, applause swelled as the students showed their appreciation
for the timeless book and the classic movie made from it.
</P>
<P>
   A reminder of both was on display Monday, as Gadsden native
Philip Alford answered questions and recounted ``a special time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you tell the difference between then and now?'' the
51-year-old asked, his smoky voice staring out at the young faces
through glasses. Balding, dressed in blue jeans and loafers, he
bore little resemblance to the boy who had just reappeared on
screen.
</P>
<P>
   When Alford was 13, he received the key to the city for his role
as Jem Finch in ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost 30 years since he quit show business. He said
he grew tired of its drug culture and the roles that were being
offered. He is now a building contractor in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently has he begun acknowledging his role in the 1962
movie, which won four Academy Awards and still retains much of its
magic. That was evident by the crowd of schoolchildren who lingered
to get Alford to sign their dog-eared editions of the Lee novel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Alford had not even read the Pulitzer Prize-winning
novel when he was offered a role in the movie. He was discovered
while acting in Birmingham, and only took the role after his mother
told him he could miss school. By that time, more than 2,500
children had already auditioned for the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the right size in the right place at the right time,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   From February to late May, he and cast members Mary Badham, the
late John Megna and Gregory Peck spent their days at the Universal
sound stage, then transformed into Depression-era Alabama. It was
originally scheduled to be a 10-week shoot, he said, until
producers realized ``they had something special.''
</P>
<P>
   In that time, he went from 89 pounds to 112, and grew 7 inches
in height. He tried desperately not to kill his co-star Badham, who
played Scout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated her,'' he admitted, smiling. ``She had this really bad
habit of mouthing your lines when she wasn't supposed to be
speaking. We were serious about killing her.''
</P>
<P>
   This antagonism sometimes translates on the screen, and remains
vividly in Alford's memory. A breakfast scene required endless
takes because of Badham, he said, forcing him to consume helping
after helping of bacon, eggs and grits.
</P>
<P>
   He also offered insights into 1960s Hollywood. The picture's
makers decided not to let the child actors watch any filming of the
movie's climactic court scenes, he said, because the trial dealt
with a supposed rape. The film's social content was supposed to
have doomed it at the box office in the South, but it ended up
being more popular there than elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Alford recalled the fun of making the film.
One story involved the book's secretive author. For the first few
days of the film shoot, Lee was on the set as a technical adviser.
When she watched Peck with the film's children in one of the first
scenes filmed, Peck spotted a tear coming down her cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad to see you were touched by the scene,'' Peck later
told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the scene,'' she replied. ``You have a pot belly,
just like my daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a pot belly,'' the screen legend shot back.
``That's acting.''
</P>
<P>
   In his seven years of acting, Alford went from making $500 to
$10,000 a week. He said he missed the applause most of all, but did
not regret the life he found with his wife and family.
</P>
<P>
   Only four years ago did he get the itch to act again. A photo
shoot with Vanity Fair magazine reunited ``Mockingbird's''
surviving cast members for the first time in more than 30 years,
redepositing them on the movie's old set. The familiar smell of
paint and glue made him want to act again, he admitted, but only
for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has retained a friendship with Peck _ always
called ``Mister Peck'' _ and the other cast members. He speaks
perhaps four times a year at colleges and schools, but this was his
first appearance in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of little things I had never heard him talk
about before,'' said his cousin, Jim Copeland of Gadsden. ``It was
very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has given up a movie career that began with great
promise, he has not had to turn his back on its adulation. Judging
by the applause he received Monday, Alford's career, and the appeal
of ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' is alive and well.
</P>
<P>
   (William Thornton writes for The Gadsden (Ala.) Times, part of
the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
