<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Behind Painting Sold Online Was a Partly False Story
</P>
<P>
   The man who sold a painting on the Internet for $135,805
acknowledged that he concocted part of the story he used to
describe the work, which bore the initials ``RD,'' creating
speculation that it was painted by the California artist Richard
Diebenkorn.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being a married homeowner who cleaned the painting out
of his garage, the man is a single lawyer who has sold paintings on
eBay before. But he said that he did not fake the painting or add
the signature and that he would cancel the sale if experts
determine that the canvas is not by Diebenkorn.
</P>
<P>
   Striving to Make Copyrights Moot
</P>
<P>
   While courts struggle over the recording industry's challenge to
digital music-swapping, software is being written that could make
it impossible to control the traffic in any kind of digital
information _ whether it is music, video, text or software.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods Hints Deal Is Possible
</P>
<P>
   When Bestfoods rejected a takeover offer from Unilever last
week, it seemed emphatic. But over the last few days, senior
executives at Bestfoods have talked with the company's largest
investors, discussing their reasons for turning down the $18.4
billion offer, saying that Unilever has underestimated the savings
of such a deal. The executives' position hints that Bestfoods would
consider a merger opportune at the right price, analysts said.
Shares of Bestfoods fell $1, to $63.50.
</P>
<P>
   Profit and Revenue Rise at Cisco
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems said that its third-quarter profit beat
expectations while it posted a 55 percent gain in sales as the
leading supplier of hardware for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Slide on Rate Concerns
</P>
<P>
   Stocks dropped on fears about the effect of an expected increase
in interest rates. The Nasdaq composite index dropped 84.37 points,
or 2.3 percent, to 3,585.01. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
66.88 points, to 10,536.75, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index slipped 12.03 points, to 1,412.14.
</P>
<P>
   No Phone Offer Seen in Hong Kong
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Telecommunications probably will not make a rival bid
for Hong Kong's flagship telephone company, Cable and Wireless HKT,
executives close to the company said. They said Singapore Telecom
was balking at the price it would have to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Janus to Close Three of Its Funds
</P>
<P>
   Under an onslaught of money from investors, the Janus mutual
fund group said that it would close three funds: the $42 billion
Janus Worldwide, the Janus Olympus Fund and the Janus Global Life
Sciences Fund.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo to Buy Dutch Stake
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo, Japan's largest mobile phone company, agreed to
acquire a 15 percent stake in the Dutch mobile phone operator KPN
Mobile for about $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Coke in Deal With Lawyer's Channel
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola said that it was becoming a major advertiser on a
cable channel owned by a Florida lawyer who represents four of the
plaintiffs in a racial discrimination suit brought by the company's
black employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Psychological Toll of Traveling
</P>
<P>
   Research by the World Bank has shown that not only can extensive
business travel take a physical toll, being on the road can also
take a psychological toll on workers and their families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
