<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-HENDERSON-76     05-09 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HENDERSON-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON'S FUTURE WITH METS TURNS CLOUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Unsure how much more production they can get from a
future Hall of Famer, the Mets have placed outfielder Rickey
Henderson on major league waivers, baseball officials confirmed
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has 48 hours to pass through waivers, giving clubs _
in order from the National League team with the worst record to the
one with the best, then the same way in the American League _ a
chance to claim him and assume the remainder of his $2 million
salary for this season. If a team claims Henderson, the Mets can
decide to pull him back, and perhaps work out a trade with that
club. Or, they can simply let him go to the other team for the
$20,000 waiver price. That team would pick up his salary.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is 41, and Mets officials do not know whether he has
reached the end of the line in a brilliant career. Henderson is a
unique talent, probably the best leadoff hitter in baseball
history, but so far he has had a bad season without any period of
extended success.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets discussed trade possibilities involving Henderson over
the winter, and putting him on waivers gives them options; they can
see who has interest now, and if they determine he is finished,
they can save money and let him go for the waiver price. The Mets
can also keep him and hope he rediscovers the form he showed in
1999, when he batted .315, stole 37 bases and had a .423 on-base
percentage. The Mets apparently have no current interest in simply
releasing him. If they did, they would owe him his full salary. If
another team then picked him up, the Mets would still have to pay
most of what he would be owed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate releasing Rickey Henderson,'' General
Manager Steve Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets are frustrated with Henderson's play. He has said
he has had problems seeing the ball, a common affliction for
players but one that rarely lasts this long, one Mets official
said. Henderson was hitting .207 after going one for four in the
Mets' 2-0 win over the Pirates in Pittsburgh on Tuesday night, and
he had no hitting streak longer than two games, just one extra-base
hit and only two stolen bases, a stunningly low number for the
career leader in steals. Even Mets catcher Mike Piazza has more
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson was unhappy that the Mets did not renegotiate his
contract this season and grumbled in spring training about the way
he was sometimes double-switched out of games last season. He did
not speak much to reporters from early April until last weekend,
when he again questioned Manager Bobby Valentine's use of him. Just
days before that, while Phillips was speaking to reporters in San
Francisco, Henderson asked him for a meeting. Phillips has been
exasperated by the distractions Henderson causes, but he insisted
the San Francisco incident did not bother him.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips and Valentine also spoke Tuesday with Henderson, who
started in left field against the Pirates and led off, as usual.
Their message, Henderson said, was this: ``Don't worry about it. It
don't mean nothing. You have a Mets uniform on and you're in the
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Henderson was critical of the way Valentine used
him in Florida, but Phillips said he had heard similar comments
before. For the Mets, Henderson's production on the field is more
important than anything Henderson says. He has always said
flamboyant things.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rickey's going to talk _ and he has talked during his
career _ he's usually able to walk his talk,'' Valentine said.
``That ability is what separated him _ not what he has said, but
what he's capable of doing. He's capable of playing better than
he's played, and he'll do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson came out early for batting practice Tuesday, something
he said he was planning to do, and he got in 40 to 50 extra swings,
concentrating on limiting movement of his head and ``tracking the
ball'' better. He thinks he is finding his stroke, he said, and he
is looking forward to warmer temperatures. He said he does not know
his waiver status now _ ``I know I've been on it probably 1,000
times,'' he said _ and said he is not bothered by it, whatever it
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get disappointed, but nothing in this game makes
me mad or sad,'' he said. ``I'm here. I think we all _ players,
managers, anybody _ we get frustrated when things aren't going the
way we want them to go or expect them to go. But this game is about
adjustments. That's what I've got to do. That's what I think
Bobby's going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything's going well, it would be no problem. When
things go bad, it seems like we have a lot of controversy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Baseball officials are fined if they comment on waivers, so
Phillips did not confirm nor deny that he had asked waivers on
Henderson. There are two types of waivers; the type the Mets are
using on Henderson, and the irrevocable waivers in which a team
cannot pull a player back if he is claimed. The fact the Mets did
not use irrevocable waivers on Henderson would indicate they have
not fully given up on him.
</P>
<P>
   As for another team claiming Henderson, one baseball official
said, it would have to be a big-market team that would be willing
to gamble on an aging, slumping player.
</P>
<P>
   Without Henderson, the Mets would seem to have few options to
replace him as their everyday leadoff hitter. While the speedy
outfielder Jason Tyner, a first-round draft pick, is hitting .314
with 16 stolen bases at Class AAA Norfolk, Phillips said: ``We have
a lot of minor leaguers with speed. I'm not sure any of them are
ready for the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Nunnally has batted leadoff six times for the Mets this
year, and Benny Agbayani and Melvin Mora have done so once apiece.
Jay Payton, who has good speed, is another possible leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rickey got hurt, I don't think we'd have any problem
finding someone for the leadoff role,'' Valentine said. ``We
wouldn't cancel the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
