<HEADER>
A0472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ARCHBISHOP-SUCCESS     05-09 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHBISHOP-SUCCESSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORD ABOUT O'CONNOR'S SUCCESSOR NEGATES A CHURCH TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was not the way it was supposed to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   As New York's archbishop, Cardinal John O'Connor, was being
buried in the crypt of St. Patrick's Cathedral on Monday, there was
little question of the usual month-long period of respect and
reflection before his successor as archbishop would be announced.
</P>
<P>
   A priest attending the funeral asked Bishop Edward M. Egan of
Bridgeport for confirmation he was indeed the Vatican's choice, as
everybody, including the bishop's brother-in-law from Maryland, had
been saying. ``I'll let you know after Wednesday,'' the bishop was
overheard answering.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the bishop will be installed in a ceremony not long
after that, according to his brother-in-law, Raymond Egan, who said
he planned to visit New York for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to papal secrecy? What of the half-dozen other
candidates whose names had surfaced since last summer? And why did
Egan not initially figure among them?
</P>
<P>
   The selection of archbishops is normally played close to the
vest, with those who participate sworn never to acknowledge even
their role in the process, much less its details. The choice
becomes official only when Rome speaks, either directly or through
its delegate in the United States, and in recent memory, there have
been no real cracks in the wall of confidentiality protecting
Vatican appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything this close to the fact covered this
way,'' said Msgr. John Doherty, who was vicar of the Bronx when
Egan worked in New York as auxiliary bishop for education.
</P>
<P>
   As O'Connor's health failed last autumn and winter, a committee
of American bishops began the search for his successor. They
canvassed leading clergymen and lay Catholics about the problems
facing the archdiocese now and in the coming years, gathering
opinions about who might best fill the job.
</P>
<P>
   A number of names surfaced as possibilities. These included that
of Bishops Henry Mansell of Buffalo and Sean O'Malley of Fall
River, Mass., and Archbishops Justin F. Rigali of St. Louis,
Theodore E. McCarrick of Newark, N.J., and Edwin F. O'Brien, who
oversees military chaplains.
</P>
<P>
   One church official who was briefed by the cardinal said that
the final list of names handed to Pope John Paul II came down to
three: Archbishops Rigali and O'Brien, and Bishop Mansell, who
O'Connor said he favored for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Another clergyman, who was consulted by the Vatican and who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said he had suggested Egan, along
with two other candidates, as his choices. Weighing heavily in this
clergyman's mind was the need to close and consolidate schools and
parishes in the New York archdiocese, whose population had changed
substantially during O'Connor's 16-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, he noted, had been able to close and merge parishes and
schools in the Bridgeport diocese, where he has served as bishop
since 1988. And at 68, this clergyman said, Egan would be an
interim archbishop, making the necessary changes before submitting
his letter of resignation upon turning 75, as Vatican tradition
demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that he would be very good for the interim position, in
which he'd take some difficult actions that would result in a
measure of unpopularity, and that was what was needed,'' the
clergyman said. But animosity, he added, was not inevitable: an
astute archbishop could win people over by revitalizing the merged
or streamlined parishes and redefining their missions.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's name was not on the list of three names, or terna,
submitted to the pope for final consideration, said the church
official in whom the cardinal confided. The Vatican had assigned
Egan to New York in 1985 shortly after O'Connor arrived here, and
the two men had had a rocky start. The clergyman who suggested
Egan's name to the Vatican said he suspected that it did not make
the terna because the cardinal and the bishop ``were just on
different wavelengths.''
</P>
<P>
   In the deliberations to narrow the choices, O'Brien's name fell
first, the official who was briefed by the cardinal said. One
faction involved in the selection supported Rigali, while another
faction, to which O'Connor belonged, supported Mansell.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the pope agreed with neither group, and selected a
name of his own, the archdiocesan official said, much as he had
done in appointing O'Connor archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In February, O'Connor visited the Vatican _ a trip that doubled
as a farewell visit and lobbying effort on behalf of Mansell, said
the official in whom the cardinal confided. Not long after that,
O'Connor, in a letter of farewell to the 870 priests who worked
under him, said he expected to see his replacement named sometime
in March.
</P>
<P>
   But March passed quietly, as did April, with church officials
whispering that the Vatican seemed inclined to allow O'Connor to
die in office, as had all previous archbishops of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as O'Connor's illness lingered, the Vatican appeared to
have decided it could not leave New York leaderless indefinitely.
Early last week, several church officials said, preparations began
to make public Egan's appointment to the Roman Catholic Church's
most visible pulpit in the country. Word of the impending
announcement went out to a limited circle of bishops and their
auxiliaries in New York and archbishops throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, O'Connor's condition deteriorated, and it became clear
that his death was imminent. Out of respect for the cardinal, the
preparations screeched to a halt. But the word, once out, could not
be locked back up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
