<HEADLINE>
COKE TO ADVERTISE ON CHANNEL OWNED BY LAWYER IN BIAS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Fla.)   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adding a new twist to the already complicated racial
discrimination lawsuit brought against Coca-Cola by a group of its
black employees, Coke said Wednesday that it was becoming a major
advertiser on a cable channel owned by a Florida lawyer who last
month began representing four of the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Coke signed a five-year agreement with the Atlanta-based
channel, MBC Network, which plans to broadcast children's shows,
movies, cartoons and sports programs specifically for black
families 24 hours a day, according to a statement from MBC.
</P>
<P>
   The channel, owned by Willie D. Gary, was formed in 1998. It is
backed by Evander Holyfield, the boxer; Marlon D. Jackson, one of
the original Jackson Five; Cecil Fielder, formerly of the Detroit
Tigers; and Alvin D. James, a longtime broadcaster, as well as
Gary.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's name will appear on print and electronic announcements
connected with the channel, which will advertise all Coke brands,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Gary represents four of the named plaintiffs in the lawsuit
against Coca-Cola, which was filed 13 months ago and contends that
the plaintiffs were denied promotions, raises and other advancement
at the company because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Coke could raise questions about a conflict of
interest between Gary's role in the lawsuit and Coke's support of
his business venture. Gary could not be reached Tuesday night for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cyrus Mehri, the lawyer who originally represented the four and
continues to represent four other current and former Coke employees
in the lawsuit, said the arrangement ``is an issue between Mr. Gary
and the four individuals he represents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My team's focus is on fighting for the best possible
resolution for the class,'' Mehri added.
</P>
<P>
   A Coke spokesman said the company's discussions and final
negotiations occurred before Gary announced his intention to get
involved in the lawsuit, which is seeking class-action status for
as many as 2,000 Coke employees,
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making the ad buy because it gives us an opportunity to
support what we believe is some very meaningful programming and
connect our advertising with African-American consumers on a
frequent and consistent basis,'' said the spokesman, Ben Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   Gary, who is best known for obtaining a $500 million award in a
1995 case against the Loewen funeral home company, was introduced
to Coke's former chairman, M. Douglas Ivester, by the Rev. Jesse
Jackson. Gary is Jackson's lawyer. The Loewen award was eventually
settled at $175 million.
</P>
<P>
   Coke and the employees named in the lawsuit began court-ordered
mediation last month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
