A0474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS10-     05-09 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wild first is grand for Lopez
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami _ The Braves gave one away with a walk-off balk the
previous night, but they were on the other end of the giveaway
Tuesday night against the Florida Marlins and walked off with some
10-5 payback.
</P>
<P>
   Using seven walks and two hit batsmen by rookie starter Brad
Penny in the first 2 1/3 innings, the Braves had a five-run first
inning on their way to snapping a three-game losing skid.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who had lost four of five since a franchise-record
15-game winning streak, tied their season high in runs.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez was the prime benefactor. He came to the plate with
the bases loaded in the first and cleared them with a grand slam on
the way to a 3-for-4 night.
</P>
<P>
   Not since they clinched the National League East division last
year in Montreal had the Braves enjoyed such a productive first
inning, when they scored five runs on their way to a 10-0 win on
Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The big first inning, which included an RBI by Brian Jordan when
he was hit by a pitch with the bases loaded, helped untrack the
Braves' offense and make a winner out of John Burkett for the first
time in three starts as a Brave.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Quilvio Veras drew a bases-loaded walk in the third
to make it 6-1 _ which would be the last the Braves saw of Penny _
they had matched their offensive output of the previous three
games.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a week since the Braves had outhit an opponent. They
were down to hitting .234 with runners in scoring position and a
lowly .225 on the road. In short, they needed this.
</P>
<P>
   Penny obliged with a display of erratic control. He has walked
17 batters in 15 1/3 innings over his past three starts. His night
included a balk among the seven walks, a wild pitch, two hit
batters, three hits and six runs allowed He loaded the bases three
times in the first three innings before Marlins manager John Boles
had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves did a lot more of what they should have done the
previous game against Vladimir Nunez, the other pitcher along with
Penny that the Marlins acquired from Arizona last season for closer
Matt Mantei, and that's keep the bat on their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   After getting Veras out to start the game, Penny allowed the
next four batters to reach when he walked two and hit two,
including Jordan with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett was making his first appearance in Pro Player Stadium
since the Marlins traded him to Texas in August 1996. He became the
fourth former Marlins pitcher to beat them in the past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett allowed five baserunners in the first three innings but
kept the damage to a minimum. He struck out seven and limited the
Marlins to two runs over six innings, the longest he has lasted in
three starts for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
