<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-EDWARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GOVERNOR OF LOUISIANA GUILTY OF EXTORTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Edwin Edwards, the flamboyant former four-term
governor of Louisiana who has been the subject of 22 grand jury
investigations, was convicted Tuesday of doling out licenses to
operate riverboat casinos to the highest bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Four others, including Edwards' son and a co-defendant of former
Houston Mayor Fred Hofheinz in another extortion case, were also
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, 72, was found guilty by a federal jury in Baton Rouge,
La., on 17 of 26 counts of extortion and racketeering in connection
with Louisiana's gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contended he extorted hundreds of thousands of
dollars from former San Francisco 49ers football team owner Eddie
DeBartolo Jr. and other wealthy businessmen seeking riverboat
casino licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards told reporters the verdict was in keeping with Chinese
prophecy. ``If you sit by a river long enough, the dead bodies of
your enemies will float by you,'' he said. ``I suppose the feds sat
by the river long enough and here comes my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Edwards hatched the extortion plot in 1996, as
his final gubernatorial term wound to an end. He told applicants he
could use his influence to help them win licenses to operate
riverboat casinos _ for a price.
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards said he was acting as a consultant, and that the
money he collected was consulting fees.
</P>
<P>
   Lead prosecutor Jim Letten said Edwards' cronies made most of
the contacts to protect the high-profile politician. They
characterized Edwards' son, Stephen, as the manager of the
extortion plot. Andrew Martin, a former Edwards aide; Cecil Brown,
a cattleman and longtime friend; and contractor Bobby Johnson were
said to be the front men.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Martin were convicted on all counts, Johnson on nine
counts and Stephen Edwards on 18 of 23 counts.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors didn't totally see the plot as prosecutors presented it.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the state gambling board, Ecotry Fuller, was charged
with giving state Sen. Greg Tarver a copy of a confidential state
police report about casino-license applicants and lying about it to
a federal grand jury. He was acquitted, as was Tarver, who had been
accused of passing the report to Edwards for DeBartolo.
</P>
<P>
   But DeBartolo's testimony was the most damaging to Edwards.
Forced to give up ownership of his team because of his part in the
extortion plot, DeBartolo testified that Edwards demanded _ and
received_ $400,000 in a cash payoff for helping him get a casino
license.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo said Edwards picked up stacks of $100 bills near the
San Francisco airport and hid the cash in a wide money belt under
his shirt.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Frank Polozolo will reconvene the jury
Wednesday to decide what assets are subject to forfeiture.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards could be sentenced to more than 40 years in prison and
nearly $1 million in fines _ if the verdict sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations began April 24, but one of the 12 jurors was
dismissed last week for failing to deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   South Texas College of Law Professor Neil McCabe said continuing
deliberations after dismissing a juror is outrageous _ and grounds
for appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system is based on the belief that one person who has a
reasonable doubt can be a defendant's salvation,'' he said, ``but
in this case, if you have somebody who has a reasonable doubt, who
votes innocent when everyone else votes guilty, then throw that
juror out.''
</P>
<P>
   McCabe said holdout jurors must learn to play the game. ``Say,
`I have reasonable doubt, so convince me otherwise.' If you're the
holdout, don't say, `I won't listen and I won't talk.'''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jordan, U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of
Louisiana, did not return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards faces another influence-peddling trial in June.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a co-defendant with Hofheinz and Texas businessman Guy
Thompson in another extortion case.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Edwin Edwards, as well as public corruption
cases involving Hofheinz, former Texas prisons director James A.
``Andy'' Collins, and others stem from information given the FBI by
Texas con artists Michael and Patrick Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Polozolo allowed the government to keep secret the details
of prosecutors' financial and immunity agreements with the Graham
brothers, even though such information is normally disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge Lynn Hughes of Houston said the Justice
Department cannot keep such information from the public. He has
ordered depositions by the Grahams, Letten and FBI agent Geoffrey
Santini.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
