<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTFOODS-UNILEVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BESTFOODS, SPURNING SUITOR, HINTS THAT PRICE IS THE ISSUE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Bestfoods rejected a takeover offer from Unilever last
week, it seemed emphatic. The price was inadequate, it said,
adding, ``It is not opportune to consider a sale of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   But over the last few days, senior executives at Bestfoods have
talked with the company's largest investors, discussing their
reasons for turning down the all-cash offer of $66 a share, or
$18.4 billion. Rather than casting doubt on the potential cost
savings of the merger, as might be expected, they have said that
Unilever has underestimated the savings at $500 million when they
could be as much as $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been saying to shareholders that we believe there
would be substantially more synergies than Unilever is
describing,'' said a spokeswoman, Gale Griffin, confirming the
discussions. ``We are trying to explain to them our rationale.''
</P>
<P>
   The executives' position hints that Bestfoods would consider a
merger at the right price, stock analysts said Tuesday. ``It's an
unusual takeover defense, because it highlights the benefits of
consolidation,'' said John R. McMillin, a food-stocks analyst for
Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   With another $500 million in cost savings at stake, Bestfoods
executives could argue that their shareholders deserve a higher
price per share than Unilever has offered. ``Let's have some of it
go to the shareholders,'' McMillin said.
</P>
<P>
   One stock analyst who had doubted that the merger would occur,
given Bestfoods' earlier comments, changed his mind Tuesday after
learning of the company's talks with investors. ``They are playing
real hardball in order to get the highest cash price,'' said Daniel
Peris, the analyst, with Argus Research. ``As a Unilever
shareholder, I might be legitimately concerned, because although
the prospects of synergies are great, rarely do these megamergers
work as well as they are planned, either on the cost side or the
growth side.''
</P>
<P>
   The union of Bestfoods and Unilever would create the largest
food and household products company in the world, with brands like
Knorr, Skippy and Hellmann's lining up alongside Wish-Bone, Dove
and Ragu. Unilever, which is also in the middle of a restructuring
designed to shed some of its less-vibrant brands and stimulate
better growth, announced plans last month to buy Ben &AMP; Jerry's
Homemade for $326 million and Slim-Fast for $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Peris said he remained concerned about what a merger with
Bestfoods would do for both sides, as well as the global effects.
``Bestfoods and Unilever are similar in their international
strength,'' he said, ``and a merger or acquisition would take
international distribution out of the system. It is more useful to
have a U.S. company plugged into Bestfoods' distribution than to
have Unilever take out or duplicate that distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Little progress has been reported by either side since the
Bestfoods board voted to reject Unilever's bid a week ago. On
Monday, Unilever said a conversation had taken place between that
company's chairmen, Niall FitzGerald and Antony Burgmans, and
Charles R. Shoemate, the chairman and chief executive of Bestfoods.
A spokesman called the conversation ``businesslike,'' and said it
was intended to open talks between the companies.
</P>
<P>
   FitzGerald and Shoemate are scheduled to speak, about three and
a half hours apart, at a conference for investors being hosted by
Goldman, Sachs next week. Goldman is advising Unilever in the deal,
while Bestfoods is represented by Merrill Lynch and Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever is scheduled to announce its first-quarter earnings
Wednesday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
