<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0479 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BRIDGE-CLOSING-KAN &LR;      05-09 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-CLOSING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN ERRORS, POOR COMMUNICATION CITED IN KANSAS BRIDGE CLOSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Design errors, along with lack of
communication between the design and construction teams, led to
problems that forced the closing of the 151st Street bridge in
Olathe, Kan., a consultant's report says.
</P>
<P>
   The report indicates that a lack of oversight also led to damage
to the newly built bridge, and that some of the errors probably
could have been caught by a thorough review of the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of such a review constituted a failure to follow good
engineering practices, according to the report, which the Kansas
Department of Transportation released this week.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge stretches across Interstate 35 and makes up a key
interchange providing access to the Great Mall of the Great Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge was finished in 1995 and cost $3.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   It was closed last month for $3.8 million in repairs because the
abutments supporting the ends of the bridge had shifted a few
inches, causing extensive damage. Engineers are concerned that the
bridge might not be able to handle normal stresses if the abutments
continue to move.
</P>
<P>
   According to an investigation by the Seattle office of the
Nielsen-Wurster Group, a national management consulting and dispute
resolution firm, TranSystems Corp. of Kansas City should be
responsible for $2.3 million of the repair costs.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen-Wurster was hired by the Kansas Department of
Transportation. The group says the abutments failed because, among
other things, parts of the bridge were designed poorly and
inappropriate soils were used when embankments supporting the
abutments where built.
</P>
<P>
   JBM Engineers &AMP; Planners and Boyd Brown Stude &AMP; Cambern designed
the bridge and interchange. The two companies, along with a third
firm, merged in 1995 to form TranSystems.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Weatherford, TranSystems office manager, said that he had
seen the report but that a contract the company had with the
Transportation Department prohibited him from commenting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is typical in this type of contract,'' Weatherford said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also criticized APAC-Kansas Inc. Wilkerson-Maxwell
Division of Kansas City, Kan.; GeoSystems Engineering Inc. of
Lenexa, Kan.; and the Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   The report said APAC-Kansas, the contractor that built the
bridge, should pay $394,462 of the repair costs; GeoSystems, which
did soil testing, should pay $12,521; and the Transportation
Department should pay $495,432.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to APAC-Kansas were not returned Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wendland, engineering manager with GeoSystems, said the
company had received a copy of the report and had no comment at
this time.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Matthews, a spokesman for the Transportation Department,
said the consultant's report would be used to negotiate an
agreement on how the repair costs would be shared.
</P>
<P>
   He said the department hoped an amicable solution would be
reached without litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews said the state considered the report final and
supported its findings. The report said highway officials failed to
catch the design problems and did not properly administer the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to take our licks,'' Matthews said. ``The
oversight was ours, and they dinged us for not fulfilling that
role. The report, however, found that we were not entirely
responsible for the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The report holds Olathe responsible for $552,436 of repair
costs. While Nielsen-Wurster did not find Olathe at fault for any
of the problems, it said that Olathe should pay for some of the
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bridge had been constructed in a manner best fitting
the subsurface conditions at the site, the original construction
cost of the bridge would have been greater,'' according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen-Wurster concluded that Olathe should be responsible for
those costs because it was sharing the original cost of the bridge
with the Transportation Department. The report said that Olathe was
responsible for 80 percent of the overall costs and that the
Transportation Department was responsible for the rest, up to a set
limit.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department maintains that the limit has been
exceeded.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Biery, public works director for Olathe, said the city had
not had a chance to completely review the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was preliminary yet,'' Biery said Monday. ``We
have not had a chance to formulate our full response yet. We also
have not met with our attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   Biery expressed concerns that the city was held responsible for
some of the repair costs. He said the Transportation Department
paid 100 percent of the costs associated with the bridge. He said
Olathe was responsible only for the roadways leading up to it.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Tuesday, Biery said he had nothing to add.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, these are the main errors made in
construction:
</P>
<P>
   - Steel pilings supporting the east abutment were not driven
deep enough to reach bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   GeoSystems' soil and geology tests showed that the site had clay
overlying shale and then limestone. GeoSystems recommended that the
pilings be driven all the way down to the limestone.
</P>
<P>
   In the design, however, the companies that later merged to
become TranSystems used the wrong elevation for the pilings for the
east abutment. Thus, those pilings were resting on shale, which
would not be expected to support the structure adequately.
</P>
<P>
   - The plans failed to specify the use of special soil that would
not expand or shift as much as clay to build the bridge's
embankments. GeoSystems' report had indicated that such special
soil should be used. But the Nielsen-Wurster report said GeoSystems
did not communicate its concerns strongly enough.
</P>
<P>
   The wrong soil was used to build the embankments leading up to
the abutments. When Transportation Department tests showed that the
wrong fill was used, the department did not order APAC-Kansas to
replace it.
</P>
<P>
   - GeoSystems was not asked to review the final plans, despite
specifically requesting to do so. Moreover, the Transportation
Department did not receive a copy of the soil testings until 1993,
nearly four years after they were completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the (errors) would likely have been caught by
a geotechnical review of the plans prior to issuance for
construction,'' the report said. ``Apparently, neither GeoSystems
nor KDOT (Department of Transportation) personnel were requested to
perform such a review.''
</P>
<P>
   - In construction, Transportation Department officials
discovered that the storm drainage system did not adequately handle
surface water from the bridge. Transportation officials made
changes to correct the problems, but those changes were not enough
to prevent storm water from eroding soil supporting the abutments.
</P>
<P>
   - It is thought that the east abutment started to settle in
construction. That movement was not recognized as settling at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, this was thought to be a survey bust (error); but
in retrospect on further review by the surveyor, it seems likely
that this was an early reflection of the settlement of the fill
and/or abutment,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   - Before completion of the bridge, the embankment leading up the
west abutment failed. APAC-Kansas fixed the embankment, but
Transportation Department crews had to repair the embankment again
after construction. At that time, the crews may have damaged the
drainage system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nielsen-Wurster finds that the current situation with the
151st Street bridge is due to a number of adverse circumstances and
irregularities in the design and construction process,'' the report
said. ``The common factor among the majority of these problems is
the poor communication between and among the design and
construction teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
