<HEADER>
A0490 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-LOBBYIST-CLOUT-KAN &LR;      05-09 2071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBYIST-CLOUT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYIST WIELDS ENORMOUS POWER IN JEFFERSON CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ The Senate debate had bogged down over how
to restrict smoking in the Capitol hallways when Sen. Danny Staples
offered a compromise that would limit the inconvenience to
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   A smoking area, Staples suggested, should be designated wherever
lobbyist John Britton was standing. The proposal passed easily.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of the mobile smoking area was a good-natured jab
at Britton, the chain-smoking dean of the Capitol lobbyist corps.
But it also illustrates the deference that lawmakers extend to
Britton, whose personal connections, powerful clients and
reputation as a kingmaker make him one of the most influential
people in Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call him `Mr. Britton,' '' said Sen. Joe Maxwell, a Mexico
Democrat now running for lieutenant governor. ``He really is an
awesome presence.''
</P>
<P>
   His influence is evident as this year's legislative session
enters its critical final days. Last week, when a House panel
gutted an effort to toughen Missouri's drunken driving laws, the
first reaction from the bill's supporters was the muttered phrase:
``It's Britton's people.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton, who has tended to the legislative interests of
Anheuser-Busch Inc. for 35 years, is often credited with derailing
any proposal that might put a crimp in beer sales.
</P>
<P>
   But Britton's fingerprints also can be found on legislation
ranging from taxes on cigarettes and deposits on bottles to funding
for arts groups and elimination of blue laws. To many people, he
embodies how and why things get done in Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   He downplays his own role with a long pull on his cigarette, a
dismissive flick of the ash and an overly modest self-assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looked at as an abrasive, garrulous old man who at one
time might have had some charm that has become somewhat
tarnished,'' Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 40 years lobbying the Missouri legislature,
Britton has achieved a rarefied status: He has been at turns
friend, adviser, mentor and sometimes antagonist to two generations
of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the original lobbyists in Missouri,'' said Bob
Johnson, a former state senator from Lee's Summit and now a
lobbyist who once worked for Britton. ``Since he didn't have a lot
of peers, he set the definition of what a successful lobbyist
was.''
</P>
<P>
   A major source of gifts and campaign contributions to his
allies, Britton can also be a bitter adversary who has financed
challengers to run against lawmakers who cross him. And for many
years, Britton helped select and nurture upcoming legislative
leaders _ favors that serve him well when proposals that affect his
clients hang in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   That combination of important connections and raw political
power has given Britton a reputation bordering on the mythical. And
each victory serves to burnish his standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is responsible for Missouri having no deposit on bottles
and cans,'' said Republican Sen. Franc Flotron of St. Louis County.
``They don't even try (any more). They know they would lose. You
put a few heads on spikes outside your office and it gets
results.''  &LR; brkstr:I I I
</P>
<P>
   Britton seems to specialize in working on behalf of
organizations engaged in the legal vices: His clients have included
the Tobacco Institute, Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Co., Station
Casinos, horse racing interests and the Missouri Wine &AMP; Spirits
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose those are the groups most under attack and thought
they needed someone,'' Britton said. ``We had the reputation that
we would fight those types of battles. And remember, most of our
clients we have had for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton keeps his presence known by spending liberally and
keeping anyone who asks supplied with beer.
</P>
<P>
   From January 1994 to January 2000, Britton and three associates
reported spending $193,694 on beer, meals, receptions, tickets and
other gifts for lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Alliance for Campaign Reform found that
Anheuser-Busch was the second-largest contributor to legislative
campaigns in 1998, with donations of $82,100. Britton said he will
direct about $75,000 in Anheuser-Busch contributions to legislative
candidates this year.
</P>
<P>
   He can be so effective on behalf of controversial clients that
several lawmakers refer to him only half facetiously as a force for
evil. But that takes into account only part of Britton's efforts.
He has lobbied on behalf of the Kansas City and St. Louis
symphonies and helped pass legislation that created the community
college system. He also has lobbied to improve vocational education
for the disabled and served as an officer of the Missouri Mental
Health Association.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his influence stems from a genuine affection for him
among many lawmakers, who describe him as thoughtful and
philosophical. He sprinkles his conversations with references to
Ralph Waldo Emerson, John Stuart Mill and Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   He is so confident in his role that he often berates legislators
who go against him. Lawmakers talk about watching as House members
cringe and change their votes when Britton yells at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had arrived in the Senate when he started screaming
at me in the hall,'' recalled Flotron, who served six years in the
House before moving to the Senate in 1988. ``And I knew I was a
senator when I screamed back. He's the only one with the nerve to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 74, Britton is still an irascible, forceful personality. Yet
his bald pate, white beard and gravely voice lend him an avuncular
quality _ befitting a man with five children and four stepchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Britton's contradictions might be the key to his success at
representing such a disparate group of clients.
</P>
<P>
   He is a four-pack-a-day smoker who says if he paid attention to
health statistics, he should be dead. A libertarian by nature, he
nonetheless helped gather initial support for the Missouri Arts
Council.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most ironic is this: The chief lobbyist for the
world's largest brewer is an alcoholic, though he has been sober
for more than four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an ex-drunk,'' Britton said emphatically. ``Don't make it
sound fancier than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that others might see his life's work as a bit
hypocritical. So he turns to a paraphrase of Emerson:
</P>
<P>
   ``Foolish consistencies,'' Britton said, ``are the hobgoblins
that haunt the minds of petty politicians, philosophers and
divines. Say what you believe today in words as hard as
cannonballs, although you may change tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   On his work for Anheuser-Busch, Britton said simply: ``There is
nothing intrinsically evil about alcohol.''  &LR; brkstr:I I I
</P>
<P>
   John Frederick Britton was born Oct. 23, 1925, in Pennsylvania,
but his family moved to the Boston area in the 1930s _ one step
ahead of the rent collector, he said. During World War II he
volunteered for the military and became a paratrooper with the
101st Airborne Division in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was glamorous and it was where the tough guys
went,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the war he attended Harvard University, where he graduated
in 1949 with a classical education that focused on the humanities.
He eventually joined an advertising firm in New York. It was the
growth industry of the day, but his ``very short and abysmal career
was fraught with failure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't belong there,'' he remembered. ``It was very
structured and I wasn't a conformist. I didn't like them and they
didn't like me.''
</P>
<P>
   After about 18 months, his father got him a job setting pavement
on a road construction crew in Nebraska. The Harvard grad learned a
bit of humility, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He married his wife, Kate, in 1954 and soon landed a job with
the Nebraska Highway Department, writing pamphlets and speeches for
department officials. In 1957, he moved to Jefferson City as
executive director of the Missouri Bituminous Contractors
Association, which represented about a dozen road contractors eager
to cash in on the road-building boom spawned by the launching of
the interstate highway system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, however, the association disbanded and Britton joined
the staff of Attorney General Thomas Eagleton. When Eagleton was
elected lieutenant governor the next year, Britton decided to hang
out his shingle as a hired lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   As a parting gift, Eagleton, who had worked for Anheuser-Busch,
took Britton to meet company chairman August A. ``Gussie'' Busch
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a two-minute interview and he hired me,'' Britton said.
Anheuser-Busch became his first client.  &LR; brkstr:I I I
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, two lawmakers, including then-Rep. Wayne
Goode of St. Louis County, were rabbit hunting near Britton's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had all these dead rabbits as they went past my house and
asked Kate to cook them,'' Britton said. ``They invited their
friends out to the house. One of the guests said, `Hey, next
Monday, we'll bring you some Lebanese food from St. Louis.' The
following week someone brought food from another part of state.
After about four weeks, someone said, `Why don't you just cook
dinner for us?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That started a 15-year tradition where a bipartisan group of
House and Senate leaders would eat at Britton's house almost every
Monday night during the legislative session. Soon, Britton started
inviting young lawmakers whom he thought had leadership potential
to join the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very select group,'' said Sen. Jim Mathewson, a
Sedalia Democrat who became president pro tem from 1989 to 1996.
``If you were invited, it was a real honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance to socialize with leadership immediately put
ambitious legislators in Britton's debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more difficult to vote against a friend than
against someone you don't know,'' Mathewson said. ``It was a lot
like voting against someone back home, because you knew you were
going to have to justify it.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton's care and feeding of lawmakers sometimes began before
they took office and continued long after. Mathewson said he met
Britton during his first campaign for a House seat in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to Sedalia just to say hello,'' Mathewson said. ``He
knew my wife's name, kids' names and my political connections. It
was a personal conversation about who I was, not who he was.''
</P>
<P>
   But he could also be vengeful.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Britton had a run-in with then-Rep. Jerry Howard of
Dexter over a bill about chiropractors. Howard criticized Britton
on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ronnie DePasco, a Kansas City Democrat who was elected to
the House that year, said Britton exacted his revenge by
bankrolling a candidate to run against Howard. Britton acknowledged
financing the campaign and working the phones on behalf of Howard's
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Howard lost a close election and was out of the legislature for
11 years before getting back into politics. He is now a state
senator.
</P>
<P>
   Britton was close to House Speaker Kenneth Rothman throughout
the late 1970s. But in 1980, Britton made one of his few missteps:
He backed then-Rep. Joe Holt when the House elected Bob Griffin
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   DePasco, one of the original ``Dirty Dozen'' Griffin supporters,
said Britton was on the outs for the first several of Griffin's 15
years as speaker. That's when he turned over much of his House
lobbying to Jennifer Durham Riks, who has been his partner since
1978.  &LR; brkstr:I I I
</P>
<P>
   After 43 years in the Capitol, Britton still arrives early to
stalk the hallways outside the Senate chamber, swapping stories and
chatting up key lawmakers and legislative staffers.
</P>
<P>
   To many younger lawmakers, Britton's in-your-face lobbying style
can be off-putting, lawmakers and other lobbyists said. Some
lawmakers predict Britton will retire after term limits begin to
take effect in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Britton acknowledges that, as he has grown older than most
lawmakers, his image has suffered a bit. He has more difficulty
identifying with the backgrounds and outlook of the younger
members. But he says he can't see himself taking a course on
medieval poetry at Lincoln University and his eyesight has grown
too bad to shoot pool any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else I'd do,'' Britton said. ``I have no
plans to retire unless I get lung cancer, I get hit by a truck or I
become so bad at this that I have to (quit). I'll be doing this
until I die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
