<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Are you the multimillionaire?
 &HT;    By Gita Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1, 2, 4, 12, 33, 37. Money ball: 4
</P>
<P>
   That's the ticket! Lottery officials in seven participating Big
Game states worked into the wee hours making their lists and
checking them twice to see whether somebody won the $350 million
jackpot that has been growing since March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Is he or she out there right now, getting a new, unlisted phone
number, or will the jackpot grow, yet again? The answer was not
expected until about 5 a.m. Wednesday, and Georgia Lottery Corp.
officials planned to put the results online by 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   A sole winner would receive either $8.9 million a year for 26
years or a one-time payment of $114 million after taxes. Those
numbers are based on Georgia state taxes, and would change slightly
if the winner bought the ticket in another state.
</P>
<P>
   But whether one person won the whole enchilada, or split it
several ways, chances are excellent that somewhere in Georgia are
several players who matched five white balls to win $150,000 or who
correctly picked four white balls plus the gold Big Money Ball to
win $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
