<SLUG> BC-RAILROAD-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTION RESTS IN RAILROAD KILLER TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (editors: Joye Carter is cq) 
 
By LISA TEACHEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The man who arrested admitted serial killer Angel
Maturino Resendiz at the Mexican border denied Tuesday that he
promised the fugitive's family anything for their help in
persuading him to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   During the second day of Maturino Resendiz's capital murder
trial, the defense team grilled Texas Ranger Drew Carter in an
effort to show he had tricked the Mexican national into
surrendering in U.S. territory. The Mexican government does not
allow the extradition of citizens who face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Carter insisted he had been forthright with the family and had
explained that Maturino Resendiz could get the death penalty if
convicted of murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't care where he was caught, as long as the
killing stopped,'' Carter testified.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution rested its case after calling 10 witnesses on
Tuesday, including Carter, the Harris County medical examiner and a
DNA expert.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, 40, has pleaded not guilty by reason of
insanity to the December 1998 slaying and rape of Dr. Claudia
Benton at her West University Place home near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He has admitted killing Benton and eight other people _ five in
Texas, two in Illinois and one in Kentucky _ while riding railcars
cross-country during a two-year rampage.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Department of Public Safety's elite
investigative team, Carter was asked by West University police to
help investigate the case.
</P>
<P>
   During questioning by prosecutor Devon Anderson, Carter said he
tracked down the wanted man's sister, Manuela Karkiewicz, in New
Mexico. After several meetings, she called Carter on July 11,
saying her brother would surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``She indicated that there might be some stipulations,'' Carter
told the jury. ``I told her we needed to know what they were to see
if we could do anything about them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said she had told him the family wanted him to get an
independent psychiatric evaluation and to be allowed to visit him
while he was in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said she also wanted to know if the family could get any
of the reward money and if there were restrictions on how the
family could use the money.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he could not guarantee anything but would write a
letter to Harris County officials outlining the demands.
</P>
<P>
   After District Attorney John B. Holmes Jr. approved the jail
visits and mental evaluations in writing, Karkiewicz arranged for
Carter to meet Maturino Resendiz on July 13 at an international
bridge connecting El Paso, Texas, and Ciudad Juarez, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he shook hands with Maturino Resendiz, allowed him
to hug his sister, then handcuffed him and brought him back.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Karkiewicz has received $86,000 of the reward money and
is eligible for another $40,000 if her brother is convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Allen Tanner said Carter had only befriended
the sister as a ruse, especially since other agencies had been
``rough with her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you lead her to believe: `Manuela you help us, I'll help
your brother'?'' Tanner asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sir,'' Carter replied.
</P>
<P>
   The ranger acknowledged that he had prayed with the family and
had offered to help answer any questions, but that he was always
upfront with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you were in New Mexico and Manuela was making demands,
did she also say she wanted her brother to be treated humanely?''
Tanner asked.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he never used the word ``humane'' in the
discussions, telling Karkiewicz only that Maturino Resendiz would
receive ``fair treatment under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked me specifically about the death penalty,'' Carter
testified. ``I informed her that the crime her brother was
suspected of was a capital crime in Texas and the death penalty was
an option that could be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was aware of that and even made the comment that it was
better to have capital punishment than rot in jail your whole
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Harris County Medical Examiner Joye Carter
testified that Benton had broken her right arm struggling for her
life while being bludgeoned, stabbed and then raped.
</P>
<P>
   Benton's head was hit 19 times with a bronze statuette and she
was stabbed three times in the back with such force that the
kitchen knife used pierced her chest completely. Both lungs were
punctured.
</P>
<P>
   As she lay face down on a bedroom floor, her head covered in a
plastic bag, Benton was sexually assaulted. Carter said it could
not be determined if she was still alive when the rape occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Semen samples collected from the scene were linked to Maturino
Resendiz, said Edith Emrick, a DNA analyzer for the Texas
Department of Public Safety. She said the chance that the semen
came from someone other than Maturino Resendiz was one in more than
six billion.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is scheduled to begin arguing its case Wednesday.
During opening statements, Tanner told the jury Maturino Resendiz
had killed all nine people, but that he was insane at the time and
had turned himself in to seek treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
