<P>
   (NYT37) LIBBY, Mont. -- May 9, 2000 -- MONT-ASBESTOS-3 -- Libby
has been left reeling from the medical and financial consequences
of a 67-year mining operation run by W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. Among the
area's residents who have developed asbestosis is Alice Priest, who
relies on an oxygen supply to breathe. Her husband, who worked in
the Grace mine, died of lung cancer. (Monica Almeida/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) LIBBY, Mont. -- May 9, 2000 -- MONT-ASBESTOS-2 -- An EPA
soil-sampling stick marks a suspected ``hot spot'' near the old
W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. processing plant. In recent months, tests have
revealed that the 21-acre site here is contaminated by a toxic form
of asbestos called tremolite - the result of years in which Grace
used the site as a transport center for the vermiculite ore the
company mined nearby. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) LIBBY, Mont. -- May 9, 2000 -- MONT-ASBESTOS-1 -- Libby
has been left reeling from the medical and financial consequences
of a 67-year mining operation. In recent months, tests have
revealed that a 21-acre site along the Kootenai River here is
contaminated by a toxic form of asbestos called tremolite - the
result of years in which W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. used the site as a
transport center for the vermiculite ore the company mined nearby.
(Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
