<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- May 9, 2000 -- GORE -- Vice President Al
Gore, at a White House rally Tuesday in support of a trade bill
with China, paid tribute to Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota. In
much the same way as he has been wooing Sen. John McCain's
supporters, Gore has also been going after the Independent party
backers of Ventura. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) ATLANTA -- May 9, 2000 -- BUSH-MCCAIN --- Following a
roundtable discussion with High Point Elementary School teachers on
Tuesday, Gov. George W. Bush stops to sign 9-year-old Susan
Boynton's bandage. Citing common goals and shared values, Sen. John
McCain at last endorsed Bush on Tuesday and pledged to help the de
facto Republican presidential nominee achieve what McCain had
wanted so badly for himself: a seat in the Oval Office. (Ben
Gray/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
HISTORIC-RECREATION-MUSIC -- The illusion - or is it delusion? - of
historical recreation onstage is being addressed in Carlo Gozzi's
``Green Bird'' at the Cort Theater, where 18th-century theater
enters into heavy negotiation with the present. Derek Smith, left,
and Andrew Weems in Julie Taymor's production of ``The Green
Bird.'' (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
CHAIRS-ANTIQUES -- Gilbert Rohde's 1938 plastic chair is in
``American Modern, 1925-1940'' at the Metropolitan Museum. The
chair - publicized during the 1939 World's Fair - represented a
futuristic approach to furniture design, using Plexiglas, then a
new acrylic plastic made by the chemical company Rohm and Haas, for
whom Rohde worked as a consultant. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
MTV-DOCUMENTARIES-TV-2 -- Dave Sirulnick is in charge of MTV's
documentary operations. This year, producers at MTV will make from
50 to 75 television documentaries. Many will be music-relatedm but
roughly a third of the documentaries tackle social problems that
affect younger people: drug addiction, school violence, sexually
transmitted disease. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
MTV-DOCUMENTARIES-TV-1 -- Lauren Lazin, vice president of MTV news
and documentaries, at the MTV offices in Times Square. This year,
