<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- May 9, 2000 -- GORE -- Vice President Al
Gore, at a White House rally Tuesday in support of a trade bill
with China, paid tribute to Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota. In
much the same way as he has been wooing Sen. John McCain's
supporters, Gore has also been going after the Independent party
backers of Ventura. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) ATLANTA -- May 9, 2000 -- BUSH-MCCAIN --- Following a
roundtable discussion with High Point Elementary School teachers on
Tuesday, Gov. George W. Bush stops to sign 9-year-old Susan
Boynton's bandage. Citing common goals and shared values, Sen. John
McCain at last endorsed Bush on Tuesday and pledged to help the de
facto Republican presidential nominee achieve what McCain had
wanted so badly for himself: a seat in the Oval Office. (Ben
Gray/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
HISTORIC-RECREATION-MUSIC -- The illusion - or is it delusion? - of
historical recreation onstage is being addressed in Carlo Gozzi's
``Green Bird'' at the Cort Theater, where 18th-century theater
enters into heavy negotiation with the present. Derek Smith, left,
and Andrew Weems in Julie Taymor's production of ``The Green
Bird.'' (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
CHAIRS-ANTIQUES -- Gilbert Rohde's 1938 plastic chair is in
``American Modern, 1925-1940'' at the Metropolitan Museum. The
chair - publicized during the 1939 World's Fair - represented a
futuristic approach to furniture design, using Plexiglas, then a
new acrylic plastic made by the chemical company Rohm and Haas, for
whom Rohde worked as a consultant. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
MTV-DOCUMENTARIES-TV-2 -- Dave Sirulnick is in charge of MTV's
documentary operations. This year, producers at MTV will make from
50 to 75 television documentaries. Many will be music-relatedm but
roughly a third of the documentaries tackle social problems that
affect younger people: drug addiction, school violence, sexually
transmitted disease. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
MTV-DOCUMENTARIES-TV-1 -- Lauren Lazin, vice president of MTV news
and documentaries, at the MTV offices in Times Square. This year,
producers at MTV will make from 50 to 75 television documentaries.
Many will be music-relatedm but roughly a third of the
documentaries tackle social problems that affect younger people:
drug addiction, school violence, sexually transmitted disease.
(Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
SIKANDER-ART -- Shahzia Sikander and her mural ``Chaman,'' veiled
in tissue, at the Whitney's Philip Morris gallery. While Western
viewers may find the allure of the exotic in her use of the imagery
and techniques of the miniature, at home in Pakistan her desire to
be trained in the tradition puzzled her teachers and fellow
students, who saw it as a something that would only impede her
creativity. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
TAUB-PIANO-MUSIC -- Robert Taub in his New York apartment. ``Every
printed edition is sterile compared to an autograph score,'' he
said. ``The calligraphy is imbued with the composer's emotion while
rehearing the music in the process of writing it down.'' Part of
Beethoven's autograph manuscript of the first movement of the
``Moonlight'' Sonata, below, which Taub will perform Friday night
in a rare piano recital in the Coolidge Auditorium at the Library
of Congress in Washington. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
CARLSON-DANCE -- The choreographer Ann Carlson adjusting the
costume of Lara Hayes, who plays the newspaper girl in Carlson's
``Night Light.'' (Ruby Washington/The New York Times) The
performance piece recreates an 1895 photograph by Alice Austen,
below, among other scenes. (Staten Island Historical Society/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- May 9, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
SCHILLER-THEATER-B&AMP;W -- To literate Europeans of the 19th century,
the poet, playwright and historian Friedrich von Schiller
(1759-1805) ranked right up with Shakespeare. Today, even in his
native Germany, Schiller's works for the stage survive mostly as
refracted through the operas of Rossini, Verdi and Tchaikovsky - a
mere handful of the dozens their revolutionary idealism inspired.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) JERUSALEM -- May 9, 2000 -- ISRAEL-INDEPENDENCE --
Israel kicked off celebrations marking the 52nd anniversary of its
founding Tuesday with a ceremony at Jerusalem's Mount Herzl.
Representatives of various branches of Israeli society lit twelve
flaming torches symbolizing the biblical twelve tribes of Israel.
(Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LOS ANGELES -- May 9, 2000 -- TVNOTES -- David
Duchovny's future with ``The X-Files'' is in doubt. The most likely
outcome is that the show will be back but not for a full season.
Gillain Anderson's character, Scully, may have a different partner
for much of the season. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LONDON -- May 9, 2000 -- TATE-MODERN -- A sculpture by
Mario Merz at the Tate Modern, opening Friday in the former
Bankside power plant across the Thames from St. Paul's Cathedral.
The fashionable Swiss architects Jacques Herzog and Pierre de
Meuron have done the renovation of this behemoth - lovingly
preserving the brick exterior with the big chimney in the middle -
at a cost of $200 million. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- May 9, 2000 -- ME2CAM-COX -- If you're
concerned with the amount of time your child spends hunched over a
mouse or joystick playing computer games, you might want to take a
look at the Me2Cam Virtual Game System from Intel Play. Playing
with the Me2Cam probably won't give a child as much activity as
playing outdoors, but it's a lot more physical than most computer
games. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BETHLEHEM, West Bank -- May 9, 2000 --
PALESTINE-BUSINESS-2 -- The lobby of Bethlehem's Intercontinental
Hotel. Once a villa owned by an Ottoman merchant, the building, in
its century-long life has served as a school, a hospital, and a
tear-gassed battleground between Israeli security forces and
rock-throwing Palestinian youths. It is now the first five-star
hotel owned and operated by Palestinians on Palestinian-governed
territory. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BETHLEHEM, West Bank -- May 9, 2000 --
PALESTINE-BUSINESS-1 -- Two school girls on their way home to the
nearby Aida refugee camp stand in front of the Intercontinental
Hotel. The villa, once owned by an Ottoman merchant and in its
century-long life has also served as a school, a hospital, and a
tear-gassed battleground between Israeli security forces and
rock-throwing Palestinian youths, is now the first five-star hotel
owned and operated by Palestinians on Palestinian-governed
territory. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) YAROSLAVL, Russia -- May 9, 2000 -- RUSSIAN-ANIMATOR --
The Russian artist Alexander Petrov hand-painted some 29,000 frames
on glass to make his 22-minute animated film, ``The Old Man and the
Sea,'' which won an Oscar this year. At home in Yaroslavl, Petrov
is still puzzling over how he ended up a national hero. ``In the
eyes of simple people, it is a victory for all of Russia, something
like a prize for football, or a sports prize,'' said Petrov, 42.
(Jacqueline Mia Foster/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MALVERN, Pa. -- May 9, 2000 -- SNAPSHOT-WORKPLACE-2 --
Office workers everywhere put up photos in their workspace that
helps define who they are and what motivates them. Jason Sehorn, a
client service representative at the Vanguard Group, a mutual fund
company, stands over photos of several heartthrobs in her cubicle
including 10 identical images of the soap opera actor Scott Reeves
which she uses as her screen-saver. Reeves provides her with
``motivation,'' she says. (Salvatore DiMarco Jr./The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MALVERN, Pa. -- May 9, 2000 -- SNAPSHOT-WORKPLACE-1 --
Executives and office workers everywhere put up photos that say,
``This is what I am all about.'' Psychologists and sociologists,
among others, see great import in their choices. Pictures in the
office of John J. Brennan are said to portray his status as chief
at the Vanguard Group, the big mutual fund company with more than
$550 billion under management. (Salvatore DiMarco Jr./The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- BIG-TOP -- A worker with the
Big Apple Circus laces up the Big Top tent in Queens, Monday, for
performances running May 11 through May 21. The Big Apple Circus is
a not-for-profit performing arts institution founded in 1977
designed to provide audiences with the intimate and interactive
environment of a one-ring circus under a Big Top tent. The tent,
made of PVC fabric in Bordeaux, France, is 138 feet in diameter and
stands 52 feet at highest point. (Librado Romero/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- NY-SAFIR-HEALTH -- New York
Police Commissioner Howard Safir, right, announced Tuesday that he
has prostate cancer. His good friend, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who
was diagnosed with the same disease last month, and Safir's wife
Carol, were at his side as he made the announcement. (Richard
Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- May 9, 2000 -- WINE-BOTTLE-OPENER -- Opening
a bottle of wine usually entails lots of yanking and tugging at a
stubborn cork that often breaks in the process. The Rabbit
corkscrew changes that with a soft rubber coating on its handles
and lever, making it easier to grip. (Tony Cenicola/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- May 9, 2000 -- OSPREY-CRASH -- Mechanical
failure has been ruled out as a cause of last month's MV-22 Osprey
crash that killed 19 Marines, and the remaining aircraft in the
fleet will resume flying this month, officials announced Monday.
Lt. Gen. Fred McCorkle, of the U.S. Marine Corps, during a news
conference at the Pentagon, Monday. (Justin Lane/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- RESTAURANT-SMELLS -- Over the
past few decades, aroma, especially in better restaurants, has
slowly disappeared. And now as more ambitious restaurants open by
the minute, an aroma-free environment has become something of a
norm. Still, some eateries are bucking the trend: Peasant in SoHo
pumps in cooking aromas from its wood-fired oven. (Thomas
Dallal/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- May 9, 2000 -- PORTIONS-EATING-WELL -- From
Lunchables to Fritos, portion sizes are getting bigger and
information is getting murkier. In 1988, the original Lunchables,
left, was small and 340 calories. The Lunchables Mega Pack has a
lot more food, including candy and a drink, and is 640 to 780
calories, depending on whether you choose pizza or nachos. (Tony
Cenicola/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PERPIGNON, France -- May 9, 2000 -- WINE-TALK -- Chateau
de Jau was a pioneer of modern winemaking in the Roussillon region.
The area encompasses some 600,000 acres of vines, 50 percent more
than in all the United States, and stretches roughly from
Carcassonne in the west to Perpignan in the south and Montpellier
in the east. (Martin Sinkoff Wines/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) JERSEY CITY, N.J. -- May 9, 2000 -- LOTTERY -- Millions
of Americans packed gas stations and stores in seven states Tuesday
in a last-minute rush to buy tickets for a $350-million lottery
jackpot -- the largest in history. In Jersey City, just outside the
entrance to the Path train to Manhattan, business was brisk Tuesday
morning. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 9, 2000 -- U.S.-CHINA-TRADE --
President Clinton, flanked by predecessors Ford and Carter, walk
towards the East Room of the White House for a gathering of past
and present administration officials to press Congress to grant
permanent normal trade relations to China, Tuesday. In the
background are James Baker, former Reagan chief-of-staff, secretary
of state and treasury under Reagan, Henry Kissinger, natinal
security advisor and secretary of state under Presidents Nixon and
Ford, Vice President Al Gore and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- May 9, 2000 -- TECHNO-TERADYNE --George
Chamillard, head of Teradyne, seen past equipment that tests
computer chips. ``We've got to build something that works seven
days, 24 hours, for 10 years, with very little human
intervention,'' says Chamillard about his products. (Dominic
Chavez/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEWTON, Mass. -- May 9, 2000 -- PROFILE-BASSUK-BOS -- At
age 55, Ellen Bassuk, seen with her dog Max, collects causes the
way many baby boomers collect hedge funds. ``Money doesn't motivate
me,'' she says. ``The defining principle of my life has to do with
community service.'' Yet even Bassuk, Harvard-educated physician
and single mother, needs time away from the miseries of the world.
Much of that time is spent walking her dogs. (Dominic Chavez/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- NY-AUCTION -- Christie's
emloyees take telephone bids Monday night for Caillebotte's ``Man
on the Balcony, Boulevard Haussmann,'' which sold for $14.3
million. Simon de Pury, the former chairman of Sotheby's in Europe,
who is now a private dealer and was bidding on behalf of a
collector, was the winning bidder. The price was a record for
Caillebotte, seven times his previous record of $2 million, set at
Christie's in London in 1989 at the height of the market. (Michelle
V. Agins/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
