<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 05/09/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) UNDATED -- May 9, 2000 -- CHRISTIES-AUCTION -- ``Still
Life With Tulips,'' a 1932 portrait by Picasso of his mistress,
Marie-Therese Walter, sold for $28.6 million Tuesday night at
Christie's. While that work brought the highest price, Picassos of
different styles and dates accounted for the four top lots in an
auction of 20th-century art that several experts described as hot
and cold. (Christie's New York/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- May 9, 2000 -- NY-MRS-CLINTON-GUNS -- In a
speech to the Newspaper Association of America in Manhattan on
Tuesday, Hillary Clinton supported gun licensing and registration.
``The moms who are marching in Washington this Sunday have it
right: we have to license and register all handguns,'' said the
first lady, who plans to participate in the march. (Don Hogan
Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) UNIONDALE, N.Y. -- May 9, 2000 -- NY-NASSAU-BAILOUT --
Democrats in the Nassau County Legislature were cautiously
favorable toward Gov. George E. Pataki's proposed financial rescue
at a press conference Tuesday: from left, Patrick C. Williams,
Jeffrey W. Toback, Judith A. Jacobs, Roger H. Corbin, Joseph
Scannell, Lisanne G. Altmann and Craig M. Johnson. (Chester Higgins
Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) LIBBY, Mont. -- May 9, 2000 -- MONT-ASBESTOS-3 -- Libby
has been left reeling from the medical and financial consequences
of a 67-year mining operation run by W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. Among the
area's residents who have developed asbestosis is Alice Priest, who
relies on an oxygen supply to breathe. Her husband, who worked in
the Grace mine, died of lung cancer. (Monica Almeida/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) LIBBY, Mont. -- May 9, 2000 -- MONT-ASBESTOS-2 -- An EPA
soil-sampling stick marks a suspected ``hot spot'' near the old
W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. processing plant. In recent months, tests have
revealed that the 21-acre site here is contaminated by a toxic form
of asbestos called tremolite - the result of years in which Grace
used the site as a transport center for the vermiculite ore the
company mined nearby. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) LIBBY, Mont. -- May 9, 2000 -- MONT-ASBESTOS-1 -- Libby
has been left reeling from the medical and financial consequences
of a 67-year mining operation. In recent months, tests have
revealed that a 21-acre site along the Kootenai River here is
contaminated by a toxic form of asbestos called tremolite - the
result of years in which W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. used the site as a
transport center for the vermiculite ore the company mined nearby.
(Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) MIAMI -- May 9, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-3 -- Marcus
Camby of the New York Knicks driving on Alonzo Mourning of the
Miami Heat during the first half of Game 2 in the best-of-seven
Eastern Conference semifinals on Tuesday night. The Heat lead the
series 1-0. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) MIAMI -- May 9, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-2 -- Patrick
Ewing of the New York Knicks attempting a hook shot over Alonzo
