<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-STOCK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 QUIP CAUSES BLIP FOR EXCITEATHOME  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ExciteAtHome shares briefly soared 60 percent
Tuesday after a news report suggested that Comcast, the cable
television company, would be interested in buying a majority stake
in the Redwood City, Calif., Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   But ExciteAtHome's stock quickly tumbled back to earth after
observers said the remark, made by a Comcast executive during a
panel discussion, was intended as a joke. Three different sources
said a Bloomberg News reporter was mistaken in taking the comments
literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comcast is not making a bid to take over ExciteAtHome,'' said
ExciteAtHome spokeswoman Melissa Walia. A source close to Comcast
confirmed that the company has no plans to buy ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would have been especially surprising given that
Comcast and Cox Communications agreed in March to sell their stakes
in ExciteAtHome to AT&AMP;T for as much as $3 billion. AT&AMP;T spokesman
Steve Lang said the company is ``happy with the arrangement'' and
has no plans to modify the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Comcast President Brian Roberts still said he was bullish on
ExciteAtHome during a panel discussion at the National Cable
Television Association's annual meeting in New Orleans. He said the
company is still a `'strategic asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned to his counterpart from AT&AMP;T and jokingly said:
``If you want to flip the deal, we'd buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bloomberg News service, taking the remark seriously, quickly
dispatched a story headlined: ``Comcast President Interested in
AT&AMP;T's Excite Stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which closed Monday at $17.50, raced up to $28 in
heavy trading before the companies denied the story. Shares closed
at $19.94, up $2.44. ExciteAtHome was the second-most-actively
traded stock yesterday. Its shares had fallen 78 percent in the
past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Both AT&AMP;T and Comcast declined to comment on the Bloomberg
story. But privately, some people complained that Bloomberg did not
report the tone and context of the remarks, which would have made
it clear that Roberts was probably joking. The company also
dispatched the story before it had had a chance to ask any of the
companies to comment on the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   A Bloomberg spokesman, Chris Taylor, defended the story. ``It's
what he said, and no one is denying that,'' she said, adding that
Bloomberg was planning to post audio excerpts of the speech so that
``readers can decide for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also said that it is the news service's responsibility to
report what is said as fast as possible, since such comments can
potentially move the markets, and that the company considered it
more important to report the words ``rather than the
interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
