<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTROCUTION-NEBRASKA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGES' RULING COULD HELP END USE OF ELECTRIC CHAIR IN NEBRASKA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) If a three-judge panel convening Wednesday decides
Raymond Mata Jr. deserves life in prison for killing and
dismembering a 3-year-old boy, Mata's personal battle against
electrocution in Nebraska becomes moot.
</P>
<P>
   But if the panel votes for death, some legal experts predict
that the case could lead to the end of the electric chair in
Nebraska _ one of only two remaining states that mandate
electrocution for prisoners sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   Scotts Bluff County District Judge Robert Hippe ruled Monday in
connection with Mata's case that Nebraska's particular method of
electrocution _ four separate jolts of electricity _ amounts to
cruel and unusual punishment. Witnesses testified that the short
delays between jolts increase the chances the prisoner will suffer
excruciating pain.
</P>
<P>
   Hippe did not rule against the death penalty, per se. But his
ruling forces the state attorney general's office to assure the
court that Nebraska's method of execution ``removes the potential
for infliction of unnecessary pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska case is unusual in that his attorneys challenged
the Nebraska method of execution after Mata was convicted in
January, but before reaching the punishment phase. If the state
judicial panel Wednesday rules for the death penalty, the question
of how death should be carried out will likely continue. The state
attorney general's office has vowed to appeal any ruling declaring
the electric chair unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   If the panel rules Mata should get a life sentence, Hippe's
ruling will not be binding. However, Mata's attorneys believe it
will have implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think practically speaking, other inmates who are on death
row and other people who are charged with first-degree murder ...
their attorneys will (make similar claims to cruelty) knowing that
there was at least one favorable ruling from a well respected
district judge,'' said one of Mata's attorneys, Jim Mowbray.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Nebraska's first execution was in 1903. Eight men
had been hanged by 1913, when the state Legislature switched to
electrocution. Fifteen men have since died in Nebraska's electric
chair, the last on Dec. 2, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has not reviewed electrocution since New
York executed its first prisoner in the electric chair in 1890.
Electricity was the new technology of the day, and advocates were
eager to find novel applications for it.
</P>
<P>
   Only Nebraska and Alabama mandate electrocution for executions.
Georgia and Florida switched to lethal injection this year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida was pressured to abandon electrocution after witnesses
to a series of grisly executions questioned whether the condemned
prisoners were, for all practical purposes, tortured. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Nebraska and Alabama will likely abandon electrocution within a
year, speculates Fordham University law professor Deborah Denno,
who testified in the Florida case. Both state legislatures have
introduced lethal-injection measures in recent sessions, she said,
and the rarity of electrocution is, in itself, a viable argument
that it is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The last man to die in the electric chair was Robert Lee Tarver,
executed April 14 in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Tarver's attorney, Bryan Stevenson of the Equal Justice
Initiative in Montgomery, said he expects the Nebraska Legislature
would change its method of execution rather than be forced to
defend it before the U.S. Supreme Court. ``I've seen it happen in
other states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
