<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-SHORENSTEIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DIGERATI AND OTHERS PONDER NEW ECONOMY  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An all-star cast of luminaries from government,
technology and academia Tuesday gathered at a posh Portola Valley,
Calif., home to discuss Washington's policies toward the
much-vaunted ``New Economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending the government's stand on antitrust issues and the
Microsoft case, Justice Department antitrust chief Joel Klein told
a largely admiring crowd of tech executives and venture capitalists
that, when it comes to assessing the abuses of monopoly power, the
new economy is just like the old.
</P>
<P>
   ``While technology changes, human nature does not,'' he said,
pointing to the Sherman Act of 1890 as the Magna Carta of a free
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Klein quoted dire predictions made a quarter century ago that
the breakup of AT&AMP;T would kill the goose that laid the golden egg.
Instead, that divestiture unleashed remarkable competition that
lead to the rise of the Internet and such technologies as
broadband, wireless and vfiber optics, as well as lower consumer
prices for phone service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he argued that splitting Microsoft into two
companies, one for operating systems and one for application
software, will produce ``substantial innovation and competition in
the software business.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporting Klein's argument, venture capitalists such as Mark
Kvamme of Sequoia Capital acknowledged that precious little VC
money has gone to fund companies making software for PCs. ``If
there's a breakup, that could change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Doerr of Kleiner, Perkins, Caufield &AMP; Byers was even more
blunt. His firm has an ``unwritten rule (that) we would never
invest in anything even remotely competitive with Microsoft,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong forum at the sprawling, wooded estate of real estate
magnate Walter Shorenstein was sponsored by the Haas School of
Business at UC Berkeley and modeled on the annual World Economic
Forum in Davos, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Laura D'Andrea Tyson, the Hass School dean, drew on her
connections from her tenure as President Clinton's economic adviser
to lure top administration officials, including Klein, Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers and Federal Reserve Vice Chairman Roger
Ferguson, to address the crowd of some 40 technology power brokers,
economists and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   On the economic front, Ferguson said he was ``cautiously
optimistic that the recent rapid productivity growth _ an annual
gross domestic product growth of 4.25 percent for the past five
years _ will continue in the future. His remarks came a week before
the Fed's next expected interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
   Several people at the meeting warned, however, that a shortage
of skilled workers could be a negating factor on continued economic
growth. ``I wonder how many highly educated, experienced people are
left,'' said Sequoia's Kvamme. ``We will pay anything for these
people.''
</P>
<P>
   George Shaheen, chief executive of Internet grocer Webvan, said
he sees a fresh supply of tech workers coming from college
campuses. ``Their worst nightmare is to have to go back into that
old economy to seek their future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although yesterday's tech boosterism was being preached to the
choir, even some of the most fervent cheerleaders expressed some
reservations about Wall Street valuations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love Cisco,'' said Stephen Roach, chief economist for
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. Still, he said, ``there's no way to
justify a triple-digit (price-earning) ratio for that stock.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
