<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-FISCAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SALES SURGE AGAIN AT CISCO  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite concerns that it could be overvalued,
Cisco Systems reassured Wall Street on Tuesday by ringing up
another solid quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose, Calif., Internet infrastructure company reported
sales surged 55 percent to $4.92 billion for the third fiscal
quarter, which ended April 29. That's well ahead of analysts'
predictions of $4.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company's profits, excluding acquisitions and
other special charges, came in at 14 cents per share, a penny ahead
of estimates, according to First Call and within the range of
``whisper estimates.'' Profits jumped 58 percent to $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Including acquisition costs, taxes and other charges, earnings
increased slightly to $662 million, 9 cents a share, up from $636
million, or 9 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a solid quarter,'' said Chase H&AMP;Q analyst Erik
Suppiger. He was especially impressed with the company's enterprise
division. The unit, which sells networking equipment to
corporations, saw a 20 percent increase in sales from the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco shares closed Tuesday, before the earnings announcement,
unchanged at $62.75. The stock seemed to hold steady in immediate
after-hours trading. Since Cisco is the most valuable technology
firm in terms of market value, its earnings announcements can
potentially have a major effect on the market as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was also significant because Cisco shares
tumbled more than 7 percent on Monday after a scorching cover story
appeared in Barron's, arguing that Cisco is overvalued and could
have trouble maintaining its growth through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   An illustration depicted Cisco, and the 58 companies it has
swallowed, as a deck of cards. It also pointed out that Cisco had a
sky-high price-earnings ratio _ 129 as of Tuesday, compared to 40
for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the article did not contain any specific bomb shells
about Cisco. And Cisco executives said the quarter demonstrates
their financials are solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows continued strong momentum across the board,'' said
Chief Strategy Officer Mike Volpi. Executives also said their $6.9
billion purchase of Cerent, an obscure Petaluma, Calif., optics
company, is already paying off. By next quarter, Volpi said Cisco
could be on track to generating $1 billion in annual sales from
fiber optics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chief Executive John Chambers warned that the company
needs to do a better job forecasting its supply needs, especially
in newer markets like optics. Companies like Cisco have been having
a tough time finding adequate supplies in some markets, like
cellular and fiber optics. ``It's a little bit of a concern,''
Chambers said in a conference call with analysts. But Volpi said
the shortages hasn't had any financial impact so far.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco also confirmed that the Securities and Exchange Commission
is investigating possible insider trading just before it bought
Arrowpoint Communications of Acton, Mass., for $5.7 billion Friday.
But Volpi said the SEC has looked into five of the six acquisitions
it has made of publicly traded companies. ``It is very common,''
Volpi said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Cisco has grown, surpassing Microsoft in market value
and gobbling up potential competitors, the company has faced
questions about whether it could attract added scrutiny from
federal antitrust regulators. It enjoys roughly an 80 percent
market share in its core market of a device called routers, which
direct bits of traffic over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Chambers insisted the parallels end there. He said Cisco
emphasizes open standards _ so its routers will work with other
companies' networking hardware. By contrast, software written for
Linux won't run on Windows, for instance. (Rivals gripe that Cisco
equipment is designed to work better with other Cisco equipment.)
</P>
<P>
   He also said the company faces stiff competition from hundreds
of startups, which can quickly grow into publicly traded rivals
like Juniper Networks and Sycamore. And Chambers insisted it hasn't
bullied other companies or sold products at a loss to drive out
competition _ two things Microsoft has been accused of. ``We get
along with most of our competitors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
