<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-FED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FED READY TO RATCHET UP RATES  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ New economy? Maybe, says the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the central bank won't keep using the
old-economy remedy of pushing up interest rates by as much as half
a percentage point to beat back inflation, the Fed's top official
in the West signaled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Federal Reserve Bank President Robert Parry, in a
speech at a meeting of financial planners in the city, praised the
spread of computer technology, which, he said, is allowing workers
to produce more goods and services with the same amount of labor.
That has fueled boom times with, until recently, little upward
pressure on prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Fed policymakers have been worrying the economy has such a
strong a head of steam that surging productivity can no longer keep
prices at bay. To cool things down, monetary policymakers ratcheted
up short-term interest rates five times since last summer, from
4.75 percent to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Fed may be poised to raise rates at a faster pace. In an
unusually broad hint, Parry said policymakers might play ``a second
note,'' when the central bank's rate-setting committee meets next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The comment was taken to mean that the Fed might raise its
target for short-term interest rates by more than the quarter-point
baby steps it has taken so far. ``He was trying to say that a
half-percentage-point increase is more likely than anything else,''
said Robert MacIntosh, chief economist at Eaton Vance, a Boston
money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   Parry made the remark in response to a question whether the Fed
will abandon its cautious policy of small rate hikes, given signs
that the economy may be overheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved cautiously, but that doesn't mean we only have a
single note to play,'' he added. ``I'm not sure I would consider a
second note inconsistent with caution.''
</P>
<P>
   The central bank's rate-setting committee includes seven Federal
Reserve governors and 12 district bank presidents. Only five of the
presidents have voting privileges, which are rotated on a yearly
basis. Parry is a voting member this year.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, higher interest rates haven't taken much of a bite
out of economic growth. But a half-point increase, particularly if
it is followed by further rate hikes, could finally put a chill in
the economy by raising borrowing costs, slowing job growth, making
housing more expensive and putting downward pressure on stock and
bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional economic wisdom holds that fast economic growth and
low unemployment rates feed inflation. But proponents of the new
economy theory believe technology lowers the cost of doing business
so dramatically that rapid growth is possible without inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the new economy crowd has had plenty of
evidence on its side. Despite the longest expansion in U.S.
history, inflation has remained below 2 percent annually in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   While inflation was subdued, the Fed at least partly embraced
the new economy argument, Parry said. That dictated a policy of
gradual rate increases, even as the economy surged forward at a
pace that might once have prompted the Fed to come out with guns
blazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to proceed with some caution, because there's a fair
bit of uncertainty about the economy's behavior right now,'' Parry
said.
</P>
<P>
   As economic growth accelerates and signs of inflation reappear,
it's becoming harder for the Fed to maintain that posture. In the
past few weeks, said MacIntosh, ``We've seen the first really
negative numbers,'' including evidence that inflation is well above
2 percent again.
</P>
<P>
   Fed watchers say the central bank may combine dovish words and
hawkish actions, as it tries to reconcile its inflation-fighting
mandate and its new economy sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
