<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: BIG TECH INVESTORS HAVEN'T UNFASTENED SEAT BELTS
JUST  YET
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was a sober crowd at the Chase H&AMP;Q Technology
Conference luncheon Tuesday, and not just because there was no wine
on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Four professional investors gave their outlook for tech stocks,
and none of them is expecting a repeat of the mad acceleration that
took tech stocks to breakneck speeds until they hit the wall in a
fiery crash.
</P>
<P>
   We have just experienced a ``a world-class speculative blow
off,'' said Roger McNamee of Integral Capital Partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had $2 stocks masquerading as $200 stocks. Now they're
masquerading as $50 stocks. Valuations are still very high.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that when the 1990s started, technology was 6
percent of gross domestic product and 5 percent of the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index. Most investors were underweighted in tech,
meaning that it represented less than 5 percent of their
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 1990s, tech accounted for 10 percent of GDP
and 30 percent of the S&AMP;P 500, and most investors were overweighted
in technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never again enjoy the benefits of the tech S&AMP;P
weighting moving from 5 percent to 30 percent,'' McNamee said.
</P>
<P>
   The other panelists tried to put a positive spin on things, but
there was also a lot of talk about the V-word.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become much more concerned about valuations,'' said
Joe McNay, CEO of Essex Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Appledorn, senior manager with Munder Capital Management,
called the term ``Internet valuations'' an oxymoron but has tried
to make some sense of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have re-evaluated every position,'' said Appledorn, who
helps manage the Munder Net Net fund. He said the old PEG ratio _
which says a company is fairly valued when its price-earnings ratio
equals its expected earnings-growth rate _ ``is not a bad place to
operate from.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the session, someone asked the question
everyone wanted to hear. It went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Intel, Cisco and Dell have emerged as the dominant
tech stocks. Do you still believe in those companies? And over the
next five years, who will be the next ``four horsemen'' of
technology?
</P>
<P>
   McNamee said he considers Microsoft a ``great value'' at today's
prices and thinks a breakup of the company would be a boon to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am stunned at the way Oracle has reinvented itself'' as an
Internet company, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But he had harsh words for Dell. ``Its days as an industry
leader are fading,'' he said, adding that the company has ``lost
control of the supply chain.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that one of the future ``horsemen'' will be Viant,
which describes itself as ``an integrated strategy and solutions
partner'' that has ``pioneered powerful approaches for successfully
incubating and launching e-commerce enterprises.''
</P>
<P>
   McNamee also thinks investors are so focused on virtual
companies that they have neglected the ``physical side'' of the
business, especially contract manufacturers. He said Flextronics is
the ``most visionary'' company in this field, but Solectron is also
``incredibly well positioned.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the other panelists, Jay Hoag, a general partner with
Technology Crossover Ventures, said, ``Ariba has the opportunity to
become the defining company in the B2B space.''
</P>
<P>
   McNay is betting on Phone.com, which provides software for
delivering Internet services to wireless phones; Broadcom, which
sells chips for high-speed telecommunications; and Brocade
Communications, which provides components for high-end data storage
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Appledorn named Oracle, Ariba (B2B software), InfoSpace
(Internet services) and Critical Path (e-mail outsourcing for
business).
</P>
<P>
   All four companies, he said, are ``leaders in their industries,
extremely well managed, know how to partner and have great revenue
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Appledorn confessed to being the only investor to raise his hand
at Monday's Chase H&AMP;Q luncheon, when venture capitalist Stewart
Alsop asked who would buy Webvan at $6.25 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Appledorn, who has been buying the online grocer since it went
public, described it as a ``lottery ticket'' that will either win
big or go to zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in the management. We believe conceptually in what
they are doing,'' Appledorn said. But he said the company needs to
increase its average order size, get up to full capacity in its
warehouses and work out the kinks in its distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at least 12 months away from getting a clear signal
which way they are going to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
