 GROW A BUSINESS: FOCUSING ON QUALITY IS TRAILBLAZING TECHNIQUE  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Home remodeler Judith Thompson's flourishing
business illustrates how entrepreneurs can sometimes avoid the mass
market and succeed in the process.
</P>
<P>
   She has built a $20 million-a-year construction business with
about 80 employees by focusing on quality rather than quantity. Her
San Francisco company, Thompson Brooks, has become the largest
woman-owned remodeling company in the country by working with only
about 10 clients at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it helps that her market is San Francisco,
neighboring Marin County, and Silicon Valley, where upscale clients
are happy to spend millions to buy a property and millions more to
tear it apart. Two of Thompson's current customers are spending
about $5 million each on fixer-uppers in San Francisco's Pacific
Heights neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Thompson will join Venture Strategy Group founder
Joanna Rees Gallanter and Bread &AMP; Roses founder Mimi Farina as
winners of the Woman Entrepreneur of the Year awards of the San
Francisco chapter of the National Association of Women Business
Owners. NAWBO, as it is known, has 82 chapters and more than 6,600
members across the country, and the local chapter has been
spotlighting top entrepreneurs since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is receiving this year's ``Trailblazer'' award for
building her successful remodeling business during the past decade
and serving as a mentor to other entrepreneurs. But Thompson tried
several careers before remodeling. She started as a high school
counselor and art teacher and then house painter in Chicago and San
Francisco. In 1987, she sold her local painting company, Windy City
West, and went to architecture school.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Thompson decided she wanted to be a general
contractor, not an architect, and started with a $20,000 bathroom
renovation in the Western Addition neighborhood. Today, she
wouldn't touch such a small project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easier to do 10 big jobs than 200 small ones,'' said
Thompson. Her firm has never advertised and depends entirely on
word of mouth for new business. Thompson said that has never been a
problem. ``We're very service oriented and do perfect work.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Rees Gallanter will receive NAWBO's ``Rising Star'' award
for her venture capital fund, Venture Strategy, which she started
in 1996 and which has $200 million in capital.
</P>
<P>
   Gallanter decided to get into venture capital after spending
most of her career in consumer products for such brands as Digital
Equipment, Evian water, Gravy Train and Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   After learning about the financial side at San Francisco's
Vrolyk &AMP; Co. and BA Securities Private Placement Group, she started
her own firm and is focusing on the nexus of branding and
business-to-business exchanges and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the companies Venture Strategy invested in, Post
Communications and Allbusiness.com, were recently acquired by
Netcentives and NBC Internet, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Mimi Farina is receiving the ``Community Advocate Award.'' For
25 years, her Bread &AMP; Roses charity organization has brought live
performances to prisons, hospitals and senior homes.
</P>
<P>
   EMERGING MARKETS: State Treasurer Philip Angelides, California's
chief investment officer, will launch an initiative today to get
public pension plans and state and local governments to invest $8
billion in California's ``at-risk communities.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, Angelides noted, the state's two largest
pension funds have invested more than $5 billion in overseas
emerging markets while some California communities remain in
serious need of capital.
</P>
<P>
   The treasurer's ``Double Bottom Line'' initiative calls for the
California Public Employees Retirement System and California State
Teachers' Retirement System to invest at least 2 percent of their
more than $270 billion portfolios _ more than $5 billion _ in
California emerging market opportunities by December 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for $600 million of additional home loans
for low- and moderate-income Californians, $1 billion in new state
deposits in California financial institutions and more than $1
billion in new urban investment programs.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; entrepreneurs(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
