 YIPES STRIKES RICH VEIN OF VC FUNDING  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yipes Communications Inc. was one of the big
recipients of venture capital dollars in the past quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco startup that seeks to eliminate the so-called
bandwidth bottleneck between high-speed corporate networks and
cross-country fiber-optic networks raised $77 million on March 8.
</P>
<P>
   The year-old company took Ethernet technology developed for
local area networks and found a way to pump the signals through
glass fiber at similar high speed over 40-plus miles.
</P>
<P>
   Yipes leases access to glass fiber rings to corporate customers
in a growing number of cities and lets them order just the service
they need in 1-megabit increments all the way to 1 gigabit (a
billion bits per second).
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses are demanding faster, simpler and more scalable
networking services,'' said Yipes Chief Executive Officer Jerry
Parrick. ``We are offering bandwidth on demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than having to order T1 (1.5 megabits per second), DS-3
(45 mbps) or other fixed-capacity lines from telecommunications
suppliers and waiting weeks or months to get the fixed-capacity
systems installed, Yipes customers can order the networking
capacity they need and expand it as their needs change.
</P>
<P>
   The company also says it offers significant cost advantages _
providing roughly twice the bandwidth at 80 percent of the price of
traditional data communications services. Another advantage for
many businesses that already have Ethernet systems is that they
don't need to change existing protocols to use the high-speed
linkup.
</P>
<P>
   Yipes' service is available only in a few markets including Palo
Alto, Calif.; San Francisco, Boston, Chicago, Denver and Los
Angeles. One client, the Palo Alto Medical Foundation, uses Yipes'
high-speed links between its Palo Alto campus, satellite clinics
and the Internet for sending teleconferencing, interactive
learning, CT scan images and other data in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Yipes, which expects to serve 15 major U.S. cities by the end of
the year, so far has raised $91 million to build its network.
Venture capital investors include Norwest Venture Partners, New
Enterprise Associates, the Sprout Group/DLJ, Chase Capital Partners
and BancBoston Ventures/Robertson Stephens. Strategic corporate
investors include Juniper Networks, Extreme Networks and Intel
Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, Yipes plans to tap big telecommunications and
other companies in a late round of financing before going public.
For an Internet infrastructure company pioneering new services,
Parrick said, ``There's no such thing as too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   Yipes, with more than 200 employees, is growing fast. Like many
other high-tech startups in downtown San Francisco, it occupies
temporary offices under renovation, with phone lines festooned from
the ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Yipes, Parrick headed data groups at US West and Pacific
Bell and then founded Diamond Lane Communications, a Petaluma,
Calif., DSL equipment supplier that was purchased by Nokia a year
ago for $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   To go along with his second startup's catchy technology, Parrick
was looking for a catchy name. The company paid a branding firm
$25,000 and received about 700 suggestions, including Lightrider
and Metrocrossing.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, management decided to follow the Yahoo approach of
trying to describe a potential customer's emotional reaction to
using the service.
</P>
<P>
   A marketing manager suggested ``Yikes,'' as in ``yikes that's
fast.'' Parrick fine-tuned it to ``Yipes,'' which also happens to
be an anagram of ``yes'' and the initials for ``Internet
Protocol.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
