<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VC-CAPITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VENTURE CASH IS FLOWING FAST  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Venture capital investors poured more than $1
billion a week into promising U.S. startups in the first quarter,
and Bay Area companies once again received a disproportionate share
of the bounty.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. venture-backed companies raised $17.8 billion in 1,040
rounds, according to VentureOne, a San Francisco VC research firm.
Bay Area companies accounted for a third of the total _ 342 of the
deals and nearly 6.3 billion of the dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The local numbers are not that much different from the torrid
totals from the fourth quarter of 1999. But the number of deals in
the most-recent quarter is nearly double the number in the first
quarter of 1999 and the amount raised is more than triple.
</P>
<P>
   The big winners in the past quarter were companies that provide
fiber-optic communications and networking services. Kestrel
Solutions raised $105 million; Telseon, $80 million; Yipes
Communications, $77 million; and Optical Networks, $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has invaded nearly every area venture capital
investing, including financial and medical services. Web-related
investments now account for 84 percent of all the dollars compared
with 60 percent a year ago and just 41 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, not all Internet sectors are equally attractive.
VentureOne research director Sasha Talebi reports that more than
half the Internet dollars in the past quarter went to business
services companies. Internet infrastructure companies also were
popular.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investments in business-to-consumer and other
e-commerce companies dropped to 5 percent of the total from 12
percent in the fourth quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The rules of the venture capital game have changed some since
many dot-com darlings and other high-tech stocks hit the skids on
Wall Street last month.
</P>
<P>
   The private equity markets are buffered somewhat from what
happens in the public market. But many venture capital investors
are now more picky.
</P>
<P>
   Talebi suggests that they are taking a rifle instead of shotgun
approach and are targeting companies that have a technology edge, a
clear market advantage or real profit potential. Venture capital
investors are also demanding more for their money, meaning that
entrepreneurs have to give up greater stakes for the same amount of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question there will be a shakeout,'' said John
Taylor, director of research for National Venture Capital
Association in Arlington, Va. ``You can only have so many people
selling dog food over the Internet.'' But he says the quality of
ideas and entrepreneurs is still very high and the reservoir of
available capital remains at record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Economics of Newark, N.J., reports that VC firms
nationwide raised $46.1 billion in capital last year and corporate
funds raised an additional $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As fledgling companies require more capital to build their
businesses and establish a dominant market position, the size of
venture capital investments is growing, too. The median U.S.
investment in the past quarter was $12 million, compared with $6
million a year ago. In the Bay Area, the median investment
increased to $13.25 million from $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the past quarter, 38 local companies received $50 million or
more from venture capital and other private-equity investors,
compared with only 16 in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list of companies that raised the most is
AdvisorTech Corp. of San Francisco. The Internet-based financial
services company that was started two years ago by former Charles
Schwab President Timothy McCarthy raised $125 million from a
variety of investors, including Whitney &AMP; Co., Chase H&AMP;Q and
California State Teachers' Retirement System.
</P>
<P>
   AdvisorTech is using the Internet to provide proprietary
research on mutual fund selection, trading services and record
keeping to financial advisers outside the United States. Its first
market is Japan, where households have $12 trillion to invest but
only 9 percent of it is invested in mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``AdvisorTech provides the resources that enable both
independent financial advisers and institutional clients overseas
to better compete in the Internet age,'' said McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Not all newly financed dot-coms are startups. Dove Brothers, a
Foster City industrial auctioneer that started in 1937, changed its
name to DoveBid and raised $109.5 million to convert to an online
business.
</P>
<P>
   Customers such as Raytheon and General Dynamics can go to
Dovebid.com to buy and sell everything from computers to office
furnishings to manufacturing equipment. Investors include Softbank
Capital Partners, Texas Pacific Group, Yahoo Inc., Sun Microsystems
Inc., Fremont Ventures and Mayfield Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Economics reports that VC firms invested $22.7 billion
in 1,557 U.S. entrepreneurial companies in the first quarter, up
266 percent from the $6.2 billion invested in the like quarter last
year. Its numbers are higher than VentureOne's numbers because it
includes more corporate investments and other private placements.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-year, investments in Northern California startups jumped
the most _ 347 percent, to $7.9 billion from $1.8 billion.
Meanwhile, investment in the Northeast grew 296 percent, to $5.4
billion from $1.4 billion; and investment in the Southeast jumped
253 percent, to $1.8 billion from $525 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent slowdown in initial public offerings, many VC
investors still favor IPOs as their so-called exit strategy. In the
past quarter, 69 venture-backed companies went public, according to
VentureOne. That compares with 75 in the fourth quarter and just 23
in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers and acquisitions remain a viable alternative to selling
shares to the public. In the first quarter of this year, VentureOne
reports 88 VC-backed companies were bought for $42.7 billion. That
topped the $40.9 billion paid for 276 companies during all of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
