<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS DEFEAT HEAT, 82-76 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT33,34,35 _ are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After the chaos he triggered in the minds of the Heat
players, near the end of a game he had scrambled with his rugged
style, the emotionally restrained Charlie Ward carried on as usual
once the rest of his team caught on to the mood he established.
</P>
<P>
   He simply faded into the background down the stretch. His work
was nearly done. For three quarters, Ward barged into the chest of
Alonzo Mourning when his teammates shied away. For three quarters
he carried the Knicks when Patrick Ewing, Allan Houston and Latrell
Sprewell could not find the basket as the Heat hovered over their
every move. For three quarters, Ward popped 3-pointers to puncture
the spirits of the Heat players.
</P>
<P>
   After he gave his team a nice lead, Ward stepped aside and let
his teammates frolic in the fourth quarter. It was almost too much
for them to handle. After some flashy dunks by Sprewell and the
late arrival of Houston's jumper, the Knicks built an 18-point,
fourth-quarter lead, only to allow the Heat to close within 7
points before ending the suspense with an 82-76 victory on Tuesday
night at American Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   That evened the four-of-seven-game, second-round series at one
victory each and stole the Heat's precious home-court advantage in
the process. Games 3 and 4 will be at Madison Square Garden on
Friday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie is one of the toughest guys on our team,'' Ewing said.
``He dives for the ball, he has no fear of injury. That's the
football player in him. We needed somebody to step up and have a
big game. I'm glad Charlie was the guy who did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward ended the game 5 for 10 with 13 points. Sprewell (2 for 13)
had 11 points, Houston (3 for 14) had 12 points and Ewing (4 of 12)
ended with 13.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Knicks shot just 35 percent, they held the Heat to
34 percent. The most important difference was at the free-throw
line. The Heat made just 19 of 33 attempts, while the Knicks hit 31
of 42. For Miami, Alonzo Mourning had a game-high 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about Miami's free-throw shooting, Heat Coach Pat Riley
said: ``When you get to the line, you've got to knock them down.
You have to stay with your routine _ take three breaths and hit
them. You have to do that. That's all there is to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to Ward, the Knicks got 10 points from Marcus Camby. The
only other Knicks to match Ward's intensity. Camby left the game,
staggering to the bench with 8 minutes 32 seconds left in the game,
after putting the Knicks up by 10. Chris Childs also gave the
Knicks a big lift down the stretch when he nailed a 3-pointer with
8:21 left. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell said: ``It was one of those hard-fought, intense games.
We played really well until those last five minutes. I'd say our
point guards really did it for us tonight. They should get all the
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 24 hours after the Knicks' Game 1 loss, Coach Jeff Van
Gundy found himself surrounded by second opinions. The active Camby
has to be on the floor at the end, the gimpy Hardaway has to be
preyed upon, a big backcourt is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   `'I know everyone is looking for monumental changes,'' Van Gundy
said on Tuesday morning. `'But we're not going to change
monumentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they simply changed their mentality. Resisting the urge
to launch jumpers, Ward set the tone by fearlessly driving right
into the biceps of the looming Mourning. It was follow the leader,
but when Sprewell and Houston ducked inside, they went in flinching
as they waited for Mourning to swat their attempts away.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Knicks' many misses, the desired result was
achieved. The Knicks got to the free-throw line, put Mourning and
Brown in foul trouble and found themselves in an unreal position at
the half: They were ahead, 38-34.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to fathom because the Knicks shot just 28.2 percent
from the field and Ewing, Houston, Larry Johnson and Sprewell
combined to hit just 4 of 27 shots. As the unlikely high scorer,
Ward led the Knicks with 7 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   The mind-boggling reason for the Heat's deficit was actually as
simple as a foul shot. The Knicks hit 16 of 22 free throws, while
the Heat missed an amazing 13 of 20, including 8 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks didn't know it would work out like this, but their
aggressive nature put them in a position to make the Heat pay for
their horrible free-throw shooting. The Knicks drove to the basket
on 6 of their first 10 attempts, with two opening driving layups by
Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Ward was also instrumental in giving the Knicks a quick start
early in the third quarter. But this time, he was the one lingering
wide open behind the 3-point arc for a shot that gave the Knicks a
43-37 lead with nine minutes left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   When given the chance to counter, the Heat missed open jumpers
and were swarmed when they dared to drive inside. After three
turnovers in two minutes, the Knicks had a 49-40 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Heat started to make the Knicks pay for double-teaming
Mourning as Hardaway hit back-to-back 3 pointers to pull the Heat
within 49-46 with four minutes left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, the Knicks had held the Heat to just 3 of 14
in the third quarter. But as intense as they were, so was the Heat.
With Bruce Bowen giving Sprewell fits, the Knick forward was forced
into his fourth turnover of the game on a play that gave Mashburn a
fast-break layup to close the Knicks' lead to 1 point.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after Ewing showed some life, Ward also came to the rescue
again. In the middle of the brutal, physical style displayed on the
floor by both teams, he calmly hit a 3-pointer with a minute left
to put the Knicks up, 57-50.
</P>
<P>
   After two free throws by Houston, the Knicks survived the
craziness to lead, 59-50, entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it was a lead built on free-throws. The Knicks were
shooting 33 percent, as was the Heat, but they had the touch at the
line. At this point, the Heat was 8 of 22 from the line. More
important, Majerle, Bowen and Brown were in deep foul trouble with
four apiece. And Mourning had three.
</P>
</TEXT>
